<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Punjab 3rdLd-Writethru a0922 03-03 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0922,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>32 Killed in Holiday Attack by Sikhs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last 3 grafs, starting ``Police say ... with 10 grafs to
UPDATE with details of attack; no pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh gunmen opened fire with automatic
rifles and machine guns on a holiday gathering early Friday in
Punjab state, killing at least 32 people and injuring 40 others,
police said.
   The attack in Hoshiarpur district was one of the bloodiest since
Sikh extremists launched their guerrilla war for an independent
homeland in the northern state in 1982.
   Punjab security forces and New Delhi police were put on alert
after the killing to prevent any backlash by Hindus.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   Police said both Hindus and Sikhs were among those killed and
injured in the assault, which occurred as India began its
celebration of Holi, or the festival of color. The national holiday
commemorates the triumph of the Hindu god Lord Krishna over evil.
   Sikhs, who make up about 2 percent of India's 780 million
people, claim they are discriminated against by Hindus who form the
majority of the population. Punjab state is predominantly Sikh.
   The latest assault occurred as about 300 people gathered to
celebrate the festival at Kari Sari village near the town of
Hoshiarpur, which is about 80 miles east of the Sikh holy city of
Amritsar.
   Suresh Aurora, senior superintendent of police at Hoshiarpur,
said about 12 gunmen dashed onto the festival ground at about 12:30
a.m. Friday and opened fire.
   He said the injured, many of them in ``extremely serious''
condition, were rushed to hospitals in Hoshiarpur town and
Jalandhar, capital of the neighboring district.
   The gunmen fled and were being sought, he said.
   The attack was the worst in Punjab since last July, when Sikh
gunmen waylaid three buses in two attacks and slaughtered 72
people, most of them Hindus.
   The latest killings raised to more than 370 the number of people
killed in attacks blamed on Sikh extremists in Punjab since the
start of the year.
   Last year, more than 1,000 people died in such attacks.
   On Thursday, Sikh extremists had gunned down a Sikh family of
eight and a paramilitary policeman in Punjab.
   Sikhism is an offshoot of Hinduism that came into existence 500
years ago.
   Punjab has been under direct federal rule since Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi dismissed the moderate Sikh state government last year
for failing to curb terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
