<1ST_LINE>r i PM-YugoslavMedicine     03-03 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslav Medicine,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia's Communist Authorities Consider Private Medicine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the state health service in
virtual bankruptcy, Yugoslavia's Communist authorities are weighing
the possibility of using private medical practice on a large scale.
   Some medical associations already have resorted to private
practice in the republics of Slovenia and Serbia, partly because of
large losses built up by the state medical service.
   The official Tanjug news agency said authorities in Belgrade are
preparing a ``detailed analysis'' of private medicine and will
announce a decision by the end of May.
   Orthodox Communist Party dogma regards private medical practice
as unacceptable.
   But under consideration are the use of privately operating
doctors and small private clinics employing up to two physicians
plus medical staff.
   Yugoslavia's deepening economic crisis is the main reason for
the financial troubles in the state-run health service.
   A sharp drop in the value of Yugoslavia's currency, the dinar,
which lost about 200 percent against Western currencies in a year,
has driven up the cost of imports of many medicines, raw materials
for their production and medical equipment.
   In addition, a government price freeze has made the production
of such goods from imported raw materials unprofitable and has
resulted in a shortage of several medical and nutrition items,
including baby formula.
   In January, due to virtual lack of baby formula in several
Yugoslav hospitals, new-born babies had to be fed intravenouly.
   Private medical practice in Yugoslavia was abolished after World
War II when the Communist Party took power.
   The statea health service is financed by deductions from
Yugoslavs' salaries.
   However, since the state is unable to entirely subsidize health
care, most parts of Yugoslavia have permitted patients to pay for
medical services on a private basis.
   ``We cannot claim any more that our medical services are free of
charge, and this shows that we don't have the system typical of a
communist country,'' said Dr. Dragan Djordjevic, a Belgrade
physician.
   ``This means that the ideological barrier, which would prevent
introduction of private medical practice, no longer exists in
Yugoslavia.''
   In addition to shortages of medical supplies, the state health
service has been afflicted by a sharp drop in services and an
increasing number of work stoppages by medical staff over wages.
   The state-run press reported recent strikes by doctors and
nurses in Belgrade, Zagreb and Ljubljana.
   The lack of drugs and medical supplies, including such basic
items as soap, detergents and alcohol, has affected the work of
many hospitals, the newspaper Vecernje Novosti said recently.
   ``Hygiene has fallen to the lowest possible level, and even
disposable items have to be sterilized for multiple use,'' it said,
adding that patients are bringing their own soap to the hospital.
   Faced with a 170-percent inflation rate, a $20 billion foreign
debt and a sharp drop in living standards, Communist-governed
Yugoslavia has been hit by its worst economic crisis in its history.
   The newspaper Politika said some state hospitals may close down
if a newly adopted bankruptcy law is strictly enforced.
   The bankruptcy law, designed to revive the ailing economy,
forsees the closing down of all enterprises that lose money.
   Serbian and Slovenian doctors maintain that private medical
practice would create additional jobs for at least 4,000 doctors
currently registered as unemployed in Yugoslavia.
   They said it would also bring a return of several thousand
Yugoslav medical specialists who have been working in Western
countries and have accumulated large foreign currency savings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
