<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Guns     03-03 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Guns,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Backs Bill To Ban Plastic Handguns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III says a
conservative Republican's bill to ban undetectable plastic handguns
would be effective against terrorists who might use such weapons.
   Meese's endorsement of legislation sponsored by Sen. James
McClure, R-Idaho, is the latest development in a growing dispute
over plastic guns.
   Supporters of rival legislation say that McClure's bill would
still permit guns to slip by metal detectors and X-ray machines at
their current settings.
   McClure on Wednesday released a letter by Meese, saying: ``Based
on our review, we believe that your bill ... is an excellent
legislative proposal to deal with the threat posed by criminals and
terrorists armed with such weapons.''
   The National Rifle Association also backs McClure's bill.
   The McClure proposal would make it illegal to manufacture or
import a plastic firearm unless one of these conditions exists:
   _The barrel is made in whole or in part of a metallic substance
that can be detected by a magnetometer.
   _The serial number required by law is engraved on a metallic
substance capable of detection.
   The measure also would require plastic portions of any such
firearm to be infused with substances that would register on a
X-ray machine.
   Handgun Control Inc. and a coalition of law enforcement groups
have joined to oppose McClure's bill and support legislation
sponsored by Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio. Metzenbaum has
support from Republican Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina.
   Metzenbaum and his supporters say their legislation has the
ingredient that McClure's measure lacks: a requirement that the
guns have enough metal to be detected at currently used settings of
security machines.
   They contend that guns meeting the guidelines in McClure's
proposal would only set off alarms if detectors were operated at
settings so low they would stop everyone with a key chain.
   Plastic guns are not yet in production, but Handgun Control Inc.
said a Florida manufacturer will be ready to produce them in a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
