<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Villages     03-03 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Villages,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Palestinian Villages Declare Themselves Liberated</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KFAR NAAMI, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian flags flutter
from the power lines in this West Bank community. PLO grafitti
adorns the walls. People here call Kfar Naami a ``liberated
village.''
   Eight miles over the mountains, residents of Bir Zeit have
blocked the roads with stones. They, too, claim their village is
``liberated.''
   Throughout the West Bank, a few communities in the past few
weeks have defied the Israeli army and declared independence from
the Israeli occupation administration.
   These little pieces of ``Palestine'' are the source of much
pride among the Arabs. But the reality is that the Israelis do not
want to take the trouble to ``unliberate'' many of the rebellious
communities.
   ``This is a liberated village here,'' said Aziz Attaya of Kfar
Naami, wearing a thick beard and a traditional Arab headdress
around his neck. ``We will all die for the creation of a
Palestinian state under the leadership of the PLO.''
   But, countered Munir Naser, a professor of biochemistry at Bir
Zeit University, ``The occupation is everywhere. Perhaps only our
homes are liberated, and in reality, it's not true even there.''
   Hamad, another Bir Zeit resident who did not give his last name,
admitted, ``We're not liberated in the true sense of lberation.
There is a feeling of not being under the control of the Israeli
occupation. At the same time, we know that they are still here and
still control the area.''
   In most liberated villages, people have run up the Palestinian
flag, organized demonstrations, blocked roads, and in some cases,
challenged the army to come and get them.
   The soldiers sometimes oblige. Sometimes they do not.
   These rebellions are irritating, even embarrassing for Israeli
authorities, but they don't have any real practical effect beyond
boosting the morale of local residents.
   The Israeli authorities believe they should be put down but note
that the priority is on keeping major roads open.
   ``The army is not everywhere, but deployed according to suitable
priorities,'' Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, the West Bank's military
commander, told Israel's army radio.
   ``They are on the main roads and secondary roads that must be
guarded. They guard the movement of Israeli residents, be it school
buses or other traffic.''
   But a high-ranking police officer sounded tougher during a
crackdown on the imminently unliberated Silwan, a village
incorporated into Jerusalem after being captured from Jordan in
1967.
   ``The people in Silwan for the last two months thought they
belonged to Palestine,'' said the officer. ``We are now teaching
them they live in Israel, and they will never forget it.''
   In Kfar Naami, a village of 2,000, one Palestinian died in a
clash with soldiers, but the army hasn't been back. The road
through Kfar Naami simply isn't important enough to be worth the
trouble of reclaiming.
   Bir Zeit has a population of 2,000. The university, closed
because Israeli officials say they want to prevent disturbances,
normally has about 2,800 students.
   There is a demonstration every Friday and Sunday in Bir Zeit.
Teachers believe the government stays away because it fears the
university will become a breeding ground for increased dissent and
organization.
   Naser says another reason the Israelis leave Bir Zeit alone is
because it has a more sophisticated population. Many of the
teaching staff studied abroad, are articulate and can use their
voices and outside contacts to tell the world what is going on.
   Some villagers are itching for a fight.
   ``The army doesn't come into the village because there are no
settlers who pass through here,'' said a teen-ager named Ahmed.
   ``I'd like to see the army come here,'' he said. ``Not coming is
not good for the town because people elsewhere, like in Gaza, think
we are not doing anything here. I hope they come. I would like to
fight them. I'd be happy to sacrifice my life.''
</TEXT>
