<1ST_LINE>r w PM-UPI     03-03 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UPI,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President Says UPI Needs $1 Million in Immediate Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Press International's new managers need
about $1 million in loans immediately to pay overdue bills for
items such as health care, rents and telephones, according to a
memo from the company's new president.
   ``At the end of our first week, our preliminary analysis shows
that the financial condition of the company has been deteriorating
steadily, and that monumental efforts are needed to save it from
liquidation,'' Paul Steinle wrote in a letter to employees dated
March 1.
   UPI needs ``short-term financing to bridge its cash flow
requirements until additional investors can be approached,''
Steinle said.
   Steinle works for WNW Group Inc., a media investment group that
assumed control of the financially ailing wire service on Feb. 19.
   WNW bought control of the company's stock from Mexican publisher
Mario Vazquez Rana for an undisclosed sum. UPI emerged from Chapter
11 proceedings in U.S. Bankruptcy Court with Vazquez Rana's
purchase of the company in June 1986.
   In his three-page letter, Steinle said the Wire Service Guild,
the union representing company employees, has been offered ``the
opportunity to participate'' in ``short-term loan financing.''
   Steinle's memo to employees included portions of a letter sent
to the guild over the weekend. Dan Carmichael, a union spokesman,
said he had no comment on the letter, which the guild received
Tuesday.
   But he said he was curious to find out what the company meant by
a ``loan opportunity.''
   In the letter to the union, UPI management said the company is
``facing an immediate and critical situation in the form of the
funding of its ongoing operations.''
   It said WNW Group ``must immediately obtain approximately one
million dollars in loans to enable UPI to begin paying past due
bills for critical items such as health care, rents, telephones,
etc.''
   In the long run, UPI's financial situation will require ``an
infusion of capital, which can only be provided by a sale of stock
or securities,'' the letter said.
   Steinle said the company wants the guild to move quickly _ by
March 14 _ to adopt an employee stock option plan. Under conditions
set by the bankruptcy court, UPI's employees have the right of
first refusal to buy the company if it is put on the block.
   Announcing the change of management last week, Steinle and Dr.
Earl W. Brian, WNW's chairman, said they hoped to have a business
plan for UPI's future within four to six weeks.
   Steinle's letter said the company intended to raise money
through the sale of stock as soon as the business plan is complete.
   The managers said that during Vazquez Rana's tenure, the company
was losing about a $1 million a month.
   Brian, 48, is also the chairman of Infotechnology Inc., an
electronics communications company based in New York. Among its
subsidiaries are Financial News Network, a 24-hour cable television
company. Infotech, as the company is known, is a minority
shareholder of WNW Group.
</TEXT>
