<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TraficantTaxes     03-03 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Traficant Taxes,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traficant Appeals Adverse Tax Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. James Traficant, a declared candidate for
president, has appealed a U.S. Tax Court decision saying he owes
back taxes and penalties for failing to report bribes of $108,000
from reputed organized-crime figures in 1980.
   Traficant, D-Ohio, filed a notice of appeal with the tax court
Wednesday, throwing the case into the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Cincinnati.
   Traficant has described himself as a regional candidate for
president and so far has not appeared on a primary election ballot.
Spokesmen have said he will focus mainly on Ohio and neighboring
states.
   In an opinion issued last September, Judge John Williams said
Traficant's actions when he was campaigning for Mahoning County
sheriff in 1980 reflected an intent to evade taxes and the Internal
Revenue Service had convincingly established that the underpayment
was due to fraud.
   ``They're intimidating,'' Traficant said of the federal
government. ``They beat you down, they wear you out, and they're
working on me.''
   The IRS has calculated that Traficant owes nearly $90,000 in
back taxes and penalties.
   The civil tax case is based on testimony and evidence from
Traficant's 1983 criminal trial in which he was charged with
bribery and income tax evasion. In that case, Traficant defended
himself and was acquitted.
   The charges alleged that Traficant accepted money in exchange
for his promise to ignore the illegal activities of reputed
mobsters in Youngstown, Ohio.
   The case was based on tape recordings allegedly between
Traficant and the mobsters and a written statement to the FBI the
government contended Traficant had signed saying he took the money
in exchange for a promise of cooperation.
   Traficant argued that the money was not income because he
returned most of it and used legitimate contributions in his
campaign for sheriff.
</TEXT>
