<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CIA-Panama     03-03 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CIA-Panama,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Checking Blandon Claims About Files On Senators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator says the CIA is conducting an
inquiry into whether the agency provided personal and political
information on U.S. senators to Panamanian military ruler Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said Wednesday two officials
identifying themselves as being with the CIA's office of the
inspector general interviewed Jose I. Blandon, a former top
Panamanian intelligence official, last week.
   Blandon alleged at a Senate hearing last month that the agency
had provided information on senators to Noriega, who in turn passed
it on to him. The CIA is prohibited by law from domestic spying on
U.S. citizens.
   D'Amato said Blandon told him the CIA investigators were
interested primarily in his charges that Noriega had received
information about both the political beliefs and the personal lives
of several senators and staff members.
   He said Blandon had gone into the lengthy interview under the
impression he would be talking to investigators from the Justice
Department. ``He was surprised that it turned out to be
intelligence people,'' D'Amato said.
   ``He didn't take it as any kind of harassment. He indicated to
the agency that he could help them if they were interested.''
   D'Amato and Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., called the hearings last
month at which Blandon and other witnesses publicly wove
complicated tales about how Noriega sold out his country to drug
traffickers.
   A CIA official, speaking on condition of anonymity, would not
confirm the internal inquiry, but said ``it would make sense'' for
the agency's investigators to want to speak directly to someone who
had made such charges. The CIA has categorically denied providing
any such information to the Panamanian government.
   D'Amato said Blandon related to the CIA investigators the same
story he gave to the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on
terrorism, narcotics and international operations Feb. 9-10.
   Blandon, who was fired in January as Panama's consul general in
New York, told investigators then that Noriega received and passed
to him materials on senators and their staff members, typed in
English on plain white paper.
   In the lower right-hand corner was the signature of a Panamanian
intelligence official who forwarded the material, along with an
indication of the original source of the information _ usually the
CIA or the National Security Council, said officials familiar with
the classified portion of Blandon's testimony. The sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   ``These were not benign official biographies,'' one official
said. ``They were very pointed descriptions, directed at the local
market'' and apparently designed to curry favor with Noriega.
   Blandon said intelligence services of other countries in the
region received similar materials regularly, the officials said.
   Blandon also has made the allegations in conversations with Sen.
David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, and members of his staff. Boren has said he has ``no
reason to believe'' the allegations, but is looking into them.
   Others involved in intelligence have sought to cast doubts on
Blandon's credibility and his motives for turning against Noriega,
whom he served as a longtime top adviser. But D'Amato reiterated
his belief that Blandon is telling the truth.
   D'Amato raised the possibility that the information about
senators and staff members could have been compiled by either a
low-level ``functionary'' at the CIA or by an outside
``contractor'' working for the agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO-Reagan'sDividends Bjt   03-03 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Reagan's Dividends, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Gets What He Wants In Last Appearance On NATO Stage</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In his final appearance on the NATO
stage, President Reagan got virtually everything he wanted,
including a bouquet for his peacemaking efforts with Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and a mandate to demand more from the Soviet leader this
spring.
   Reagan leaves Brussels today with a strong reaffirmation of
alliance solidarity, criticism of the Soviet record on human
rights, and NATO demands for sweeping cutbacks in Warsaw Pact
tanks, artillery and other non-nuclear forces.
   In the spirit of harmony, major differences were muted or
ignored as NATO leaders celebrated the signing of a U.S.-Soviet
treaty to eliminate a whole class of nuclear missiles in Europe and
Asia.
   As the leader of the Western alliance, Reagan can take
satisfaction that NATO weathered the disarmament storm of 1982 and
deployed intermediate-range nuclear missiles, a step that brought
the Soviets back to the negotiating table and produced the INF
treaty.
   Now, with just 10 months remaining in office, he has a vote of
confidence for negotiations with the Kremlin toward a 50 percent
cut in strategic nuclear arms, as well as a strategy for East-West
talks in which NATO will insist on lower levels of Warsaw Pact
tanks, artillery, planes and ground forces.
   Gorbachev has scored points in Europe with his talk of peace and
disarmament, and now Reagan has been put in the same spotlight with
new attention focused on the INF treaty.
   ``Over the last several months, a number of people have said the
INF agreement has caused fissures within the alliance; the alliance
is troubled; Europe is adrift; they're not sure of the United
States' commitment,'' said Lt. Gen. Colin Powell, the president's
national security adviser.
   ``Well, the president reaffirmed our commitment to Europe. He
did it clearly, and that reaffirmation was welcomed by the other
members of the alliance,'' Powell added. ``So I think it's been a
most useful meeting, one that was necessary, one that was
important.''
   The summit was a bright spot in what is likely to be a difficult
year at home for Reagan.
   As a lame-duck president with a Democratic-controlled Congress
hoping to keep Republicans out of the White House, Reagan will have
little chance to advance his legislative agenda.
   Traditionally, then, foreign policy becomes the focus of
outgoing presidents, and Reagan is no exception.
   The NATO summit with the leaders of 15 other countries was
another in a series of farewell sessions, though he will see five
of the officials in Toronto at the annual economic summit in June.
   Before the economic summit, however, comes the trip to Moscow,
his fourth meeting with Gorbachev. It is expected sometime in late
May or early June.
   Both sides seem eager for Reagan's visit, even though it appears
unlikely the leaders will be able to sign another major arms pact.
Reagan said in a recent interview it appeared unlikely there would
be enough time to wrap up a strategic arms treaty before the Moscow
summit, but he said he thought it could be completed before he
leaves office.
   Regardless, a Reagan trip to Moscow, to the heart of what he
once called the Evil Empire, would dominate world attention and
give both the president and the Soviet leader another forum to seek
a legacy as peacemaker.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Terence Hunt has covered Ronald Reagan since
1980 and is the AP's White House correspondent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
