<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0234EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NATO-ConventionalForces     03-03 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Conventional Forces,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Measuring Balance In Conventional Forces Tricky</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-NATO Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Measuring the difference in NATO and Warsaw
Pact conventional forces is more than just a numbers game. It is a
complicated and tricky task that goes beyond simply counting tanks
and soldiers.
   Western leaders meeting in Brussels on Wednesday issued a
special statement demanding huge cutbacks in Soviet bloc
conventional forces, highlighting an issue that has divided
negotiators for years.
   Since 1973, negotiators for the alliances have been trying to
agree on how many troops the blocs could throw into a fight in
Europe. Western analysts say it would be more than 2 million on a
side.
   Now, as Europe heads for elimination of medium-range nuclear
missiles under a treaty signed by President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, new attention has been focused on
conventional forces.
   The Pentagon says the Soviet bloc has a substantial edge over
NATO in five major ground force categories.
   According to the Pentagon's 1987 report ``Soviet Military
Power,'' Moscow and its European allies have 230 divisions compared
with NATO's 121. The Soviet edge in main battle tanks is 52,000 to
24,250. They lead in antitank guided weapons launchers 28,000 to
22,580.
   The report says the East bloc has 42,000 artillery and mortar
launchers compared with the West's 18,350 and has 54,000 armored
personnel carriers, while NATO has 41,500.
   Of the direct comparisons, NATO leads only in attack
helicopters, 1,250 to 970.
   The numbers include forces deployed in Europe and those that can
be rapidly deployed from the United States.
   When he was supreme allied commander in Europe from 1979 to
1987, Gen. Bernard W. Rogers used such figures in a set speech on
the subject. He would say, in effect: ``We'd give them a good fight
if deterrence failed and a war broke out, but it wouldn't be long
before I'd have to pick up the phone and ask the NATO politicians
to let me use nuclear weapons.''
   Even Rogers warned, however, against what has become known as
``bean counting'' _ judging strength by mere numbers.
   Joshua Epstein, a Brookings Institution scholar, for example,
has said ``neither the Pentagon nor the Congress actually behave as
though numerical equality mattered. If either did, it would be
frantically shoveling money out of aircraft carriers, where we lead
14:1 _ and into tanks ...''
   There are many variables that have to be weighed. They include:
   _ The difference in requirements of defensive and offensive
forces. Military history has shown that offensive forces need
massive superiority at any given point of an attack against
well-fortified positions.
   Since NATO is a defensive alliance, it presumably does not need
more or even equal numbers of troops to stop an attack, according
to NATO doctrine.
   _ The quality of weaponry. NATO considers its forces have better
and more modern equipment than the Soviets have.
   _ Troop reliability. Would Soviet allies fight as fiercely in an
invasion of West Europe as U.S. allies defending their homelands?
Many analysts doubt they would, and the authors of ``Soviet
Military Power'' concede it ``is not a certainty.''
   _ Terrain. The potential battlegrounds of NATO's central front _
West Germany in particular _ are full of streams, forests, bogs,
cities and other choke points that could lower the effectiveness of
tanks. ``Wars are not fought on paper,'' wrote George Perkovich, a
World Policy Institute fellow who recently studied the conventional
balance.
   _ Asymmetries. Even with the Soviet edge in ground forces, the
West has an advantage of 3,450 to 2,800 in fighter-bombers for
ground attack, which would be used to hit forces massed for
offensives.
   The London-based International Institute for Strategic Studies _
whose annual report ``The Military Balance'' is the quintessence of
bean counting _ says the ``conventional balance is still such as to
make general military aggression a highly risky undertaking for
either side.''
   ``There would still appear to be insufficient overall strength
on either side to guarantee a victory,'' the IISS said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
