<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0308EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxCheating     03-03 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Cheating,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Says Employers Haven't Paid Billions Taken from Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service is looking for
ways to make 338,000 employers hand over $3.73 billion in
delinquent employment taxes, most of which was withheld from
workers' paychecks.
   Because employment taxes account for 69 percent of all federal
revenues, says William Wauben, IRS assistant commissioner for
collections, ``even a slight decline ... can have a devastating
impact'' on government operations.
   The size of these delinquent taxes has grown 49 percent from
$2.5 billion in 1982, Wauben said at a news conference Wednesday.
This rise, which coincided with a steady growth in the value of
business payrolls and increases in Social Security taxes on workers
and their employers, is especially notable in the Southwest, where
the economy has suffered from declining oil prices.
   Even if an employer fails to forward withheld taxes, employees'
tax accounts and Social Security benefits will not be jeopardized
so long as they file an individual tax return, Wauben said.
   Meanwhile, the IRS reported that individual taxpayers are still
slow to file this year's tax returns. Through last week, the agency
said:
   _30.2 million returns had been received, down 4.9 percent from
the same period last year. But the gap is closing; last week, 6.7
million returns were received, up 3 percent from last year. The IRS
attributes this year's slowness to all the 1986 tax changes that
are affecting returns for the first time.
   _The IRS is processing returns at a faster rate. The inventory
of filed but unprocessed returns totaled 14.9 million last week,
down from 16.5 million a year earlier.
   _More than 7.55 million of the processed returns had been
certified for refunds, down 4.5 percent from a year ago. The
average refund is up 7.9 percent, to $793.
   Wauben said employers' failure to forward taxes withheld from
workers' checks often is caused by ignorance of the law or greed.
Often as not, Wauben said, the problem is traced to a failing
company's efforts to stay afloat.
   ``When employers find they are no longer able to keep their
business operating on the cash available and they ... are unable to
borrow from a bank or other lending institution, some begin using
the funds withheld from their employees' wages as their own,'' he
said.
   Employers are required to withhold Social Security and income
taxes from workers' wages, to contribute matching amounts for
Social Security and to pay unemployment taxes on their employees.
Businesses must forward these employment taxes to the IRS at least
once a quarter, although most employers pay once every week or two.
   To reduce delinquency, the IRS is stepping up efforts to educate
employers about their responsibilities and changing procedures to
put collections officers in touch with businesses more quickly. The
agency also is expanding a program designed to catch employers who
unlawfully classify some workers as independent contractors, rather
than employees, to avoid taxes.
   Employers do not withhold taxes from independent contractors,
who are required to make quarterly payments on their taxes. In many
cases, the IRS says, those workers understate earnings and some
don't even file tax returns.
   During a two-year study in 26 areas of the nation, IRS
collections officers audited 1,196 employers suspected of
misclassifying workers as independent contractors. As a result of
the study, 9,004 delinquent employment-tax returns were filed (a
return covers only one quarter) and the IRS hit 92 percent of the
audited employers with tax bills averaging $3,000.
   Because of those findings, the IRS has assigned nearly 400
collections officers to concentrate on investigating similar cases
and hopes to add another 350 next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
