<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BridgeRescue     03-03 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bridge Rescue,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Climber Lands Trespass Charge After Rappelling Off Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYNCHBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rock climber hoping to land in the
Blackwater Creek ravine after rappelling off a bridge instead
landed in police custody.
   David Gloudemans, 24, of Lynchburg, said he was looking for a
new challenge and a shortcut when he tried to propel himself 150
feet off the Rivermont Bridge on Wednesday.
   ``Normally I do this on rocks, but it's hard to find good
climbing places close to home,'' he said, ``and I was a little
short on gas money today. I figured I'd just tie up, slip on down
and no one would know the difference.''
   His stunt didn't go unnoticed.
   Police officer M.L. Coleman was driving across the bridge and
saw Gloudemans vanish over the railing.
   ``I didn't know what to think,'' said Coleman, who has gone to
the bridge several times on suicide reports and accidental falls.
``I looked down over the side, and there he was. He was going to
tie on his rope and go on down. I said, `Let's talk about this.'''
   When rescuers from the Lynchburg Fire Department arrived, the
unruffled Gloudemans was sitting cross-legged on a concrete
abutment 20 feet below the bridge, dressed in jeans, a blue denim
jacket and a bandana. Far below him, a cluster of police officers
stood looking at the other end of his blue and orange ropes, which
were trailing across the ground. Above him on the bridge, an
impromptu command post discussed ways of bringing him back.
   Emergency medical technician Linda Eagle, a recent graduate of a
``rope course,'' was lowered over the bridge to bring him back. She
attached a harness to Gloudemans while eight police officers and
firefighters fed line down from a fire truck.
   ``The height didn't bother me,'' Eagle said, ``but I was a
little worried that he (Gloudemans) might not cooperate. The first
thing he said was `Why can't I go the rest of the way?'''
   Gloudemans eventually was retrieved, but not until after traffic
on the bridge's eastbound lane had been halted nearly 45 minutes.
He was arrested and charged with common law trespassing, and was
released on his own recognizance, Coleman said.
   ``Maybe I should have just gone ahead and jumped off,''
Gloudemans said, ``but I thought that would make it worse.''
</TEXT>
