<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-03 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judith Sherman and William Foley have
changed their wedding plans from small to mall.
   The couple had planned a ceremony attended just by relatives and
close friends, followed by a modest reception at a restaurant.
Instead, they will exchange vows Saturday in the middle of Hanover
Mall, surrounded by family, friends and up to 5,000 shoppers.
   ``This is probably the most public wedding anyone has ever
had,'' said Miss Sherman, 21, of Halifax. ``We always like
everything to be different and this is about as different as it
gets.''
   Miss Sherman and Foley had planned a small ceremony because they
could not afford a big wedding. But their mall nuptial won't cost
them a penny, because they won a drawing to promote a bridal fair
there.
   Merchants are donating an estimated $15,000 worth of goods and
services, including the bride's gown, tuxedos, invitations, wedding
rings, flowers, music, and a honeymoon in Florida.
   ``We really wanted a big wedding, but we didn't have the money
so we didn't even bother to discuss it,'' Miss Sherman said. ``And
then all this happened. All we have to do is sit back and enjoy
ourselves.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH TARRYTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some residents of this New York
City suburb want to bring the legend of Sleepy Hollow home.
   Residents will vote March 15 on whether to rename the town for
the famous Washington Irving story about the Headless Horseman.
Irving lived near here and modeled his fictional Sleepy Hollow
after the picturesque Hudson River region.
   ``It's a part of history that we're Sleepy Hollow,'' said Chris
Skelly, a member of the Village of Sleepy Hollow Committee. ``It's
not a made-up name. It gives us the potential to be famous because
everyone's heard of Sleepy Hollow.''
   Skelly said Irving, for whom nearby Irvington was named, didn't
make up the name, but reached back to 17th century Dutch
descriptions of the area. Dutch pioneers dubbed the area ``sleepy''
because it was easy to dock along the riverside and spend the night.
   Proponents of the change say a new name would distinguish their
8,000-resident community from neighboring Tarrytown and would bring
in tourist money to help local business and tax base, which has
suffered in recent years.
   Opponents say it would be confusing and costly and wouldn't
accomplish anything.
   ``History will not pay the bills or solve the problems,'' said
Edna Belanich, a founder of Concerned Citizens Against Changing the
Name of North Tarrytown. ``We can keep history in our hearts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
