<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Court-Blacklist     03-03 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-Blacklist,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Slams State For ``Blacklisting'' Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's ruling that the Gov. Mario Cuomo's
administration blacklisted construction companies and then allowed
them to buy their way off the list is ``a personal assault on my
integrity,'' says the state's transportation commissioner.
   Justice Harold Hughes of the trial-level state Supreme Court
cited federal extortion laws Wednesday in refusing to dismiss a
lawsuit filed by paving companies that challenged, among other
things, state-imposed affirmative action requirements on
contractors.
   Hughes did not say that any crimes had been committed by
officials but that he was referring the case to federal and state
prosecutors and the state's Commission on Goverment Integrity for
review.
   State Transportation Commissioner Franklin White, one of the
administration's highest-ranking blacks, characterized Hughes'
decision as ``a personal assault on my integrity as a public
official and I'm outraged by it.''
   White denied any blacklist for contractors existed and said the
ruling will be appealed immediately.
   The lawsuit was filed by the New York State Asphalt Pavement
Association, which represents 34 contractors, against White and
state Office of General Services Commissioner John Egan.
   In denying a state motion to dismiss the lawsuit, Hughes said
one company had agreed to pay $150,000 to benefit the state's
Disadvantaged, Minority, Women's Business Enterprise Program to get
off the blacklist.
   ``Compelling contractors to enter into the agreements ...
constitutes unethical and possibly criminal conduct,'' Hughes wrote
in his eight-page opinion.
   Hughes said that as part of the agreements, the companies had to
promise not to sue the state over their blacklisting.
   The lawsuit stems from White's attempt to crack down on
contractors who are not meeting state and federal minority hiring
requirements, or who have established ``front'' companies that
falsely claim to be minority owned, or who have engaged in criminal
activity such as bid-rigging.
   White has moved against companies under criminal investigation
or that have been convicted of crimes that relate to public works
projects.
   State courts recently have ruled against some of DOT's attempts
to force minority hiring by contractors. Those decisions are on
appeal.
   White's spokesman, Timothy Hulbert, said there was nothing
illegal about barring contractors from doing business with the
state if they had violated state laws or regulations. He said that
was done only on a ``case-by-case basis'' and denied a blacklist
was maintained.
   He also said there was nothing illegal about having those
companies pay money to improve minority hiring programs as part of
any agreements for them to get back in the state's good graces.
</TEXT>
