<DOCNO> AP880303-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-AlaskaGOP     03-03 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alaska GOP,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grass-Roots Drive Gives Robertson Victory In Alaska Caucuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grass-roots campaign focusing on
contributors to his former television ministry helped give Pat
Robertson a 2-to-1 victory over Vice President George Bush in the
Alaska Republican precinct caucuses.
   Robertson claimed 47 percent of the votes compared to Bush's 24
percent in a preference poll of 2,020 delegates elected at the
precinct level. Sen. Bob Dole took third with 20 percent and Jack
Kemp trailed at 7 percent, party officials announced Wednesday.
   Robertson's effort was a low-cost affair concentrating on
telephone canvassers and volunteers handing out pamphlets and
inspirational cassette tapes at shopping malls, said Walter Wood,
Robertson's statewide coordinator.
   The focus was on getting ``disenfranchised'' voters involved in
the political process, Wood said. It helped to have lists of
contributors to the Christian Broadcast Network, which Robertson
headed before starting his presidential campaign, he said.
   ``You go where your strength is,'' Wood said. ``It yielded us
some great benefits. Our sparks would start with the church and
then they would expand out. Get beyond the label of television
evangelist, and people perk up. He's got answers.''
   Other campaign coordinators vowed to turn things around as the
delegate selection process continues.
   ``These delegates aren't bound'' to Robertson, said Frank
Bickford, state coordinator for the Dole campaign. ``There will be
a chance to pick up delegates.''
   Clifford Groh, Bush's state coordinator, said that campaign
could have done better with an investment of ``time and effort,
maybe a little money, too.'' The Bush campaign put less than $1,000
into the caucus effort, he said.
   Bickford said the Dole campaign spent about $25,000. Wood did
not reveal the cost of Robertson's campaign, but said it was
considerably less than $25,000.
   The 2,020 precinct delegates will be winnowed later this month
to 400 district delegates, who then will choose 19 delegates to
attend the national convention in August.
   Allegiances can shift among the precinct and district delegates,
but GOP delegates to the national conventions have never abandoned
their chosen candidates, said Jim Crawford, chairman of the Alaska
Republican Party.
   Nearly 4,000 of the state's 55,000 registered Republicans turned
out for the caucuses, held throughout the state from Saturday to
Tuesday, Crawford said.
   ``There were a lot of strange faces,'' said Linda Shafer,
volunteer media coordinator for the party. ``There were people new
to the political process. You could tell by their political
platforms _ things like anti-marijuana and anti-abortion _ that
they were church folks.''
   Alaska, with only 19 of the 2,270 delegates at the national
Republican convention, has not been a high priority for the
candidates. None has made a campaign stop here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BankDeregulation     03-03 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Deregulation,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Approves Giving Banks New Securities Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation granting banks broad new
securities powers cleared its first big hurdle after two days of
contentious debate behind closed doors by the Senate Banking
Committee.
   The committee voted 18-2 late Wednesday night to repeal most of
the Glass-Steagall Act, which has separated commercial banking from
the securities business since the Depression.
   But the approval came only after Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
pushed through an unrelated amendment limiting the ability of banks
to expand into the insurance business.
   The bill faces a vote in the full Senate. Similar legislation
still must pass the House, where two powerful committee chairmen,
Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., and Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
have expressed great skepticism about expanding bank powers too
much.
   However, Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., said the lopsided
committee approval of the compromise package improves the chances
for its enactment.
   The vote ``means a good strong bill will not only pass the
Senate but will survive in conference,'' he said.
   The legislation, as orginally proposed by Proxmire and Sen. Jake
Garn of Utah, the panel's senior Republican, addressed only
securities powers.
   But, Dodd, who represents a state where insurance companies are
important employers, added a new element to the debate that
stalemated the committee for two days. He successfully pushed for
closing several loopholes that have permitted some banks to enter
insurance in states which authorize that.
   Under the bill adopted by the committee, bank holding companies
would be permitted to underwrite and sell mortgage-backed
securities, commercial paper and municipal revenue bonds
immediately after enactment of the bill. They would be allowed to
underwrite and sell corporate bonds and mutual funds six months
after enactment.
   However, a separate vote by Congress by April 1, 1991, would be
required before banks could deal in corporate stocks.
   Dodd said he did not obtain everything he wanted, but Paul A.
Equale, a lobbyist for the Independent Insurance Agents of America,
said, ``We think Chris Dodd did a terrific job.''
   Under the insurance compromise, bank holding companies could
deal in insurance in states that authorize it, provided those
activities are limited to that state. The bill imposes no
restrictions on state banks not owned by holding companies.
   Bank holding companies could not sell insurance through banks
located in another state. A loophole that had permitted some
national banks to deal in insurance would be closed.
   The committee left to the Senate as a whole a decision on
whether several states could agree to allow each others' banks to
engage in insurance activities across state borders.
   The Glass-Steagall Act was passed in the wake of the 1929 stock
market crash to preserve the safety of the banking system during
future market downturns. But banks have argued that the
internationalization of financial markets and the development of
new securities products have made the Glass-Steagall barriers
outdated.
   Voting for the compromise bill were Proxmire; Garn; Dodd; and
Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Donald W. Riegle, D-Mich.; Paul
Sarbanes, D-Md.; Alan Dixon, D-Ill.; James Sasser, D-Tenn.; Terry
Sanford, D-N.C.; Richard Shelby, D-Ala.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.;
Timothy Wirth, D-Colo.; John Heinz, R-Pa.; William Armstrong,
R-Colo.; Chic Hecht, R-Nev.; Christopher Bond, R-Mo.; John Chaffee,
R-R.I., and David Karnes, R-Neb.
   Voting against the bill were Sens. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., and
Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0202EST</FILEID>
