<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Rise In Morning Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures. PICKS up
4th graf pvs bgng, Before the ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar continued to rise against the
Japanese yen after opening above the 129-yen barrier, and stock
prices temporarily topped pre-crash levels before closing lower in
Tokyo trading Thursday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues closed after moderate trading at 25,596.31 points,
down 86.51 points or 0.34 percent from Wednesday's close.
   The dollar closed at 129.30 yen, up 0.83 yen from Wednesday's
close of 128.47. The dollar opened at 129.05.
   Before the October stock crash, the Nikkei index stood at
25,746.56 points.
   ``Basically we saw a bit of a fall off in early morning
trading,'' said Paul Warren of the investment house Salomon
Brothers. ``But the market has neatly switched to new areas, like
electronics and utilities, which is keeping the momentum going.''
   Warren said he expected the market to return to its all-time
high over the next two or three months.
   A currency dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke
on condition of anonymity, said the dollar's strength was due
partly to a Japanese news report that a senior U.S. monetary
official in Washington had suggested the United States would
tolerate a considerable rise in the value of the dollar if the
nation's trade deficit kept improving.
   The dollar had traded below 129 yen in Tokyo since Feb. 23.
</TEXT>
