<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0441EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CountryClubSlurs     03-03 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Country Club Slurs,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Demands Apology For Alleged Country Club Slurs</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: note objectionable language in 5th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ELLICOT CITY, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP is moving a convention and
demanding an apology from a popular country club after a telephone
recording during which the club's manager allegedly made racial
slurs.
   The comments were recorded on the telephone answering machine of
Howard County NAACP member Sherman Howell, who had phoned the Turf
Valley Country Club last week to ask why it seemed no black waiters
and waitresses worked there.
   The Washington Post obtained a copy of the tape, and included
comments from the recording in an article in today's editions.
   According to the tape, a man identifying himself as club manager
Fred Grimmell returned the call, and left a short message on
Howell's answering machine. But then after a click, the voice
continued in a conversation with two other people and made several
racial slurs, the Post said.
   At one point, the voice on the tape said: ``This nigger, I am
going to put him against the wall ... He should say, `This is
Sherman Nigger.' Yo nigger, yo bub.'' As the man who had identified
himself as Grimmell and an unidentified woman discussed whether
Howell had ever visited the club's restaurant, a third voice said,
``Well, we don't like niggers. ... I'm discriminated because all
the niggers get all the jobs.''
   A black Washington Post reporter then went to interview
Grimmell, and heard another racial slur from behind closed doors
about a person ``that wants to grill me.''
   Later, the Post said, Grimmell told the reporter: ``I have no
time to talk to you at all. Here's the door, sweetheart. Our
conversation is over.''
   The Howard County NAACP chapter, which had planned to hold its
spring ``Freedom Fund'' meeting at the club on March 24, is moving
it elsewhere.
   Maryland NAACP President Rev. John Wright, at a news conference
Wednesday, said his organization is demanding Grimmell's immediate
resignation and an apology. The NAACP is also considering picketing
and demonstrations if the issue is not resolved quickly, Wright
said.
   ``This is 1988 and we have this type of statements... This is
blatant, outright racism,'' said Wright.
   Louis Mangoine, son of club owner Nick Mangione, said he would
investigate the complaints about Grimmell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
