<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0403EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson-Libel     03-03 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-Libel,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Wants To End Legal Fight, But Denies He Avoided Combat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GOP presidential candidate Pat Robertson isn't
retreating from his firm denial of charges he avoided combat in
Korea although he wants to end a legal battle with a former
congressman who made them.
   Robertson and his lawyer have formally announced plans to ask a
federal judge to dismiss the $35 million lawsuit against Rep. Paul
N. McCloskey Jr., R-Calif., to avoid beginning a three-week trial
on Super Tuesday.
   Going to trial next Tuesday means Robertson ``is being asked to
sacrifice his presidential campaign in order to vindicate his
personal honor,'' attorney Douglas Rigler told reporters Wednesday.
   ``We think that's extraordinarily unfair,'' Rigler said,
referring to U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green's refusal to
postpone the trial date until June 20, when the primary season has
ended.
   The decision to seek dismissal of the suit ``does not in any way
indicate he is unwilling to confront Mr. McCloskey or that he shies
away from any judicial determination of the merits of the
charges,'' Rigler said.
   ``Robertson does not intend to back away at any time from his
denial of the charges that Mr. McCloskey made,'' Rigler added.
   McCloskey, meanwhile, said Robertson is ``chickening out of the
trial just like he chickened out 37 years ago.''
   The former congressman's lawyer, George Lehner, said he would
oppose Robertson's motion to dismiss the lawsuit and request to
proceed with the trial on Tuesday.
   ``I think the truth ought to be told,'' McCloskey said. ``I
don't know any better place to get the truth than in the courtroom.
He invoked the process, he ought to go through with it.''
   McCloskey was sued in 1986 following publication of his charges
that Robertson called his father, the late Sen. A. Willis
Robertson, D-Va., from Japan to get out of combat in the Korean War.
   McCloskey, who was on the troop ship from which Robertson and
five other Marine officers were removed for special training, says
the former television evangelist later was the ``liquor officer''
to a rear-echelon unit in Korea.
   Rigler distributed a statement from Robertson saying ``the
pretrial process has already demonstrated the total falsity of Mr.
McCloskey's statements about me.''
   ``Not one of his witnesss ever heard me make such a call or
state that I had made it. The official records of the Marine Corps
fully supported my denial of ever having sought or received special
treatment,'' Robertson's statement said.
   A number of former Marines who were also aboard the USS
Breckinridge in 1951 have supported various parts of McCloskey's
story.
   A report on the case prepared by Rigler's office charged that
the pre-trial testimony of McCloskey's `` handful of volunteer
witnesses has been discredited. Mr. McCloskey has been reduced to
an admission that his charges constitute merely his `opinions' and
`impressions.'''
   By successfully opposing the motion to postpone the trial, ``Mr.
McCloskey is holding Mr. Robertson hostage,'' Rigler said.
``McCloskey knows that the March 8 date is impossible.''
   ``That is a terrible choice and I can't understand why a
respected judge did it,'' Rigler said.
   In her Jan. 6 order denying Robertson's motion, Green noted that
he filed the lawsuit and launched his candidacy ``at the same
time.''
   ``That these ventures might somehow come into conflct is a risk
that plaintiff assumed when he began them,'' the judge wrote.
   Under federal rules of civil procedure, the judge could order
Robertson to pay McCloskey's court costs and possibly legal fees.
   Rigler acknowledged that ``it is quite possible that Mr.
Robertson will be asked to pay a substantial amount of court
costs'' to cover the expense of taking depositions from more than
50 witnesses.
   But Rigler said he would be likely to appeal a large award.
   Lehner said he would ask the judge to order payment of
McCloskey's court costs and lawyers fees, which total more than
$400,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0046 </DOCNO>
