<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Economy     03-03 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Economy,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama's Economy Become Focus Of Noriega Foes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's hard-pressed economy has
become the focus of those trying to end the military rule of Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle has joined other Noriega
foes in calling for fiscal actions to keep up pressure on the
government.
   Delvalle, who is in hiding, said in a videotape that the
political crisis in Panama would make it impossible for the nation
to get new loans from international agencies, and described the
country as ``totally bankrupt.''
   Nine months of political unrest already have eroded Panama's
service-oriented economy, which is particularly vulnerable to a
loss of trust and confidence caused by political upheaval.
   In addition, financial experts say billions of dollars in bank
deposits are being withdrawan from Panama, destablizing it as a
financial center.
   Manuel Solis Palma, installed last week to replace Delvalle,
charged that the United States ``wants to asphyxiate the Panamanian
people economically, snatching away the salt and water of our
existence.''
   In a speech Tuesday, Solis Palma denounced attempts to promote
``sanctions, pressure out of proportion (and) unjust recrimination
against a people who has honored its commitments .... We will
struggle without pause or truce for our survival.''
   Delvalle pointed to the deteriorating economic situation in his
unsuccessful attempt Feb. 25 to dismiss Noriega as chief of the
15,000-member Defense Forces of Panama, which include both the
military and police.
   ``The reasons that might take us to fiscal and economic
imbalance and that might push thousands of Panamanians to
unemployment, misery and despair cannot persist,'' Delvalle said in
announcing the general's dismissal.
   Noriega rallied his officer corps and loyalist politicians, and
the next day Delvalle had been replace and in hiding.
   The backbone of Panama's economy is formed by banks, insurance
companies, a large duty-free zone, the Panama Canal and
well-stocked retail and wholesale stores that attract buyers from
throughout Latin America.
   In New York, lawyers for Delvalle sued in federal court
Wednesday to block a bank from transferring an estimated $10
million to the Noriega regime. The lawyers later dropped the
lawsuit against Republic National Bank of New York after the bank
agreed to transfer the money to the U.S. Federal Reserve Bank.
   On Tuesday, Delvalle froze all Panamanian assets outside the
country. The United States, which still recognizes Delvalle as
president, supported the action. State Department spokewoman
Phyllis Oakley called it ``the legitimate action of the
constitutional government.''
   Panama's commercial bank debt is $2 billion and the total debt
for banks and government agencies is $5.5 billion, said a banking
source in the United States who spoke on condition of anonymity. He
said about $85 million in interest and principal is due to banks
and bond holders by March 31.
   The World Bank said Panama's total foreign debt was $4.8 billion
at the end of 1986, the latest year for which figures are
available. The debt, in a nation of 2.2 million people, is one of
the world's highest per capita.
   An ongoing general strike to protest Noriega's rule that began
Monday has had particular impact on construction and industrial
activity.
   Among the actions reported under consideration in the United
States is withholding payments from Panama Canal activities.
   The U.S. Commerce Department said Panama's gross income from the
canal in 1986 was $532 million. Revenue figures were not available
for last year, but the number of ships passing through the waterway
was said to be up slightly. evenue from the canal represents 10
percent of Panama's gross national product.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0453EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     03-03 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Touts Ideas For Oil Industry and Agriculture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says the
United States' flagging petroleum industry needs drilling
incentives rather than an oil import tax, while agriculture is
starting to rebound because of the Reagan administration's farm
policy.
   Talking with reporters after a rally at Louisiana State
University on Wednesday, Bush, a former oilman, said making changes
that will benefit the oil industry would enhance national security.
   ``The answer has to be national security and not economics. The
answer has got to be there is no security for this country with
increasing dependence on foreign oil. You can't make the case
simply on economics,'' he said.
   In addition to providing drilling incentives, Congress should
repeal the windfall profits tax, passed during the late 1970s when
the oil industry was deregulated, while petroleum prices are down
and do away with controls on natural gas, Bush said.
   ``I think if you take the case to the people in the fall for
this, I think it can get done,'' Bush said.
   The vice president was asked about suggestions by rival Bob Dole
that Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega was on the CIA
payroll during Bush's tenure as chief of the spy agency.
   ``He says he made all the decisions at the CIA,'' Dole said at a
news conference in New Orleans. ``What were they? Was Noriega on
the payroll when he was CIA director?''
   Dole, asked if he were accusing Bush of having knowledge of
Noriega's alleged drug trafficking, said: ``All I'm saying is that
Bob Dole said no to drugs, no to thugs, no to Noriega.''
   To that, Bush replied: ``I find it amazing that a United States
senator will talk about CIA matters. I took an oath of office to
protect sources and methods of intelligence and I would never
discuss anything I was doing at the CIA that would affect the
national security.
   ``There has just been one charge after another in this campaign
and I have just decided not to respond to Mr. Dole's charges.''
   On another matter, Bush said Reagan administration farm policy
was leading to a recovery in agriculture.
   ``The cattle people are doing much better now. Beef prices are
up. Hog prices are up. Don't fool with the farm bill,'' he said.
   Bush said he wanted to encourage foreign markets to buy more
American agricultural products, rather than enact protectionist
legislation.
   ``If we go the protection route, they'll go the protection
route,'' he said.
   In his speech before about 1,000 people, Bush said wins in
Louisiana and the other 19 states in next Tuesday's Super Tuesday
primary could translate into the Republican presidential nomination.
   ``If I do well in Louisiana and that's an indicator of doing
well in my home state of Texas and across to Florida, where I came
from this morning, I am absolutely convinced that I will be the
next president of the United States,'' Bush said.
   Rep. Richard Baker, who is serving as Bush's state campaign
chairman, told reporters that he was confident that the vice
president would win at least five of the state's eight
congressional districts.
   ``We will take a majority of the congressional districts and the
ones we take won't be close,'' he said.
   During Bush's speech, a group of about six protesters,
describing themselves as members of the Progressive Student
Network, raised a banner saying: ``Hey Bush, tell us about Contra
drug running.'' A man sporting a Bush campaign button reached up
and tore part of the banner down, drawing applause from other
supporters.
   The protesters also briefly chanted: ``Tell us about Contra
aid,'' also in reference to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   At the end of his speech, Bush pointed to one of the protesters
and said, ``Give that man a little jambalaya. He sounds starved to
death.''
   Bush then shed his suit coat and donned a white apron and served
jambalaya _ a spicy Cajun rice dish with sausage and chicken _ to
some of those in attendance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
