<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Religion-Pornography     03-03 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion-Pornography,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swaggart Far From Only Minister Addicted To Pornography, Group
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Swaggart will need more than counseling
and a three-month suspension from the ministry to overcome his
attraction to pornography, says a psychologist.
   ``No matter how much he prays to God, no matter how sincere, it
won't change him unless he seeks more extensive therapy,'' Victor
Cline said Wednesday at a gathering of the Religious Alliance
Against Pornography.
   Cline, a professor at the University of Utah, described an
effective treatment as one that treats pornography addicts in much
the same way as Alcoholics Anonymous treats alcoholics _ with a
24-hour-a-day support system.
   Swaggart last week confessed to unspecified sins. He reportedly
paid a prostitute to pose naked numerous times over a period of
about a year.
   Assemblies of God church officials in Louisiana have recommended
barring Swaggart from preaching for three months, but officials
asked for reconsideration after receiving hundreds of calls
protesting the penalty as too lenient.
   Allliance chairman Jerry Kirk estimated that between a dozen and
two dozen of the 5,000 or so ministers he has talked to in his
travels for the alliance are hooked on pornography.
   ``In my travels, I've had pastors confess to me their addiction,
and it truly is an addiction,'' alliance chairman Jerry Kirk said
at a news conference during a break in the seminar.
   About 400 members of the alliance gathered at a Washington hotel
for a seminar on how to battle pornography.
   The Religious Alliance Against Pornography was formed in July
1986 to battle child pornography and obscenity not protected by the
First Amendment to the Constitution.
</TEXT>
