<DOCNO> AP880303-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0510EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SniperAttack     03-03 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sniper Attack,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Records Show Suspect Had Been In Mental Instiution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former mental patient opened fire
with two six-shooters near the Alamo, shooting four people at
random and trading shots with police before he was wounded and
taken into custody, authorities said.
   Marvin Duncan, 55, shot in the left thigh by police, was charged
with six counts of attempted capital murder, police spokesman Sgt.
Paul Buske said. Bond was set at $1.5 million.
   The most seriously wounded victim, Deborah Reyes, 29, was shot
in the chest and stomach and was in critical condition at Brooke
Army Medical Center late Wednesday, said hospital spokesman Sgt.
William Banks.
   The three others, shot at point-blank range, were not injured
seriously, officials said.
   Witnesses said the shooting, which took place in the week that
marks the 152nd anniversary of the fall of the mission to Mexican
troops, resembled something from a movie.
   ``All hell broke loose,'' said Todd Tarble, 20, who was waiting
for a bus about three blocks from the Alamo when the shooting began.
   ``He had two guns in his hands. I've never seen anything like
that. The guy was acting like John Wayne. This guy was crazy,''
Tarble said.
   Duncan was listed in good condition at Medical Center Hospital.
   Court records show Duncan was placed in Rusk State Hospital for
the mentally or criminally insane in October 1980 after being found
incompetent to stand trial on an attempted murder charge.
   He was released in March 1981 to stand trial, but Bexar County
prosecutors dismissed the charge in favor of a civil commitment to
San Antonio State Hospital. The records did not indicate Duncan's
status at the state hospital.
   Duncan took a taxicab downtown about 9 a.m. Wednesday, and about
three blocks from the Alamo he pulled out two .357-caliber Magnum
revolvers and began shooting from inside the cab, got out and
continued firing, authorities said.
   Taxi driver Frank Esquivel, 42, jumped from the cab when the
shooting started. He said the man said nothing during the four-mile
ride. ``I have no idea what set him off,'' he said.
   Homicide Lt. Albert Ortiz said the gunman was methodical in his
shooting.
   ``From the time he was picked up at his residence, throughout
the shooting he remained calm and his actions were deliberate, not
hurried,'' Ortiz said.
   Duncan has been arrested numerous times since 1973 on charges
including assaults and an attempted murder charge, said Police
Chief William O. Gibson.
   ``As to why the suspect began shooting, we don't know why, with
the exception that he wanted to gain some attention,'' Gibson said.
   As passers-by dived for cover, officer Donald Kawazoe, on his
way to work, saw the man and ordered him to stop.
   The two traded shots and the gunman fled and confronted Park
Ranger Bennie Burley. They also exchanged gunfire before the gunman
was arrested, Gibson said, but could not say which officer shot
Duncan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0539EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     03-03 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Prepares For Super Tuesday With Eight-State Television
Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson will begin $100,000 worth
of TV ads in the crucial campaign days before Super Tuesday and has
borrowed $410,000 to keep his campaign going until after that
contest, his campaign manager says.
   The TV buy, the largest to date for Jackson's cash-poor
campaign, will target Alabama, Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi,
North Carolina, South Carolina, Texas and Virginia, said campaign
manager Gerald Austin.
   The ads start Friday.
   Austin said the loan, for expenses other than the ads in those
eight Super Tuesday states, was borrowed from Adams Bank in
Washington two weeks ago and will be paid back March 18.
   Austin made the comments aboard Jackson's plane as it
hopscotched across five southern states Wednesday.
   In his bid to woo Southern whites and build on the white support
he has won this year in Iowa, Maine, Minnesota, New Hampshire and
Vermont, Jackson picked up the endorsement Wednesday of Jim
Hightower, the popular agriculture commissioner of Texas.
   Jackson was welcomed to Selma, Ala., by the white mayor who had
Martin Luther King Jr. and other civil rights activists arrested
more than three decades ago.
   Austin said Jackson's success on Super Tuesday depends on
getting out the black vote, attaining close to 10 percent of the
white vote and the unknown potential of GOP candidate Pat
Robertson, the former TV evangelist, to pull Demoratic voters into
the Republican primaries.
   The campign will spend about $350,000 on the Super Tuesday
contests, Austin said, which is far less than the $3 million-plus
some Democratic competitors are expected to shell out.
   Austin would not say how many of the 1,307 Super Tuesday
delegates he thinks Jackson can get, but said the goal is to win
more than the 222 Jackson won in his 1984 race in those states.
   In Selma, Jackson received the key to the city from Mayor Joe
Smitherman, who was mayor in 1965 when state troopers forcefully
stopped civil rights marchers from crossing the Alabama River
bridge that Jackson's motorcade drove across on Wednesday.
   ``I had Dr. King arrested,'' Smitherman said. ``The Voting
Rights Act was right. We were wrong. We've admitted that.''
   Jackson called Smitherman's reception a sign of the ``New
South.''
   ``People grow,'' he said. ``We have a new challenge now. He
fought it in '65 and he lost. Now we have a common battle.''
   In the Texas state capitol, Hightower said Jackson speaks to
``an ignored majority of Americans whose lives have been frustrated
or flattened by the economic policies of recent years.''
   Jackson is appealing to whites with a message of ``economic
common ground'' that binds the underprivileged of all races.
   Jackson's message includes calls for a higher minimum wage,
comparable worth pay for women, child care and housing programs.
   He often mentions the plight of hard-hit textile workers, saying
he ``reluctantly'' supports congressional legislation to limit
textile imports because of the ``dire emergency'' of the South's
once-thriving industry.
   He encounters mixed reactions from whites.
   He began Wednesday in his home state of South Carolina, arriving
just after dawn with a troop of reporters in tow, for a breakfast
of grits, biscuits and eggs at Tom Trantham's dairy farm.
   Trantham and three white neighbors talked farm policy with the
presidential contender and told reporters how Jackson supported
them during the 1986 drought and helped unload hay brought in from
other states.
   But when asked if they supported him for president, they were
noncommital.
   ``I'm not supporting anybody at this point,'' said Michael Sly,
a farmer organizer.
</TEXT>
