<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gephardt     03-03 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Says He'd Consider Carter, Ford as Envoys to the Middle
East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt says he would consider
former presidents Jimmy Carter and Gerald Ford to serve as special
envoys to the Middle East if he is elected president.
   In a meeting with St. Louis Post-Dispatch editorial writers,
while on a swing through his home state Wednesday, Gephardt said he
had discussed the idea with Carter on Tuesday when he stopped in
Plains, Ga.
   ``We talked about it,'' Gephardt said. ``He said he was ready,
willing and able to do anything asked by a future president.''
   Elsewhere, Gephardt's home-turf message was concentrated on the
country's foreign trade policy. He told the St. Louis Board of
Aldermen that he would seek policies that reduce the trade deficit
by enabling U.S. businesses to compete fairly in world markets.
   ``How do you tell people who are out of work that the trade
deficit is a fact of life?'' Gephardt asked. ``I don't accept the
deficit and I don't think you do either. We have the power to make
the nation better than it was before. This is your fight too.''
   Gephardt, called for new policies that ``ask trading partners to
treat us as fairly as we treat them.''
   Without getting specific, Gephardt said it was time for the
government to enact trade policies that ``take the heat of unfair
foreign competition off those who farm our land, forge our steel
and build our cars.''
   Gephardt said he did not agree with a statement by President
Reagan that the trade deficit is a ``sign of strength.'' Nor, he
said, did he agree with the attitude that the trade deficit ``is a
fact of life.''
   Gephardt also touched on agricultural issues in his speech.
   ``The agriculture program doesn't make sense,'' he said. ``Isn't
it time we had an agriculture program in this country that let the
farmers vote and let the farmers decide what we're going to do?''
   Gephardt began a two-day swing through his home state Wednesday
for a series of speeches and four fundraisers six days before
Missouri's ``Super Tuesday'' primary.
   Saying ``My, how good it is to be home,'' Gephardt brought his
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination to the place
where he got his start in politics.
   After the address in the St. Louis City Hall chambers where he
began his political career, Gephardt traveled to Springfield for a
campaign fundraising reception. He returned to St. Louis for a
fundraiser Wednesday night before flying to Kansas City.
   Gephardt arrived in Springfield the day after the Springfield
News-Leader endorsed Sen. Paul Simon in the race for the Democratic
nomination.
   Gephardt, who was a St. Louis alderman from 1971 to 1976, used
the economic rebirth of the city during those years as an example
for his promise to return economic prosperity to those who work in
the nation's factories, farms and steel mills.
   ``I began my career right here in this room when this was a city
with many difficulties and troubles,'' Gephardt said. ``A lot of
people were giving up on St. Louis. They said the future was
elsewhere. But we didn't believe that. We did what needed to be
done to make St. Louis a success story.''
   Sam Hamra, a Springfield attorney and finance chairman for the
Gephardt campaign in Missouri, said $25,000 was raised at the
event. During the day $425,000 was raised, bringing the
campaign-long total in Missouri to nearly $2 million, said S. Lee
Kling, Gephardt's campaign treasurer.
</TEXT>
