<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy, Panetta Introduce Anti-Hunger Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Democratic proposal by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy would pump an extra $266 million into food stamps and other
government emergency food programs.
   ``We could obviously do more, but we cannot afford to do less,''
Kennedy said Wednesday in introducing the measure.
   The Massachusetts Democrat, chairman of the Senate Labor and
Human Resources Committee, said the bill would increase funding for
federal programs for food stamps, school breakfasts, child care
food and summer food service.
   Kennedy said domestic hunger had been largely eradicated by the
late 1970s, but that the recession of the early 1980s, coupled with
sharp cuts in social programs under the Reagan administration, has
brought it back at record levels.
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said the question of hunger is ``a
moral issue'' and ``a test of America's conscience.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., introduced companion legislation in
the House.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bank Profits in 1987 Lowest Since Depression</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks recorded their least profitable year
since the Great Depression in 1987, but a top federal regulator
says he's hopeful about the future.
   The nation's federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7
billion last year on assets of $3 trillion, down from $17.5 billion
earnings in 1986, said L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp.
   That amounted to a return on assets of only 0.13 percent last
year and was the lowest level since the FDIC, which insures
deposits of up to $100,000, was established in 1934.
   The year-to-year drop in earnings was due entirely to large
banks adding to reserves to cover anticipated losses on loans to
Third World countries, Seidman said. Nine of the 10 largest banks
and 17 of the 25 largest reported a loss for 1987.
   ``Absent the extraordinary reserving for (developing country)
loans ... net income would have been roughly equal to 1986's
level,'' Seidman said Wednesday in the FDIC's bank profile for the
fourth quarter of 1987.
   Seidman said he believed there was a good chance that banks
could avoid further large additions to reserves for bad Third World
loans and said, ``The outlook for 1988 is cautiously optimistic.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Army Stops Random Drug Testing of Civilians, But Seeks Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army says it has stopped random drug
testing for civilian workers to comply with a court ruling, but was
asking the Justice Department to appeal the judgment.
   The service, in a brief statement, said Wednesday it would limit
its civilian drug testing for the time being to those instances in
which ``there is a reasonable suspicion that a specific employee is
under the influence of drugs while on duty.''
   ``The Army has asked the Department of Justice to appeal the
ruling,'' the service said in its statement. ``The Army has also
requested that Justice ask for a stay of the judge's order during
the appeal process.''
   Testing on a random basis, however, has been halted for now, the
service added.
   The move follows a decision in U.S. District Court in Washington
on Tuesday in which a judge ruled that random drug testing amounted
to an unreasonable search prohibited by the Constitution.
</TEXT>
