<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Goldwater     03-03 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Goldwater,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goldwater Stumps South For Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush brought out a
campaign weapon as he made a swing through this crucial Super
Tuesday state _ former Arizona Sen. Barry Goldwater.
   Supporters at Miami International Airport clapped and cheered as
Goldwater picked his way slowly down the ramp of Air Force Two.
Goldwater campaigned with Bush throughout South Florida and in
Tampa as Bush began a five-state Southern swing.
   The former Arizona senator, a hero to conservatives, campaigned
for Bush last month in the final days before the New Hampshire
primary, which the vice president won handily.
   Tanned and appearing healthy, although walking with a cane,
Goldwater praised Bush's experience and dedication during brief
remarks at campaign stops. Bush said he had discussed issues and
gotten advice from Goldwater during the flight from Washington to
Florida.
   With Bush considered strong in most of the South, delegate-rich
Florida has been targeted by his rivals, and Bush is fighting to
keep them from making inroads.
   ``Barry Goldwater is the grand old man of the Republican Party,
the true statesman for American conservatives,'' said Ken Wright,
Bush's Florida campaign director.
   Wright said he believed Goldwater's help could be important in
luring some of the Florida conservatives who have been leaning
toward Pat Robertson, who has shown strong organization in some
parts of the state.
   Wright also pointed to Florida's large share of senior citizens.
   ``Many of these people probably voted for Barry Goldwater,''
Wright said, referring to Goldwater's 1964 GOP presidential bid.
   Wright said Goldwater's visit shows the former senator's
commitment to Bush.
   ``I think he (Goldwater) did it out of long friendship and
belief that the vice president can carry on the conservative
ideals,'' Wright said. ``It's not like you have somebody who's
working for you because he wants something in return. It's not like
he wants to be secretary of defense.''
   Bush campaign officials weren't sure whether Goldwater would do
any more campaigning in the South.
</TEXT>
