<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SweepstakesLosers     03-03 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweepstakes Losers,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Fooled By $2 Million Lure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple say they feel foolish that they
bought two new cars and planned to quit their jobs after concluding
they had won a $2 million in a mail-order company sweepstakes.
   Kathy and Dale Work said they still hope that they have won the
money from United States Purchasing Exchange of Los Angeles.
   ``I know they claim we haven't won anything, but I still have
faith in that company, that they're going to come across for us,''
Mrs. Work, of suburban Stoney Ridge, said Wednesday.
   ``I guess it seems like we're a couple of country hicks,'' she
said. ``We went out and bought a new pickup truck and a new car.
We'd made all kinds of plans. I don't know what we're going to do
now.''
   David Carlin of Loeb & Loeb, a New York law firm representing
USPE, said the company thinks someone is sending out fake contest
information to USPE contestants, and that it was unlikely the Works
would get any money.
   The U.S. Postal Service said it has received complaints about
the company and forwarded them to the Federal Trade Commission for
investigation.
   A man who answered USPE's telephone said the sweepstakes is
still running and Mrs. Work is one of thousands who won a chance at
the $2 million-plus top prize. He would not give his name and would
not answer other questions.
   Mrs. Work is not the first to be confused by the sweepstakes.
Debra Long of Pearl City, Mich., told reporters she recently quit
her job and vacationed in Las Vegas, Nev., before learning she had
not won $1.7 million, as she thought.
   Michael Flitcraft, a truck driver from Chardon, said he thought
he had won the contest after receiving a certified letter from the
company on Monday.
   Carlin said Miss Long apparently was the victims of a hoax. He
said she reported receiving a certified notification letter from
USPE and confirmed her winnings with a telephone call to USPE on
Feb. 15, Presidents' Day.
   ``The company does not notify winners by certified mail, the
company's offices were closed on Presidents' Day, the company does
not request bank account numbers from winners nor does it require
the other information Miss Long claims was requested of her,'' he
said.
   Carlin said the company referred the matter involving Miss Long
to the FBI.
   Dee Ellison of the Washington, D.C., office of the Federal Trade
Commission declined comment on whether the agency is investigating
the company, but she said the FTC has received complaints about the
company.
   Mrs. Work said she received a letter from the company in October
that read: ``We are pleased to inform you that you have been
designated to receive certified bank checks from the United States
Purchasing Exchange for $1,894,876 ... your winnings in our
multimillion dollar sweepstakes when you are the grand prize
winner.''
   A few weeks later, Mrs. Work got another letter saying that her
winnings stood at $2,024,464. Then she received what she thought
were two checks, one for $2 million and one for $24,000.
   She was asked to endorse them and send them back to the company
along with her Social Security and bank account numbers. At that
point, the Works thought they were millionaires.
   However, the mailing said, ``Certified bank check for this
amount ... will be drawn and issued to Kathy Work upon verification
that the Kathy Work entry has been selected by the independent
judging organization as the prize-winner in accordance to the rules
and regulations set forth and established.''
   Carlin said the sweepstakes does not close until Dec. 31.
   Mrs. Work said she'd planned to close the beauty salon she runs
out of her home and her husband considered quitting his job when
they thought they had won. Work works at Manville Corp. in
Waterville, about 15 miles southwest of Toledo.
</TEXT>
