<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BritishStocks     03-03 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-British Stocks,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Share Prices Higher In Early London Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose in early London trading today as
investors continued buying leading stocks.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100 index was up 16.60 points
at 1,825.3 at 10 a.m.
   When the market officially opened at 9 a.m., the index was up
12.8 points at 1,821.5.
   Dealers said they saw a repeat of Wednesday's buying interest in
early trading.
   The buying helped reinforce hopes that the FT-SE 100 index will
consolidate above the 1,800 point level in the run up to Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's March 15 budget statement.
   On Wednesday the FT-SE 100 broke through the barrier for the
first time since Jan. 18 to close up 26.8 points at 1808.7.
   The early rise in London today followed small gains in New York
Wednesday, where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 0.83 to
2,071.29, and a fall in Tokyo overnight, where the Nikkei index
fell 86.51 to 25,596.31.
</TEXT>
