<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Little Changed, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was little changed against most
major currencies in moderate European trading early today. Gold
prices fell.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar would trade within a
narrow range before the March 17 release of the latest U.S.
merchandise trade figures.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 129.30 yen from 128.47
yen. Later, in London, it eased to 129.27 yen. A Tokyo dealer said
the dollar rallied after a news report said a senior U.S.
government official had suggested the Reagan administration was
willing to allow a substantial rise in the U.S. currency.
   In London, the British pound edged down to 1.7677 from 1.7680
late Wednesday.
   Other rates at mid-morning, compared with rates late Wednesday:
   --1.6955 West German marks, up from 1.6945
   --1.4025 Swiss francs, up from 1.4005
   --5.7365 French francs, up from 5.7345
   --1.9026 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9013
   --1,248.90 Italian lire, up from 1,247.00
   --1.2555 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2558
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.70 a troy ounce, up
from $429.50 late Wednesday, but fell back slightly at mid-morning
today, when the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $429.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.50, down from $429.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to a closing bid of $433.96,
down from $434.95 bid late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion fell in London to a bid price of $6.21 a troy
ounce, down from $6.24 bid late Wednesday.
