<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HealthCare     03-03 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Health Care,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mass. House Passes Universal Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' first-in-the-nation
proposal to provide health insurance to all Massachusetts residents
won House approval and was sent back to the state Senate, which
passed a similar bill last session.
   The House approved the $1 billion measure late Wednesday night
by a 100-53 vote after three days of debate, with opposition
focusing on the plan's potential cost.
   House Minority Leader Steven Pierce, a Republican, said the bill
``reminds me of the old, hopefully gone, consumer ripoff when
people door-to-door sold home improvements.''
   ``They said sign on the dotted line and if you have any problems
I'll take care of them,'' he said. ``Everything wasn't all right,
but once the consumer realized the problems, it was too late.''
   ``I think in the end we are going to have a good bill,'' said
Senate Ways and Means Chairman Patricia McGovern, a Democrat and
the key proponent in the Senate. ``The thing that pleases me is
that we begin the process probably very much in agreement.''
   A bill adopted by the Senate late in the 1987 session served as
the outline for the House proposal.
   Dukakis was informed of the House vote late Wednesday while
campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination in Texas.
   ``The Massachusetts House has committed itself to health
security for every man, woman and child in the Commonwealth and I
congratulate (the leadership) and all the members on this historic
action,'' Dukakis said in statement.
   The governor said he hoped the Senate would move expeditiously
on the bill. ``I continue to hope the work can be completed in
mid-March,'' he said.
   While the bill outlines a four-year plan for phasing in
universal health care coverage in Massachusetts, it wasn't until
Wednesday that lawmakers committed themselves to a specific state
financing level beyond the bill's $125 million first-year cost.
   The price tag they set as the maximum the state would pay for
three years, when added to the lowest estimate for the remaining
year, would put the tab for health care for all in Massachusetts at
$1.1 billion.
   The measure would make health insurance available to all
residents, notably the estimated 600,000 now uninsured, by 1992.
   Employers who did not provide health insurance would be required
to pay an unemployment tax surcharge to the state. Businesses
providing insurance for the first time would be entitled to tax
credits.
   The House, unlike the Senate, voted to exempt businesses with
nine or fewer full-time employees from mandatory coverage. McGovern
said Wednesday night her chamber would consider the exemption.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
