<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Indians     03-03 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Indians,0602</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Plan Encourages Return of Nicaragua's Indians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indians who fled into exile to escape
war and government persecution are returning to their homes on the
Caribbean coast now that hostilities in the region have largely
ceased, a U.N. official said.
   ``The number of returning Indians is increasing dramatically,''
Serge Ducasse, head of the Office of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees in Managua, said in an interview Wednesday.
   Tens of thousands of Miskito, Rama and Sumo Indians left their
tribal homelands beginning in 1981 after the leftist Sandinista
government tried to impose Marxism in the area and said it would
move them to relocation camps.
   The government said then that relocation was necessary because
it had discovered a rebel plot that called for the killing of
Sandinista authorities and Indians who collaborate with the
government.
   Many of the Indians crossed the Rio Coco and sought refuge in
Honduras rather than move to relocation camps. Thousands took up
arms, creating rebel movements that, like the larger Nicaraguan
Resistance, received U.S. aid.
   Now, the Sandinistas have acknowledged mistakes in their
treatment of the Indians and have agreed to work with them to set
up a regional government along the 75-mile seaboard known as the
Mosquito Coast.
   Ducasse said that in 1986, the U.N. agency helped about 2,000
Indians return from Honduran refugee camps to the coast, which is
isolated from most of Nicaragua's 3.1 million people by tradition
and a spine of rugged mountains.
   Last year, 3,206 Indians returned and in the first two months
this year 1,502 returned, said Ducasse.
   Thousands of others returned on their own, without official help.
   ``I think it's the impact of the peace plan,'' Ducasse said.
   A regional peace plan signed in August by Nicaragua, Guatemala,
El Salvador, Honduras, and Costa Rica calls for the countries to
aid the return of refugees. Tens of thousands of people have fled
civil strife in Guatemala, El Salvador and Nicaragua. The peace
plan also calls for democratic reforms, cease-fires and political
amnesties.
   Fighting continues in Nicaragua despite government talks with
the Contra rebels, who began their insurgency in November 1981. But
the Sandinistas have succeeded in breaking up the Indian rebel
movements.
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge traveled to the coastal city of
Puerto Cabezas in October to accept the amnesty request of Indian
rebel leader Uriel Vanegas and 400 of his troops.
   Borge now is negotiating with another Indian leader, Brooklyn
Rivera.
   The Caribbean coast is both economically and strategically
important for the Sandinistas. Its ports are used to receive Soviet
arms shipments and East bloc supplies, and it is considered most
vulnerable to a foreign invasion.
   The area was given little attention by Nicaraguan governments
until the Sandinistas came to power in July 1979. It was controlled
by the British until the last century and some of the inhabitants
still speak English, along with their own dialects, rather than
Spanish.
   A majority of the 180,000 or so Indians are Protestants, while
the rest of the nation is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
   ``There is relative calm in the zone now,'' Ducasse said.
   But thousands of non-Indian refugees from Nicaragua still live
in makeshift camps in Honduras.
   Ducasse said that just 136 non-Indian Nicaraguans returned last
year from refugee camps in Honduras.
   ``It will be slow for them to come back,'' Ducasse said. ``Most
of them left conflict zones or to avoid (compulsory) military
service.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0707EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NATORdp5thLd-1stAdd a0546   03-03 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO Rdp 5th Ld-1st Add, a0546,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BRUSSELS: we're free.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Following Reagan's four-minute statement before reporters,
Secretary of State George P. Shultz hailed the two-day summit.
``Here was freedom on display,'' he said. ``It was a very moving
experience.''
   The secretary seemed fatigued from his recent Middle East
peacemaking tour, and was leaving immediately for another round of
talks with Arab and Israeli leaders on Reagan's orders.
   NATO Secretary General Lord Carrington said the summit ``gives
me some satisfaction'' because of the 16 alliance leaders' good
will and harmony as they charted future policy.
   The final communique said alliance strategy must be ``based upon
an appropriate mix of adequate and effective nuclear and
conventional forces,'' and that NATO's remaining short-range
nuclear weapons must be improved ``where necessary.''
   The communique avoided the term ``modernization'' of short-range
missiles because of the opposition of West Germany, where most of
the weapons are based.
   Carrington said the allies were concerned that some people might
think ``modernization'' might signal introduction of new, more
destructive weapons. ``Modernization actually means weapons that
are more accurate and possibly less destructive,'' he said.
   The allied leaders expressed solid support for Reagan's efforts
to negotiate sharp reductions in U.S. and Soviet intercontinental
ballistic missiles, and renewed their endorsement of the December
agreement between Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
ban ground-launched, medium-range missiles in Europe.
   Carrington said he was heartened that Gorbachev has recognized
the East-West imbalance in European conventional forces that favors
the Eastern bloc and ``is willing to do something about them.''
</TEXT>
