<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Bangladesh-Election     03-03 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Election,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Killed, Dozens Injured During Parliamentary Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least two people were killed today
in riots outside polling places as the nation voted to choose a new
Parliament in an election marred by a general strike and charges of
fraud.
   Homemade bombs exploded as fighting between supporters of rival
candidates broke out near pollings places in and around Dhaka,
injuring dozens of people, police, witnesses and hospital officials
said.
   Near Dhaka University, a fire station and fire truck were set
ablaze by supporters of opposition parties who charged that workers
from the governing Jatiya Party were trying to steal ballot boxes
at a nearby polling station.
   In Old Dhaka, two people were shot to death in fighting,
hospital officials said. One election official was beaten in front
of reporters at a voting station, and another was reportedly
stripped of his clothes and chased from his post.
   Major opposition parties, which have been trying for four months
to oust President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, called for a boycott of
the election for Parliament and some municipal offices. The
opposition also called a general strike for Wednesday and today in
a bid to disrupt the election.
   On Wednesday, bands of youths hurled bombs, burned cars and
trucks, and shouted anti-government slogans, and at least eight
people were injured.
   In Dhaka, the strike appeared successful Wednesday, shutting
down shops and businesses and leaving streets empty of the bicycle
rickshaws that make Dhaka traffic a nightmare. But the strike
appeared to have little effect outside Dhaka other than preventing
trucks and buses from operating.
   It was the 24th strike called by the opposition since Nov. 10,
when it began its campaign to oust Ershad.
   ``No election, no election,'' young men and teen-agers from
opposition parties shouted today near one polling station in Old
Dhaka. ``Go in there. You won't even find a dog,'' one of them
shouted.
   The gates to the polling station were locked, and armed police
could be seen peaking out of a doorway inside. Witnesses said
homemade bombs had been tossed outside the polling station earlier.
   Outside a nearby voting station in a school, the pavement was
littered with pieces of broken bricks tossed by supporters of rival
candidates for municipal posts.
   The polling station was closed, and election official Muhammad
Akbar Ali, 45, said a gang of youths had burst in and made made off
with five ballot boxes. He said he did not know who the attackers
represented.
   A policeman at the scene, Abul Hasan, said police at opened fire
with blanks to chase away agitators who set off small homemade
bombs.
   After the policeman spoke, a young man wearing on his clothing
the plow symbol of the Jatiya Party began shoving and punching an
election official. He demanded that the polling station be
reopened. Police dragged him away.
   In Narayanganj, an industrial area southeast of Dhaka, an
election official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had
been unable to prevent Jatiya Party supporters from stuffing ballot
boxes.
   In a move to compromise with his opponents, Ershad dissolved the
330-seat Parliament last December, 3{ years before its term was to
expire, and scheduled new elections.
   But opposition leaders have said no election conducted under
Ershad can be fair, and they are urging a voter boycott.
   At least 33 people have been died since Nov. 10, either in
clashes, by police gunfire, or in campaign-related violence.
   Sheik Hasina of the opposition Awami League said she expected
only 5 percent or 10 percent of the 47.8 million voters to cast
ballots.
   More than 900 candidates from 102 political parties are running
for Parliament. Eighteen candidates, all from Ershad's Jatiya
Party, already have been declared elected for lack of opposition,
and voting in one district was canceled because a candidate was
killed.
   In addition to the Parliamentary election, municipal elections
will be held in the cities of Dhaka, Chittagong, Khulna, and
Rajshahi.
   In similar polling for town and village councils three weeks
ago, more than 100 people were killed in battles between supporters
of candidates.
   Ershad seized power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and won election
in 1986. He ordered 9,000 army troops and about 290,000 local
police and paramilitary troops deployed to ensure security for the
elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
