<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Train Crash,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passenger Trains Crash, Eight Dead, 25 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLADOLID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people died and at least 25
others were injured early today when one passenger train rammed
into a second one standing in a railway yard in this northern city,
a government spokesman said.
   Maximo Regidor said rescue workers recovered the bodies of eight
people, seven men and a young woman, trapped in the wreckage of a
sleeping car just after noon.
   The accident happened just after 3 a.m., when the north-bound
Madrid-Bilbao express of the state-owned railway company RENFE
rammed the stationary Madrid-Santander express train, he said.
   Valladolid is 112 miles northwest of the Spanish capital.
   Regidor said two of the victims were government officials of the
northern Cantabria region, and he identified them as Felix Ducasse
and Vicente Alcon.
   Regidor said the young woman was estimated to be between 15 and
18 years of age.
   ``Initially it appears the cause of the accident was a brake
failure,'' he said.
   Spanish National Radio reported 25 people were treated for minor
injuries at local hospitals and released.
