<2ND_LINE>PM-Abandoned Child, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0555,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospital Says Darlwin Should Be `On Roller Skates' Next Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to restore time element.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl whose lower legs were amputated
after she suffered frostbite has recovered well enough to ride a
bicycle and could be ``on roller skates'' next week, hospital
officials say.
   Darlwin Carlisle may leave the hospital within two weeks, Dr.
Paula Jaudes, who is supervising Darlwin's care at La Rabida
Children's Hospital and Research Center, said Wednesday.
   ``I expect that we'll have Darlwin on roller skates a week from
Friday,'' said physical therapist Roberta Kuchler-O'Shea, who is
helping the Gary, Ind., youngster learn to use artificial limbs.
   A construction worker found the girl locked in the freezing
bedroom attic of her family's apartment Jan. 17. Authorities
believe the girl was left there several days earlier by her mother,
who has pleaded innocent to felony neglect.
   Doctors at the University of Chicago's Wyler Children's Hospital
determined they could not save Darlwin's lower legs, and they
amputated Jan. 23. The girl later was transferred to La Rabida to
be fitted with artifical limbs.
   According to hospital spokeswoman Kris Bangert, custody of
Darlwin is to be decided by the state of Indiana.
   The child's father, James Carlisle, of Fort Wayne, has said he
wants custody. Foster parents are also an option, Ms. Bangert said.
   While at La Rabida, Darlwin has learned how to put on her
artificial legs and progressed from walking with the help of
parallel bars to using a walker, Ms. Jaudes said.
   The girl should be able to walk unassisted by next week, she
said.
   Ms. Kuchler-O'Shea said Darlwin is learning to resume activities
she could do before, such as bicycling and roller skating.
   The girl has learned to pedal a stationary bicycle and has
received a real bicycle _ a pink one with training wheels _ that
she has ridden in hospital halls and soon should be able to take
outside.
</TEXT>
