<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0733EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TreasureHunt     03-03 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasure Hunt,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasure Hunt Raises Nationalist Outcry, Skepticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Excavators led by a former American
Green Beret are digging in an old Spanish fort for buried treasure,
raising an outcry from Filipino nationalists and bemused skepticism
in the Manila press.
   The loot is believed to be part of a fortune in gold which
legend says was buried by the Japanese in World War II. Estimates
on its value range as high as $200 billion, more than enough to pay
off this country's $29 billion foreign debt.
   But the search has also raised charges in a nationalist-minded
Congress that foreigners are desecrating hallowed ground where
Filipino and American soldiers died and where the country's
national hero, Jose Rizal, was imprisoned before his execution in
1898.
   ``I have nothing against people having high hopes,'' wrote
columnist Larry Sipin in the newspaper Malaya. ``But when those who
rule us act as if our only hope lies in a pot of gold at the end of
a rainbow, or at the bottom of Fort Santiago, we're in trouble.''
   Rumors have circulated for decades that Japanese Gen. Tomoyuki
Yamashita buried a fortune in gold and jewels which he looted from
Southeast Asia before his transfer to the Philippines near the end
of the war. Yamashita was hanged as a war criminal in 1946.
   Last month, a team led by Charles McDougald, a former Green
Beret captain and official of the Las Vegas-based International
Precious Metals Inc., began digging at Fort Santiago, a Spanish
fortress used by the Japanese as a prison during the war.
   McDougald says his group was hired in 1975 by former President
Ferdinand Marcos to search for the treasure. According to
McDougald, Robert Curtis, president of International Precious
Metals, pinpointed more than 170 sites but then fled to the United
States, fearing Marcos would double-cross him.
   McDougald told reporters later today he had evidence that
Marcos, who was ousted in a civilian-military revolt in 1986,
uncovered $6 billion in treasure from the site in 1983. He did not
specify the evidence.
   Marcos today urged the government to ignore a treasure-hunting
craze that has swept the country and work instead to end the
communist insurgency.
   ``After all the sacrifices, all they (officials) are talking
about now is money, money, money,'' Marcos told radio staion DZMM
in Manila from his exile home in Honolulu. ``What will happen to
the communists who are attempting to takeover the country? That is
what our priority should be.''
   Marcos spoke in Tagalog, the main Philippine language. His
remarks were translated by The Associated Press. He also denied
published reports in Manila that he had recovered billions of
dollars in gold from the fort.
   Under an agreement with President Corazon Aquino's government,
McDougald's team can keep 25 percent of whatever it finds. The rest
goes to the Philippine treasury. McDougald told reporters this week
he expects to find the booty within two weeks.
   The dig began in secret but word leaked out when the fort was
closed to the public and Filipino reporters began noticing troops
of the elite Presidential Security Group guarding the site.
McDougald and presidential aides then confirmed the excavation
after two Filipino workers were killed when the tunnel in which
they were digging collapsed.
   Catalino Macaraig, presidential executive secretary, told
reporters that the permit was issued ``in accordance with the rules
and regulations of treasure hunting'' and that the government's
interest would be protected.
   But Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, a former defense minister,
complained that the excavation was an insult to national honor. The
Senate unanimously approved a non-binding resolution to halt the
dig.
   The upper chamber then subpoenaed McDougald to appear before a
Senate committee investigating the project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
