<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0802EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Film     03-03 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Film,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two `Enemies of the People' Are the Unlikely Heroes of New Soviet
Film</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They are political prisoners, branded ``enemies of
the people'' under Stalin. They have been banished to a ramshackle
fishing village in the Soviet north, where they live alongside, but
apart from, villagers.
   Their names are Luzga and Kopalych, and they are the heroes of a
new Soviet film that illustrates the country's confusion after the
death of Josef V. Stalin in March 1953 and its continuing attempt
to come to grips with the dictator's legacy.
   In ``The Cold Summer of '53,'' by producer Alexander Proshkin,
the two exiles are the only village dwellers who do not submit when
their settlement near the Finnish border is seized by six common
criminals who were freed in a prison amnesty that followed Stalin's
death.
   The others, including a mustachioed old captain whose cabin is
decorated with a portrait of Stalin, allow themselves to be put
under lock and key, or even cross the line between obeying their
armed captors and seeking to help them.
   Luzga and Kopalych resist, and kill off the criminals, one by
one.
   The film, shown to Moscow-based journalists Wednesday night at
the Foreign Ministry Press Center, seems an apt summary of the
terrible paradoxes of the Stalin era, when innocent people could be
convicted of crimes, and those who committed injustices could be
honored members of the community.
   ``Cold Summer'' is the latest Soviet artistic work dealing with
the Stalinist legacy to emerge under Communist Party chief Mikhail
S. Gorbachev's loosened restrictions on depicting the often
troubled Soviet past and Stalin's 29-year reign.
   ``Confession,'' a film by Georgian director Tengiz Abuladze
released in late 1986, portrays a pudgy, mustachioed Communist
Party official that Soviet audiences immediately recognized as
Lavrenti Beria, the feared head of Stalin's secret police.
   Beria's image also makes a small appearance in ``Cold Summer,''
in a scene that shows the contradictory feelings Soviets still have
for Stalin and his henchman.
   A policeman, who will become the first villager killed by the
amnestied criminals, spies a portrait of Beria in a publication
lying in the captain's house.
   He starts to rip out the picture, but the captain stops him.
   ``By what instructions do you destroy portraits?'' asks the
captain, ever the fearful bureaucrat.
   The policeman tosses Beria's picture away, but it is picked up,
carefully smoothed out and saved by one of the leading members of
the small fishing community, a man who will later do more than
anyone else to assist the criminals.
   Luzga is a gaunt Red Army veteran with the drawn features and
permanent 5-day-old whiskers of a Soviet Indiana Jones. Played by
veteran actor Valery Priemykhov, Lyzga is often lost in reverie,
and scoffs at the suggestion that he might one day be able to
return to his former life.
   ``Were you ever in Moscow?'' a blonde-haired village girl asks
him at one point.
   ``I don't remember,'' he says with a blank look.
   The gray-haired, baggy-eyed Kopalych is played by Anatoly
Papanov, who died after filming his last scene in ``Cold Summer''in
August. The film was completed in November.
   Papanov's gruff voice is familiar to Soviet children as the
voice of a wolf in a popular cartoon series broadcast by state-run
television.
   The plot of ``Cold Summer'' is reminiscent of countless cowboy
movies where mild-mannered characters find the strength in
themselves to resist injustice, and go on to slay the villains.
   Many in the audience of journalists, Foreign Ministry officials
and guests applauded when Luzga killed one of the more odious
criminals with a pistol shot to the head.
   He finished off the gang's fleeing ringleader by wading into the
water and drowning him.
   Proshkin, 47, who appeared at the screening to present his film
and answer questions, acknowledged the movie's script was a ``pure
Western,'' when he got it, but said he had tried to made something
more eclectic with a political edge.
   ``The average spectator today in the country is young,''
Proshkin said. ``You need strong action to get across the moral and
political point of view.''
   Proshkin was 13 when Stalin died, and said he hopes his film
will deliver a political message about the Stalin era to the
country's youth.
   ``I think the current generation is less politicized than mine
was,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrushFire     03-03 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brush Fire,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Ignore Evacuation Order: Join Firefighters Battling
Brush Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAISLEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents ignored evacuation orders and
joined firefighters battling a wind-fueled brush fire that
threatened dozens of homes in rural Central Florida near the Ocala
National Forest.
   About 475 acres had burned by early today, but no homes were
destroyed and no injuries were reported. Police, state forestry
firefighters and U.S. Forest Service workers battled flames sparked
Wednesday and fueled by gusty winds.
   ``The fire's under control,'' Florida Forestry Division
spokesman David Bucher said this morning. Fire crews would check
today for flareups, he said.
   Katherine Henrie, 64, was among the residents of the remote Lake
Kathryn Heights neighborhood who stayed with their homes. As
towering flames threatened to consume a nearby house, she sprayed
her yard with a garden hose.
   ``They told me to leave but I got no place to go if I did,''
said Mrs. Henrie. ``I'll just lose everything I have. I got no
insurance. They just told me to keep watering the best I could. I
got the sprinkler going over there and three dogs waiting in the
car.''
   Late winter and early spring are generally are the worst times
for brush fires in Central Florida. Pastures and woodlands become
tinder-dry and frost often has killed grass to create hay in
underbrush, which becomes fire fodder.
 
</TEXT>
