<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0812EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Trantino     03-03 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trantino,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parole Board Reverses Decision; Convicted Cop Killer Must Remain
Behind Bars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of killing two police
officers in 1963 must remain behind bars at least three more years,
a Parole Board has ruled in revoking an earlier decision to release
him.
   After two hours of closed-door discussions, the board voted 4-3
Wednesday to cancel Thomas Trantino's March 15 release, set by two
members in January. It was the second time Trantino, who has spent
nearly 25 years in prison, came within a hair of parole.
   Trantino was convicted of shooting of two Lodi police officers
in 1963. He originally was sentenced to the electric chair, but the
penalty was changed to life in prison when the death penalty law
was struck down in 1972.
   The possibility of parole sparked a candlelight vigil, a
petition drive and a letter-writing campaign in recent weeks. The
day after a television show on the case, 1,000 people called the
board to argue against parole.
   Those opposed to Trantino's release, including police and
relatives of his victims, expressed relief at the board's decision.
   ``Crime is on a runaway train in this country, and a crime of
this type needs an appropriate punishment,'' said Lodi Police Chief
Andrew Voto, brother of one victim.
   In Wednesday's decision, the board ruled that Trantino must
remain behind bars for more than three years, but it left open
exactly when he will again be eligible for parole. Parole Board
Chairman Louis Nickolopoulos said the panel will decide that later.
   In 1980 the board said he could be released if he made
restitution to relatives of his victims. After a court fight the
panel decided in 1982 that he should remain in prison.
   Nickolopoulos, asked about Trantino's reaction, said: ``There
was no comment. He was very calm. He was very courteous and polite
throughout the hearing.''
   Trantino's wife, Charlee, whom he married while on a prison
furlough, said she her husband ``doesn't feel any bitterness toward
anyone.''
   Trantino's lawyer, Stuart F. Pierson, who has criticized what he
called undue pressure on the Parole Board by police and others,
said he wasn't certain whether the denial will be appealed.
   Nickolopoulos said he could not discuss the reasons for the
panel's decision until Trantino is notified in writing. The board
has 21 days to inform the inmate, who then has 14 days to ask for a
reconsideration. If he is denied again, he can appeal to the courts.
   Trantino, 50, now in a medium-security prison in Camden, was
convicted for the murders of Sgt. Peter Voto and patrolman Gary
Tedesco.
   The two were investigating a report of a disturbance at tavern
when they were surprised, partially stripped and shot dead by
Trantino and an accomplice. The accomplice was fatally shot the
next day by police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0821EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Violence     03-03 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Violence,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeland Legislator Shot Dead In Violence-Torn Region</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawmaker in a black homeland
where rival political groups are engaged in a bloody power struggle
was shot to death at home as he and his children watched
television, police said today.
   The 36-year-old legislator, Petrus Mbatha, was a member of
Inkatha, a Zulu political organization that has been locked in the
fierce feud in KwaZulu homeland with backers of militant
anti-apartheid groups.
   Mbatha lived near Camperdown on the fringe of the area around
the Natal province capital of Pietermaritzburg, where more than 400
people have been killed in the feud since early last year.
   Police said it was not known who killed Mbatha late Wednesday,
but reported finding cartridges from Soviet-made AK-47 automatic
rifles. Police regularly link these weapons to members and
supporters of the outlawed African National Congress, the main
guerrilla group fighting to end white-minority domination.
   Inkatha's prinicpal rival in the Natal power struggle has been
the United Democratic Front, South Africa's largest anti-apartheid
coalition.
   Last week, the government banned the UDF from political activity
and barred several of its senior leaders from further involvement
with the organization. Several of these leaders had been involved
in negotiations aimed at halting the Inkatha-UDF feud, and the
government's action was widely viewed as undermining the peace
process.
   Mangosuthu Buthelezi, leader of Inkatha and chief minister of
KwaZulu, contends UDF cooperates with the African National Congress
in a campaign to seize control of black townships and oust black
moderates who oppose violence.
   UDF leaders have criticized Buthelezi for refusing to support
militant anti-apartheid strategies such as boycotts and sanctions.
   This week, the government reinforced its security forces around
Peitermaritzburg with 300 so-called ``instant constables'' _ black
policemen assigned to duty after relatively short training programs.
   The Law and Order Ministry has declined to comment on
allegations most of the new constables are Inkatha members.
   Buthelezi describes Inkatha as a Zulu cultural organization,
although it functions as KwaZulu's dominant political party.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0824EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Elections     03-03 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Elections,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Party Wins Elections, Predicts More Victories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the extreme
right-wing Conservative Party said today that victories in two
special parliamentary elections show growing white support for his
staunchly pro-apartheid policies.
   The Conservatives won decisively Wednesday in the rural
Transvaal province districts of Standerton and Schweizer-Reneke
despite an intensive campaign by President P.W. Botha's National
Party.
   They had won the seats in May's national white elections, but
the winners were forced to resign, one on a technicality, the other
because of bankruptcy.
   In both contests, the Conservatives substantially increased
their margin of victory.
   Conservative Party leader Andries Treurnicht said the victories
would ``have a snowball effect.''
   Botha called them ``temporary disappointments'' for the National
Party.
   ``Foreign interference as well as actions by radical elements
that break internal laws undoubtedly cause aversion to patriotic
voters,'' he said without elaborating.
   The Conservatives are favored to win another special election
later this month and appear likely to cut into National Party
support in nationwide municipal elections in October.
   Chris Van Den Heever, the Conservatives' chief spokesman in
Transvaal, predicted the 8-year-old party would take control of
local councils throughout rural areas of Transvaal. He said the
party also expected to do well in coastal areas where many whites
have protested the recent opening of beaches to blacks.
   Van Den Heever said the National Party, in an effort to preserve
its support, would place increasing emphasis on security issues. He
predicted the government would launch some type of law-and-order
campaign.
   The independent Pretoria News said in an editorial today:
``After being fed a diet of National Party racism for decades, it
is not surprising that the farmers ... voted for the old precepts
of that party as espoused now by Treurnicht.''
   The Conservative Party seeks to reinstate all rescinded
apartheid laws. It charges that Botha is capitulating to the
country's 26 million black majority through his limited reforms of
recent years.
   Botha maintains his reforms will not threaten ``white
interests,'' which he promises will be protected through continued
segregation of housing, schools and health services.
   The National Party, which has been in power since 1948,
advocates limited power-sharing, with blacks gaining a say in
national politics, but whites maintaining power. It firmly controls
the 178-member white chamber of Parliament, with 133 seats to the
Conservatives' 22, though the Conservatives won 26 percent of the
votes nationwide last May.
   The anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party, which has 17 seats
in the white chamber, did not field any candidates in Wednesday's
two by-elections.
   Both the National and Conservative parties rely largely on
support from Afrikaners, descendants of the 17th-century Dutch
settlers who comprise about 3 million of the 5 million whites.
   South Africa's Parliament has separate chambers for whites,
Asians and people of mixed-race. Blacks are excluded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
