<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-PLOMission     03-03 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-PLO Mission,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Law To Close PLO Mission Assailed By General Assembly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. official said the General Assembly
acted prematurely when it voted in emergency session to order the
United States to submit to binding arbitration its plan to close
the PLO U.N. mission.
   The vote Wednesday was 143-1. America's Western allies joined
the majority. Israel cast the only dissenting vote. The United
States did not vote.
   Arab diplomats hinted the United Nations might have to leave New
York if the U.S. government insists on enforcing an anti-terrorism
law that would close the Palestine Liberation Organization mission
by March 21.
   The U.S. deputy permanent representative, Herbert S. Okun,
called the special session ``inappropriate and premature.''
   Although U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters was not present
Wednesday, he has said various branches of the government are
discussing the issue and its legal implications.
   Clovis Maksoud, Arab envoy, said America was opening ``a
Pandora's box of diplomatic, legal and political problems'' by
trying to close the mission and putting U.S. domestic legislation
above international treaty obligations.
   Most diplomats, however, said a move from New York was
undesirable and unlikely. The PLO has non-voting, observer status
at the United Nations.
   Maksoud, representative of the League of Arab States, told a
news conference Congress should repeal the anti-terrorism law and
said President Reagan could exclude the PLO U.N. mission from
application of the law.
   Maksoud said the issue is a problem between the United States
and the United Nations, not the PLO.
   ``This demonstrates the level of embarrassment for the United
States. It is opening a Pandora's box of political, legal and
diplomatic problems,'' he said.
   Alexander M. Belonogov, Soviet ambassador, called the dispute a
``self-inflicted wound'' to U.S. prestige.
   The United Nations and the State Department say the U.S. law
would violate international law and the Headquarters Agreement of
1947 that allows all U.N. missions to operate.
   The United States said it has not decided if it will implement
the measure calling for closing of the PLO mission.
   The assembly also voted 142-0 to ask the International Court of
Justice in The Hague to rule whether the United States has the
right to refuse arbitration. The United States and Israel did not
vote.
   General Assembly votes are considered expressions of
international will and mainly carry moral authority. They are not
legally binding and there is no enforcement mechanism. Assembly
resolutions are often ignored or defied.
   The assembly decided to reconvene and consider its next move if
the United States goes ahead and orders the PLO mission closed.
   The United States so far has rejected arbitration provided in
the Headquarters Agreement for dispute settlement. It is the first
time the clause has been invoked. The next step will be a Justice
Department announcement on whether it will enforce the new law.
   The World Court is also expected to submit an opinion on whether
the United States has to submit disputes to binding arbitration.
   America and other nations have disregarded court rulings in the
past.
   Benjamin Netanyahu, Israeli ambassador, called the PLO a
terrorist organization whose commitment to armed struggle conflicts
with the U.N. Charter. He walked out when PLO Representative Zehdi
Labib Terzi said Israel has disregarded ``norms of civilized
behavior.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
