<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CampusTakeover 1stLd-Writethru a0447 03-03 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campus Takeover, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students End Nine-Day Occupation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT that office, sted building, taken over.
Tightens throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minority students who took over a
Hampshire College dormitory office for nine days to protest alleged
campus racism headed back to class today, saying they were relieved
the sit-in was over.
   ``I think everybody's pretty much exhausted,'' said Anita
Fearman, a spokeswoman for the 40 black, Hispanic and other
minority students who ended the takeover Wednesday with the signing
of a 16-point agreement designed to encourage racial harmony at the
private school, where about 100 of the 1,100 students are
minorities.
   Fearnab and 20 other protesters were among the 150 students who
watched as college President Adele Simmons and two other
administrators signed the document outside the office that had been
occupied since Feb. 23.
   The settlement provided for a dean of multicultural affairs, an
adviser for the group that occupied the Dakin House office and at
least $4,500 in yearly funding for the group. The administration
also agreed not to discipline the students, and to allow them to
make up work missed during the takeover.
   ``I think the occupation strengthened the institution,'' said
Simmons. ``For the last several years we've been working to improve
student life and this represents a finishing of the old agenda.''
   Fearman said the protesters were relieved to trade in their
sleeping bags for dormitory beds, although ``a few are feeling that
it will be hard not to have each other for support 24 hours a
day.'' She said the protesters had begun returning to classes
Wednesday afternoon.
   The occupation began a week after the end of a takeover at
nearby University of Massachusetts that was sparked by campus
racial violence. That takeover ended when Chancellor Joseph Duffey
agreed to increase funding of minority student programs and to
other demands.
   Hampshire protesters said racial violence is rare at their
school, but the college had long ignored their concerns.
   College officials said the allegation was a surprise, given the
school's aim to be a progressive alternative to the traditional
liberal arts education offered at nearby Amherst, Mount Holyoke and
Smith colleges. Hampshire students design their own courses of
study and must complete individual research projects and pass three
divisional examinations to graduate.
   The protesters, however, said that the settlement and the
sympathy shown them by the college community, which organized
rallies and sent food to the protesters throughout the occupation,
had changed their minds about warning minorities away from the
school.
   ``I really would tell them to come here,'' said protester Penny
Predmas.
</TEXT>
