<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SubwayRevolt     03-03 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Subway Revolt,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subway Riders Refuse To Leave Train in Rare Revolt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was something unheard of among the mild and
compliant commuter ranks in London, but it happened this week _ an
underground revolt.
   The underground in this case was a subway train on the aging
Northern Line of the London Regional Transport system.
   The riders were told Tuesday night to get off their
delay-plagued train five stops before their destination and wait
for the next train. A signal failure was blamed.
   Not a rare occurrence.
   What was rare was that they balked.
   Transport spokesman David Morris said the passengers, bound for
High Barnet at the end of the Northern Line, started filing off.
That's what London subway riders always do. Grumbling, maybe, but
obeying orders.
   But then, according to the London Evening Standard newspaper, a
``mild-looking and well-dressed'' passenger declared: ``I've had
enough. I'm staying put. If we all do it, they'll have to take the
train on.''
   He was among about a dozen passengers who got back into the
train, the paper said. More passengers followed. After hurried
consultations the staff gave in and waved the train on.
   London Regional Transport called the subway mutineers selfish.
   Morris complained to The Associated Press. ``Those passengers
had only a narrow and selfish view and put their needs above
others.''
   But the Standard newspaper hailed it as ``The Great Tube
Revolt'' _ the subway is known as the tube in Britain _ and called
the unidentified leader ``a superhero in the Clark Kent mold _
quiet, mild-mannered and unassuming.''
   The paper quoted passenger Sheila Golding of High Barnet as
saying the rebels cheered and laughed, because ``we knew that if
everyone did it _ and stayed put _ there wasn't anything they could
do about it.''
   It quoted passenger Maria Gama as saying: ``Everybody was just
totally fed up. The waiting room was freezing and nobody could tell
us why the train was stopping where it did. But when everybody
climbed back on, it was a marvelous moment.''
   The Northern Line, which carries 700,000 passengers between
south and north London, is sometimes called ``The Misery Line'' by
newspapers and criticized for defective trains and equipment,
last-minute schedule changes, signal failures and dirty stations.
   Morris denied the line was worse than others.
   But none of that mattered.
   The meek, mild, patient, uncomplaining London subway riders had
had their day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
