<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Djilas     03-03 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Djilas,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gets Story Published In Yugoslav Magazine First Time In 34 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Milovan Djilas, Yugoslavia's best
known dissident and a former vice president, got a short story
published in a regular literary magazine for the first time in 34
years.
   The story, titled ``The War,'' was published Wednesday in the
Knjizevne Novine periodical of Belgrade. It deals with a summary
execution of a young deserter in the presence of his parents during
World War II.
   In a note, the editors of the March 1-15 issue that reached news
stands Wednesday, stressed, ``We have no intention today ... to
engage in assessing the political ideas, stands and programs of
Milovan Djilas.''
   It said that ``publishing the literary work of Milovan Djilas, a
test of his artistic achievement by the literary public, will
confirm ... the democratic strength of the principled attitude'' of
the Yugoslav leadership ``toward cultural creativity.''
   ``We believe that freedom of art creations and autonomy of an
artistic work are a major achievement of our policy and our
culture,'' the editors said.
   Djilas, a top partisan leader, emerged from the war as heir
apparent to Marshal Josip Broz Tito, who became Yugoslavia's first
president.
   However, after he began writing articles displaying his
disenchantment with communism in the early 1950s and then published
his first book, ``The New Class,'' Djilas fell into disgrace and
spent about nine years in jail.
   Last September, a Belgrade company said it was considering
publishing Djilas' book ``The Revolutionary War,'' known in the
West under the title ``War-Time.''
   No book or article by Djilas, now 76, has been officially
published in Yugoslavia after his fall from favor.
   But Djilas received a passport in January 1987 and has traveled
widely since.
   Knjizevne Novine, in its 40th anniversary issue, put Djilas'
name on the front page listing its contributors.
   ``Removing the silently perpetuated taboo (on publishing his
work), now that administrative obstacles no longer exist, means
permitting a potentially worthy work to establish itself in a place
that belongs to it _ or to lose it, should it prove worthless,''
the editors' note said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
