<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Blood     03-03 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Blood,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospice Sought for Homosexual Prostitute Acquitted of Poisoning
Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County officials are searching for a hospice
to care for a male prostitute acquitted of attempted poisoning
charges after selling his AIDS-tainted blood.
   ``Right now, it is hard to place a person like that,'' said Eric
Rofes, executive director of the Gay and Lesbian Community Services
Center.
   Joseph Markowski, 29, was acquitted Wednesday by a Superior
Court jury on two counts of attempted poisoning. Jurors decided he
lacked the intent required under state law to kill or injure
someone by selling his blood.
   ``What he did was inexcusable, but we had to follow the law,''
juror William E. Ferguson said after the verdict was read. ``I hope
they will come up with a law to prevent people from doing this in
the future.''
   ``We need legislation on this,'' said Deputy District Attorney
Antonio Barreto Jr., who prosecuted the case. ``He can go out and
do this again today, as long as he said, `I just did it for the
money.'''
   Markowski, who suffers from mental illness and carries the AIDS
virus but has not developed the disease, could have faced up to
seven years in prison if convicted.
   He had been accused of selling his tainted blood for $10 to
Plasma Production Associates on June 22 and of trying to do so
again June 25.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome can be spread is by
transfusion of infected blood or blood products. AIDS cripples the
body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and
cancers. There is no known cure.
   Markowski originally was charged with attempted murder, but
Judge Ronald S. Coen dismissed those counts, saying the law
required a specific intent to kill that was not present in the case.
   The homeless prostitute was arrested June 23 after screaming,
``Kill me! Kill me! I have AIDS!'' in a Hollywood bank while
attempting to grab a security guard's gun. Police found his receipt
from the plasma center.
   Court-appointed defense attorney Guy O'Brien said Markowski was
happy to be acquitted but concerned about where he would make his
home.
   ``I don't know what's going to happen to him,'' said Dr. Eugene
Kunzman of the mental health unit at County Jail. ``All the
agencies involved are attempting to do what is best for everyone
involved.''
   Last year, Los Angeles County District Attorney Ira Reiner
lobbied for legislation making it a felony to knowingly sell or
donate AIDS-contaminated blood. The state Assembly failed to
approve it.
   Markowski allegedly admitted to police that he sold his blood
because he needed money and didn't care about the public, but Coen
ruled the statement inadmissible because Markowski had not been
informed of his right to remain silent and wait for an attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
