<DOCNO> AP880303-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0842EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APonTV-Grammys     03-03 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Grammys,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Don't Laugh, Little Richard Could Get a Series Out of This</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Grammys Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0459 to fix category code, style on Grammys,
sted Grammies, in keyword line; this column normally moves in
advance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until Little Richard took the Grammy Awards
hostage for several minutes, the high point might have been Michael
Jackson's Pepsi commercial.
   But seriously, folks, perhaps because no one artist dominated
the awards, Wednesday night's was one of the best Grammy shows in
years.
   Billy Crystal was host of the three-hour CBS special, but New
York _ more specifically Radio City Music Hall _ was the star.
   The show seemed to have gotten a new soul infusion by returning
from Los Angeles. It was broadcast live from the venerable old
Music Hall, all decked out in a brilliantly glitzy art deco set
design that was just made for Cab Calloway to strut across singing
``Minnie the Moocher'' and coaxing the tres cool audience into
joining in on ``Hidy, hidy, hidy ho.''
   But it was Little Richard who stopped the show when he was
supposed to announce the winner for best new artist. Instead, he
ran off with the envelope, insisting, ``The best new artist is _
me!'' A pain to the waiting nominees, but undeniably great
television.
   Richard had come out complaining that co-presenter Buster
Poindexter had stolen his pompadour. ``Everything I get, they take
it from me,'' he said.
   His giggling outburst prompted a standing ovation from the
audience, a fuming ``shut up!'' from Poindexter _ but no Grammy.
Maybe an Emmy if they create a best supporting player on a
self-congratulatory industry awards show.
   Dion represented oldsters without causing trouble; he just came
out and sang ``Why Must I Be a Teen-Ager in Love?'' and wrapped up
the show with ``Runaround Sue.''
   Michael Jackson didn't get any awards during the broadcast, but
he turned in a stunning performance that concluded with an inspired
James Brown-esque gospel number complete with robed choir, even
upstaging his Pepsi trilogy.
   Until Jackson came out, some of the best musical moments were in
the ads. It was a little hard to pay attention to Jackie Mason's
mushy borscht-belt humor _ he was doing Ed Sullivan, for Pete's
sake _ after Eric Clapton's wailing guitar solo on behalf of
Michelob.
   When it came to acceptance speeches, the Irish consciousness
band U2 was in a class by itself. When it won for best performance
by a duo or group, guitarist The Edge thanked, ``Martin Luther King
... Bob Dylan for `Tangled Up in Blue,' Flannery O'Connor, Jimi
Hendrix, Walt Disney, John the Baptist, George Best, Gregory Peck
... Dr. Ruth, Fawn Hall, Batman and Robin ... the YMCA, sumo
wrestlers throughout the world, and of course Ronald Reagan.''
   Later, for best album, lead singer Bono made a self-deprecating
poke at the band's messiah image.
   ``It really is hard having the weight of the world on your
shoulders,'' he said. ``But we enjoy our work.''
   He also added, ``it's hard when there are 60 million people
watching not to talk about South Africa and what's happening there,
... but tonight is maybe is not the night to do that.'' He made his
point.
   As usual, the show was a hodgepodge of American musical tastes,
though the flamboyance level of the rock stars being what it is,
everybody else looked like badly dressed tourists who wandered away
from the bus. How about a segue from Vladimir Horowitz to George
Strait singing ``All My Exes Live in Texas?''
   Crystal's humor depended largely on insider entertainment jokes
_ who cares at this point that ``The Wilton North Report'' got
canceled? He set up the tribute to the Apple with his touching bit
on an old, black jazz musician _ ``Can you dig it? I knew that you
could.'' Unfortunately, the routine plays better in a dark club
than on a glitter-drenched, island-sized stage.
   Steve Allen was funnier. (Crystal later kept crediting Allen
with writing the hottest of the rock numbers.) Allen presented the
best comedy album award with Steven Wright. He led off by
announcing the good news that ``they did find Liza Minelli's
dress.''
   ``Steven asked me to read the list of nominees,'' he said,
``because he suffers from dyslexia. Actually he doesn't suffer from
it, he digs it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BERGEN SERIES _ Movie star Candice Bergen has been signed to
star in ``Murphy Brown,'' a pilot for a CBS half-hour comedy
series. It's Bergen's first venture into series television, though
she starred earlier this season in the CBS movie ``Mayflower
Madam.'' Warner Bros. Television says she plays the title
character, ``a tough, get-the-story interviewers who is ready to
tackle anyone from David Letterman to the president of the United
States.'' And we all know how painful that can be.
</TEXT>
