<2ND_LINE>PM-Editor Named,0144</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit News Editor To Join Commercial Appeal In Memphis, Tenn.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lionel Linder, editor and vice president of The
Detroit News since March 1983, has been named editor of the
Commercial Appeal in Memphis, Tenn., newspaper officials said.
   Linder, 56, assumes his new post today. The Tennessee newspaper
is owned by Scripps Howard Publishing and has a circulation of
240,000 daily and 350,000 on Sunday.
   Linder had been a News employee since 1977.
   ``The new position is an opportunity for me to move on,'' Linder
said. ``I love the challenge to build and rebuild newspapers.''
   Before becoming editor at the News, Linder was executive editor
and managing editor with the paper. The News, owned by Gannett Co.
Inc., has a circulation of 678,720 daily and 839,319 on Sundays,
according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
