<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MemoryBoards     03-03 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Memory Boards,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEC Agrees to Pay Consumer Redress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer company has agreed to make refunds
to about 100 consumers who bought memory expansion boards in
response to exaggerated advertising claims, according to the
Federal Trade Commission.
   NEC Home Electronics, a subsidiary of NEC Corp. of Japan, agreed
to pay $15,000 in consumer redress to settle charges that it had
made deceptive claims for some of its computers, the FTC said
Tuesday.
   According to the commission, NEC advertised its PC-8000 series
of computers and accessories from 1981 to 1984, including the claim
that the average person with no training could quadruple the
device's memory by buying accessory equipment.
   The FTC said expanding the memory to that extent required a
skilled programmer or access to a sophisticated operating system
which was never made available in the United States.
   Under the consent agreement, NEC will refund the $150 purchase
price to consumers who bought memory expansion boards for the
computers, which it estimated at about 100 people.
   Purchasers of the boards can contact the company about refunds
by writing to NEC at 1255 Michael Drive, Wood Dale, Ill., 60191.
</TEXT>
