<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0924EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugConference 2ndLd-Writethru a0504 03-03 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Conference, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0504,510</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III said today
the Justice Department backs a new Customs Service decision to
seize the passports of Americans suspected of entering the country
with illegal drugs.
   ``We're in favor of it and we're looking now at the legal
aspects of it. I hope we will find legal ways to do that,'' Meese
siad in an interview on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
   ``There's no reason that drug traffickers should have freedom to
travel around the world peddling their wares,'' he added.
   William von Raab, the Customs Service commissioner, told the
White House Conference on a Drug-Free America on Wednesday that his
agency, on March 15, will begin taking the passports of Americans
who try to re-enter the country with illegal drugs. Customs Service
spoksman Edward Kittredge said the passports would be seized as
evidence of a crime and forwarded to the State Department.
   Meese also refuted Reagan administration critics who say the
military is not being used to stop the flow of drugs into the
United States.
   ``We've been using the military in this country for six years
against drugs,'' he said, adding, ``They help with the
interdiction. They provide the surveillance, which is what they can
do.''
   Addressing the conference Wednesday, Meese said recalcitrant
bureaucrats and meddling members of Congress are hampering the
federal war on drugs.
   ``I am extremely concerned about the fragmentation that goes on
in Congress,'' he said.
   ``We have 32 different committees in the Congress with
cognizance over the drug problem so that too many of the leaders
who are seated on the stage here are spending their time testifying
in front of congressional committees instead of leading the forces
that ought to be out in the field working on the drug problem.''
   Meese was among four Cabinet members and five other top-ranking
administration officials appearing together on a panel at the
conference.
   Von Raab complained to the estimated 2,000 delegates that
federal bureaucrats are too lax in pushing anti-drug efforts, a
position subsequently embraced by Meese.
   ``I have been flat out told by many bureaucrats that just
because the president is supporting an effort it doesn't mean that
money goes with it,'' von Raab said. ``We don't need a bunch of
bureaucrats that will deal with this war on drugs the way they
dealt with the war in Vietnam. We need heart in this effort. ...
   ``There are still too many people who work for us _ in my
organization as well _ who still have their noses too deeply buried
in their old books.''
   Meese said later, ``I am worried about what Mr. von Raab talked
about: Some people in the trenches who do not have the message.''
   The attorney general called on state and local officials to pour
more money into anti-drug efforts.
   ``If state and local governments will increase their efforts
threefold _ 300 percent _ as the federal government has in the last
seven years _ I think we will have adequate funds to provide the
necessary resources for all aspects, enforcement as well as
treatment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
