<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dishwasher-Death     03-03 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dishwasher-Death,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Found Dead in Dishwasher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy whose body was found in
a dishwasher may have tried to take a shower in it, his uncle said.
   ``I really believe he crawled in there thinking he could wash up
and crawl back out,'' Darold DeGrand said of his nephew, Michael
Conard, of Humboldt.
   The boy's nude body was discovered by his mother, Jean, 33, when
she returned home from work Tuesday afternoon.
   ``It's a strange situation,'' Brown County Sheriff's Commander
David Zasada said Wednesday. ``Right now we're not looking at this
as foul play.''
   The boy was 4 foot, 10 inches tall and weighed about 90 pounds.
   DeGrand said he was convinced the death was accidental.
   The portable dishwasher was found hooked up to the kitchen sink
and running, Zasada said, and the mother turned it off and found
her son's body inside.
   The uncle said the dishwasher had no safety features to prevent
such an accident. ``It was an older model where, once you shut the
door, if the dial was set right, it kicked in. They bought it
secondhand may years ago.''
   Zasada said investigators were trying to determine whether there
was forced entry or sign of a struggle. There were no external
injuries that might have indicated the boy was shoved into the
dishwasher.
   ``I would certainly not at this time say there was a suicide,''
he said.
   An autopsy to determine the casue of death was inconclusive,
Zasada said, and further tests were planned.
</TEXT>
