<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Obit-Szeryng 1stLd-Writethru a0539 03-03 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Szeryng, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0539,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Virtuoso Violinist Henryk Szeryng, 69</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `He eventually...,' to ADD details on where
he lived.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virtuoso violinist Henryk Szeryng, a Polish emigre
and Mexican citizen who gained fame after performing extensively
for Allied troops during World War II, died today in West Germany.
He was 69.
   Szeryng died at 4 a.m. in Kassel, West Germany, of a cerebral
hemorrhage he suffered early Wednesday, his Paris and New York
offices said.
   A recipient of numerous international awards, the violinist was
to have played in Brussels Wednesday night with the Orchestra of
Sarrebruck and begin a U.S. tour in a few weeks.
   ``Real music lovers want emotion _ great moments _ which
Szeryng's playing gives them,'' Arthur Rubinstein, who died in
1982, once said.
   Szeryng had a preference for resurrecting neglected works and
bringing relatively unknown contemporary works to the public. In
1971, he reconstructed and gave the first performance in modern
times of Paganini's Concerto No. 3.
   He made numerous recordings and authored several publications on
technique and interpretation.
   Szeryng was born in Warsaw Sept. 22, 1918 and educated in West
Germany, then in France, where he studied under Gabriel Bouillon
and Nadia Boulanger at the Paris Conservatory. In 1937, he
graduated with the coveted First Prize.
   Szeryng was firmly associated with the French school of violin
playing, although the major musical force behind him was Carl
Flesch.
   At the outbreak of World War II, Szeryng, who spoke eight
languages, was appointed liaison officer and interpreter for Gen.
Wladislaw Sikorski, premier of the Polish government-in-exile and
commander of the Free Polish Army.
   In 1941, he went with Sikorski to Latin America in search of a
home for about 4,000 Polish refugees. The refugees were accepted by
Mexico. Moved by this humanitarian gesture, Szeryng took on Mexican
citizenship in 1946.
   During the war, he performed more than 300 concerts for Allied
troops.
   He eventually became an adviser to the Mexican government on
cultural matters, but he maintained his base in Europe. He lived in
Paris for about 20 years, but for the past five years he lived in
Monaco and went to Mexico about twice a year.
   He was decorated by governments from Italy to Finland, including
France, which gave him its illustrious Legion of Honor in 1984.
   Szeryng made his American debut in Carnegie Hall in 1943 and
went on to make numerous recordings, reaping a Grammy award for one
of them.
   In 1970, he was appointed special music advisor to Mexico's
UNESCO delegation in Paris.
   Encouraged by Rubinstein to extend his musical activities
worldwide, Szeryng did so, increasing his reputation and making
numerous recordings with Rubinstein.
   Funeral services are to be held in Monte Carlo, Monaco, at a
still unspecified date, his Paris office said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0928EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ExitPolls     03-03 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exit Polls,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media Attorney Says Ruling on Exit Polling Sets Precedent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge set a precedent when he struck down
a Florida law that would keep reporters at least 150 feet from
polling places on election days, an attorney for three television
networks said.
   U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus ruled that reporters have a
constitutional right to speak to voters, but said they could be
kept 50 feet away from polling places.
   ``I think Judge Marcus' decision is going to be cited in a lot
of other states besides Florida and will be a significant part of a
body of law which is being formed striking down similar statutes
elsewhere,'' said Floyd Abrams, attorney for the ABC, CBS and NBC
networks.
   The networks, along with The Miami News, argued that reporters
needed to be closer to polling places to conduct exit polls during
next week's Super Tuesday voting.
   ``The decision will make it possible for more people to have
more information more quickly about the Super Tuesday results in
Florida than would have otherwise been conceivable,'' Abrams said.
   Marcus' decision left intact a provision of the law allowing
poll workers to keep the media, campaigners and petitioners 50 feet
away from the polls. David Kraslow, publisher of the News, said
that restriction would not interfere with exit polling.
   The decision is the second Florida ruling in a week against the
150-foot rule. U.S. District Judge Howell Melton in Jacksonville
ruled Friday that petitioners seeking to put a medical malpractice
measure on future ballots could also approach up to a 50-foot limit.
   Reporters ``have a constitutional right to engage in speech or
other expressive activities'' near the polls, Marcus said in his
opinion Wednesday. His decision followed similar rulings by federal
judges in Georgia and Washington state.
   David Leahy, Dade County's elections supervisor and a defendant
in the suit, said the decision left polling officials with
difficult choices.
   Since the Jacksonville ruling applied only to medical
malpractice petitioners and the Miami decision only to the media,
officials would be left in the uncomfortable decision of allowing
some people up to 50 feet away while others had to stay 150 feet
away.
   ``We are looking at abandoning any effort to enforce the
150-foot rule,'' Leahy said.
</TEXT>
