<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AnthemDispute     03-03 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anthem Dispute,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Banished From Homeroom for Singing National Anthem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school senior who has taken
to singing the national anthem aloud when it is played over the
school intercom in the morning has been banished from homeroom for
improper behavior.
   Paul Rennick, principal of North Kingstown High School, said
Sara Sprague is ``playing games'' by violating policy that requires
silence when ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' is played on the public
address system each morning.
   But Miss Sprague, 17, says her patriotic expression is a
``spontaneous reaction to the music.''
   Nevertheless, she has spent the last three weeks in the school
office each morning. Katherine Janis, her homeroom teacher, said
the singing and humming was part of ``noisy and disruptive''
behavior on the student's part.
   ``It's not a matter of discipline, it's a matter of the right of
a student to participate in singing the national anthem,'' said
Miss Sprague, a member of the school's concert choir.
   Her mother, Jane Sprague, said she backs her daughter.
   ``It's hard for me to believe that a school supported by local,
state and federal taxes won't let students sing the national anthem
if they want to,'' Mrs. Sprague said. ``I've never been anyplace
where the anthem was played that singing it wasn't welcome.''
   The controversy began last month when Miss Sprague began humming
along with the anthem. She was reprimanded by Ms. Janis.
   The next day Miss Sprague sang, quietly she says, and quickly
found herself in the assistant principle's office for a lecture on
homeroom behavior.
   The issue went public when Miss Sprague wrote a letter to a
local newspaper protesting her case.
   Rebecca Tougas, a member of the student council's executive
board, said the council will take up the issue in a survey of the
school's 1,600 students.
   ``This is a pretty patriotic school,'' Rennick said. ``The flag
is everywhere. George Washington is on the walls. It's not a
question of patriotism, it's a question of who's in charge.''
</TEXT>
