<NOTE>Eds: Inserts states in datelines of last 2 items.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan would return to a presidential
primary election in 1992 under a bill unanimously approved by a
legislative committee.
   The Senate Government Operations Committee voted 7-0 Wednesday
to replace the current caucus system of selecting presidential
convention delegates with a primary election on the third Tuesday
in March four years from now.
   ``I'd rather have a system more open than we have'' under the
bill, said Sen. Dick Posthumus, R-Alto, sponsor of the measure. But
he noted that Democratic objections to allowing ``crossover''
voting _ Democrats voting in Republican races and vice versa _
forced the party preference provision.
   However, unlike Michigan's earlier presidential primary, voters
would have to designate a party preference at least 30 days before
the election in order to vote. The party preference would be in
effect only for the presidential primary election, and not for
other primaries or general elections.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Opponents Fail To File Delegate Slates, So Bush Picks Up 24 NY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Delegates
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate George Bush
picked up 24 delegates in New York this week by virtue of his
opponents' failure to file delegate slates in eight of the state's
congressional districts.
   And successful challenges to non-Bush delegate slates in other
districts, if upheld by the courts, could leave the vice president
with at least two dozen other delegates running unopposed.
   The Board of Elections on Tuesday wiped two slates of delegates
supporting Bob Dole off the the April 19 primary ballot, one day
after stripping the Kansas senator's slate and one backing New York
Rep. Jack Kemp from the ballot.
   The petitions were rejected mainly because they did not contain
the required 1,250 signatures of registered Republicans, or were
signed by Republicans living outside the congressional district the
petitions were filed for.
   At stake in New York are 102 delegates, three from each
congressional district. The Republican state committee will
designate 34 other delegates after the primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Favorites In Early Quinnipiac College Poll </HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMDEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush and
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis emerged as the favorites in a
Quinnipiac College poll of Connecticut voters taken before the Iowa
caucuses and New Hampshire primary, the college said.
   The poll was based on telephone interviews between Jan. 25 and
Feb. 2 with 818 registered voters and showed that a large portion
was undecided on a favorite candidate for Connecticut's March 29
primary.
   The poll, the first of the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute
sampled, 256 Republicans, 316 Democrats and 212 unaffiliated
voters. It asked voters of each party which candidate they would
pick among those running in their party. Unaffiliated voters were
given a choice among candidates of both parties.
   Among the registered Republicans surveyed, 43.4 percent favored
Bush. Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas was in second place with 20.5
percent, while Rep. Jack Kemp of New York was third with 4.1
percent. The other Republican candidates polled less than 2
percent, while undecided Republicans totalled 25.4 percent.
   Of the Democrats polled, Dukakis had 32.6 percent of the vote,
followed by Gary Hart of Colorado with 13.4 percent and Jesse
Jackson of Illinois with 10.3 percent. Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois
had 4.8 percent, while none of the other candidates polled more
than 1.4 percent. Registered Democrats who said they were undecided
totalled 30.9 percent.
   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus five percentage
points, the college said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD> Hawaii Governor, Democratic Leaders Endorse Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. John Waihee has thrown the support of
Hawaii's Democratic Party leadership behind the presidental
campaign of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, abandoning the
uncommitted stance he and other party leaders had taken.
   ``I think the game is on the line Tuesday. We can stand on the
sidelines and watch, or we can get into the game,'' Waihee told a
news conference Wednesday, while Dukakis listened in from Miami,
Fla., on a telephone conference call.
   ``I'm sitting here glowing,'' Dukakis said, describing Waihee as
``a man who has shown great wisdom in his choice of presidential
candidates.''
   Waihee said the Dukakis endorsement has the backing of Hawaii's
U.S. Sens. Daniel Inouye and Spark Matsunaga and U.S. Rep. Daniel
Akaka, Lt. Gov. Ben Cayetano and other Democratic leaders.
   Waihee said he is encouraging Democrats to vote for Dukakis in
Hawaii's Super Tuesday precinct elections which will include a
presidential preference vote that will be binding on at least 20 of
Hawaii's 28 delegates to the Democratic Party National Convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Darden Endorses Gore For Democratic Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Buddy Darden, D-Ga., has endorsed
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee for the Democratic nomination for
president.
   Darden, a Democrat from Marietta, said in a statement released
Wednesday s office that he has been impressed by Gore's ``strong
stand for maintaining a national defense second to none.
   ``He realizes that all the rights and privileges guaranteed by
the Constitution depend on the preservation of our freedom and
independence,'' Darden said.
   ``He is the youngest candidate in the field and the only one who
served his country during the Vietnam conflict,'' he said. ``He
knows firsthand the challenges of low-intensity conflict which
America faces in the world today.''
   He said he decided that Gore offers ``the best overall plan for
leading America toward the challenges and opportunities of the
1990s and beyond.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hightower Backs Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim
Hightower has endorsed Jesse Jackson for the Democratic nomination
for president, saying Jackson is carrying a populist message to
voters and speaking for the little guys.
   ``I am here today not merely to endorse a presidential contender
but to make a statement of conscience, to stand as a matter of
principle with one who has stood consistently for the needs of the
many against the greed of the few,'' Hightower said.
   ``Jesse Jackson is speaking in a clear and an articulate voice
to an ignored majority of the American people whose lives have been
frustrated, if not actually flattened, by the economic policies of
recent years,'' the popular commissioner told a crowd of about 400
Wednesday in the Texas Senate chamber.
   Jackson called Hightower's endorsement ``an historic moment''
for his campaign and said it marks ``a revival of the soul of the
populist movement'' in the United States.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Group Pushes to Put Cuomo Name on California Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California backers of Mario Cuomo say
they have about half the 22,500 signatures they are seeking to try
to place the New York governor's name on California's June 7
Democratic presidential primary ballot.
   But state officials say that even if the draft-Cuomo committee
succeeds in collecting 22,500 verified signatures of California
voters by the March 24 deadline, they still won't add his name to
the ballot unless Cuomo authorizes the petition drive.
   ``The law and party rules make no provisions for unauthorized
slates (of delegates). Even if they get their signatures, we can't
place his name on the ballot,'' said secretary of state spokeswoman
Caren Daniels-Meade.
   ``You've got to have an official steering committee named by the
candidate. He has to be at least partially a willing participant,''
Daniels-Meade added.
   ``Our strategy all along has been to get the signatures and then
take her (California Secretary of State March Fong Eu) to court to
obtain an order placing the governor's name on the ballot,'' said
Los Angeles attorney Steven Polard, head of the California Draft
Cuomo for President Committee.
</TEXT>
