<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Scotland-AIDS-Addicts 1stLd-Writethru   03-03 0854</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotland-AIDS-Addicts, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0456,0877</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scottish Capital Hit By AIDS Epidemic Among Drug Addicts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, ``Acquired immune...is blamed,'' to ADD U.S.
statistic. Pick up 8th pvs, `Heroin smuggled...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well out of sight of tourists
strolling along the spectacular Royal Mile between Edinburgh's
medieval castle and Holyrood Palace, the Scottish capital is
grappling with a double epidemic of drug abuse and AIDS.
   The graceful old city, whose arts festival draws 600,000
visitors each summer, is becoming stigmatized as a European center
for drug-related AIDS.
   Unlike the rest of Britain, where drug addicts account for only
7 percent of AIDS carriers, needle-users make up 60 percent of the
infected population in Scotland and the majority live in Edinburgh.
The sharing of contaminated needles is one way that the AIDS virus
is transmitted.
   The number of full-blown AIDS cases in Scotland remains low _ 39
at the end of 1987 _ but 1,500 people in Edinburgh alone are
thought to be carrying the AIDS virus, an undetermined proportion
of whom will eventually die. The city of 440,000 inhabitants has
reported 824 confirmed AIDS carriers since mid-1983.
   Thirty-nine babies born in Edinburgh hospitals since 1985 had
AIDS antibodies, indicating their mothers were infected. It is not
known how many of the babies will develop AIDS.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's natural
immune system. Throughout most of Western Europe and the United
States, it has been confined largely to male homosexuals, although
it also affects hemophiliacs and intravenous drug users. About 25
percent of U.S. AIDS victims are intravenous drug users.
   In Edinburgh, AIDS is spread mainly through the sharing of
needles.
   Heroin smuggled through England's southern ports doubles in
price by the time it reaches this northern city and is so
adulterated that a dose becomes ineffective when inhaled or smoked.
   Edinburgh addicts, therefore, tend to inject drugs.
   ``There's a peculiar sort of Scottish characteristic here,''
explained Chief Inspector Douglas Kerr, Edinburgh's drug squad
chief. ``People didn't want to see themselves as being soft or
lacking guts. So anyone who failed to use heroin by injecting was
seen as copping out.''
   Also, needle-sharing ``is part of the scene in the same way that
a reefer is passed around at a party,'' he said. ``It's the social
thing.''
   Several specialists said a crackdown on drugs helped create a
needle shortage and may have quickened the spread of AIDS by
forcing more addicts to share.
   ``They're driving people, almost, into injecting,'' said Ray de
Souza, head of Simpson House, a drug rehabilitation center.
   But Kerr said experts were jumping to conclusions for want of
any other explanation for Edinburgh's predicament.
   With an estimated 2,000 to 3,000 drug abusers in Edinburgh, many
of them prostitutes, health officials are worried that AIDS will
spread into the general heterosexual population.
   ``It's the scale people are concerned about,'' said Carol
Skidmore, a psychologist with the Edinburgh Drug Addiction Study, a
research unit based at the West Granton Medical Group. She said the
infection rate among women due to sexual contact with male addicts
was 13 percent to 14 percent.
   An 11-doctor group in Muirhouse, a grim blue-collar district
known as ``Smack Alley,'' has 300 drug abusers among its 18,000
patients. Ms. Skidmore said 56 percent of the addicts are infected
with the AIDS virus _ and the clinic is having trouble coping with
them.
   Dr. George Bath, AIDS coordinator for the Lothian Health Board,
which is responsible for an area of 745,000 people in Edinburgh and
Lothian County, said the AIDS epidemic has created heavy demand for
screening and counseling.
   But so far, there's been minimal pressure on hospitals because
most of those carrying the virus are still well. ``The situation,''
he said in an interview, ``is the calm before the storm.''
   Drug abuse exploded in Scotland's inner cities in the early
1980s amid rising unemployment, social deprivation and plentiful
heroin. Edinburgh was hardest hit, although the industrial cities
of Glasgow and Dundee also experienced sharp rises in drug
trafficking.
   While Scottish officials cracked down on heroin, many addicts
simply switched to prescribed drugs, mainly painkillers and
tranquilizers, creating a new set of problems.
   ``We're finding that a lot of drug abusers are coming in to get
prescriptions for drugs because they're not able to get heroin,''
Ms. Skidmore said in an interview.
   ``They always want more than we're prepared to give. ... Really,
it's like a bottomless pit. You could just keep throwing
prescriptions at them and they would just keep using them.''
   Worse yet, she said, most addicts who switched from heroin were
taking prescription drugs in liquid form and still injecting them
despite the danger of AIDS.
   Last year, the government set up 15 pilot centers in British
cities, including Edinburgh, Glasgow and Dundee, where addicts can
swap old needles for new.
   Scottish Health Minister Michael Forsyth said in an interview
that he has extended government funding for the Scottish projects
through the end of March, but said preliminary results have been
disappointing. The Dundee clinic, for example, closed after only
six weeks.
</TEXT>
