<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Alcoholic-Discrimination     03-03 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alcoholic-Discrimination,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recovered Alcoholic Sues Government Successfully Over Firing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recovered alcoholic who was fired for
missing 389 days of work in three years has successfully sued his
federal employer for job discrimination because he didn't receive
legally mandated counseling.
   A federal judge ruled that Clarence Ferguson, 48, should be
allowed to re-apply for his job as a purchasing agent and ordered
the government to give him more than $150,000 in back pay.
   Ferguson said he didn't know he had a drinking problem until he
began attending Alcoholics Anonymous meetings regularly in 1984
after his dismissal from the National Wildlife Fisheries Service.
   A government worker for 20 years, Ferguson said he used to drink
a pint of gin daily. He doesn't drink now, he said.
   U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich, in a ruling Tuesday,
cited a federal law requiring all federal agencies to ``make
reasonable accommodations'' for handicapped workers, including
those who are alcoholics and drug addicts.
   ``This is a very specific federal mandate that says the federal
government has to take certain steps that the private sector
doesn't have to,'' said Ferguson's lawyer, Roger Benson.
   Attorneys for the government argued they couldn't offer Ferguson
counseling before firing him because he never told them he was an
alcoholic. He never smelled of alcohol, never staggered and didn't
sneak drinks, they said during a non-jury trial last month.
   But Kovachevich ruled he was legally crippled by alcoholism and
that his employers should have helped him get counseling before
dismissing him. His absenteeism should have been a tipoff, she said.
   Attorneys for the Department of Commerce, which controls the
fisheries service, declined comment on whether they will appeal.
   The U.S. Supreme Court is scheduled to hear arguments that could
legally define alcoholism as a disease and carry consequences for
the private sector.
   The nation's highest court agreed last October to hear a
challenge filed against the Veterans Administration for excluding
alcoholism from a list of illnesses and disabilities that veterans
can claim when seeking more time to apply for education benefits.
   The VA policy defines alcoholism as ``willful misconduct.''
</TEXT>
