<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Ferret Killing,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced For Shooting Friend In Ferret Quarrel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 18-year-old man who shot and killed his
best friend during an argument over a pet ferret was sentenced to
four to five years in prison.
   Michael L. James, sentenced Wednesday in Douglas County District
Court, said he would always regret the shooting of David Klotz, 20.
   ``I'd like to say something to his parents that I haven't
said,'' James said. ``Really, I'm sorry.''
   James shot Klotz in the head Sept. 6 at the apartment they
shared. Witnesses told police James threatened to kill a pet ferret
because it had fleas. Klotz protested and James shot him after a
struggle, authorities said.
   Judge Jerry Gitnick sentenced James to three to five years in
prison for manslaughter and to one additional year for using a
weapon in the commission of a felony.
   He originally was charged with second-degree murder but pleaded
guilty to the manslaughter and weapon charges.
</TEXT>
