<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0593 03-03 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0593,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Offers Rebels High-level Talks In Nicaragua, Without
Mediator</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf: `It was...,' to UPDATE with
Contra comment. Pick up 4th graf pvs: `Nicaragua previously...'
Edits thereafter to conform and tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government for the first time
offered to hold peace talks with Contra rebels inside Nicaragua and
recommended they be conducted without a go-between because past
mediation produced no results.
   President Daniel Ortega said Wednesday the talks should be held
March 10-12 in the Nicaraguan town of Sapoa near the Costa Rican
border. He also said his brother, Defense Minister Humberto Ortega,
would lead the Sandinista delegation.
   It was the first time the leftist Sandinista government proposed
negotiations in Nicaraguan territory with the U.S.-backed rebels,
and it would be the highest-level Sandinista delegation to meet
directly with the Contras.
   In Miami, the Contras had no immediate response to the proposal,
but a spokesman said today they viewed it with suspicion.
   ``We are following the situation closely and with concern,''
said Jorge Rosales, spokesman for the Nicaraguan Resistance,
umbrella organization for rebel groups. ``We have to have
first-hand information.''
   ``The Sandinistas have violated the peace accords and don't
honor their own signature,'' he said.
   Nicaragua previously demanded that the rebels accept a
government amnesty as a condition for meeting inside Nicaragua.
Until now, the highest-ranking Sandinista negotiator has been a
deputy foreign minister.
   Ortega made the announcement after meeting for 20 minutes with
Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, who mediated two rounds of
cease-fire talks with the Contras.
   The last round of negotiations broke off Feb. 19 in Guatemala
after the cardinal declared an impasse. The first meeting, in Costa
Rica, was noted both for its cordial atmosphere and lack of
progress.
   Ortega said he decided ``to take the bull by the horns'' because
Obando y Bravo's efforts to halt the 7-year-old war had produced no
results.
   Erick Ramirez, leader of the opposition Social Christian Party
in Managua, said the cardinal's dismissal ``will mean an increase
in war and violence ... because the cardinal had the confidence of
the people.''
   ``I expressed to Cardinal Obando my concern over time passing by
and that, as he himself had said, we must take the bull by the
horns and that a direct contact at the highest level and here in
Nicaragua would be very important because it would make the job of
the mediator unnecessary,'' Ortega said.
   The peace talks are being conducted under a Central American
peace plan signed last August by the presidents of Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Costa Rica, Guatemala and Honduras.
   Ortega publicly thanked Obando y Bravo for his efforts, adding:
``We would not have reached this decisive moment where we will put
to the test the will to work for a cease-fire if we had not had his
contribution in this first phase when there was no direct contact
with the counterrevolution and when the role of the mediator was
necessary and indispensable.''
   ``I hope they can find peace now, even if I am not there anymore
as mediator,'' Obando y Bravo told The Associated Press a few hours
later. ``I have often said that a mediator is necessary when both
parties want him. I hope they find peace and put an end to the war,
the suffering.''
   ``We worked a lot. There were many problems at first. They (the
government) refused to meet in Central America first, then they
did; then they had refused to meet in Nicaragua, now they are
proposing it,'' the cardinal said.
   Ortega said: ``They (the Contras) cannot have any excuse now.
They themselves have requested the highest level talks possible and
in Nicaragua. This is a delegation of the highest level.''
   Before Wednesday, Ortega had insisted the Contras seek a
government amnesty forcing them to pledge to stop fightingbefore
they would be allowed into the country to hold cease-fire talks.
   Obando y Bravo sent a letter to Ortega earlier Wednesday calling
for a resumption in truce talks. Ortega left him a letter in reply,
outlining his decision proposing new negotiations without a
mediator.
   The cardinal said he had read the letter to leaders of the
Nicaraguan Resistance.
   The regional peace plan calls for cease-fires in civil wars in
Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala; as well as amnesties, greater
democracy, the end of using a country's territory to launch attacks
on a neighbor and a halt to outside aid to insurgents in the region.
</TEXT>
