<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeanResigns     03-03 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dean Resigns,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dean Says Resignation Voluntary After Slaying In His Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A university dean has confirmed that a
man accused of a slaying in his home is his former lover, but says
he was not pressured into resigning because of the scandal over the
killing.
   Timothy J. Lyons, dean of Youngstown State University's College
of Fine and Performing Arts, on Wednesday confirmed a police
affidavit that identified the defendant as his former lover.
   Brian Scott Blevins, 22, of Boardman, is charged with murder in
the Feb. 12 death of Kenmore B. Drake. Blevins is in jail in lieu
of $250,000 bond.
   Drake, 21, was staying at Lyons' home while Lyons was in
California visiting his daughters. Lyons said he and Drake were
friends, not lovers.
   ``It is essential to the police case to establish my
homosexuality, that Scott Blevins and I lived as lovers,'' Lyons,
43, told reporters Wednesday. ``I don't resent that people know
something is true. I have a problem with the way people react. ...
My homosexuality is so damned irrelevant to my profession.''
   Youngstown State officials announced Tuesday that Lyons would
leave his post Monday because of ``difficulties'' resulting from
Drake's death. University officials have not commented on the
situation, other than to issue Lyons' resignation statement.
   Drake, a Youngstown State senior, was stabbed about 50 times
with a pair of scissors, the Mahoning County coroner's office says.
Blevins was not a university student.
   Lyons said he persuaded the university's board of trustees to
consider his resignation and that he wasn't pressured to quit.
   Lyons said he's upset that people are allowing his homosexuality
to overshadow the fact that ``a good man is dead.''
   Lyons said he planned to leave the area after his testimony if
the case goes to trial. He said he didn't know if he would stay in
academics.
   Lyons is to be paid his salary, $59,000 a year, through Dec. 31.
He joined Youngstown State as dean in 1985.
</TEXT>
