<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReverseDiscrimination     03-03 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reverse Discrimination,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mistrial in Reverse Bias Case Declared After Former Police Chief
Admits Lying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mistrial was declared in a reverse
discrimination case of four white police officers after Chicago's
former head of police admitted he lied under oath.
   U.S. District Judge Paul E. Plunkett declared the mistrial
Wednesday in the $12 million lawsuit, in which four officers say
they were demoted because of their race and for political reasons.
The judge said former Police Superintendent Fred Rice's admission
and reasons he cited for lying tainted the jury and undercut the
case.
   Matthew Piers, an assistant corporation counsel for the city who
represented Rice, said it was ``ridiculous'' when asked if Rice
could face perjury charges. ``It is not a possibility at all,''
Piers said.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas would not comment.
   Piers had argued against a mistrial, telling the judge that
Rice's admission harmed no one but himself. ``A mistrial is a gross
injustice to the defendant's case,'' he said.
   But Plunkett did not agree. He said he would rule April 13 on a
request for a default judgment in favor of the four officers.
   A few months after the 1983 election of Harold Washington, the
city's first black mayor, Rice was named as the first black police
superintendent, and 25 white officers were demoted.
   Four officers are seeking $12 million from the city, maintaining
they were demoted because they are white and because they supported
Washington's Democratic primary opponent, former Mayor Jane Byrne.
   Rice said politics had no part in any reassignments during his
years as police superintendent.
   In court Tuesday, Rice said he concealed his real reasons for
demoting a number of ranking white officers to protect their
reputations and preserve police morale. He said ``negative
information'' was a factor in the demotions.
   Rice, 61, said he lied in depositions taken in October 1984 and
August 1985 when he was still superintendent. He retired last year.
   Rice's unexpected admission brought an angry response from
Edward Theobald, attorney for the plaintiffs, one current and three
former officers.
   ``You know it's a felony crime, and you deliberately lied when
you were sworn to tell the truth,'' Theobald contended.
   ``That's right,'' said Rice, who said ``there were extenuating
circumstances that caused me to say the things I did.''
   ``I tried to be as considerate to those people as possible,''
the former police chief said. ``I felt I was protecting the
reputation of all the people I reduced.''
   Theobald requested the mistrial and asked Plunkett for a default
judgment.
   In a telephone interview late Wednesday, Theobald said that if
the judge rules in the officers' favor, a jury would be chosen to
set damages. If Plunkett denies the default judgment, a new trial
would begin.
</TEXT>
