<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Lugar'sMother 1stLd-Writethru a0617 03-03 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lugar's Mother, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0617,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Of Sen. Richard Lugar Found Safe In Illinois</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with woman located.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of U.S. Sen. Richard G. Lugar was
reported missing early today by relatives, but she was found
unharmed in Illinois by mid-morning, according to a spokesman for
the senator.
   ``We assume that she was driving around and got disoriented,''
Andy Fisher, an aide to the Indiana Republican, said from
Washington.
   Bertha Lugar Caldwell, 81, may have gotten disoriented while
driving late Wednesday in Indianapolis, which is about 70 miles
from the Illinois state line, Fisher said.
   Fisher would not specify where Mrs. Caldwell was but said she
was OK and at a hotel. Relatives were en route.
   ``There was no foul play involved,'' said Wendy Snitko of the
Indianapolis Police Department.
   Fisher said a doctor probably would examine Mrs. Caldwell in
Indianapolis but that her health ``has been fine all along.''
   ``It is one of these things that happens from time to time with
older people. She may have gotten disoriented.''
   Mrs. Caldwell was reported missing about 1:30 a.m. today by her
stepdaughter, Lynn Caldwell.
   She had last been seen Wednesday night driving in the city's
northside.
   Sally Lugar, wife of the senator's brother Thomas, said she
received a call late Wednesday from a friend who said she had seen
Mrs. Caldwell driving her car at the Christian Theological Seminary.
   ``With the weather, we were a little concerned,'' Mrs. Lugar
said. ``I called at her home. When I didn't get an answer, I went
over. It's been a long night.''
   There was rain, freezing rain and sleet in the area during the
night.
</TEXT>
