<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LorraineResident     03-03 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lorraine Resident,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protester Says Night on Street Was Long, Wet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wrapped in a clear plastic sheet to ward
off drizzle, Jacqueline Smith today sat on a sidewalk and protested
plans to make a civil rights museum out of the small motel where
Martin Luther King Jr. was killed.
   Ms. Smith, who was forcibly evicted Wednesday from The Lorraine
Motel, said she would stay in front of the motel as long as she
could.
   ``I don't mind being a little uncomfortable,'' she said. ``I'll
try to sit here as long as my body allows.''
   Ms. Smith said several friends dropped by during the night to
offer food and encouragement and two supporters took turns sitting
with her until daybreak.
   She was carried from the motel by Shelby County sheriff's
deputies who deposited her just outside an 8-foot chain-link
surrounding The Lorraine, which was closed last month to make way
for an $8.8 million museum.
   ``You people are making a mistake. You people are making a
mistake,'' Ms. Smith sobbed as the deputies evicted her.
   The Lorraine was closed Jan. 11, but Ms. Smith ignored repeated
requests to move from her room, about 25 feet from where King was
felled by an assassin's rifle slug.
   Ms. Smith, who has lived and worked at The Lorraine for 11
years, argued that the motel should be turned into shelter for the
homeless, not a museum. She argued a museum will speed efforts to
gentrify her low-income neighborhood.
   The Lorraine, which has fallen into disrepair over the years,
was bought at a foreclosure auction in 1982 by a group pushing
plans for a museum.
   The state has appropriated $4.4 million for the project and city
and county governments have agreed to match that. The state has
title to the property and will build and operate the museum,
scheduled to open in 1991.
   King was in Memphis to help organize a strike by city sanitation
workers. James Earl Ray, a prison escapee from Missouri, pleaded
guilty to the killing and is serving a 99-year sentence at the
Southeast Tennessee Regional Prison near Pikeville.
</TEXT>
