<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Hostage 7thLd-Writethru a0604 03-03 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostage, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0604,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Hostage Freed, Taken To Syria</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Schray turned over to embassy,
ADD quotes from mother, CORRECT captor's name to `for Freedom' sted
`of;' CHANGES byline. no pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede BEIRUT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German hostage Ralph Rudolf Schray
was freed by his pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem kidnappers in Beirut
today and turned over to the West German embassy in Damascus,
officials said.
   An embassy employee in Damascus, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said he saw Schray being escorted into the embassy at
around noon. The 30-year-old industrial engineer was kidnapped Jan.
27 and released before dawn.
   ``He is still inside, resting and waiting for his wife,'' the
employee said. ``A car has been sent to Beirut to bring her.''
   A military source at the Syrian command in Beirut, also speaking
on condition of anonymity, told The Associated Press that Schray
was driven to the Syrian capital, 56 miles east of Beirut, under
heavy Syrian escort.
   In a statement issued in Bonn, Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher thanked the Syrian government for its help. A ministry
statement said Schray was in good physical condition.
   Schray, a Lebanese-born West German, was seized in Moslem west
Beirut. A Shiite faction, Holy Warriors for Freedom, on Wednesday
claimed responsibility for his abduction.
   The group also claimed responsibility for kidnapping two other
West Germans in Beirut in January 1987. It is believed headed by
the brother of two Lebanese Shiite Moslems who are being held in
West Germany on terrorism and kidnapping charges.
   Schray's mother, Fahima Schray, called her son's captivity ``the
most terrible days of my life. It was so difficult.'' Mrs. Schray
was interviewed in Fort Myers, Fla.
   ``I couldn't sleep last night one minute. This morning,
everything has changed completely, as if I'm a new woman,'' she
said.
   Schray's Lebanese wife of six months, Rana Mounla, and his
uncle, George abu Nassar, left by car for Damascus carrying a
suitcase of clothes for the freed German.
   ``I'm going to see him,'' a beaming Mrs. Schray told reporters.
``I'm taking clothes for him.''
   She indicated that she planned to return to Beirut with her
husband from Damascus. ``When we're back together in Beirut
tomorrow we'll both talk to you,'' she said. She declined to
elaborate.
   Abu Nassar, a wealthy Lebanese businessman of Palestinian
descent, refused to talk to reporters.
   There are still 22 foreigners missing after being kidnapped in
Lebanon. They include nine Americans, four Frenchmen, three
Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian and two
unidentified men.
   Longest held is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   The Holy Warriors for Freedom made its claim in a typewritten
Arabic statement released to the Reuters news agency in Beirut. It
was accompanied by a recent snapshot of Schray.
   The statement said Schray could be released within hours as a
result of mediation by Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Abdul-Hadi Hamadi is reputed to lead the Holy Warriors for
Freedom, and he also heads the security apparatus of the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Hamadi's brother, Abbas Hamadi, is on trial in West Germany on
charges of kidnapping West Germans Rudolf Cordes and Alfred Schmidt
in January 1987 in Beirut.
   Those kidnappings allegedly were to pressure the Bonn government
into releasing a third Hamadi brother, Mohammed, who is being held
in Frankfurt on terrorism charges.
   In their statement Wednesday, the kidnappers said that while
they were negotiating with the West Germans over Schray, ``a
mediation team from the brothers in Syria, led by President Assad,
gave a chance for a new round of commitments that made the case of
the German Schray head for a solution within the coming hours.''
   ``The Hamadi brothers are still in Germany. The release (of
Schray) is goodwill gesture No. 2,'' it added.
   Schmidt, 47, was released Sept. 7 as a goodwill gesture. Cordes,
53, is still in captivity.
   Mohammed Hamadi has been indicted in the United States on murder
and air piracy charges in connection with the June 1985 hijacking
of a TWA jetliner in which 39 Americans were held hostage and a
U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   He was arrested Jan. 13, 1987 when he arrived at Frankfurt
airport carrying explosives. The Bonn government last year turned
down a U.S. request for his extradition, saying he will be tried in
West Germany on similar charges.
   Cordes was kidnapped in Beirut on Jan. 17, 1987, and Schmidt
seven days later, on Jan. 21, 1987.
   Abbas Hamadi was arrested also upon arriving at Frankfurt
airport Jan. 26, five days after Schmidt was abducted.
 
</TEXT>
