<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hostage'sMom     03-03 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage's Mom,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Of Lebanon Hostage Says Son's Release Is Great Relief</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a West German industrial
engineer freed early today after being kidnapped in Lebanon five
weeks ago said the news ended the ``most terrible days of my life.''
   Farina Schray said she was waiting for word from her only child,
30-year-old Ralph Rudolf Schray, who was abducted Jan. 27 in Moslem
west Beirut.
   Schray was freed unharmed before dawn today by Shiite Moslem
kidnappers and taken to Damascus. He was reported in good physical
condition.
   ``It was so difficult,'' said Ms. Schray, who is visiting her
son's uncle. ``We were praying all the time. ... It was the most
terrible days of my life.''
   Ms. Schray said that during the ordeal she has maintained
contact with her son's wife of six months, Rana Mounla.
   Ms. Schray said she wasn't sure how long she will stay in
Florida or if her son will come here. If he doesn't, she will
probably return to her Beirut home in a week or so, she said.
   The Syrian government was credited with mediating the release of
Schray, a Lebanese-born West German. Since March 1985, 22
foreigners have been kidnapped in Lebanon, including nine
Americans, four Frenchmen, three Britons, a West German, an
Italian, an Irishman and Indian and two unidentified men.
   Longest held is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
