<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1125EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaTrial     03-03 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Trial,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Witness Says Meteorologist Was Negligent in Jet Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meteorologist says it would have made
``all the difference in the world'' if National Weather Service
forecasters had passed along information about a thunderstorm that
downed Delta Airlines Flight 191.
   William Haggard also criticized a weather service meteorologist
assigned to monitor weather near Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport for going to dinner 40 minutes before the crash.
   Flight 191 crashed Aug. 2, 1985, while attempting to land at
Dallas-Fort Worth during a severe thunderstorm, killing 137 people
and injuring 25 others.
   Delta is suing the government, claiming the failure of weather
service employees and air traffic controllers to warn the flight
crew of the storm was a primary cause of the crash.
   The National Transportation Safety Board concluded that the
crash was caused in part by the pilot's decision to fly into an
area of potential wind shear, a violent downdraft of air beneath
thunderstorms.
   The L-1011 widebody jet was hit by such a downdraft while
approaching the runway, and slammed into airport water tanks and
exploded into flames.
   Haggard, who owns a private meteorological consulting firm in
North Carolina, said Wednesday that government meteorologist
Richard Douglass should not have left his post for more than 10
minutes on the evening of the crash because conditions suggested
dangerous weather might be ahead.
   ``I think all the difference in the world would have been made
if he (Douglass) had been there and been alert,'' Haggard said.
``He would have had the opportunity to call the (control) tower and
warn them.''
   Justice Department attorney Kathlynn Fadely has argued that the
Delta flight crew knew of the thunderstorm in its landing path when
co-pilot Rudolph Price spotted lightning about 1{ minutes before
the crash.
   Haggard testified that while Douglass was at dinner, a second
forecaster stationed at Stephenville, southwest of Fort Worth,
spotted signs of a storm but telephoned his warning to the weather
service in Fort Worth instead of the airport control tower. He said
weather service officials failed to relay that warning in the
minutes before the crash.
   The non-jury trial will determine whether the government must
pay part of $91.2 million in claims that Delta's insurers have paid
so far in connection with the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
