<DOCNO> AP880303-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-PolygraphBan 3rdLd-Writethru a0639-0621 03-03 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygraph Ban, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0639-0621,890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted overwhelmingly today to
prohibit most employers from using lie detectors to screen job
applicants and randomly test the honesty of employees.
   On a 69-27 vote, the Senate passed a bill by senators Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., and Orrin Hatch, R-Utah _ normally adversaries on
labor-management issues _ over the objections of a small group of
conservative Republicans.
   A similar but more stringent ban was approved last November by
the House. Differences between the two versions must be resolved
and a compromise passed by both houses.
   Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., a leader of the opposition, predicted
that President Reagan would sign a polygraph bill despite a vow by
administration officials last year that they would encourage him to
veto it.
   ``The administration does not have the backbone at this time to
veto this bill,'' Quayle complained. ``They have folded up shop,
caving like a house of cards.''
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., another opponent, predicted that
denying employers the opportunity to screen job applicants using
polygraph examinations will raise consumer costs through increased
thefts on the job.
   Kennedy and Hatch, however, said no one has presented any
statistics in states where use of the test already is prohibited to
demonstrate a higher incidence of theft or embezzlement.
   Hatch called the softening of the administration's opposition
``encouraging.''
   ``Some 320,000 honest Americans are branded as liars every
single year because of these devices,'' he said. ``That's a stigma
they are going to have to wear every day the rest of their lives
and careers.''
   Kenneday said the polygraph has become ``to the 20th century
what witchcraft was two centuries ago.''
   ``We're going to see the day where the average worker is going
to be able to walk into the workplace with dignity and
self-respect,'' he said. ``These devices are no longer going to
scar people in ways that they and their families can never forget.''
   The Senate voted after Quayle, Cochran and Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, dropped plans to introduce three more amendments aimed at
weakening the ban.
   The House version would ban all use of polygraph examinations in
private industry except for security personnel and pharmaceutical
companies.
   While imposing the same prohibitions on lie detectors to screen
job applicants, the Senate measure would allow their use to
investigate incidents of ``economic loss or injury'' such as
alleged thefts or other criminal acts, but only under strict
regulations to be enforced by the Labor Department.
   Hatch said the compromise acceptable to many retailers and other
companies plagued by thefts was formulated primarily by leaders of
the 1-million-member United Food and Commercial Workers Union.
   ``Honest people each year are branded as liars,'' Hatch said,
because of false results from polygraph tests often administered in
15 minutes and in ways that minimize their accuracy.
   ``Conversely,'' he said, ``it is a regrettable fact that
employees steal. This bill addresses both concerns by barring use
of polygraphs where they are most likely to make a false
identification but permitting the use of these tests where they are
likely to be most accurate ... in conjunction with the
investigation of a specific incident.''
   Before any test, employers would first have to file a police
report, insurance claim or report to a regulatory agency _ or sign
a statement detailing their reasons for testing a specific worker.
   And the tests would have to be administered under strict
guidelines to be developed by the Labor Department requiring at
least 90 minutes for each exam.
   Violations could result in fines of up to $10,000 each, and
employees or job applicants would have the right to file civil
suits against offenders.
   Disciplining or firing employees for refusing to take the test
or for failing it without additional supporting evidence of
wrongdoing would be prohibited.
   Administration officials have said they would urge President
Reagan to veto the House version as an unwarranted federal
intrusion into labor-management relations and pre-emption of state
regulations.
   The administration also has gone on record opposing the Senate
measure but not in as strong terms.
   Kennedy, citing reports from the congressional Office of
Technology Assessment and the American Medical Association that the
tests give false results 15 percent to 50 percent of the time,
called lie detectors ``inaccurate instruments of intimidation.''
   ``We know that in most applications, the devices cannot be
trusted,'' he said. ``It is time to put an end to their
unacceptable misuse that unfairly places so many workers' jobs in
jeopardy.''
   The legislation was prompted by an explosive growth _ ``like
wildfire,'' according to Kennedy _ in the use of lie detector tests
by employers over the past eight years.
   An estimated 2 million people are now subjected to the tests
each year, double the number just three years ago, according to
Kennedy. He and Hatch estimated their bill would outlaw about 85
percent of those tests.
   Like the House, the Senate voted Wednesday to also exempt
security guards, armored car companies and firms that install and
service security alarms from the prohibition.
   And it extended the House exemption to include workers at
nuclear power plants and contract employees hired by the government
with access to classified information.
   However, it rejected several other amendments aimed at weakening
the ban, such as allowing the tests if employees request them and
exemptions for airline, railroad and other employees in the
transportation industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
