<1ST_LINE>r a PM-10-YearEscapee     03-03 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-10-Year Escapee,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alderson Escapee Caught After 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALDERSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman located through income tax errors
has pleaded guilty to escaping from a federal women's prison 10
years ago, but even a prosecutor cites her good behavior since then.
   Mary Hughey Cantrell, who failed to return from a 1977 Christmas
furlough, pleaded guilty Wednesday in federal court in Beckley to a
charge of escape from the Alderson Federal Correctional
Institution. She was returned to the prison to await her April 22
sentencing.
   The charge carries a maximum five-year sentence and a $5,000
fine.
   Federal public defender Ira Kirkendoll said Cantrell, 40,
originally from North Carolina, moved to Arizona shortly after her
escape and apparently remained law-abiding while working for
several years as a maid in private homes and resorts.
   ``It's pretty unusual, the length of time,'' Kirkendoll said.
``Apparently she has reformed to some degree.''
   Even Assistant U.S. Attorney Kirk Brandfass said the woman's
decade of crime-free living, aside from maintaining a false
identity, should be considered at sentencing.
   ``My heavens, that ought to count for something,'' Brandfass
said outside court.
   U.S. marshals wouldn't allow an interview with Cantrell, who had
been sentenced to three years after a 1975 conviction for passing
counterfeit money.
   She was paroled in May 1976 but was returned to the Alderson
prison in early 1977 after a parole violation, and has about 470
days left to serve on her original sentence.
   She was arrested Jan. 5 in Phoenix, Ariz.
   During her 10 years of freedom, Cantrell acquired an
acquaintance's identification cards. She was discovered after the
Internal Revenue Service spotted a discrepancy in income tax
returns for a woman who had never worked in Arizona.
   ``Then it was a matter of running the paychecks back to where
they were earned,'' Brandfass said. ``And it zeroed in at Phoenix,
Ariz. I'm told she was pretty stunned when the marshals showed up
to get her.''
</TEXT>
