<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDS-Bennett     03-03 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Bennett,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Renews Call for Sexual Abstinence Among Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett today
renewed his call for sexual abstinence among teen-agers as their
best defense against AIDS, and said he and Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop are not as far apart on the issue as perceived.
   Bennett was responding to a statement by retired Adm. James D.
Watkins, chairman of President Reagan's AIDS commission, that one
of the panel's main tasks is to resolve seemingly differing
opinions in making its recommendations this summer.
   Commenting on publicized differences between Bennett and Koop
over what emphasis to place on urging sexually active people to use
condoms, Watkins said, ``Whether it is real or non-substantive, it
is a real perception out there.''
   Watkins said many witnesses have told the commission they fear
top federal officials are sending ``equivocal messages'' to the
nation on AIDS prevention and that it is important for the federal
government to speak with one voice on the issue.
   ``Dr. Koop and I are very close, extremely close,'' said
Bennett. `'I think Koop and I agree 95 percent of the way. It's all
right for the surgeon general and the secretary of education to
speak a little differently about these things.''
   He compared it to a young woman or man who might discuss ``what
he or she is doing'' with a doctor with a counselor.
   ``The doctor's advice would probably emphasize the medical
aspects, as it should,'' said Bennett. ``The teacher or counselor's
advice might emphasize other things. Some shading of difference is
OK. Some measure of disagreement is OK.''
   ``When the American people ask for leadership, they are not
saying, `we're a bunch of dummies, tell us what to think','' said
Bennett, ``They want to know our best thinking. And if our best
thinking diverges on some points, they can handle it.''
   Although saying he agrees that people, including teen-agers,
need to know that condom and spermicide use offers the only
protection against contracting AIDS sexually, Bennett said it was a
matter of emphasis.
   What he fears, he said, is teachers going through ``a kind of
incantation'' on abstinence and sexual monogamy in AIDS prevention
classes, ``then proceeding for the rest of the class to talk (to
teen-agers) about how to protect themselves.''
   ``It's like saying, don't smoke, but if you do, smoke low tar.
Don't drink, but if you do, keep it to 70 proof. I think these are
equivocal messages.''
   Koop told the White House AIDS commission earlier in the week
that while it is important to recommend abstinence, ``I think it is
also realistic to understand that sexually active teen-agers are
unlikely to reverse their pattern and go backward, and therefore
prevention for them has to be our third line of defense. ... We
have to teach them about the protection of themselves and others
through the use of condoms and spermicides.''
</TEXT>
