<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MurderCharge     03-03 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murder Charge,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Football Star Charged in 31-Year-Old Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former football star who now is a
college athletic director has been charged with first-degree murder
in the 31-year-old slaying of a reputed whiskey runner, police said.
   Bobby Hoppe, 53, of Ringgold, Ga., and athletic director at
Chattanooga State Technical Community College, was arrested
Wednesday after a Hamilton County grand jury indicted him for the
1957 shotgun death of Teddy Donald Hudson in North Chattanooga.
   Hoppe's arrest followed a 14-month investigation by two
Chattanooga detectives who interviewed at least 45 witnesses after
reopening the case, police said.
   Hoppe was a suspect in the original 1957 investigation, said
police spokesman Freeman Cooper.
   ``Allegations were made during that investigation that Hoppe had
shot Hudson over his (Hoppe's) sister, whom Hudson was dating at
the time,'' Cooper read from a statement. ``However, police could
not develop enough evidence to arrest him.''
   After Hudson, 24, was shot to death in a car near his home,
police investigated the possibility that the slaying was related to
the moonshine liquor business, for which Hudson had served time
previously.
   The investigation was reopened after Hudson's mother, Georgia,
talked with detectives following a meeting of Families and Friends
of Murder Victims, a support and counseling group.
   At the time of the slaying, Hoppe was a starter on the Alabama
Polytechnic Institute, now Auburn University, football team that
went on to win a national championship. Before that, he was an
all-state player at Chattanooga's Central High School.
   Hoppe, who was released after posting $7,000 bond, said
Wednesday: ``My attorney has told me not to make a statement. ... I
am not going to answer more questions.''
</TEXT>
