<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0638,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Agree To Nine-Month Timetable For Soviet Withdrawal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with announcement of
agreement. Pick up 4th graf pvs: `Soviet leader...' Edits
thereafter to conform and trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators in the U.N.-sponsored Afghanistan
peace talks agreed today that the Soviet Union should withdraw its
115,000 soldiers from the country within nine months.
   Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil announced the agreement and
told reporters that half the troops would leave within the first
three months.
   Wakil said the accord was reached during 2{ hours of meetings
that U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez conducted separately today with
Afghan and Pakistani representatives.
   ``Nothing important stands in the way of concluding a
settlement,'' Wakil said. The accord on the timetable had been
expected after the gap between the two sides' positions had
narrowed from an original 43 months to two months in almost six
years of negotiations.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev last month had said Moscow would
bring home its troops within 10 months starting May 15 provided a
settlement is signed in Geneva by March 15.
   Cordovez planned to brief U.S. and Soviet officials later,
including Deputy U.S. Secretary of State Robert Peck, sources said.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in 1979 and replaced the
communist government with another communist regime. They have been
helping the government fight anti-communist Moslem guerrillas.
   A new U.N. report said success at the Geneva talks may leave a
primary problem unresolved: the return of more than 5 million
Afghan refugees who fled the war to neighboring Pakistan and Iran.
   The head of the Pakistani delegation, acting Foreign Minister
Zain Noorani, told reporters that Islamabad wants a broad-based
transitional government to be set up, but would not specify when
that should be done.
   ``We are firmly convinced that a settlement without creating
circumstances of peace and stability in Afghanistan will not
pursuade 5 million Afghan refugees ...to return,'' he said.
   Asked when such a government should take office, he said the
timing depends ``on when efforts to bring about a settlement among
the Afghans can be visibly seen and when we are able to pursuade
all parties concerned '' to establish it.
   Before the new round got under way Wednesday, Cordovez
reaffirmed that the future makeup of the Kabul government is
outside the scope of negotiations.
   The Soviets also have said they are not interested in
influencing its composition.
   The U.N. report, prepared for the 43-nation U.N. Human Rights
Commission, warned that most refugees were unlikely to return
unless the Afghan government is replaced by one that includes
opposition and refugee representation.
   The report also says the human rights situation in Afghanistan
has improved, though there is evidence political prisoners are
still being tortured and killed.
   The regime of President Najib is backed by little more than the
115,000 Red Army troops.
   The ``national reconciliation'' policy Najib proclaimed more
than a year ago has failed, Austrian jurist Felix Ermacora, special
investigator for the 43-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission, says
in the 29-page report.
   Ermacora visited refugees in Pakistan and government-controlled
areas of Afghanistan in January.
   He says in the report that most refugees he spoke with said they
would return only when ``the foreign troops had withdrawn and a
government in which they had confidence had been established.''
   Government sources were quoted in the report as saying there
were 3,147 political prisoners in January, though more than 7,000
had been released under amnesty decrees.
   But the report cites ``reliable reports'' that political
prisoners had recently been killed in the Kabul area and that there
had been torture in Ghazni province.
   It says the new Afghan constitution makes no provision ``for
free, secret and universal elections to the National Assembly'' in
balloting to be held by June. Ermacora says he doubts the Najib
regime will allow multi-party participation.
   The United States last year gave an estimated $700 million worth
of military assistance to the 200,000 guerrillas.
</TEXT>
