<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     03-03 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16 Killed in Tamil Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels disguised as soldiers
attacked a village with submachine guns and automatic rifles and
killed 16 people, a military official said today. Most of the
victims were woman and children.
   In a separate incident today, three rebels were killed in a gun
battle with police manning a roadblock in the southeast.
   Police Chief S. Wijesinghe of the Ampara district said there
were no police casualties. Police seized a Chinese-made T-56 rifle
and a submachine gun from the slain rebels, he said.
   The military official said the 16 were killed Wednesday at
Morawewa village, 27 miles west of Trincomalee port on the eastern
coast of Sri Lanka. He spoke on condition of anonymity according to
regulations.
   The victims included nine children, four women and three men, he
said. All were Sinhalese except for one Tamil. Three people were
injured.
   The official blamed the attack on members of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest rebel group. The Tigers have
been at the forefront of a four-year war for a separate Tamil
homeland and have targeted attacks on the majority Sinhalese
community.
   The Tigers were blamed for the killings of more than 200
Sinhalese in October last year soon after they renounced a peace
accord aimed at ending the separatist war.
   More than 8,000 people have been killed in the Tamil conflict
since 1983. Tamils, who form 18 percent of the country's 16 million
people, claim that they are discriminated against by the majority
Sinhalese, who form 75 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
