<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Huntington'sSurgery 2ndLd-Writethru a060ordisn'tintheNewDictionaryofAmericanSlangbutChapman
03-03 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Huntington's Surgery, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0602,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experimental Surgery May Help Victims of Deadly Huntington's
Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th and 2 after 8th pvs, `Vanderbilt
doctors...' to update with Ross news conference today. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHERA GROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A victim of degenerative Huntington's
disease underwent experimental surgery in which doctors removed an
adrenal gland and grafted the tissue onto the man's brain.
   It was the first time a patient with Huntington's, a fatal
disease marked by mental deterioration and uncontrollable
movements, underwent a procedure that has shown promise in
relieving symptoms of Parkinson's disease, surgeons at Vanderbilt
University Medical Center said Wednesday.
   ``It will be several months before we know if it works,'' said
Dr. George S. Allen, chairman of the Department of Neurosurgery and
director of Vanderbilt's neurotransplant program.
   The 41-year-old patient was in critical but stable condition
this morning, said John Houser, a medical center spokesman.
   ``Our hope is that this (surgery) is something that would
dramatically affect this disease,'' Dr. J.C. Ross, associate vice
chancellor for health affairs at Vanderbilt, said at a news
conference today. ``It is not a cure. Our hope is that it might
slow down the illness.''
   Surgeons said the procedure Tuesday is similar to surgery
performed at Vanderbilt last year on 18 patients with Parkinson's
disease, a brain disorder characterized by rigidity and tremors.
   ``We aren't as likely to see improvement in symptoms as with the
Parkinson's surgery, but we hope this procedure will slow down or
stop the progress of Huntington's disease,'' said Dr. Noel Tulipan,
principal investigator on the project.
   Vanderbilt doctors decided to apply the procedure to
Huntington's patients based on experiments on rats.
   The team hopes to perform more of the operations, depending on
how many volunteers there are, Ross said today.
   Vanderbilt is searching for identical twins suffering from
Huntington's who might participate in the pilot study, he said.
Because twins' genetic makeup would be exactly alike, researchers
could study the effects of the surgery by performing the operation
on one twin and allowing the disease to progress naturally in the
other, he said.
   Houser said there is evidence that a naturally occurring
chemical in the brain, quinolinic acid, may cause the degeneration
seen in Huntington's.
   Experiments demonstrated that the adrenal tissue transplant
could protect against the damage caused by the acid, he said.
   In Huntington's disease, as nerve cells in the brain die,
patients experience involuntary spasms of the face and body,
slurred speech and trouble walking.
   The patient, whose name was withheld at his family's request,
was diagnosed as having Huntington's five years ago. The disease
has caused him trouble talking and performing ordinary tasks,
forcing him to quit working three years ago. He has a wife but no
children.
   Between 10,000 and 20,000 Americans have Huntington's disease,
and 500 to 1,000 new cases occur each year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
