<HEAD>Witness Jailed While Defendants Freed On Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who feared a key witness would
not show up for the trial of two people charged in the drug
overdose of their baby has ordered the witness jailed, while the
parents are free on bail.
   ``This is obscene,'' attorney Patrick McNeal said of his client,
Bruce Chavez, who was ordered jailed Wednesday as a material
witness by Orange County Superior Court Judge Francisco Briseno.
   ``This is the worst miscarriage of justice that I've seen in
recent years. It's ludicrous.''
   Gilbert Delgado, 24, and his wife, Debbie, 22, are charged with
murder, child endangerment and drug possession in the September
1986 death of their 2-month-old daughter, Stephanie. Delgado was
free on $100,000 bail and his wife was free on $50,000 bail.
   The trial of the Costa Mesa couple is scheduled June 20. Chavez,
Mrs. Delgado's brother, could be held until he testifies or posts
$100,000 bail.
   Chavez had told police that his sister and brother-in-law used
cocaine regularly and that he had seen the drug and paraphernalia
near baby bottles and bottle nipples.
   But when he was subpoenaed to appear at a preliminary hearing,
he took extreme measures to avoid an appearance, said Deputy
District Attorney Rick King. The measures included sleeping in his
truck or in parks, refusing to go home and changing his appearance.
   It wasn't until more than a year after the baby's death that the
Delgados were arrested because initial coroner's reports attributed
the death to infant death syndrome, police said. Three months
later, tests revealed she died from cocaine overdose and the
Delgados were arrested last October.
</TEXT>
