<HEAD>Parents of Groom in Drought Area Get Unique Dowry: Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a groom in a
drought-stricken Indian state demanded that the bride's family give
them an unusual dowry: water.
   Two barrels of water have been delivered every day to the house
of the groom, Prashant Pandeya, since his recent marriage, the
United News of India reported Thursday.
   Under the dowry pact, the bride's parents, who have a steady
source of underground water, must keep up the supply until the next
monsoon, the news agency reported.
   Gujarat and 15 other states have been hit by drought, the worst
in India in a century.
   The parents of a bride normally give clothes, jewelry, cash,
furniture or electronic goods as dowry to the groom and his family.
Although outlawed in 1961, dowry still persists.
