<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ManureProtest     03-03 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manure Protest,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesting Farmers Dump Manure in Gov't Office, Smash Computers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry farmers smeared manure in a
government office and smashed its computers to protest a planned
levy on fertilizer, police said.
   A group of about 250 farmers stormed the Netherlands Manure
Agency building during a demonstration against the levy in this
northern Dutch town, said police spokesman Eduard Vissia.
   The levy, which is to be monitored by the manure agency, is
aimed at curbing the mammoth manure surplus that threatens
Holland's water supplies.
   ``The farmers smeared dung all over the place'' after breaking
into the building's computer room, Vissia said.
   The protesters also destroyed computer equipment with farm
implements before they were thrown out of the building by riot
police, Vissia said.
   No arrests were made. No damage estimate was made, although
Vissia said it probably ran into the tens of thousands of dollars.
   The surplus amounts to about 90 million tons produced annually
by the Netherlands' 14 million pigs, 5 million cows, and 92 million
chickens.
   The oversupply stems directly from the Common Market farm
subsidy system, which until recently stimulated large-scale animal
husbandry operations.
   Under the contested plan, farmers are required to pay the
equivalent of 13 cents for every kilogram _ 2.2 pounds _ of manure
they produce in excess of the permitted 275 pounds per 2{ acres of
arable land, according to a spokeswoman for the Dutch Agriculture
Ministry.
   The levy soars to about 25 cents for every kilogram in excess of
440 pounds per 2{ acres.
   The farmers claim that the measures are punitive and demand that
the government adopt and fund a project to distribute the manure
more evenly over the Netherlands through a system of pipelines.
</TEXT>
