<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia Scandal,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Head of Agrokomerc Indicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State prosecutors have filed charges
against the former head of the Agrokomerc company that issued
almost $1 billion in uncovered promissory notes, it was reported
Thursday.
   State prosecutors filed the charge of making
counterrevolutionary threats to socialist property against Fikret
Abdic, 48, the former director of the firm, the official news
agency Tanjug said.
   Seven of Abdic's aides were similarly charged, and four were
charged with abusing authority in the economy under especially
grave circumstances, Tanjug said.
   Abdic was arrested last summer after Yugoslav media uncovered
the scandal surrounding Agrokomerc and its practice of issuing
uncovered promissory notes.
   He has already been charged with threatening the social system
and embezzlement of social property. He faces a maximum sentence of
20 years in jail if convicted on all counts.
   The indictment against him may be altered during the trial,
according to Yugoslav law. No trial date has yet been set.
   Agrokomerc once employed 13,500 people at its headquarters in
Velika Kladusa and was touted as a model company. It has since laid
off many employees and is kept running on loans from the republic
of Bosnia, where it is located.
   More than 30 people have been arrested in the Agrokomerc scandal
and charges may be brought against as many as 200 others.
   Jail sentences of up to seven years have been passed so far on
some local officials.
