<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MechamImpeachment 3rdLd-Writethru a0622 03-03 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Impeachment, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0622,0959</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor's Attorney Defends Memo to Senators</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 3-5 with 5 grafs to update wiht testimony today.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Presiding Judge...'
^By LAURIE ASSEO</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham drew criticism at his
Senate impeachment trial for sending all 30 senators a statement
pleading his case, but gained promises of $100,000 in defense funds
at a raucous rally.
   Several senators said Wednesday it was inappropriate for the
first-term Republican governor to contact them because they are
serving as his judges and jury. Mecham attorney Thomas Crowe
contended there was nothing wrong with the governor's action.
   The trial resumed today with testimony by Department of Public
Safety Lt. Col. James Chilcoat on an allegation that Mecham tried
to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state
official.
   Chilcoat told about meetings that occurred before Mecham was
told about the alleged threat on Nov. 13, 1987. ``It appeared to me
that somebody was attempting to threaten a potential witness before
a statewide grand jury,'' Chilcoat testified.
   The Senate today also threw out a subpoena of state grand jury
records in connection with the alleged threat.
   In television interviews this morning, Mecham said he hasn't
broken any laws and will be found innocent if the senators listen
to their constituents.
   The Senate also was expected to consider whether to allow
testimony intended to discredit DPS Director Ralph Milstead, the
key witness on the death threat allegation.
   Presiding Judge Frank X. Gordon Jr. said Wednesday he would not
allow testimony on allegations about Milstead's sex life, but the
Senate could decide to overrule his decision. Milstead has
dismissed as ridiculous the allegation that he had an affair with
an employee in 1982.
   Mecham is accused of ordering Milstead not to cooperate with the
attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat.
   Mecham's former chief bodyguard, DPS Lt. Beau Johnson, testified
he considered the alleged threat to be a possible felony and that
he fully informed Mecham of the seriousness of the matter.
   In cross-examination, defense lawyer Fred Craft suggested the
alleged threat by then-state official Lee Watkins against former
top Mecham aide Donna Carlson was a ``political matter,'' not a
crime. But Johnson testified, ``I did not really think of it in the
political sense.''
   At the time of the alleged threat, Ms. Carlson was scheduled to
testify before a grand jury on a $350,000 campaign loan Mecham is
accused of concealing. Watkins has denied he told state official
Peggy Griffith that if her friend Ms. Carlson did not keep her
mouth shut she might ``go on a long boat ride.''
   Craft might become a grand jury witness himself, some senators
said, because he attended the meeting at which Johnson has
testified that he told Mecham of the alleged threat. Minority
Leader Alan Stephens, a Democrat, said he believes Senate rules
allow a senator to ask that Craft be called as a witness.
   Stephens also said many senators were questioning whether it was
appropriate that Mecham sent senators a copy of a public statement
he made Saturday arguing that the Senate trial be delayed until
after his March 22 criminal trial on charges of concealing the
$350,000 loan.
   Democratic Sen. Jesus Higuera displayed the statement on the
Senate floor and urged fellow lawmakers not to read it.
   ``I hope Governor Mecham understands the oath we have taken,''
Higuera said. ``It's inappropriate to attempt to communicate with
us.''
   But Crowe said, ``It's a political proceeding. ... The senators
have received communications from many people pro and con. I don't
see why the governor should be any different.''
   Mecham, who also faces a May 17 recall election, received a
$50,000 check from supporters at a $20-a-person rally Wednesday
night in Tempe. The rally by 4,000 people would raise more than
$100,000 after expenses, said organizer John Thomas.
   This morning, on NBC's ``Today'' program, Mecham said there is a
``groundswell'' of support for him because ``people are now seeing
what's happened, that this is an attempt at a railroad job.''
   Mecham told ABC's ``Good Morning America'' that now that the
trial is being televised ``there's great reaction from the people.''
   The governor also told ``CBS This Morning'' that he wasn't
attending the impeachment trial because he expected to return to
office and ``was keeping track of some things. .... I don't want
everything to get clear out of hand.''
   Among those in the wildly cheering crowd Wednesday was a man in
a train engineer's cap, signifying the ``railroading'' of the
governor, and a woman in a kangaroo costume, symbolizing a
``kangaroo court.''
   Mecham, 63, was forced to step down pending the trial after the
House impeached him Feb. 5. In addition to the death threat and
loan allegations, he is accused of misusing $80,000 from the
governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership.
   A two-thirds Senate vote is required to convict Mecham, the
first U.S. governor in nearly 60 years to face an impeachment trial.
   Meanwhile, acting Gov. Rose Mofford, a Democrat, fired one of
Mecham's top aides, Max Hawkins, saying he had ``engaged in a
number of personal attacks on state elected officials.'' Hawkins
said he was fired because he is a whistle-blower.
   Hawkins has accused Rep. Jim Skelly, chairman of the House
impeachment committee, of interfering on a friend's behalf in a
state Racing Commission investigation. Skelly responded Wednesday
on the House floor that Hawkins is ``a pathological liar, and it's
not surprising because he works for Governor Mecham, and Governor
Mecham wouldn't know the truth if it bit him in the nose.''
</TEXT>
