<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NATO-Congress     03-03 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Congress,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Nato Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Carlucci: Appeals for More NATO Spending Must be Carefully Worded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American requests to Europe to spend more for
NATO's defense will fail if the appeals are based on U.S. budget
deficits, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said Thursday.
   Instead, the United States must convince the other 15 members of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization to increase NATO's budget
because it is in the best interests of the alliance, Carlucci said.
   As Carlucci was speaking, President Reagan and other NATO
leaders were winding up a two-day meeting of alliance leaders,
their first such session since 1982.
   Carlucci, speaking to the Senate Budget Committee, echoed
Reagan's call for NATO to go ahead with its previous plans to build
a new generation of non-nuclear weapons to defend against a Soviet
attack.
   Criticism of NATO has long been popular on Capitol Hill among
legislators of both parties, who complain that Western European
nations don't pay enough of the common defense bill.
   That criticism has increased in recent months, particularly
because rising U.S. budget deficits have led Congress to target the
Pentagon as a chief method of cutting federal spending.
   ``I think we need to approach a burden-sharing undertaking as an
effort to strengthen the alliance, not as effort to solve our
budget problems,'' said Carlucci.
   ``If we go to the allies and say we've been obliged to cut our
budget, therefore you have to make up the difference, I predict a
lack of success,'' he said.
   ``On the other hand, if we're able to exercise leadership,''
NATO may go along with previous plans to improve weapons, despite
political opposition in Europe, Carlucci said.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the committee, noted
that ``the lion's share of the load (borne by NATO) has been
carried by the United States.''
   While U.S. wealth is less compared to the years after World War
II, he said ``the contribution we make to our alliances remains
very high.''
   ``And so it seems reasonable to ask how those with new wealth _
acquired in a world made more stable by American sacrifice _ might
carry more of freedom's burden,'' he said.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., suggested that public criticism is the
not the best way to win increased defense budgets in Europe and
suggested that ``quiet diplomacy'' be used.
   ``NATO-bashing at this time is not the way to solve the
problem,'' Exon told the committee.
   The United States is becoming more and more reliant on its
partners in NATO, said Adm. William Crowe Jr., chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   ``With respect to risks, the 1989 budget recognizes that a
coalition strategy has become more _ not less _ important to the
United States,'' he said.
   ``Similarly, it (the budget) was structured to preserve and
optimize U.S. contributions to the collective security of NATO
Europe and our allies in Asia,'' Crowe said.
   ``We are not well positioned, however, to fill the gaps if, for
one reason or another, some of the allies decide to reduce defense
spending levels, shed defense commitments, or trim back on
conventional force improvements,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
