<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Drugs-Aviation     03-03 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drugs-Aviation,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department today proposed
widespread drug testing covering tens of thousands of airline
employees and said such tests are needed to ``maintain public
confidence'' in the aviation system.
   The proposal, due to take effect in several months, would cover
pilots, flight attendants and other workers involved with safety or
security.
   Aviation unions have strongly opposed widespread testing,
agruing that no evidence has been produced showing drug use to be a
significant problem among the nation's airlines.
   But Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said that the tests are
needed because ``all it takes is one person on drugs in one of
these sensitive airline jobs to endanger the lives of hundreds of
innocent people.''
   The regulation, when it takes affect after a period of public
comment, would require a broad range of testing including
pre-employment tests, random tests and post-accident tests.
   Employees covered by the proposal would include all flight crew
members as well as aircraft dispatchers, mechanics and security
workers at airport screening checkpoints.
   ``I firmly believe that drug testing, especially random testing,
is absolutely critical in our efforts to create a drug-free
aviation system for the American people,'' Burnley told a news
coinference.
   Allan McArtor, administrator of the Federal Aviation
Administration, which will enforce the new regulations, said that
the testing program, although controversial, is ``essential to
maintaining public confidence in flying (by) ... insuring a
drug-free aviation workforce.''
   The airline pilots association and unions representing flight
attendants have strongly opposed plans for widespread testing,
arguing it is an invasion of privacy when no safety threat has been
shown.
   Congress has been debating legislation that would require drug
testing in various forms of transportation, including aviation and
railroads, but no legislation has been approved, partly because of
strong labor opposition.
</TEXT>
