<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShooting     03-03 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect Charged In Shootings At School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUKEGAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities charged a 21-year-old man
today in the shooting of four teen-agers fired on after a high
school basketball game.
   Nathan Ward of North Chicago was charged with aggravated battery
and armed violence, Deputy Police Chief Terry House said.
   The shooting occurred late Wednesday outside Waukegan East High
School after a regional semifinal basketball game between Waukegan
East and North Chicago High School. Waukegan East won, 77-56.
   Investigators had not established a motive for the shooting, but
had ruled out involvement with drugs, gangs and the game, House
said.
   Investigators recovered a .38-caliber handgun, he said, and a
second person was being sought for questioning.
   Two teen-agers injured in the shooting were in satisfactory
condition at Victory Memorial Hospital with arm wounds. Two others
were treated at the scene and sent home, police said.
   Frank Young, principal of Waukegan East, said the shooting
occurred 30 minutes after the game, and most of the estimated 2,000
fans had left.
   Larry TenPas, a Waukegan alderman and teacher at Waukegan East,
said he saw a man fire shots at the students who were milling
around the school.
