<DOCNO> AP880303-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ContraAid 2ndLd-Writethru a0649 03-03 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0649,820</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, As with, with procedural
vote. May stand; a vote is unlikely before 5 p.m. EST, and that
timetable could slip.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright said today a
Democratic plan for giving purely ``humanitarian'' aid to
Nicaragua's Contra rebels represents a chance for the United States
to take a positive role in its relations with Central America.
   ``It's a battle for peace in Nicaragua and for a constructive
role for the United States in Central America, as opposed to a
destructive role,'' Wright, D-Texas, said of a showdown vote over
rival Democratic and Republican aid plans set for later in the day.
   But President Reagan, in a letter to House Republicans sent
while he was attending a meeting of Western allies in Brussels,
Belgium, said Wright's plan ``does not meet the essential
criteria'' of keeping the Contras alive as a fighting force capable
of putting military pressure on the leftist Sandinista regime.
   ``Today could represent a watershed in our policies toward
Central America,'' Reagan wrote. ``One avenue will lead to rapid
debilitation of the resistance and further encouragement of
Sandinista intransigence. The other could keep alive prospects for
democracy and meaningful talks toward peace.
   As with virtually all past votes on U.S. aid for the Contras,
the showdown late today promised to be close. But Democratic
vote-counters said they believed they would win with at least as
wide a margin as a month ago, when the House defeated a Reagan aid
package 219 to 211.
   On an early procedural vote to adopt rules for floor debate,
Democrats prevailed, 225 to 187. But leaders cautioned that the
ballot was not a true test of whether the Democratic aid package
would pass.
   They also said they believed a move by Nicaraguan President
Daniel Ortega to dismiss Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo as mediator
in cease-fire talks with the Contras and propose direct talks in
Nicaragua would have little effect on the outcome.
   In Brussels, Reagan said during a picture-taking session that
``we have always believed there should be direct talks between the
people of Nicaragua who want freedom and have been called Contras
because of that, and the present government.''
   But of the move to dismiss the cardinal as an intermediary,
Reagan said: ``I don't understand that at all.''
   House Republicans, angry over what they considered an unfair
procedure under which the bill was being brought up, vowed not to
go away quietly.
   ``We're going to fight them on everything,'' said Rep. Mickey
Edwards, R-Okla., who has led the fight for Contra aid in the
House. ``It's gotten a lot of Republicans mad.''
   The $30.5 million Democratic proposal called for about $16
million in food, clothing, medicine and shelter for the
anti-Sandinista rebels, and another $14 million to set up a fund to
help children injured in the seven-year Nicaraguan civil war.
   Democrats were working to keep the support of moderate party
members who helped design the package, and keep to a minimum
defections by members of the party's left wing, most of whom never
have voted for aid to the rebels in any form.
   Party leaders argued that passage of this purely
``humanitarian'' aid bill would lessen chances that the
administration could come back to Congress soon with a request for
weapons and ammunition to sustain the guerrilla war.
   A Republican alternative contained more money _ about $36
million _ and placed fewer restrictions on the way the Contras
could use the aid. But it appeared unlikely the GOP version would
come to a vote because of Democratic-designed rules that called for
their package to come up first.
   Edwards said the key difference between the two bills was that
the Democrats' version offered no guarantees of quick consideration
of a future Reagan administration request for military aid for the
rebels. The GOP package would permit Reagan to ask for such aid any
time after April 15, and would require expedited congressional
action.
   ``Unless we put expedited procedures in the bill, the Contras
get nothing and the Sandinistas get no threat. That really is the
bottom-line issue,'' he said.
   And Edwards noted that the Democratic bill would turn over
responsibility for delivery of the ``humanitarian'' supplies to the
Pentagon, rather than the existing CIA-run supply network. Even if
the Pentagon retained the private contractors now used by the CIA
to make supply flights, U.S. military personnel would have to be
present in the region to oversee them, he said.
   The Republican alternative would leave the delivery of supplies
in the hands of the CIA.
   Wright on Wednesday defended the procedure under which the two
bills were being brought to the floor, saying the Republicans had
had their chance for a vote a month ago, when the House defeated
Reagan's last aid request.
   ``If ours were not offered (under the Democrats' procedure),
many of our members argued we might never get to vote on our
plan,'' Wright said. ``I don't think it's unfair to them.''
</TEXT>
