<DOCNO> AP880303-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-03 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eleven Reported Killed in Election Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LABELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 11 people were reported killed
and hundreds injured Thursday in violence related to Parliamentary
elections, which the opposition denounced as fraudulent and a
failure.
   Early results showed President Hussain Muhammad Ershad's Jatiya
Party with the lead in 53 of the 282 constituencies where ballots
were cast. Eighteen of his candidates had already been declared
elected to Parliament for lack of opposition candidates.
   Initial returns from nine other constituencies showed minor
opposition parties leading. Major opposition parties boycotted the
vote.
   Newspapers, quoting reliable sources, said 11 people were killed
in confrontations during the day between supporters of rival
candidates.
   Home Minister Abdul Matin said only five people died _ four in
Dhaka and one in nearby Manikganj. He said 80 were injured and 55
were hospitalized.
   The opposition's call for a general strike shut down most of the
capital.
   ``There was no turnout, there was no election,'' said Sheik
Hasina, leader of the main opposition Awami League. ``Perhaps the
so-called candidates voted.''
   But Matin told reporters that on the basis of 12 voting centers
he visited in Dhaka, he estimated voter to be 50 percent of the
47.8 million eligible to cast ballots.
   Reporters who went to a dozen polling stations in and around the
capital said a reasonable turnout was apparent at only three. Two
had been shut down by violence by midmorning.
   At several stations, election officials and even workers for
Ershad's Jatiya Party admitted that ballot boxes were stuffed and
voter turnout exaggerated.
   Ms. Hasina vowed the opposition camp of 21 parties would keep up
the campaign it began in November to oust Ershad as president.
   Ershad scheduled Thursday's elections after he dissolved
Parliament last December, 3{ years ahead of schedule. The move was
aimed at working out a compromise with his foes, but they demanded
instead that Ershad step down and said elections held under him
wouldn't be fair.
   The governing Jatiya Party won 152 seats in the last
parliamentary elections in 1986, and the Awami League won 102 of
the 330 seats. Small parties held the rest.
   Ershad, speaking to reporters after casting his ballot in Dhaka,
said he thought this election would end the violence.
   ``After this, things certainly will improve,'' he said.
   Ershad said he had no plans for another election soon. ``The
parliament is elected for five years by the people ... I expect it
to serve for five years.''
   Ms. Hasina maintained that Bangladeshis had rejected the
election.
   ``The whole nation has sided with us,'' Hasina said. ``That is
our achievement.''
   At Savar, 12 miles north of Dhaka, a Jatiya worker named Khalil
Mahmood said ballots were fraudulently stamped for Jatiya and also
for other parties to make the rigging less obvious.
   ``We finished by 11 a.m. and we even gave some votes to other
candidates,'' he said.
   Matin said he had no reports of vote rigging. He said voting was
suspended at 170 of the 22,393 polling booths because of violence
or election officials' failure to arrive to man the stations.
   Matin noted that there had been 21 deaths in the 1986
parliamentary election and said of Thursday's vote: ``It's a
successful and peaceful election.''
   In Chittagong, Bangladesh's second largest city, reporters
quoted police and hospital sources as saying more than 100 people
were injured in violence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
