<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DoleintheSouth     03-03 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole in the South,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole's Southern Strategy Is To Slow Down Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dole is looking beyond next
week's big round of Southern primaries and hoping his candidacy can
get beyond it too.
   ``When all is said and done,'' the Republican presidential
hopeful said at a Florida rally, ``this is probably going to go all
the way to California now.''
   If the race for the Republican presidential nomination doesn't
prove as long as he suggests, going on until the last round of
primaries in early June, Dole probably won't be the nominee.
   The Southern primaries _ South Carolina on Saturday and the rest
of the region on Super Tuesday _ aren't going to get him there.
George Bush leads Dole by as much as 3-to-1 in polls of the South.
   While Dole figures to run better than that in the popular vote,
the Republicans' delegate allotment system means the real score in
delegates may be that bad or worse. And Pat Robertson is a GOP wild
card that could siphone off more delegates.
   ``It's a struggle,'' said Dole press secretary Dale Tate. ``But
I don't think anybody here thinks we won't survive. It's going to
be a long time to New Orleans'' and the Republican convention.
   But with 712 GOP delegates at stake that day, Bush has the
potential to go a long way toward the 1,139 delegates needed to
nominate.
   Dole's problem is how to keep Bush from running up such a
collection of victories on Tuesday that he is unstoppable when the
race turns to the next round of big industrial states.
   The grim potential of Super Tuesday for Dole heightens the
importance of the next primary, Illinois on March 15.
   Dole forces figure they must be able to bounce back there.
   ``I think if Dole doesn't win Illinois, it's just about over,''
said one Dole campaign official, speaking only on condition of
anonymity.
   Facing that reality, Dole is attacking Bush with a broad brush
as a man with no more of a record than the embarrassment of
involvement in the sale of arms to Iran for hostages.
   But he also is carefully choosing his spots in the states and
congressional districts where he has a chance of success.
   ``We're going to win some states here,'' Dole pollster Richard
Wirthlin said in Atlanta last weekend. ``We're doing well in areas
that can be typified as the New South.
   ``We're going to be very competitive in four or five states,''
Wirthlin said.
   Dole forces see their best chances among the 14 Southern and
border states voting Tuesday to be in Missouri, with 47 delegates
at stake, Oklahoma, with 36, and North Carolina, with 54.
   They would like to score some surprises in Alabama, Arkansas,
and in certain portions of Florida and Georgia.
   Among the states outside the South voting on Tuesday, they are
focusing on Rhode Island, with 21 delegates, and Washington state,
where the 41 delegates aren't allocated by the primary but where a
victory would give Dole something to talk about.
   North Carolina is the state where Dole's wife Elizabeth is from
and where together they have appeared often over the years. It is
also a state where textiles is a major industry, and Dole has been
attacking the vice president's opposition to limits on foreign
textile imports.
   Dole is also on the air in South Carolina, Missouri, Oklahoma
and Arkansas, and has small amounts of TV commercials on in Rhode
Island and Florida.
   Doe has injected anew the Iran-Contra affair into the campaign
with another ad that says: ``Dole opposed selling arms to Iran.
Bush supported the arms for hostages deal.''
   Part of Dole's frustration is that Bush has been able to appear
the rightful heir to President Reagan's conservative legacy in the
South, where Reagan has always been strong. Dole seeks to tarnish
Bush, while straining to avoid seeming to attack Reagan, which he
knows would backfire.
   And he has been frustrated that Bush's support in the region,
often described as broad but thin, has not proven brittle.
   ``We know Bush has a big lead in the South,'' Dole said. ``For
some reason, his people believe he's from the South or something.''
</TEXT>
