<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperTuesday-Delegates 2-Takes   03-03 0958</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Tuesday-Delegates, 2-Takes,930-1,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Super Tuesday Scorecard Presents Challenge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political scorekeepers face a complex
challenge next Tuesday as they try to track who wins roughly
one-third of the delegates to the Democratic and Republican
national conventions.
   Super Tuesday's chain of events, stretching from the U.S.
Atlantic coast almost to the international date line in the Pacific
Ocean, relies on dozens of complicated and often confusing rules.
   In some cases, the process is so tangled that it's hard to agree
even on how many delegates are involved.
   For example, the Republicans are holding 16 or 17 events on
Super Tuesday, and 712, 753 or 803 delegates are involved. All of
those figures are correct, depending on how the question is phrased.
   The reason for the discrepancies is some of the GOP events
count, some don't and others can't be sorted out until later.
   Sixteen of the Republican events will have some effect on how
national convention delegates will be divided, but only fifteen of
those yield results that can be calculated immediately into
national delegate totals. That leaves the grand totals at 16 states
yielding 712 national convention delegates.
   The Democrats aren't a lot easier to figure out. The 21 states
and territories holding Super Tuesday events have 1,455 delegates.
But 148 of them are a special type of delegate not affected by what
happens in the primaries or caucuses. That leaves 1,307 Democratic
delegates at stake on March 8.
   To complicate matters further, Minnesota's Democrats, who held
their caucuses on Feb. 23, are releasing the results on March 8.
This is an outgrowth of a convoluted compromise between the state
and national parties to allow Minnesota to hold caucuses two weeks
earlier than allowed by the rules without breaking the rules. These
results will govern who wins 78 of the state's national convention
delegates.
   In both parties, a state's national convention delegates are
chosen both on the basis of how much support a presidential
candidate has in each congressional district and how much support
the candidate commands statewide.
   Democrats require that a presidential candidate reaches a
certain level of support to be eligible for winning delegates. Each
candidate must receive at least 15 percent of the vote in any given
congressional district or statewide.
   The corresponding Republican requirements vary from state to
state.
   Here is a state-by-state breakdown of how the delegates will be
calculated from Super Tuesday's events:
   _ Alabama: People running for 37 seats as delegates to the
Democratic National Convention will be listed on the ballot in the
primary along with the presidential candidate they support. Another
19 Democratic delegates will be picked later, but the results of
the primary govern how they will be awarded to presidential
candidates. The Republicans, too, list their delegates on the
ballot _ three in each of seven congressional district and 17
statewide. These are awarded on a winner-take-all basis in each
district and statewide. Total: 56 Democrats, 38 Republicans.
   _ American Samoa: The Democrats gather in one spot and pick six
people who will each cast one-half vote at the national convention.
The Republican Party does not provide for a delegation from
American Samoa. Super Tuesday total: 3 Democrats, 0 Republicans.
   _ Arkansas: The Democrats vote in the primary for presidential
candidates, and delegates will be awarded in proportion to these
results. The Republicans, too, award their national convention
delegates in proportion to the primary results. Super Tuesday
total: 38 Democrats, 27 Republicans.
   _ Florida: In each of the state's 19 congressional districts,
the presidential candidate receiving the most votes in the primary
gets one delegate as a bonus, while the remaining delegates are
divided in proportion to the vote. Statewide, another 47 delegates
will be awarded in prortion to the overall vote. The Republicans
use a somewhat simpler method: The winner in each congressional
district gets all of the delegates from that district, and the
winner statewide receives all 18 of the at-large delegates. Super
Tuesday total: 136 Democrats, 82 Republicans.
   _ Georgia: The Democrats use rules similar to those in Florida:
a ``bonus delegate'' awarded to the winner in each congressional
district, the rest allocated proportionally. The Republicans also
use the same kind of rules as the Florida GOP: winner-take-all by
congressional district and statewide. Super Tuesday total: 77
Democrats, 48 Republicans.
   _ Hawaii: The Democrats hold precinct caucuses to elect
delegates to the state convention. The people attending the
caucuses will register their presidential preference, and the
national convention delegates will be awarded to presidential
candidates in proportion to those results. Hawaii's Republicans
held their precinct caucuses last month. However, in this as well
as other GOP caucus systems, the presidential preferences of the
people at the first step of the process do not in any formal way
bind those who attend the following steps. In addition, the
conventions and caucuses later in the process need not follow any
uniform set of rules. Thus, the number of national convention
delegates won by each presidential candidate cannot be figured with
precision based only on the results of the first step. Super
Tuesday total: 20 Democrats, 0 Republicans.
   _ Idaho: The Democrats hold caucuses similar to those in Hawaii,
picking delegates to the state convention in June, when the
national convention delegates will finally be selected. The
allocation of those delegates among the presidential candidates
will be governed by the support registered by those attending the
March 8 caucuses. Idaho Republicans hold a primary on May 24. Super
Tuesday total: 18 Democrats, 0 Republicans.
   _ Kentucky: Both the Democrats and Republicans divide their
national convention delegates among the presidential candidates in
proportion to the results of the primary. Super Tuesday total: 55
Democrats, 38 Republicans.
</TEXT>
