<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SuperTuesday-Delegates 1stAdd   03-03 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Tuesday-Delegates, 1st Add,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: 38 Republicans.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ Louisiana: The Democrats divide their delegates in proportion
to the results of the primary. The Republicans award 24 of their
delegates on a winner-take-all basis in each of the state's eight
congressional districts. The remaining 17 GOP delegates from
Louisiana are awarded in proportion to the results of the primary
statewide. Super Tuesday total: 63 Democrats, 41 Republicans.
   _ Maryland: The Democrats elect 44 delegates listed on the
ballot by congressional districts and award another 23 delegates in
proportion to the statewide results of the primary. The Republicans
award their delegates on a winner-take-all basis by congressional
district and statewide. Super Tuesday total: 67 Democrats, 41
Republicans.
   _ Massachusetts: The Democrats use a system similar to that of
Georgia and Florida, awarding a ``bonus delegate'' to the
presidential candidate who wins in each congressional district and
dividing the rest proportionally. The Republicans award their
delegates in proportion to the results of the primary. Super
Tuesday total: 98 Democrats, 52 Republicans.
   _ Mississippi: The Democrats award their delegates in proportion
to the results of the primary, both by congressional district and
statewide. The Republicans divide their statewide delegates
proportionally, while those from congressional districts are
awarded on a winner-take-all basis. Super Tuesday total: 40
Democrats, 31 Republicans.
   _ Missouri: The Democrats award their national convention
delegates in proportion to the results of the primary, with a
``bonus delegate'' given in each of the state's nine congressional
districts to the presidential candidate carrying that district. GOP
presidential candidates win delegates in proportion to the results
of the primary. Super Tuesday total: 77 Democrats, 47 Republicans.
   _ Nevada: Democrats meet in precinct caucuses to choose
delegates to the county conventions to pick delegates to the state
convention where the delegates to the national convention will be
selected.
   Participants at each level of the process are required to
declare whom they support for president, and this governs how the
national convention delegates are to be divided among the
presidential candidates. The Republicans had their precinct
caucuses last month, but the final outcome will not be known until
the national convention delegates are chosen in April. Super
Tuesday total: 16 Democrats, 0 Republicans.
   _ North Carolina: Democrats use a ``bonus delegate'' system in
the congressional districts and award the 29 at-large delegates in
proportion to the statewide primary vote. The Republican delegates
are awarded to presidential candidates in proportion to the primary
vote. Super Tuesday total: 82 Democrats, 54 Republicans.
   _ Oklahoma: The Democrats allocate their delegates in proportion
to the results of the primary. The Republicans award their
delegates, winner-take-all, by congressional district and
statewide. Super Tuesday total: 46 Democrats, 36 Republicans.
   _ Rhode Island: Democratic and Republican presidential
candidates win delegates in proportion to how well they do in the
primary. Super Tuesday total: 22 Democrats, 21 Republicans.
   _ Tennessee: The Democrats divide their delegates proportionally
based on the results of the primary. The Republicans elect 33 of
their delegates directly from the ballot by congressional district
and award another dozen based on the statewide vote. Super Tuesday
total: 70 Democrats, 45 Republicans.
   _ Texas: The results of the primary by congressional district
govern the proportional allocation of 119 of the Democratic
delegates from Texas, but there's a twist in how the remaining 64
delegates statewide are picked. In Texas, Democrats who vote in the
primary can also take part in precinct party caucuses held after
the polls close. In many cases, this would require people to make
two trips to the polls in one day. The at-large delegates will be
awarded to presidential candidates based on the preferences of the
people attending the caucuses. The Republicans award their
delegates on a winner-take-all basis by congressional district and
statewide. Super Tuesday total: 183 Democrats, 111 Republicans.
   _ Virginia: Democrats award their delegates in proportion to the
results of the primary. Republicans also are holding a primary, but
its results have no effect at all on who eventually wins the
delegates. That will be handled through a system of caucuses and
conventions concluding in May and June. Super Tuesday total: 75
Democrats, 0 Republicans.
   _ Washington: The Democrats hold precinct caucuses similar to
those in Nevada, and allocation of national convention delegates
will reflect the presidential preferences of the participants.
Republicans also are holding precinct caucuses and will cast votes
for presidential candidates in a non-binding straw poll. However,
just as in other GOP caucus states the delegate allocation cannot
be calculated until the delegates themselves are chosen later in
the season. Super Tuesday total: 65 Democrats, 0 Republicans.
</TEXT>
