<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-South Bjt   03-03 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-South, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President Appears Solid in the South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He pronounces y'all as two distinct words,
but George Bush speaks the language of the South in a way that
overcomes his New England accent. It can be summed up in two other
words: Ronald Reagan.
   With the Super Tuesday primaries and caucuses offering 712
delegates, a majority of them in the South, polls indicate Bush
could end the day with a big lead in the race for the Republican
presidential nomination.
   And during a hectic campaign schedule this week, including 10
stops in five Southern states Tuesday and Wednesday, Bush exuded
confidence as he predicted Tuesday's winner will be the next
president.
   ``He's in a very upbeat mood,'' said Bush spokesman Peter
Teeley. ``When you consider what we went through the last four or
five days of New Hampshire. ...''
   Teeley meant a period when it seemed Sen. Bob Dole might follow
his Iowa victory by beating Bush in the New Hampshire primary.
Bush's Feb. 16 victory changed all that, giving him momentum to go
with his strong organization as he headed south.
   And he hoped to benefit from the president's popularity.
   Throughout his Southern swing this week, Bush referred to ``the
Reagan-Bush administration'' and said he was the man who could
build upon ``the superb foundation of the Reagan revolution.'' He
criticized other candidates for differing with the president on
some issues and for criticizing Bush as a yes man.
   ``If the price of winning this nomination is to turn my back in
some way on Ronald Reagan, then I'm not willing to pay that
price,'' Bush said in Tampa.
   ``You Mississippians also know that loyalty is a strength,''
Bush told shipyard workers in Pascagoula, Miss.
   Lanny Griffith, Bush's Southern campaign coordinator from
Corinth, Miss., said rivals' attacks on Bush were unlikely to
succeed in the South.
   ``People here think of George Bush as Reagan's partner, a war
hero, the former CIA director, and as a Texan,'' Griffith said.
``They don't pay attention to that D.C.-New York type of stuff.
`Doonesbury' does not shape the conventional wisdom here.''
   Bush has important advantages in the two largest Super Tuesday
states, Texas and Florida. He made his mark in the Texas oil
business and entered politics there.
   In Florida, he has the support of Gov. Bob Martinez, who
appointed Bush's son, Jeb, as Florida's secretary of commerce. The
younger Bush formerly headed the Dade County Republican Party.
Bush's mother lives in Palm Beach, and the vice president has
visited Florida often, both for personal reasons and on such
official business as his role heading the South Florida Task Force
on Drugs.
   As he campaigned energetically this week, Bush said Dole-leaning
New Hampshire polls preceding Bush's victory there had taught him a
lesson.
   ``You have to continue to fight like you're behind,'' Bush said.
``So you don't let up, you don't go home, and you stay out of the
mud.''
   Bush said he was waging a positive campaign on a ``higher
plain,'' while making indirect jabs at his opponents by calling
himself the most stable and most mature candidate.
   The Bush campaign's officials said they had been outspent in
much of the South but were ready for a final television blitz.
   ``I believe that you should hold back everything you can to
spend as late as possible,'' said Southern coordinator Griffith.
   Bush's late campaigning was concentrated on pockets in the South
where it seemed former television evangelist Pat Robertson had
strong grass-roots support or where Dole was most active.
   In the Deep South states, Bush expected to capitalize on the
administration's stand for strong defense and tough foreign policy.
   He often sprinkled in references to his Navy World War II combat
experience. In case anyone missed them, he was greeted upon arrival
in Tampa with a Grumman Avenger plane, like the one he flew. Bush
put on a flight jacket and climbed into the cockpit for the cameras.
   His strong organization and the advantage of Secret
Service-aided logistics helped allow Bush to pack many appearances
into his swing _ driving a paving machine at a North Miami Beach
construction site, playing shuffleboard with retirees in Boca
Raton, Fla., serving catfish in Biloxi and jambalaya in Baton
Rouge, La.
   The dean of American conservatives, 1964 presidential nominee
Barry Goldwater, campaigned with him in Florida and filmed an
endorsement commercial. Former Navy Secretary John Lehman also
campaigned with Bush in the South.
</TEXT>
