<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Robbery     03-03 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Robbery,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Men Rob Van of $1.7 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen burst into the home of a security guard and
his wife, then used them as hostages in a ``meticulously planned
raid'' to steal up to $1.7 million from an armored van, according
to Scotland Yard and a published report.
   The robbery began Tuesday night when two men with pistols took a
Security Express guard and his wife hostage at their southeastern
London home, said a Scotland Yard spokeswoman.
   A third man arrived at the house Wednesday morning and drove the
woman away, she said, speaking anonymously in keeping with British
custom.
   The two remaining robbers drove the guard to work in his own car
and ordered him to drive his money-laden van to a south London
location, the spokeswoman said.
   The guard explained his predicament to two other guards in the
van and they drove to the prearranged meeting point, she said.
   Two men on motorcycles met the van and ordered the guards to
drive to a nearby soccer field, she said. The guards were ordered
to lie beneath stands in the stadium along with three gardeners who
had seen one of the robbers, she said.
   Minutes later they were joined by the guard's wife and held at
gunpoint until the van's cash was loaded onto another vehicle and
the robbers escaped, the spokeswoman said.
   ``This was a very meticulously planned raid. The raiders had
obviously been following the movements of the guard for many days
and knew where to find him,'' one of her male colleagues at
Scotland Yard added later.
   Police refused to say how much cash was taken, but the Times of
London on Thursday quoted unidentified police sources as saying the
gang got away with between $1.32 million and $1.76 million.
</TEXT>
