<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CensusAdjustment     03-03 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Census Adjustment,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Census Adjustment Decision Attacked On Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's decision not to
adjust the 1990 national census to allow for people who are
overlooked was ``shameful'' and blatantly political, a New York
congressman charged Thursday.
   The action was not based ``on fairminded concern about accurate
statistics; it's a raw exercise of partisan politics,'' Rep.
Charles E. Schumer charged at a hearing of the House Post Office
and Civil Service census subcommittee.
   Schumer and Reps. Mervyn M. Dymally of California and Robert
Garcia of New York all raised concern about the decision not to
adjust, which was announced last October by the Commerce
Department, parent agency of the census. All three are Democrats.
   Commerce Undersecretary Robert Ortner denied that it was a
political decision, however, contending that statisticians disagree
on whether there is an accurate method of making adjustments.
   ``I don't think it would make the problem any better if we were
to devise an elaborate mathematical system to make up new
numbers,'' Ortner commented.
   The focus of the problem is the fact that all 435 seats in the
House of Representatives and billions of dollars in state and
federal money are distributed on the basis of the figures collected
every 10 years by the Census Bureau.
   No head count can be perfect in a nation the size of the United
States, with the current population estimated at more than 244
million people. But concern centers on studies that show that the
number of people missed is much higher among minorities.
   That results in such groups as blacks and Hispanics getting less
economic and political clout, and has led to calls for an
adjustment of census figures to compensate for this problem.
   Census statisticians have been working on finding a way to
adjust the figures, but disagreement exists as to whether this can
be done in an accurate fashion.
   Thus, Ortner announced last fall that no adjustment would be
made in 1990, stating that the time for experimenting was over and
the agency had go get on with the task of taking the census.
   That drew a barrage of criticism, however, from groups
contending that those most often missed are urban minorities,
usually Democrats, and that the decision not to adjust was a
political action to boost the power of conservatives and
Republicans.
   ``The administration's position is shameful. It's shameful
because the administration's problem with adjusting census figures
is not statisatical, it's political,'' Schumer said.
   ``That's absolutely untrue,'' responded Ortner. He said the
department simply wanted to go out and conduct the best actual
count possible, adding that cuts in post-census surveys which might
have been used to make later adjustments were designed to save
money.
   Dymally commented that he found it interesting that the decision
not to make an adjustment was made by Commerce Department officials
just 10 days after he proposed a bill to require an adjustment.
   The decision should have been left up to xensus statisticians
rather than being made by Commerce officials, he added.
   Schumer pointed out that Barbara Bailar, a census official who
had been in charge of developing adjustment methods, resigned from
the agency charging that the decision was political rather than
technical.
   Bailar said in her prepared testimony that while opinion was
divided in the bureau, she believed that the census figures could
be accurately adjusted using a survey of residents on specific
areas to estimate the undercount.
   But Ortner reiterated that statisticians continue to disagree on
the matter and presented a letter from about a dozen academic
popualation experts opposed to making adjustments in the census
counts.
</TEXT>
