<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MinimumWage     03-03 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minimum Wage,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs $1.30 Boost in Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled House labor
standards subcommittee voted along party lines Thursday to increase
the minimum wage from $3.35 to $4.65 an hour over the next three
years.
   The 6-3 vote came after Democrats defeated Republican amendments
designed to either water down or kill the measure, which would
raise the minimum wage 50 cents an hour on Jan. 1, 1989 and 40
cents an hour each of the following years.
   However, the subcommittee refused, 7-2, to tie future increases
to inflation, a proposal once wanted by organized labor but which
it abandoned in an effort to preserve the $4.65-an-hour figure.
   Rep. Timothy J. Penny, D-Minn., who proposed the elimination of
the indexing of future increases, said he was ``concerned about
something like this being on automatic pilot. Congress should
review an future increases.'' He also said automatic increases in
the minimum wage would could drive up salaries of workers who make
higher than the minimum, leading to inflation.
   Rep. Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the full House
Labor and Education Committee, voted against the Penny amendment,
saying it ``is ill-timed, unwarranted and not justified by the
facts. There is no indication that it leads to inflation. Wages lag
behind inflation and will always do as long as they are based on
past experience.''
   Hawkins said the full committee would take up the measure next
Thursday.
   A similar bill has been introduced in the Senate by Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Labor and Human Resources
Committee. That panel has held hearings on the proposal but has not
scheduled further action on it.
   The House subcommittee rejected, 6-3, a substitute measure
proposed by Rep. Thomas E. Petri, R-Wis., that would have raised
the minimum wage to $4 an hour over the next three years.
   Rep. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt., offered an amendment to increase
the ``tip credit'' for restaurant workers, it also lost, 6-3, after
Rep. Tommy F. Robinson, D-Ark., said he planned to introduce a
similar bill when the full committee meets next week and had worked
out a deal with Hawkins to do so.
   The restaurant industry wants to be able to count a waiter's
tips as a credit toward half the minimum wage requirement. Labor
and Hawkins are opposed to the proposal, but Robinson said he
believed he had enough votes in the full committee to pass it.
   The panel also defeated, 6-3, an amendment by Steve Bartlett,
R-Texas, to create what he called training wage of $3.35 an hour
for a 180-day period during which an employer can teach a new
worker.
   Hawkins said the proposal was nothing more than a ``subminimum
wage'' that had been rejected by Congress many times in the past.
``How long does it take a youngster to learn how to flip a
hamburger?'' he asked.
   Voting for the minimum wage increase were Reps. Hawkins, Penny,
Robinson, subcommittee chairman Austin J. Murphy, D-Pa.; Pat
Williams, D-Mont., and Robert E. Wise Jr., D-W.Va. Voting against
it were Petri, Jeffords and Bartlett.
   The minimum wage was raised to $3.35 an hour in 1981 from $3.10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
