<1ST_LINE>r w AM-McDonaldTaxes     03-03 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McDonald Taxes,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Seeks $6 Million From Estate of Late Rep. Larry McDonald</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estate of the late Rep. Larry McDonald,
who died in 1983 when a Korean Air Lines plane was shot down by a
Soviet fighter jet, is challenging an IRS claim for $6.1 million in
taxes.
   The key dispute is the contention by the Internal Revenue
Service that the value of the estate should include $10 million in
punitive damages and $2 million for pain and suffering that are
being sought in litigation against the airline. No damages have
been awarded.
   The Georgia Democrat's widow, Kathryn J. McDonald, the
administrator of the estate, filed suit in U.S. Tax Court to
protest the IRS claim.
   Her petition says that because the damage suit against the
airline is controlled by international law, no punitive damages are
possible.
   ``No recovery has been made for any damages relating to the
decedent's pain and suffering, and ultimate recovery is doubtful,''
said the peition, which was filed Jan. 21.
   McDonald was among 269 people who died when the KAL jumbo jet
was shot down after passing through Soviet airspace on Sept. 1,
1983, while flying from Anchorage, Alaska, to Seoul.
</TEXT>
