<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHELTENHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eddie ``The Eagle'' Edwards, the
scrappy ski-jumper who became the superstar loser at the Winter
Olympics, came home Thursday in a white Rolls-Royce to the cheers
of crowds.
   About 3,000 townsfolk waving ``Welcome Home Eddie'' flags lined
downtown streets for more than an hour to catch a glimpse of the
24-year-old who left home an unknown plasterer and returned a
celebrity.
   ``It's great to be back home and I'm just staggered by everyone
turning out to welcome me in the town,'' said Edwards. He finished
last in his two events but won over Olympic crowds with his
ever-ready smile and often-bumbling antics.
   He flew back from Calgary on Tuesday but spent two days in
London saying he had to sort out offers from manufacturers, movie
moguls, publishers and a vodka distiller.
   His parents, sister and brother greeted him wearing ``I Love
Eddie'' sweaters knitted by his 80-year-old grandmother.
   ``After all the fuss he has had around the world, he is still a
home-loving boy,'' said his mother, Janette. ``He's coping well
with it all.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of U.S. Sen. Richard G. Lugar,
reported missing early Thursday by relatives, was found unharmed at
a hotel in neighboring Illinois, a spokesman for Lugar said.
   Bertha Lugar Caldwell, 81, was last seen driving her car late
Wednesday in Indianapolis, about 70 miles from the Illinois state
line, Andy Fisher, an aide to the Indiana Republican, said from
Washington.
   ``We assume that she was driving around and got disoriented,''
said Fisher.
   Fisher said a doctor probably would examine Mrs. Caldwell in
Indianapolis but that her health ``has been fine all along.''
   Rain, freezing rain and sleet pelted the area during the night.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 21,000 rock fans have signed
their names to a pink Cadillac in an unusual petition drive to get
Bruce Springsteen to schedule a stop here on his ``Tunnel of Love''
tour.
   But Berry Bell of Premier Talent, Springsteen's New York booking
agency, said Rockford's 10,000-seat Metro Centre couldn't hold such
a concert.
   ``Your building is too small. ... Besides, he's booked through
the end of May,'' Bell said.
   Radio station WZOK bought the 1968 car and had it painted pink
in honor of ``Pink Cadillac,'' an early Springsteen hit.
   Mark McClure, operations manager at the station, said
Springsteen's tour, which began last week in Worcester, Mass., will
stop in suburban Chicago on March 16-17 and won't resume until
March 22 in Atlanta.
   ``He's got a five-day window between Chicago and Atlanta,'' he
said. ``But we say, `Come anytime you want.'''
   McClure plans to drive to Philadelphia on Monday when
Springsteen performs at The Spectrum there and park the
signature-decorated car near the back stage door. A similar
promotion, he said, persuaded the Rolling Stones to play Rockford
in 1981.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First graders at Del Obispo
Elementary School ate green eggs and ham this week in honor of the
84th birthday of Theodor Seuss Geissel, known to readers of his
children's books as Dr. Seuss.
   From his home in La Jolla Wednesday, Dr. Seuss said the tribute
was flattering but joked he was ``terrified'' to think the
youngsters actually ate green food.
   ``Are you calling from a hospital?'' he quipped.
   The 120 youngsters used food coloring to create the culinary
tribute to one of Dr. Seuss' most famous nonsensical works _
``Green Eggs and Ham.''
