<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Bradley admits that his speeches as a
rookie U.S. senator were boring, according to an interview
published Thursday.
   ``There was a strong sense that I was competing with Sominex,''
the New Jersey Democrat told Parade magazine, which said his skills
have greatly improved since he first announced a Senate bid in 1977.
   Despite continuing speculation of a presidential draft, Bradley
maintained he has a lot more to learn and do in the Senate. Running
for president, he sasid, would mean he no longer could enjoy the
freedom to make mistakes.
   ``You can no longer quietly and anonymously visit with and
listen to ordinary Americans in their homes,'' he said. ``You start
to exist tarmac to tarmac.''
  
