<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY29</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newly crowned Miss USA said Thursday that
the ``astronomical'' odds she faced in her bid to become the fourth
straight Miss Texas to win the title provided the extra push she
needed.
   At a Manhattan news conference, Courtney Gibbs said of her
beauty pageant win, ``I've been extremely overwhelmed, very numb.
It's just starting to settle in as I open up newspapers or turn on
the television.''
   The 21-year-old college student and model was crowned Tuesday in
the nationally televised event staged in El Paso, Texas.
   Miss Gibbs' win marked the fourth year in a row that a Texas
woman has won the event, prompting a stunned pageant spokeswoman,
Stacy Sacco, to assure reporters that the contest was not rigged.
   On Thursday, Miss Gibbs, a junior at Texas Christian University,
said that going into the pageant the computer-generated odds were
``something astronomical'' against another Texas woman winning.
   ``I think just that little bit of challenge, that little bit of
extra `you can't' really gave me the push to think that I could.''
   Miss Gibbs, an aspiring actress, will represent the United
States in the Miss Universe pageant May 23 in Taipei, Taiwan.
