<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1450EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Grammys     03-03 0969</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grammys,1008</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>You Can't Predict the Grammys, Nor the Presenters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It used to be easy to handicap the Grammys. But
as the music industry awards moved into their third decade, they
proved they can pack some surprises.
   Take Michael Jackson, for example.
   Four years ago, he nabbed a record eight Grammys with his
``Thriller'' LP. At the 30th Annual Grammy Awards on Wednesday
night, he was a big loser. He was nominated for four Grammys and he
didn't win any, though his engineers won for their work on his
album, ``Bad.''
   The Irish quartet U2, with their introspective songs of
humanity, were expected to sweep the National Academy of Recording
Arts & Sciences awards for their 12 million-seller LP, ``The Joshua
Tree.''
   The group was nominated for four Grammys and won two, including
album of the year. ``I Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For''
lost song of the year honors to ``Somewhere Out There,'' a sweet
song from an animated mouse movie, and lost record of the year to
Paul Simon's title track from last year's Grammy-winning
``Graceland'' LP.
   The ``Graceland'' single was released within the Oct. 1, 1986 to
Sept. 30, 1987 eligibility year to qualify for this year's awards.
   Simon wasn't at Radio City Music Hall to collect his trophy, nor
to see Ladysmith Black Mambazo, his collaborators on the South
African-inspired ``Graceland'' album, win a Grammy for their own
``Shaka Zulu'' collection, which Simon produced.
   Robert Shaw and the Atlanta Symphony Chorus and Orchestra won
more Grammys than the rock and pop stars who usually make the
headlines. Their recording of requiems by Gabriel Faure and Maurice
Durufle won awards for best engineered classical recording and for
producer Robert Woods. The Atlanta group's recording of Paul
Hindemith's ``When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd'' won as
best choral performance.
   There were more surprises: Sting beat Jackson and Bruce
Springsteen as best male pop vocalist for his album ``Bring on the
Night''; veteran rocker Frank Zappa zapped Springsteen and Stevie
Ray Vaughan as best rock instrumentalist for his LP ``Jazz From
Hell''; Smokey Robinson topped Jackson and Stevie Wonder as best
rhythm 'n' blues male vocalist for his single, ``Just to See Her.''
   And Suzanne Vega, whose soliloquy of an abused child touched
listeners throughout the world, won nothing for the song ``Luka.''
She had three nominations, including song and record of the year.
   ``I was hoping it would win, but I was prepared for anything to
happen,'' she said backstage. ``I'm a little disappointed I guess.''
   It wasn't surprising that Whitney Houston was chosen best female
pop vocalist for her single ``I Wanna Dance With Somebody (Who
Loves Me)'' or that Springsteen was chosen best rock vocalist for
his album, ``Tunnel of Love.''
   But one of the evening's biggest surprises and best moments came
from a presenter _ the strutting, screaming and outrageous Little
Richard. He stole the show and held it captive for a few hilarious
minutes when he declared he had won the prize for best new artist.
The award really went to Jody Watley.
   ``I have never received nuthin'. Y'all ain't never gave me no
Grammys, and I've been singing for 30 years,'' declared the man who
sang ``Tutti Frutti'' and ``Good Golly, Miss Molly.''
   ``I am the architect of rock 'n' roll,'' he shouted, and the
crowd jumped to its feet and roared approval.
   Bill Medley, who never won a Grammy with Bobby Hatfield as the
Righteous Brothers and said he'd ``been waiting 26 years for one of
these suckers,'' won with Jennifer Warnes. Their duet, ``(I've Had)
the Time of My Life,'' from the ``Dirty Dancing'' soundtrack, was
named best pop vocal performance by a duo or group.
   Aretha Franklin became the woman who owns the most Grammys,
moving ahead of Leontyne Price and Ella Fitzgerald, by winning two
this year for a total of 14. She won as best female rhythm 'n'
blues vocalist for her album ``Aretha,'' and with George Michael as
best rhythm 'n' blues duo or group for ``I Knew You Were Waiting
(for Me),'' a track from ``Aretha.''
   Diane Schuur won over jazz veterans Carmen McRae, Sarah Vaughan
and Ella Fitzgerald, and Manhattan Transfer's Janis Siegel, named
best female jazz vocalist with her critically acclaimed LP, ``Diane
Schuur and the Count Basie Orchestra.''
   The late Duke Ellington was represented by ``Digital Duke,'' the
Ellington Band conducted by Mercer Ellington.
   ``I felt Pop over my shoulder the whole time in the studio,''
Mercer Ellington said backstage.
   Posthumous albums won in two categories. ``Unfinished Business''
by Steve Goodman, who died of leukemia, won as best contemporary
folk record. Peter Tosh, slain in his Jamaica home last year during
a robbery, had recorded ``No Nuclear War,'' which won in the reggae
category.
   In classical categories, the Chicago Symphony's music director,
Sir Georg Solti, winner of more Grammys than anybody, added another
to his collection of 25, when ``Beethoven: Symphony No. 9'' was
named best orchestral recording.
   Pianist Vladimir Horowitz, who had been tied for second place
with Henry Mancini with 20 Grammys, pulled ahead. He picked up the
best classical album Grammy for ``Horowitz in Moscow.'' The record
was also named best classical instrumental solo performance without
orchestra.
   Violinist Itzhak Perlman received two Grammys, for best solo
instrumental with orchestra, for ``Mozart: Violin Concertos 2 and
4'' and, with cellist Lynn Harrell and pianist Vladimir Ashkenazy,
for best chamber performance, for ``Beethoven: the Complete Piano
Trios.''
   Soprano Kathleen Battle also received two. Her ``Kathleen Battle
_ Salzburg Recital'' won as best vocal solo performance and she was
a principal soloist on Strauss' ``Ariadne auf Naxos,'' which won as
best opera recording. Miss Battle was a featured soloist on four of
the five opera recordings that were nominated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1452EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Film     03-03 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Film,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Movie About Invader Packing House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film about an American adventurer
who took over Nicaragua more than 100 years ago was a box-office
flop in the United States, but it has been drawing long lines in
Managua.
   A downtown movie house has been packed since the film ``Walker''
opened Feb. 25. That's an unusual occurrence because the $5 tickets
cost more than many workers earn in a day.
   Moviegoers said they were curious and eager to see the scenes of
Granada, the central colonial city on the shores of Lake Nicaragua
where most of the film was shot last year.
   The movie, directed by Briton Alex Cox for Universal Pictures,
is about William Walker, a 19th century American adventurer who is
little-known in the United States but featured in every child's
history book in Nicaragua. The satirical film stars Ed Harris as
Walker nd Academy Award-winner Marlee Matlin as his
hearing-impaired wife.
   Walker is seen here as the first invader from the United States,
the man who started more than 100 years of U.S. intervention and a
symbol of Yankee imperialism.
   Walker came to Nicaragua in 1855 and after capturing Granada,
named himself president the following year. He offered an uneasy
warning of today's friction between Nicaragua and the United States
by saying, ``We'll be back, time and time again.''
   Walker surrendered to the U.S. Navy in 1857, tried to conquer
Central American in 1860 and was finally turned over to Honduras.
He was executed by firing squad in 1860.
   Reviews so far have been mixed.
   Roberto Fonseca wrote in the culture magazine Ventana that the
film was ``a joke in bad taste.''
   ``It's a shame that we lost the opportunity to make a film, a
work with instructive and political ends,'' Fonseca wrote.
   He noted that the film contained unnecessary violence and was
``extemely weak not only because of its ommissions but _ voluntary
or not _ for its misrepresentations.''
   The movie starts out by saying that ``This is a true story.''
   But reviewers find scores of factual errors, including the wrong
presidents at the time in Nicaragua and the United States.
   The 20th century props used in the film amused the crowd in the
Teatro Gonzalez movie house and they broke into laughter when
scenes showed contemporary news magazines, a recent model car and a
Soviet-made troop helicopter that was supposed to be carrying U.S.
government officials.
   But Fonseca, in his review, said: ``Personally, the
misrepresentations don't make me laugh.''
   The pro-government newspaper Nuevo Diario quoted Roberto Cruz,
described as a movie enthusiast, as saying the ``satire covered up
what Walker means in Nicaragua.''
   Most of the people at the theater hurried out, chatting among
themselves about the film.
   ``I liked it,'' one woman said, pulling the hand of a youngster.
``Why? Well, I like the scenes.''
   A young man, who said he didn't want to give his name, said: ``I
thought it was funny.''
   But another spectator, also declining to give his name, said
simply, ``It was silly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Book     03-03 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Book,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Jokes, No Photos But Plenty of (Economic) Recipes in Dukakis
Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0690 to fix category code.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidental candidate Michael Dukakis has joined
the literary campaign trail by co-authoring a book that chronicles
development in Massachusetts under his governorship.
   Dukakis wrote only two chapters of ``Creating the Future,'' but
his name is listed ahead of co-author Rosabeth Moss Kanter of the
Harvard Business School on the new $17.95 hardcover book that
explains the secrets of Massachusett's economic success.
   The book may instruct students of economic development policy.
But the average reader could come away thinking that political
campaign books are to books what political campaign food is to food.
   Several other presidential candidates have published books,
ranging from Democrat Gary Hart's novel, ``The Double Man,''
co-authored with Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, to Kansas Sen. Bob
Dole's ``Unlimited Partners,'' written with his wife, former
Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole, and Richard Norton Smith.
   Dukakis' book is neither a novel nor a biography. It has no
plot, poetry or photos. But it is full of recipes _ economic
recipes.
   Resolutely serious, the book focuses on the reversal of
Massachusetts' economic fortunes since Dukakis began his first term
as governor in 1975, when the state's unemployment rate was 12
percent and the state Treasury was more than $500 million in the
red. He lost in 1978 but won two more terms, in 1982 and 1986.
   Dukakis walks a fine line between praising himself and praising
others for what he calls ``the Massachusetts comeback'' or the
``Massachusetts miracle.''
   ``There is a lesson for America in the Massachusetts success
story. It is not that every specific program we tried here will
work everywhere else,'' Dukakis writes.
   ``Rather, the lesson is in the idea of hands-on economic
development and the approach we've used to get it done,'' he says.
The key ingredients were fiscal reform, investments in public
infrastructure, worker training and capital formation, and the
creation of public-private partnerships to encourage innovation.
   In the early stages of his presidential campaign last year,
Dukakis stressed his role in the turnaround that brought lower
taxes, rising personal income and the lowest unemployment rate of
any industrial state.
   Dukakis uses the book to lecture his critics who claim that
Massachusetts has benefited from the Reagan defense build-up.
   ``The world may identify Massachusetts with high technology, and
high technology with defense, but the facts are otherwise,''
Dukakis writes. He maintains that only about 4 percent of
Massachusetts employment depends on defense spending.
   Dukakis is credited as the author of chapters on the state's
comeback and on his now-familiar prescriptions for a national
economic development strategy.
   The bulk of the book was written by Kanter, an expert on
entrepreneurship and an ally of the Dukakis administration. Kanter
said the book grew out of discussions she had with Dukakis in 1986,
well before he decided to run for president.
   ``It might have been me first saying, there's a great story
here. Then his staff picked up on it,'' Kanter said in an interview.
   ``In February (1987) we met and decided a book was a good idea.
That was at his inititative,'' she said.
   According to Kanter, the chapters attributed to Dukakis were
based on speeches and policy statements he had made before, but she
insisted that Dukakis was actively involved in updating, editing
and rewriting them.
   ``He had somewhat less time than we were expecting,'' Kanter
said.
   John DeVillars, the governor's deputy chief of staff, said
Dukakis worked on the book while flying from one campaign stop to
another. ``He probably, in writing the book, traveled 15,000
miles,'' DeVillars said.
   The publisher, Simon and Schuster, refused to divulge any
figures about sales or orders. But if the book makes any money,
Dukakis and Kanter have decided to donate any proceeds to the
state's Adult Literacy Corps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
