<1ST_LINE>u a PM-FamilyPlanning     03-03 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Planning,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Implementation Of Ban On Federally Funded Abortion
Counseling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today blocked implementation of
new Reagan administration regulations designed to cut off federal
funds to family planning clinics which perform abortions or offer
abortion counseling.
   The new regulation, which were scheduled to take effect today,
would have had no immediate impact on the estimated 4,000 family
planning clinics around the nation operated with federal funds
because the rules apply only to new grants.
   U.S. District Judge Walter Jay Skinner issued a permanent
injunction against the Department of Health and Human Services
regulations.
   Skinner said in a 28-page order that the regulations issued last
month by the department ``as a whole violate both congressional
intent and rights protected by the Constitution.''
   It was not immediately clear if the ruling had effect outside
Massachusetts. Federal judges in Denver and New York City earlier
had issued temporary injunctions against implementation of the
rules.
   ``In my opinion, a governmentally imposed block on the flow of
neutral information bearing on abortion is an impermissible burden
on the presently recognized rights of a pregnant client'' of a
family planning clinic.
   Skinner also said the regulations violate First Amendment
protections of free speech for those who advocate abortion
   The injunction was requested last month by the state of
Massachusetts, the National Family Planning and Reproductive Health
Association and 13 other local and national family planning groups.
   The new rules would prohibit federally funded family planning
programs from providing abortion counseling, referring women to
abortion providers and engaging in lobbying or legal action to
increase availability of abortion.
   If the facility also performs abortions, to keep federal funding
for its other programs the clinic must maintain separate personnel,
separate accounting procedures, and provide different and clearly
defined waiting and treatment rooms for each type of patient.
   About 4,000 family planning clinics nationwide would be affected
by the regulations.
   In requesting the injunction, the state and the family planning
association told Skinner at a Feb. 17 hearing that the new
regulations were contrary to the intent of Congress when it
established the Family Planning Program under Title X of the Public
Health Service Act in 1970.
   The Title X budget for fiscal 1988 is $137 million, down from
$142 million in fiscal 1987. An estimated 5 million poor women
receive services from the program.
   In Massachusetts, there are 84 clinics serving 87,000 recipients
with the help of a $2.9 million Title X appropriation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
