<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-03 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Spokesman Reports Deaths in Southern Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government spokesman said Thursday some people
were killed in the southern city of Sumgait during weekend riots,
which he said were provoked by ``hooligans'' reacting to rumors of
ethnic confrontation.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov gave the first
official confirmation of deaths during the riots in the Caucasian
republic of Azerbaijan, but would not say how many people were
killed.
   ``Even one single life lost is already much too much,''
Gerasimov said when asked at a news briefing about a claim by
Armenian dissidents that 17 people were killed at Sumgait, an
industrial city of more than 160,000.
   Trouble between ethnic Azerbaijanis and ethnic Armenians began
early last month with a dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, a region
just north of Iran and east of Turkey. More than three-quarters of
the population is Armenian but it was made part of neighboring
Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Protesters in Nagorno-Karabakh demanded that it be joined to
Armenia and peaceful protests spread to Yerevan, capital of Soviet
Armenia.
   Riots were reported Sunday in Sumgait, 150 miles from
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``A group of mutineers, of hooligans, provoked disorders,''
Gerasimov said. ``These riots involved people who fell for
provocative rumors and instigations with respect to what happened
in Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``Using the situation of spontaneity, the instigators of
violence participated in actions which led to casualties.''
   He referred at other times in the briefing to loss of life,
indicating the casualties were deaths.
   On Wednesday, an employee of the television station in Baku,
capital of Azerbaijan, said one or two people had been killed in
Sumgait. He spoke in a telephone interview on condition of
anonymity.
   Gerasimov acknowledged that problems also developed in
Kirovabad, another city in Azerbaijan. ``The situation in Kirovabad
is normal, although over there some things might have happened
too,'' he said, but refused to elaborate.
   The television worker said 50-60 young ethnic Azerbaijanis who
live in Armenia traveled to Sumgait last weekend and told relatives
and friends about ethnic confrontations. He said ``young
hooligans'' then went on a rampage and killed people.
   On Thursday, Gerasimov said people were arrested and prosecutors
were investigating. He said order had been restored in Sumgait,
businesses and stores were running normally and the curfew had been
lifted.
   He said two ranking Soviet officials were in Sumgait
``investigating these anti-social manifestations.'' He identified
them as Pyotr N. Demichev, a non-voting member of the national
Communist Party Politburo, and Kyamran Bagirov, first secretary of
the Azerbaijan Central Committee.
   Some ethnic Azerbaijanis had fled their homes, he said.
   ``Influenced by such provocative rumors and rumor-mongering, a
small number of Azerbaijani families left Azerbaijan,'' Gerasimobv
told the journalists. ``They went to their relatives regularly,''
he said, but did not say where they settled.
   The only other confirmed report of deaths in the
Armenian-Azerbaijan unrest was a Soviet prosecutor's comment
Saturday that two people in Agdamsky, a district of Azerbaijan
bordering Nagorno-Karabakh, had been murdered in disorders linked
to the territorial dispute.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed Feb. 26 for calm in
Armenia and Azerbaijan, and said the Communist Party Central
Committee would review the dispute.
</TEXT>
