<HEAD>Restrictive Abortion Regs Face Challenges</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs last 3 grafs to update with Boston judge's ruling</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New regulations to deny federal funds to
family-planning organizations that counsel abortion technically go
into effect today, but three court challenges have left the picture
murky.
   Even if the new rules weren't in legal limbo, there would be no
immediate practical impact on the estimated 4,000 family planning
clinics around the nation operated with federal funds.
   That is because the new regulations apply only to new grants.
   All the clinics that might eventually be affected are now
operating with money approved under the old regulations. No new
grant applications are in the final approval stage.
   Federal judges in Denver and New York City have issued temporary
injunctions against implementation of the new rules, but it is not
clear whether they have full nationwide force.
   In Boston today, a third federal judge, Walter Jay Skinner,
issued a permament injunction against the Department of Health and
Human Services blocking implementation of the rules.
   Skinner said the regulations violate Congress' intent and rights
protected by the Constitution.
   ``In my opinion, a governmentally imposed block on the flow of
neutral information bearing on abortion is an impermissible burden
on the presently recognized rights of a pregnant client'' of a
family planning clinic, the judge said.
