<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Women     03-03 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Women,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Find AIDS Virus in Cervix Tissue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors have isolated the AIDS virus from the
cervixes of AIDS-infected women, a discovery that sheds some light
on how the disease is transmitted.
   It may explain how a woman passes on the disease to babies
during birth and to her sex partners, researchers say.
   Doctors at Massachusetts General Hospital isolated the virus
from the cervixes of three of four AIDS-infected women.
   ``These findings indicate that there is actually virus within
the cervix tissue itself, and the virus can be secreted'' into the
genital fluids, said Dr. Martin S. Hirsch, senior author of the
report. ``These might be a source of subsequent infection to
others.''
   Experts had known before that infected women can have AIDS virus
in their genital regions, although it was unclear where it came
from.
   ``This shows pretty clearly that the source of the virus within
the genital secretions is actually cells within the cervix,''
Hirsch said in an interview.
   He said the cervix might also be infected directly during
intercourse from contact with virus-laden sperm, although the study
doesn't prove the AIDS virus actually gets into women's bodies this
way.
   The study, directed by Dr. Roger J. Pomerantz, was published in
the March issue of the Annals of Internal Medicine.
   The researchers found the virus in endothelial cells that line
blood vessels in the inner layer of the cervix, as well as in
germ-eating macrophages and other blood cells within the cervical
tissue.
   ``It's interesting and raises possibilities that perhaps the
cervix could be infected directly by the virus, rather than get
there through the blood,'' said Dr. Jay A. Levy of the University
of California, San Francisco.
   The new research adds one more site to the growing list of
targets of the AIDS virus, known as HIV.
   The virus kills by destroying helper T-cells, blood cells that
orchestrate the body's immune defenses against all kinds of
microscopic invaders, among them the AIDS virus itself. However,
experts have learned that the virus also infects other types of
blood cells as well as other parts of the body, including the eyes
and the brain.
   Last month, Levy and others published a report showing that the
AIDS virus also infects the rectum and colon. That could explain
one way that the disease is spread during anal intercourse.
   Many experts have assumed that for an AIDS infection to occur,
the virus must enter the bloodstream through a tear in the body's
tissues. The discovery of infected rectal and cervical tissue,
however, suggests this might not always be necessary. Instead,
infection might occur by direct viral contact with the rectum and
the female sex organs.
   ``A local infection of susceptible cervical cells from infected
semen may preceed systemic spread of HIV,'' the researchers wrote.
   Hirsch said he believes, though cannot prove, that the AIDS
virus can penetrate intact cervical tissue, but infection might
occur more readily if the cervix is inflamed by venereal disease.
   About 40 percent of babies born to infected women catch the
virus themselves, either before or during birth. The study raised
the possiblity that delivery by Caesarean section might lower the
risk to the newborn but says there is no proof for this.
   The women tested in the study were all heroin users who likely
got infected from contaminated needles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0173 </DOCNO>
