<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RailTheft     03-03 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Theft,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City-Owned Railroad Track Disappears _ Ties, Gravel and All</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may not be the great train robbery,
but it could be the great rail theft _ every inch of a 2,000-foot
stretch of city-owned railroad track in Great Falls has disappeared.
   ``They did a good job, too,'' said City Engineer Stu Pearson.
``They took the railroad, the ties and the gravel.''
   Time of the theft is a bit uncertain _ sometime between August
1984 and last week. Value of the stolen track was estimated at
$80,000.
   Pearson said he learned last week the track was missing. He was
notified by the manager of the construction company that laid the
track for the city.
   ``I had to sit down and catch my breath,'' Pearson said. ``I
couldn't believe it was gone. But sure enough, you go up there and
there's not a lick of rail.''
   He has since done some investigating. ``Everybody that I've
talked to ... can remember work going on, but they can't remember
who did it,'' he said.
   The track spur, installed in 1978, extended from the Burlington
Northern Railroad's main line into an industrial park that is now
partially occupied.
   The problem is serious, Pearson said, because rail service is an
important factor in selling lots in the industrial park. Although
the spur obviously had not been used much in the last few years, it
may be needed when the economy improves, he said.
   Pearson said he has asked officials from the BN and Milwaukee
Road railroads to check records to determine whether their workers
removed the track by mistake. He has yet to receive a response.
   The cost to replace the track would be about $160,000, he
estimated, but the city has no plans to do so yet.
</TEXT>
