<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KidnapReunion     03-03 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnap Reunion,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caseworker's Hunch Brings Reunion Of Kidnapped Boy And Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESQUITE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hunch by a caseworker led to a tearful
reunion of a mother with her 15-month-old son who was kidnapped
when he was 18 days old.
   Alisha Wetselline-Rodriguez held her son, Eric, on Wednesday and
was so excited she could barely speak.
   ``I understand he has to get used to me,'' Ms.
Wetselline-Rodriguez said as she cradled the boy, dressed in red
overalls and a striped shirt, during a visit to the home where he
has been cared for.
   For months after Eric was kidnapped from his home on Dec. 9,
1986, Ms. Wetselline-Rodriguez called police and got the same
message: Nothing yet.
   She then resorted to a nationwide search using fliers and
getting in touch with child-welfare agencies.
   On Christmas Eve last year, Texas Department of Human Services
worker Mary Forrester noticed a striking similarity between a
picture of Eric on a missing-children flier and the picture of an
abandoned child who had been turned over to the agency.
   The identification process began then; the boy's mother was
officially notified Monday night that her son had been found.
   ``It was a one-in-a-million case,'' said Ms. Forrester. ``I
wasn't even supposed to get the case, but another worker was
overloaded. And when I first saw the flier, I threw it away.
Something made me go back and look at it.''
   Family Court Judge Harold Gaither Jr. on Wednesday returned the
boy to Ms. Wetselline-Rodriguez's custody after reviewing evidence
from blood tests and testimony by officials.
   A few months after his kidnapping, a Dallas woman took Eric to a
local Catholic church and told a priest that a woman she met in a
park had asked her to care for the child for a week while the woman
went to Houston to seek work.
   The church turned the child over to the state last May.
   The woman never returned, and efforts to find her have failed,
according to Dallas County Assistant District Attorney Beverly
Storey.
   Ms. Forrester said the boy would have been eligible for adoption
in November, but she postponed that process because she had a
feeling about the case.
   John and Diane Noster, who have nurtured the boy for 10 months
and have celebrated his first steps and first birthday, will keep
the boy for another week, giving him a chance to grow accustomed to
his mother.
   ``I've waited this long, what's another week?'' said Ms.
Wetselline-Rodriguez, who turned 22 on Dec. 29. ``This is the best
Christmas and birthday present I've ever had.''
</TEXT>
