<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC-Dengue     03-03 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC-Dengue,0256</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 6:30 p.m. EST _ time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>CDC: Programs Needed To Stop West Hemisphere Epidemics Of Dengue
Fever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. health officials warned Thursday that new
prevention and control programs are needed to prevent Western
Hemisphere epidemics of dengue fever, a tropical disease carried by
mosquitoes.
   ``The incidence of dengue in most countries of the (Americas)
region has continued to increase in recent years,'' the U.S.
Centers for Disease Control reported.
   In Brazil alone, 47,370 cases of dengue were officially reported
in 1986, and health authorities there estimate that between 300,000
and 500,000 cases may have actually occurred. In Mexico, 21,975
cases were officially reported.
   Dengue fever is caused by infection with a dengue virus and can
prompt fever, pains in the joints, and even death.
   Thirty-three cases of dengue fever were reported in the United
States in 1986.
   The CDC noted that the disease is transmitted by mosquitoes,
including the Aedes albopictus, or ``tiger mosquito,'' which is
increasingly prevalent in the United States. The species has now
spread to 17 states, mostly in the South, East and Midwest.
   ``While the ultimate significance of the presence of (the tiger
mosquito) is not known, it is likely to increase the efficiency of
virus maintenance in infested areas,'' the CDC said in its weekly
report.
   The CDC also blamed the increase in dengue infections in the
Americas on the simultaneous circulation of several different types
of dengue virus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
