<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LimburgerTheft     03-03 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Limburger Theft,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>73-Year-Old Man Sentenced To Prison For Stealing Food</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Hairm in 2nd graf is CQ</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LEBANON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 73-year-old man described as a dangerous
repeat offender was sentenced to 6 to 25 years in prison Thursday
after he pleaded guilty to stealing Limburger cheese and other food
from a grocery store.
   Hairm Richardson entered the plea to a single count of
aggravated robbery just before he was to go on trial on charges of
aggravated robbery, felonious assault and possessing criminal
tools. Warren County prosecutors agreed to drop the other charges
in exchange for the guilty plea.
   Richardson, of Miamisburg, was accused of shoplifting two pounds
of bacon, a sausage and a jar of Limburger cheese from a Franklin
grocery store last October and then pulling a knife on a store
employee who tried to stop him.
   Prosecutors said Richardson's ``criminal tool'' was a large coat
with extra pockets sewn inside, allegedly for the purpose of hiding
shoplifted food.
   James Beaton, an assistant county prosecutor, said he was
satisfied with the sentence and said Richardson will probably spend
the rest of his life behind bars.
   ``I don't think he'll see the light of day,'' Beaton said.
   In 1942, Richardson and three brothers were convicted of
first-degree murder in the slaying of a man who tried to stop a
robbery in a bar and all four were sentenced to life. Richardson
was paroled in July 1964 after then-Gov. James Rhodes commuted his
conviction to second-degree murder.
   In 1981, Richardson was convicted of misdemeanor theft in
Miamisburg and was sentenced to 30 days in jail and fined $250,
police said. In 1982, Franklin police charged him with drug abuse
and trafficking in marijuana; he served less than 10 months of a
1-to 5-year sentence before being paroled in May 1983, officials
said.
   ``We have to take a hard line on it. The guy's dangerous,''
Beaton said in an interview. ``This guy is not your average
73-year-old man, not by a long shot.''
   ``He's as strong as an ox and in perfect health,'' Franklin
police Detective Rick Thacker said.
   If convicted of the original charges, Richardson could have
received a 10- to 25-year term for aggravated robbery and 8 to 15
years for each of the two felonious assault charges.
</TEXT>
