<DOCNO> AP880303-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1611EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Condo-Spanish     03-03 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condo-Spanish,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`English Only' Condo Rule Causes Furor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apartment cooperative that requires
new owners and renters to speak English has sparked threats of
picketing among Hispanics, who claim the rule is discriminatory.
   The language requirement was imposed at the Paradise Towers
apartment building after communications problems arose with a
Colombian couple who could not speak English. Other residents
complained they could not make the couple understand that their
grandchildren were wandering too close to a dangerous seawall, the
president of the condominium's board of directors said.
   The bylaw, which went into effect more than year ago, was
publicized recently by a story in the Miami Herald.
   Hispanics, angered at what they call a discriminatory policy,
plan to picket outside the 70-unit cooperative later this week.
   ``This is a blatant violation and we will do whatever has to be
done to get this changed,'' said Mike Morales, a South Broward
Hispanic leader. ``So long as people have the money to pay, be it
from Spain, Europe or any other part of the world, they should be
able to live where they want.''
   According to the Fair Housing Act of 1968, discrimination in
housing is prohibited on the basis of race, religion, sex, color
and national origin. Representatives of the U.S. Justice Department
say the cooperative's bylaw could violate the act.
   Under the bylaw, no apartment can be sold or leased unless at
least one member of the new household can read, understand and
speak English.
   ``It's sad that in a place like South Florida, which depends a
lot on economic relations with South America for its livelihood,
that something like this could happen,'' said attorney Osvaldo
Soto, chairman of the Spanish American League Against
Discrimination in Miami.
   But residents of the cooperative, which screens all prospective
owners and renters, say the rule is necessary to maintain safety
and the building's private club atmosphere.
   ``We screen everyone for the protection of our tenants. We don't
want undesirables living here,'' said Charles Levy, retired lawyer
and president of Paradise Towers' board of directors. ``And if we
can't communicate with people, it creates a real burden.''
   The Colombian couple moved out of the condominium in October
1986, and the bylaw was passed overwhelmingly in January 1987 by
board members and residents. If the couple had stayed, they would
have been exempt from the new bylaw, Levy said.
   No one has yet been turned away or kicked out because of the
rule, he said.
   Despite the ruckus, board members said the cooperative has no
plans of amending the bylaw unless residents demand it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
