<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SkiBindingRecall     03-03 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ski Binding Recall,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyrolia Recalls 450,000 Ski Bindings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 450,000 Tyrolia ski bindings are being
recalled because of heel and toe lug breakage which could lead to
serious injury, the Consumer Product Safety Commission said
Thursday.
   The voluntary recall was announced by Tyrolia Freizeitgerate of
Austria, which said consumers should cease using the affected
bindings.
   If the lugs holding the ski bindings to the ski should fail
during use, serious injury could occur because of loss of control
by the skier, the commission said.
   Generally, should breakage occur, it happens when the boot is
being inserted into the binding. But five injuries have been
reported that may have been related to lug failure, the agency said.
   The affected bindings can be identified by the color of the toe
lug and the production code stamped on the right side of the base
of the heel plate.
   Bindings being recalled are:
   _Grey toe lugs: Models 480, 230 and 177 with production codes
starting with H; Model 190 with production codes starting with G or
H.
   _Blue toe lugs: Model 290 with production codes starting with F.
   _White toe lugs: Model 290 with production codes starting with
F; Model 280 with codes starting with G; Models 220 and 170 with
codes starting with F or G or ending with 4; Model 180 with codes
starting with G; Model 90 Junior with codes ending with 4.
   _Black toe lugs: Model 80 Junior with codes ending with 4 or 2.
   Ski bindings with red lugs are not being recalled.
   Tyrolia said consumers who bring their ski bindings to the shop
where they were purchased or to their nearest Tyrolia dealer by
April 30 will be given new replacement bindings at no charge.
   After April 30 consumers will be given a choice of reconditioned
bindings at no charge or new replacement bindings at a charge of
between $18 and $21.
   Consumers with questions can contact Tyrolia at 1-800-343-5999
in the United States or 1-800-265-7252 in Canada. The commission
can be reached at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
