<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0726 03-03 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jeane Kirkpatrick Endorses Dole; Senator Eases Up On Bush-Noriega
Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, Dole also, to remove possessive from reference
to Bush.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole pocketed an endorsement from
conservative former U.N. Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick on Thursday
and urged a federal death penalty for drug ``overlords and
kingpins'' as he sought to invigorate a faltering Super Tuesday
campaign.
   Dole also stepped gingerly around the issue of whether GOP
presidential campaign rival George Bush was involved in possible
CIA payments to Panamanian strongman Manuel Noriega. Bush has
refused to discuss anything he did as CIA director that might
affect national security and criticized Dole for talking about CIA
matters.
   On Thursday, Dole cited news reports saying Noriega may have
gotten millions of dollars from the CIA but did not speak directly
of Bush the way he did when the Kansas senator first raised the
subject on Wednesday.
   Dole's aides hoped to use the endorsement from Kirkpatrick, a
former Democrat, to attract conservative support in several of the
Southern states holding primaries and caucuses next Tuesday. Ms.
Kirkpatrick, who declined some moves to get her to run for the GOP
presidential nomination, is popular among conservatives for her
hard-line foreign policy views.
   Michael Murphy, whose firm produces campaign commercials for
Dole, said Ms. Kirkpatrick's endorsement statement had been taped,
and advertisements would be ready by the end of the day in case
senior officials decide to use them in the Super Tuesday campaign.
   Dole's aides concede he is running behind Bush in most of the 17
states holding primaries and caucuses next Tuesday, many of them in
the South. The senator said his goal for those primaries is ``to
get our share of delegate'' at stake, and insisted it was not
possible for Bush to strike a knockout blow on that day.
   But he offered no prediction on how many of the 712 available
delegates he hopes for.
   He also conceded he is running behind Bush in South Carolina,
which holds its primary on Saturday _ and talked instead of
same-day caucuses in his home state of Kansas and in Wyoming, two
states where he said ``we look particulary good.''
   Ms. Kirkpatrick, who left the Democratic party after joining the
Reagan administration, praised Dole warmly as a candidate who is
``serious and strong and smart and honorable and can be elected.''
   ``I know George Bush and Bob Dole,'' she told a news conference.
``I've worked with both of them on foreign policy problems, and I
have more confidence that Dole can produce the flexibility and the
strength'' to deal with the country's problems and sit across from
Soviet Leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Dole called Ms. Kirkpatrick the ``heart and soul of the Reagan
Revolution.''
   Earlier, in a speech to a White House conference on drug abuse,
Dole said it was wrong to give clean needles to drug addicts, as is
being done in New York. ``Giving clean needles to addicts may be
intended to prevent disease, but it also endorses addiction,'' he
said.
   He added that he favors imposition of a death penalty for ``the
drug overlords and the kingpins'' of the international drug trade.
   Dole used his speech to take a slap at Noriega, who has been
indicted on drug charges in this country, saying, ``we don't need
him around either.''
   But he seemed to back off slightly from comments he made while
campaigning in Louisiana on Wednesday.
   At the time, he said there were ``some who say he's (Noriega)
been on the (CIA) payroll since 1966.''
   Speaking of Bush, who served as CIA director from 1976 to 1977,
he said, ``He made all those decisions in the CIA. What were they?
Was Noriega on the payroll when he was CIA director? The CIA
payroll?''
   Asked to explain his comments at a news conference at which he
won Ms. Kirkpatrick's endorsement, Dole cited published reports
saying that ``for many years Noriega was on the CIA payroll, maybe
got millions of dollars from the CIA.
   ``That's all I've suggested. There are a lot of CIA directors
over the past 20 years. I'm also suggesting that it shouldn't come
as any surprise to anyone that Noriega and others in Panama have
been involved in the drug business.''
</TEXT>
