<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Szeryng     03-03 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Szeryng,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violinist and Cultural Ambassador Henryk Szeryng</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virtuoso violinist and cultural ambassador Henryk
Szeryng, known for his refreshing and moving renditions of Bach and
Brahms, died Thursday of a cerebral hemorrhage. He was 69.
   Szeryng died in Kassel, West Germany, according to Herve Corre
of the musician's Paris office. He had suffered a cerebral
hemorrhage early Wednesday, then died after 24 hours in a coma.
   Renowned worldwide for a vast repertoire which he executed with
great skill and feeling during a career that spanned more than 50
years, Szeryng was to have performed Wednesday in Brussels at a
concert to benefit AIDS research.
   The Polish-born musician, who traveled on a diplomatic passport
as Mexico's official cultural ambassador, also was known for his
special preference for resurrecting neglected or lost works for the
violin.
   Last fall he delighted concert-goers in Atlanta with a
performance of a previously lost violin concerto by Reynaldo Hahn.
   Szeryng also prided himself on introducing relatively unknown
contemporary works to audiences worldwide.
   A tonalist and colorist with the technical command of a master,
he thrilled audiences with what critics called ``his obvious
delight in playing.'' Instead of wrinkling his brow with the pained
look of many of his colleagues, he appeared enraptured, smiling
happily as he played favorite passages.
   Arthur Rubinstein, the Polish-born pianist who died in 1982,
once called him ``a musician's musician ... who gave real music
lovers what they wanted: great moments of emotion.''
   Szeryng was born on Sept. 22, 1918, in Zelazowa-Wola, Poland,
which was Frederic Chopin's birthplace. His father was a wealthy
iron and lumber magnate and his mother was a professional pianist
who taught the young Henryk the piano and harmony when he was only
five. His elder brother played the violin and Szeryng, fascinated
by the instrument, took it up at seven.
   ``It was totally beyond my comprehension,'' he said in a 1983
interview. ``How could one find the right notes and the right
intervals on a fingerboard which is totally blank? Piano playing
was much simpler. You had white keys and black keys.''
   Polish violinst Bronislaw Huberman, a family friend, encouraged
Szeryng to pursue his violin studies and persuaded his parents to
send him to Berlin where he studied with Carl Flesch. Huberman's
political ideas also influenced Szeryng's lifelong commitment to
peace.
   In 1936, he studied at the Paris Conservatory, winning the
coveted first prize only nine months after entering. He studied
composition with the legendary Nadia Boulanger and Gabriel Bouillon
and became friends with Jean Cocteau, Pablo Picasso and Igor
Stravinsky.
   At the outbreak of World War II, Szeryng, who spoke seven
languages fluently, was made Polish Prime Minister Wladislav
Sikorski's official translator and later became a personal
goverment liaison officer. But he never abandonded his music,
giving more than 300 concerts at Allied hospitals and bases, even
during air raids in Britain.
   In 1941, he accompanied the exiled prime minister to Latin
America in search of a home for about 4,000 Polish refugees
displaced by the war. They were accepted by Mexico. Moved by this
humanitarian gesture, Szeryng took Mexican citizenship in 1946.
   In 1970, he was appointed special music adviser to Mexico's
UNESCO delegation in Paris and became the first musician to enjoy
diplomatic status.
   Although he once called Bach his ``bible'' and Chopin his
``first musical food,'' Szeryng also had a passion for contemporary
music. He said it gave him ``an extra portion of spontaneity and
freshness.''
   Funeral services are to be held in Monte Carlo, Monaco, his
European home for many years, at a date to be announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
