<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1621EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DebtCommission     03-03 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debt Commission,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gray Says Administration Trying To Put Wraps On Panel Till
Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commission created to recommend solutions
to the government's debt woes is apparently embroiled in a dispute
with the Reagan administration even before it begins meeting.
   House Budget Committee Chairman William Gray III complained
Thursday that the administration was trying to dictate how the
National Economic Commission would conduct its work in an effort to
keep the panel's deliberations secret during the presidential
election campaign.
   ``I don't think this commission should start off being dictated
to by the White House,'' Gray, who is a member of the commission,
told reporters. ``Someone is suggesting that we meet in a cave and
roll a stone over the opening.''
   Gray took issue with a suggestion made by Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III that the 14-member bipartisan commission, which
was created by Congress last year, should hold its deliberations in
secret and not release any reports before the November presidential
election.
   While saying that the administration wanted the commission ``to
go to work,'' Baker suggested in an apperarance before the Senate
Appropriations Committee on Tuesday that the commission's findings
would carry more weight if the panel did not become embroiled in
the presidential election campaign.
   The commission, which includes former Democratic Party leader
Robert Strauss and Chyrsler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca, is
scheduled to hold its first meeting on Friday in Washington.
   Gray said the first session would be a get-acquainted luncheon,
but he said the panel would need to quickly make decisions on
setting up a schedule of meetings and deciding how it would operate.
   However, the disagreement over such a fundamental issue as
whether to hold open hearings suggests that the panel may have
trouble operating, particularly if the members split along party
lines. Six members have been appointed by Republicans and six by
Democrats.
   Gray suggested that Republicans were trying to keep the
commission under wraps so that it would not become a forum for
airing Reagan's biggest economic failure, the string of record
federal budget deficits.
   ``I don't think it is appropriate for the White House to say
there should be nothing said or done until they get out of town,''
Gray said. ``That is like the guilty party saying don't hand down
sentence until we leave town.''
   The commission is considered by many to be the best hope the
next president will have to reach a quick consensus with Congress
on significant ways to reduce the budget deficit, which is expected
to exceed $150 billion this year.
   The commission is scheduled to issue its final report on March
1, early in the next administration and presumably when a new
president would have the most leverage to get his proposals through
Congress.
   The commission eventually will have 14 members. President Reagan
has already named as his choices former Defense Secretary Caspar W.
Weinberger and former Transportation Secretary Drew Lewis, who is
now chairman of Union Pacific Corp.
   Republican and Democratic congressional leaders have named 10
other members and the new president-elect will name the final two
members after the November election.
   Gray's comments came following a Budget Committee hearing in
which Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan repeated his
suggestion that a 15-cent-a-gallon increase in the federal gasoline
tax would be a good way to help shrink the budget deficit. The
gasoline tax is currently at nine cents a gallon.
   Greenspan had voiced the same suggestion in testimony Wednesday
before the Senate Budget Committee.
   In some unusually specific suggestions to Congress, Greenspan
said Thursday that an increase in the gasoline tax of 15 cents
would raise $15 billion annually in new revenues while leaving
retail gasoline prices still well below the levels of the early
1980s.
   Responding to questions, Greenspan said he favored a gasoline
tax over an oil import fee, which is favored by the domestic oil
industry, because an oil import fee would raise energy costs for
American manufacturers, thus reducing their competitiveness with
foreign producers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
