<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Higgins-Promotion     03-03 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Higgins-Promotion,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnapped Marine Officer Selected For Promotion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Marine officer kidnapped in Lebanon
two weeks ago has been selected for promotion to the rank of
colonel, the corps said Thursday.
   Lt. Col. William ``Rich'' Higgins, until last summer a military
aide to former Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger, was selected
by a promotion board along with 78 other lieutenant colonels for
advancement.
   The promotion list was published Thursday. Higgins is No. 55 on
the list of 79 and would not actually receive the new rank for
another year at the earliest.
   The Marine promotion board was formed early this year to screen
a field of 165 men and women, long before Higgins' kidnapping on
Feb. 17.
   The 43-year-old officer was in Lebanon because he had been
assigned to temporary duty with the United Nations, heading a group
of observers in Lebanon attached to the U.N. Truce Supervision
Organization.
   A decorated Vietnam combat veteran, Higgins served as the junior
military assistant to Weinberger for two years _ from June 1985 to
June 1987.
</TEXT>
