<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1642EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AirForceCuts     03-03 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Force Cuts,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Slows Space Launches, Furloughs Workers Because of
Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget cuts imposed by Congress will lead to a
slowdown in the Air Force's space launch operations this year and
layoffs of as many as 500 contractor employees, the service said
Thursday.
   The roughly 28,000 civilian employees who work directly for the
Air Force Systems Command, however, should not have to endure any
unpaid furloughs, the service added.
   The Air Force said the head of the Systems Command sent a
message to his field commanders Thursday informing them of a
variety of steps aimed at coping with a $281 million cut in his
operations and maintenance fund.
   Gen. Bernard P. Randolph has ordered a slowdown in operations at
Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif., and Cape Canaveral Air Force
Station, Fla., the service said. That move will force the
contractors who operate the two space launch facilities to trim
their work forces and delay some scheduled space launches, the Air
Force said.
   The command also is offering early retirement to employees;
cutting spending on travel, supplies and maintenance; and enforcing
a hiring freeze.
   ``Based on your planned and very difficult reductions in mission
support, the command can still meet its critical mission without a
furlough at this time,'' Randolph wrote.
   ``But we have almost no room for error.''
   The Air Force Systems Command, headquartered at Andrews Air
Force Base, Md., outside Washington, is the arm of the service
responsible for developing and procuring new aircraft and weapons.
It is also the parent, however, of the Air Force's Space Division.
   The Air Force uses facilities at Vandenberg and Cape Canaveral
to launch military satellites into space.
   To save money, the Air Force said the contractors at the two
facilities have been told to cut back to one shift per day, five
days a week. Currently, the contractors _ Pan American World
Services Inc. at Cape Canaveral and the Federal Electric Corp. at
Vandenberg _ employ a total of about 5,000 workers.
   Lt. Col. Doug Kennett, a spokesman, said it would be up to the
contractors to decide how many employees to lay off but ``it could
get as high as 10 percent.''
   The reduction in shifts ``will increase processing time to
prepare for launches by at least 30 days,'' the service added.
   ``Some test launches will have to be delayed and maintenance of
existing facilities will be deferred.''
   Kennett declined to say how many launches might be delayed or
which satellites would be affected.
   The move to avoid furloughs within the Systems Command follows a
congressional outcry over plans by the Air Force Logistics Command
to furlough its 84,000 civilian workers up to 10 days this year
because of budget cuts.
   The operations and maintenance account for the Systems Command
was reduced this year to $1.65 billion from $1.935 billion in
fiscal 1987. Of that fiscal 1988 total, about $231 million is
earmarked for the operation of the two space centers _ down $22
million from fiscal 1987.
   The cuts stem from a reduction in the Pentagon's budget under
the terms of a deficit reduction compromise that was negotiated by
the White House and Congress last November.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
