<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--NairobiFinances     03-03 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nairobi Finances,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Official Says Nairobi Is Broke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Nairobi is broke and it is
raiding other budgets and intercepting employees' health fund
contributions in order to continue providing essential services, it
was reported Thursday.
   J. Musyoka-Annan, the town clerk, told the Kenya Times that the
city is owed about $38 million in unpaid rates and other charges.
He did not say how much the city owed its creditors.
   In order to continue providing services to its 1.5 million
residents, city officials have not been paying debts, forwarding
employees' tax deductions to the government or paying their
National Health Insurance Fund contributions, Musyoka Annan said.
   He said officials are paying for other services by borrowing
money from the World Bank-financed Water Fund, which was set up to
fund water projects in the city.
   Property assessments, the city's only source of money, is not
expanding and expenses are increasing, he said.
   President Daniel arap Moi dismissed elected councillors in 1982
and appointed a commision to run the city following public outcry
over uncollected garbage, irregular hiring practices and
mismanagement at City Hall.
</TEXT>
