<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuelSpill     03-03 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Spill,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foundation Shift Suspected In Ashland Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shifting of a clay and limestone foundation is
being considered as a possible cause of the Ashland Oil Inc. oil
tank collapse that fouled two rivers and threatened drinking water
in parts of three states.
   ``We are looking at a number of things, including the quality of
materials and possible issues surrounding the tank foundation,''
said Matt Hayman, spokesman for the National Bureau of Standards.
   Two Ashland contractors disagree about whether the stone and
clay pad under the 4-million-gallon steel tank sank before the
collapse or was eroded by escaping oil.
   Workers began taking soil samples last Saturday from the
120-foot diameter foundation that supported the tank bottom and
will continue their search for clues next week, Betsy Mallison,
spokeswoman for the state Department of Environmental Resources,
said Wednesday.
   ``One of our researchers was there specifically to be included
in the soil examination of the base,'' said Hayman.
   The Jan. 2 collapse allowed an estimated 730,000 gallons of oil
to enter the Monongahela River, which joins the Allegheny River at
Pittsburgh to create the Ohio River. About 23,000 suburban
Pittsburgh residents lost water service for most of the week after
the collapse, and shutoffs were threatened in Pennsylvania, Ohio
and West Virginia towns that draw water from the Ohio.
   Employees of Dennis Jaskolski Contracting Co. helped dismantle
the tank after it collapsed and found that portions of the
foundation appeared to have sunk between 12 and 18 inches, said
Dennis Jaskolski.
   ``After we moved the floor pieces off, you could see that a
third of the foundation had dropped lower,'' he said.
   ``There appeared to be a defect in the stone base,'' Jaskolski
said. ``When the metal bottom was laying flat on top of it you
couldn't see it, but then we started cutting up the floor.''
   ``There is no visible settlement on the tank pad,'' said Ralph
Zimmerman, whose company, Ralph Zimmerman Excavating Inc. of nearby
Clairton, laid the foundation.
   ``When the tank collapsed it ripped the bottom too, and where it
ripped quite a bit of stone was washed out,'' he said.
   Zimmerman said state and federal investigators questioned him
about the work his company performed.
   Bid specifications required a base of compacted clay 3 to 4 feet
thick, topped by a foot of crushed limestone.
   Ashland spokeswoman Margaret Thomson said company officials
would not speculate on whether the foundation played any role in
the collapse.
   Others have speculated that the collapse might be traced to
metal fatigue in the 45-year-old steel used for the tank, freezing
temperatures the day of the accident or problems with vents in the
tank.
</TEXT>
