<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IrishAliens     03-03 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish Aliens,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Indicted For Illegally Bringing Irish Nationals Into US To
Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a nursing home has been indicted on
charges he induced 11 Irish nationals to illegally enter the United
States and work for him without permits, federal officials said
today.
   A federal indictment handed up Wednesday alleges that Peter H.
Starr persuaded the 11 nurses' aides and orderlies to quit their
jobs and move to the United States even though he was told that it
was unlikely they would be granted work permits.
   Starr, 35, of Scituate, owner of the Queene Anne Nursing Home in
Hingham, allegedly recruited the workers through advertisements in
a Dublin newspaper. After receiving 75 responses, he traveled to
Dublin to interview the applicants before offering jobs to 11 of
them, the indictment alleged.
   In May 1977, he applied for temporary permits allowing the 11 to
enter the United States and work.
   Starr was informed by the state Division of Employment Security,
which processes the applications for the federal Labor Department,
that it was unlikely the requests would be granted. But then Starr
allegedly told the workers to obtain tourist visas and falsely
state on their applications that they never had requested
permission to work in the United States.
   The Irish nationals are cooperating with investigators and
likely would be witnesses if Starr is brought to trial, U.S.
Attorney Frank McNamara Jr. said.
   Charles T. Cobb, district director of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said the 11 men and women have been granted
permission to remain in the United States until August and could
request resident status. They range in age from the low 20s to 38,
said Cobb, who refused to release their names.
   Starr faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine if
convicted.
 
</TEXT>
