<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Productivity     03-03 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Productivity,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Productivity Improvement Halved in 1987</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improvements in the nation's efficiency in
churning out goods and services slowed by almost half last year
despite revised figures showing higher output in the the fourth
quarter, the government said Thursday.
   The Labor Department said productivity among non-farm businesses
responsible for three-fourths of the nation's economic activity
rose at an annual rate of 0.3 percent in the fourth quarter in
contrast to a deterioration of 0.2 percent reported in preliminary
figures last month.
   The revisions raised the productivity improvement for the entire
year from 0.8 percent to 0.9 percent, slightly more than half the
1.6 percent gain of 1986, despite the lowest hourly labor cost
increases in more than four decades.
   The efficiency improvements for the year were the smallest since
1982, when an economic recession depressed output so much that
productivity actually declined 0.6 percent from 1981.
   ``Anything less than 1 percent is a disappointing number,'' said
Roger Brinner, an economist for Data Resources Inc. of Lexington,
Mass. ``It gives you very little room to buffer pay increases and
not much leeway to improve the standard of living.''
   The revised figures showed output of goods and services by
non-farm businesses _ which account for about three-fourths of the
nation's economic production _ rising by an annual rate of 5.6
percent in the fourth quarter.
   That is the greatest increase in nearly two years and compares
with a rise of 5.1 percent in the preliminary figures before the
gross national product was revised upward last week by the Commerce
Department.
   But in achieving that higher output, businesses increased the
total hours worked by their employees by 5.3 percent.
   Brinner said that reflects an increase of 3 million in the
number of Americans with jobs last year and ``gives you an
indication that we may have an employment glut as well as an output
glut'' as seen in the high level of unsold inventories.
   Still, the higher output helped reduce the annualized increase
in labor costs associated with each unit of goods or services in
the fourth quarter from 3.7 percent in the preiminary figures to
3.1 percent in the final ones, the Labor Department said.
   Despite figures showing that hourly wages rose an average 2.8
percent for all of last year, workers still lost 0.8 percent of
their income for each hour they worked after taking inflation into
account, according to the revised statistics.
   Manufacturing workers fared even worse. Their average wage
increases of 1.3 percent dropped their purchasing power after
inflation by 2.2 percent for the year.
   Productivity in manufacturing improved 3.3 percent over the year
_ unchanged from the preliminary figures _ with output up 4.3
percent on only a 1 percent increase in the number of hours worked.
   That combination dropped the labor costs associated with each
product coming out of the nation's factories by an average 1.9
percent in 1987, the report said.
   ``Frankly, we don't foresee much improvement in productivity
this year,'' said Donald Straszheim, chief economist for Merrill
Lynch. ``Productivity improvements require rapid growth and we
haven't been experiencing much of that lately.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0194 </DOCNO>
