<HEAD>Sir Georg Solti Still Biggest Grammy Winner; Aretha Franklin Top
Woman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Grammys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aretha Franklin, long ago canonized as the queen
of soul music, has become the all-time biggest female Grammy winner
with 14 awards.
   Before Wednesday night's telecast of the 30th Annual Grammy
Awards show from Radio City Music Hall, Franklin fell behind opera
diva Leontyne Price and jazz great Ella Fitzgerald, who held 13 and
12 trophies respectively.
   Franklin soared ahead after picking up prizes for best female
rhythm and blues vocalist for her LP, ``Aretha,'' and with George
Michael for best rhythm and blues performance by a duo for their
single, ``I Knew You Were Waiting (For Me).''
   Still, she has a long way to go to overtake Grammy's all-time
top winner, Sir Georg Solti, conductor of the Chicago Symphony,
whose recording of Beethoven's 9th Symphony won a Grammy for best
orchestral recording and raised his lifetime total to 26.
   Vladimir Horowitz, the pianist who had 20 Grammys entering the
ceremonies, won two more for best classical instrumental
performance and best classical album for ``Horowitz in Moscow.'' He
also received the President's Special Merit Award from the Academy.
   Horowitz is followed on the list by composer Henry Mancini, with
20 awards; producer-musician Quincy Jones with 19; pop-rhythm and
blues superstar Stevie Wonder with 17; composer John T. Williams
with 15; Franklin with 14; Price with 13; Fitzgerald tied in 9th
place with singer-songwriter Paul Simon with 12 Grammys each; and
conductor Pierre Boulez in 10th place with 11 trophies.
