<1ST_LINE>r a AM-10-YearEscapee     03-03 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-10-Year Escapee,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Prison Escapee Caught After 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALDERSON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prisoner who escaped 10 years ago from
the federal women's prison here apparently lived a crime-free life
in Arizona using an acquaintance's identification cards, federal
officials said.
   Mary Hughey Cantrell, who was 30 when she failed to return from
a 1977 Christmas furlough, pleaded guilty Wednesday to a charge of
escape from the Alderson Federal Correctional Institution.
   She will be held at the prison pending her April 22 sentencing,
federal officials said Thursday. The charge carries a maximum
five-year sentence and a $5,000 fine.
   Federal public defender Ira Kirkendoll said Cantrell went to
Arizona shortly after her escape and worked for several years as a
maid in private homes and resorts.
   Cantrell was arrested Jan. 5 in Phoenix, Ariz., after the
Internal Revenue Service spotted a discrepancy in income tax
returns for a Harriet Walker, Cantrell's acquaintance, who had
never worked in Arizona.
   Officials said they didn't know how Cantrell gained possession
of Walker's identification or where Walker lived.
   ``It's pretty unusual, the length of time,'' Kirkendoll said
after U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Hallanan accepted Cantrell's
plea. ``Apparently she has reformed to some degree.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Kirk Brandfass said the woman's decade
of crime-free living, aside from maintaining a false identity,
should be considered at sentencing.
   ``My heavens, that ought to count for something,'' the
prosecutor said outside Hallanan's court in Beckley.
   U.S. marshals wouldn't allow an interview with Cantrell, who was
sentenced to three years after a 1975 conviction for passing
counterfeit money. Cantrell, who still has about 470 days to serve
on her original sentence, was paroled in May 1976 but was returned
to the prison in early 1977 after a parole violation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
