<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ArcticSkiers     03-03 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arctic Skiers,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skiers On Top of the World as They Start Polar Expedition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE ARCTIC, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Canadian and nine Soviet
skiers set off Thursday under a hazy, primrose-colored Arctic
sunset to cross the North Pole and make a statement about East-West
cooperation.
   The 13 men face not only a 1,073-mile trek, but also must eat
and sleep in the same tent for 100 days.
   The journey got off to a late and rocky start from the snowy
fields of ice floes that link this northernmost tip of the
archipelago known as Severnaya Zemlya _ which means ``Northern
Land'' _ with the polar ice cap.
   Their faith was tested on the eve of thier departure when
expedition leader Dmitri Shparo proposed expanding the Soviet team
to nine members.
   ``It was an 11th-hour decision,'' said Canadian team leader
Richard Weber, revealing some of the uncertainty his countrymen
felt in allowing a further shifting of numbers in favor of the
Soviets. ``But when we sat down, we couldn't come up with any good
reasons why not.''
   Weber and Shparo met with Western and Soviet reporters at a
remote encampment on Sredny Island, 93 miles south of this
departure point.
   Shparo termed the Canadian concession ``magnanimous.''
   Weber said Shparo informed him Wednesday that he didn't want to
cut from the team any of the Soviets who had been in training.
   By morning, which arrives late on the Severnaya Zemlya, spirits
were high and the explorers lumbered through crowded barracks
weighing packs and redistributing gear.
   An Mi-6 helicopter shuttled the skiers and a small group of
journalists to the starting point, a windswept jumble of ice floes
frozen into a single white expanse that stretches 1,240 miles to
the Canadian Arctic.
   The Rev. Laurie Dexter of Fort Smith, Northwest Territories, an
Anglican minister, stood on a snowy ridge overlooking the solid
field that is the Arctic Ocean and called on ``the faith we have in
each other'' to take his fellow skiers safely across the pole and
into a new age of understanding.
   The men, bundled in red suits trimmed with dog fur and sponsors'
logos, sped off at 2:30 p.m. as the sun hung just over the horizon.
   The expedition will continue to Canada's Cape Columbia, with an
arrival scheduled for early June.
   The route has been covered in two parts by members of separate
teams, but this is the first attempt at a transcontinental crossing
of the pole.
   The joint expedition was planned for 1980, but the Canadians
abandoned the attempt when Soviet troops drove into Afghanistan in
December 1979.
   Shparo, 46, led the first Soviet polar ski trek in 1979, and
Weber, 28, of Old Chesea, Ontario, covered the Cape Columbia-North
Pole segment in 1986.
   ``The most interesting part for me will be the social factor of
being in a very small tent with a large number of people for a very
long time,'' Weber told reporters who visited the ski team's
headquarters in Dickson, the Soviet Arctic Circle settlement that
is the northernmost city in the world.
   Dexter said the tent measures about 14.8 feet square.
   ``There are inevitably frayed nerves and tensions, but all of us
are experienced enough and mature enough to let those things pass
and get on with the expedition,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1620EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     03-03 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Key Points Agreed Upon; Issue of Future Kabul Government Clouds
Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan and Afghanistan agreed Thursday on a
nine-month timetable for the withdrawal of Red Army troops from
Afghanistan and said half the Soviet soldiers should be out of the
country in the first 90 days.
   The two points had long hindered progress toward a settlement
aimed at ending nine years of fighting in Afghanistan, where an
estimated 115,000 Soviet troops are backing the government against
Moslem guerrillas.
   But a U.N. report released Thursday warned that success at the
Geneva talks could leave another primary problem unresolved: the
return of more than 5 million Afghan refugees who have fled to
neighboring Pakistan and Iran.
   The report said the refugees are unlikely to return unless the
Afghan government of President Najib is replaced by one that
includes opposition and refugee representation.
   That didn't dampen the optimism of Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul
Wakil, who told reporters, ``Nothing important stands in the way of
concluding a settlement. From our side, things could be regarded as
finalized.''
   He said U.N. officials had established that ``all refugees want
to return.''
   Agreement on the withdrawal timetable had been widely expected.
   When the U.N.-mediated talks began nearly six years ago, Moscow
offered a four-year withdrawal span and gradually lowered this.
   Last month, Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev said the estimated
115,000 Red Army troops could be out of Afghanistan within 10
months starting in mid-May if a Geneva settlment was signed by the
middle of this month.
   Wakil said he was confident that remaining ``other issues,''
which he did not specify, also would be resolved, provided
``Pakistan could abide by the tacit and formal agreement not to
raise anything new.''
   Pakistan represents the insurgents in the talks.
   Pakistan has said that a successful settlement must be
accompanied by formation of a broad-based transitional government
to replace the Afghan government.
   Pakistan's chief delegate, acting Foreign Minister Zain Noorani,
reaffirmed that position to reporters after meeting with mediator
Diego Cordovez, who shuttled between the two sides for 2{ hours
Thursday.
   ``We are firmly convinced that a settlement without creating
circumstances of peace and stability in Afghanistan will not
persuade 5 million Afghan refugees to return,'' Noorani said. He
did not name any specific time limit as to when that government
should be in office.
   Noorani planned to return to Islamabad for a weekend of
consultations between the goverment and political leaders. He said
Pakistan would then decide whether it was prepared to sign a
settlement with the Najib government, which Pakistan does not
recognize.
   Wakil reiterated that Najib's policy of national reconciliation
envisaged a ``coalition government'' open to all political forces,
including the Pakistan-based resistance movements.
   The resistance movements, claiming to represent about 200,000
guerrillas, have rejected any power-sharing with Najib. They have
presented a plan of their own for an Islamic government.
   Wakil also took issue with the U.N. report, prepared for the
43-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission. It voiced reservations
about Kabul's plans for a ``National Front'' of the various parties
that would have a leading role in charting policies. It noted that
such umbrella bodies exist in Soviet bloc countries.
   Wakil said the National Front envisaged by Kabul could not be
compared with those existing in Czechoslovakia and East Germany.
These, he said, came into being long ago and ``under completely
different circumstances.''
</TEXT>
