<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RemakingCities     03-03 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Remaking Cities,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mill Towns Urged To Take Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communities that once relied on a single
industry for jobs and looked to corporate mangers for leadership
must diversify their economies and take charge of their destinies,
urban planners said Thursday at an international symposium.
   ``Before, like it or not, companies took care of life. You may
not have liked everyting they did. But they were there. It was
secure,'' said John Clarke, a Trenton, N.J., architect who headed a
team that studied depressed mill towns in this once mighty
steelmaking region.
   ``But when that goes away, suddenly you turn around and say,
`Gee, the leadership used to be the company.' Now the leadership
has to be you,'' Clarke said at the International Remaking Cities
Conference.
   It's a painful transition experienced by older industrial
centers worldwide, the experts said.
   ``The trend is inescapable in that we're moving from an
industrial, manufacturing economy into a service economy,'' said
James Franklin, an architect and land planner with American
Institute of Architects.
   ``There are many cities that already face the same problem and
will continue to face it for a period of time,'' he said.
   The four-day conference is exploring ways to revitalize aging
industrial cities in the United States and Great Britain.
   Britain's Prince Charles, honorary chairman of the meeting, will
get a first-hand look Friday at the dispair and disrepair of the
mill towns lining the Monongahela River south of Pittsburgh.
   An outspoken advocate of inner-city rehabilitation, the prince
plans to visit a new jobs center for the region's blue-collar
unemployed and a high school computer training classroom.
   On Saturday he will address the approximately 350 people
attending the conference, sponsored by the American Institute of
Architects and Royal Institute of British Architects.
   In his speech, the 39-year-old heir to the British throne is
expected to comment on the recommendations made by conference
delegates for revitalizing cities.
   ``The mayors are asking us ... do they have a right to determine
land use and a right to determine the future development of the
community. These communities have got to learn that'' their leaders
have not only the right but the obligation to influence the use of
former mill sites, Clarke said.
   ``They've been so much under the mantle of the steel industry
that their sense of the company town was so great that there was
very little sense that they could in fact control what they had to
do with an economy,'' said Charles Zucker, community planning
consultant with the American Institute of Architects in Washington,
D.C., and a member of Clarke's planning team.
   In its 120-page report, presented Monday after a four-day study
of area communities, the 17-member team recommended ``the greening
of American industry'' with parks, gardens, marinas and shops to
replace darkened hulks dominating the riverbank.
   Although drawing praise from many, the report was criticized by
those waiting and praying for the resurrection of the steel
industry.
   The general feeling is ``you're getting a garden. You're getting
flowers. You're getting no jobs,'' said Tony McGann, a community
planner from Liverpool, England, and another team member.
   ``In our area, we didn't want to see shipping die. We didn't
want to see the shipping factories die. But they all died. They
never came back,'' he said. ``So people who are waiting for steel
to come back, they live in a cuckoo land.''
   Public participation is a key to success in urban planning, the
conference participants said.
   ``We've seen what happens when nothing happens'' and when
outsiders' views are thrust upon communities, said Raymond
Rhinehart, a spokesman for the American Institute of Architects.
   No one, least of all urban planners, want regions to forget
their industrial heritage. That's why the planning team suggested
that several ironmaking furnaces near Pittsburgh become museums.
   But there's another motive.
   Displays of equipment used in the ``heroic and hard old days,''
make it clearer that ``you need to rethink you goals and move on
with your life,'' Franklin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
