<HEAD>Conference Ends With Call for Local Action Against Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A White House conference on fighting drugs
ended Thursday with the chairwoman exhorting representatives to
return to their communities to fight the scourge of drugs.
   Lois Haight Herrington called for a ``final assault'' on drugs
in the last year of the Reagan administration.
   Those interested in eliminating drugs cannot ``give themselves
the luxury'' of relaxing after the three-day Conference for a
Drug-Free America because ``dealers, users and smugglers'' are
``waiting to see us let down, become distracted,'' Ms. Harrington
said.
   Members of the conference will present recommendations to
President Reagan, she said.
   The conference turned into a critique of the administration's
record on what is being done. Several speakers, including a member
of Reagan's Cabinet, said that not enough is being done to
eliminate drugs.
   ``We need to get away from a policy of containment,'' said Rep.
Clay Shaw, R-Fla. ``We want you to come up with a plan for victory.
Let's fight it like we fought World War II, not like Vietnam. Let's
fight to win.''
