<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SenateArrests     03-03 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate Arrests,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senators Want New Rules on Member Arrests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Republican senators on Thursday
demanded that Senate rules be changed to make it more difficult to
arrest absent senators, the fate of Sen. Bob Packwood last week
when he missed a quorum call.
   Their ``sense of the Senate'' resolution proposed a rule change
that would prohibit the seizure of an absent senator between 11
p.m. and 8 a.m. ``unless the pending business is of a compelling
nature.''
   The Senate sergeant-at-arms arrested Packwood, R-Ore., in his
office at about 1:30 a.m. last Wednesday when he and most other
Republicans fled the chamber to prevent the Senate from
establishing a quorum. A quorum of 51 senators was needed to keep
the Senate in session, and the Republicans were trying to end an
all-night debate on a campaign spending bill.
   Packwood literally was carried into the Senate chamber by U.S.
Capitol Police detectives accompanied by Sergeant-at-Arms Henry
Giugni. Giugni had been ordered to bring senators to the floor by a
45-3 vote of senators who were present.
   Packwood's unique arrival gave the Democrats a quorum and the
Senate remained in session all night.
   Packwood seemed to take his arrest in good humor and later
appeared at a news conference with Giugni, laughing about the
incident.
   Other Republicans were not amused. Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.,
complained Thursday that the incident meant senators might have to
remain in hiding in their offices. ``Senators should not have to
make a decision whether to leave the light on in your office at
night,'' he said.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., who had made the
original motion that absent senators be arrested, said Thursday:
``We bored the American people today with almost four hours of talk
about the `tough life' of senators.'' He called the discussion ``a
tale of woe'' and suggested ``there are several million Americans
who would be glad to trade places with us.''
   Byrd criticized the resolution, citing the provision that would
limit late-night arrest warrants other than for ``compelling''
reasons. ``Who's to determine that?'' Byrd said. ``The Senate
determines that and it determined that the other evening.''
   The resolution, which was referred to the Rules Committee, also
proposed that any arrest warrant include ``a written statement
establishing the reasons for arrest.''
   Sponsors were Sens. Alan Simpson of Wyoming, John Chafee of
Rhode Island, William Armstrong of Colorado, Rudy Boschwitz of
Minnesota, Thad Cochran of Mississippi, Arlen Specter and John
Heinz of Pennsylvania, Dan Quayle of Indiana, Mitch McConnell of
Kentucky, Kit Bond of Missouri, Dan Evans of Washington, Robert
Kasten of Wisconsin, Alfonse D'Amato of New York, Gordon Humphrey
of New Hampshire, Jake Garn of Utah and Wallop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0206 </DOCNO>
