<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     03-03 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Says Tamils Kill 16 in Village</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels dressed as soldiers
raided a village and killed 16 people, most of them women or
children, a military official said Thursday.
   He said the Tamils attacked with automatic weapons Wednesday at
Morawewa village, 27 miles west of Trincomalee port on the island
nation's eastern coast.
   On Thursday, three rebels were reported killed in a gun battle
with police at a roadblock in the southeast. Police Chief S.
Wijesinghe of the Ampara district said there were no police
casualties.
   The officer reporting the Morawewa raid said nine children, four
women and three men were killed and three people wounded.
   All the dead were of the Sinhalese ethnic majority except for
one Tamil, he said, speaking on condition of anonymity in
accordance with police regulations. He blamed the attack on members
of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest rebel group.
   Members of the Tigers militia led a four-year ethnic war for a
separate Tamil homeland. They were blamed for the killings of more
than 200 Sinhalese in October last year soon after the Tigers
renounced a peace accord designed to end the war.
   More than 8,000 people have been killed in the ethnic conflict,
which began in 1983.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of the country's 16 million people and
most are Hindus. They claim discrimination by the majority
Sinhalese, who are predominantly Buddhist and control the
government and army.
</TEXT>
