<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpaceSpending     03-03 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Spending,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Committee Members Decry Lack of Support in Congress, White
House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA administrator James C. Fletcher went to
Capitol Hill Thursday to argue for an $11.5 billion space budget
but listened instead as space committee members complained that
their recommendations were being ignored by the committee that
holds the purse strings.
   ``I'm not so certain that anything we say in these hearings is
going to make much difference,'' said Rep. Robert Walker of
Pennsylvania, the ranking Republican member of the House Science &
Technology subcommittee on space science and applications.
   ``There is an attitude in the budget committee at the present
time that NASA will get no more money this year than they got last
year,'' he said.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration, trying to
recover from the January 1986 Challenger shuttle accident and
gearing up for a start on a manned space station, will spend an
estimated $8.9 billion this year, far below what the agency had
requested.
   NASA had asked $767 million to begin the space station and but
received just $425 million. President Reagan's budget for 1989
would give the agency $11.5 billion, but lawmakers at Thursday's
hearing said no amount approaching that would be approved by the
House Appropriations Committee, which sends legislation for
spending to the full House.
   Fletcher told the subcommittee that the budget now being
considered could make or break the nation's space program.
   ``It is not an overstatement to say that the future of the U.S.
civil space program rides at risk in this budget,'' he said.
   No one on the committee argued with him. But Walker and others
suggested that NASA had to do a better job in selling itself to the
rest of Congress.
   ``It seems to me they (NASA) have to bring people of
credibility, like astronauts, to go in and buttonhole members of
Congress and explain the facts of life,'' he said. ``It seems to me
that NASA is going to have to begin to get awfully aggressive in
how the NASA budget is presented.''
   Walker said the American people are willing to support a
rational space program but ``there is no pressure being felt on
Capitol Hill at the present time, none whatsoever.''
   Rep. George Brown, D-Calif., a strong space program booster,
talked of ``erratic funding'' for the space program.
   ``That is not the way to develop a strong, world-class
program,'' he said. ``While these cuts have been happening, the
military program doubled or tripled.''
   Rep. Bill Nelson of Florida, the subcommittee chairman, said
``there is only one person who can really lead the nation's space
program and that is the duly elected leader of this nation. The
nation's space pgoram is going to depend on the degree of
commitment coming from President Reagan in this next year.''
   Fletcher protested that Reagan is committed to the budget, that
``it is not a half-hearted budget.''
   To that, Nelson responded: ``I'm talking about real deeds as
well as words. I'm talking about threats of vetoes that are real
threats; I'm talking about sitting down at the table and working
with the congressional leadership.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
