<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Contras-Ortega     03-03 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras-Ortega,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Accept Face-to-Face Meeting in Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders agreed Thursday to meet their
Sandinista foes inside Nicaragua, but insisted on the participation
of Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, who has drawn objections from
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega.
   ``We are accepting a face-to-face meeting in Nicaraguan
territory,'' director Alfredo Cesar said in a communique after a
daylong meeting of the directorate.
   The Contras Thursday appointed Adolfo Calero, considered to be
one of the more hardline directors, to head their delegation.
   Ortega has proposed that the talks take place in southern
Nicaragua with his brother, Defense Minister Humberto Ortega,
heading the Sandinista delegation.
   The Contras also said that Obando y Bravo, who was dismissed by
Ortega as a mediator after two previous negotiating sessions, must
be present as a ``witness and guarantor.''
   ``Cardinal Obando y Bravo represents the only moral authority in
Nicaragua that can guarantee compliance'' with the peace agreement
reached last year by the five Central American presidents, Cesar
said.
   Ortega had suggested that the meeting be held in the town of
Sapoa near Nicaragua's Costa Rican border on March 10-12, but Cesar
said the time and place should be worked out later.
   He said guarantees of the Contra delegation's safe passage must
also established before the meeting.
   The communique signed by the five directors of the Nicaraguan
Resistance, as the Contra rebels are formally called, lambasted
Ortega for dismissing Obando y Bravo as a mediator.
   It called the action ``unilateral and dictatorial,'' and praised
the cardinal of Managua for his help in getting the peace talks
going.
   The Contras had been the first to propose talks inside
Nicaragua, which the Sandinistas inititally rejected. Now that the
Sandinistas have reversed their position, they must demonstrate
their sincerity, said Cesar.
   ``It would be very difficult for them to put this on the table
as a bluff,'' he said. ``Public opinion is going to be judging all
these actions.''
   The communique said the talks in Nicaragua should be based on
the agreement reached before the breakup of talks in Guatemala last
month.
   That includes a 30-day truce while the Contra troops enter
protected enclaves, a total amnesty, freedom of expression and a
national dialogue, said Cesar.
</TEXT>
