<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NYCChancellor     03-03 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYC Chancellor,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City's New Schools Chancellor Says He'll Cut Into Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declaring that New York City schools are ``on
trial,'' a new chancellor was sworn in Thursday to lead the
939,000-pupil education system and vowed to cut deeply into the
central bureaucracy to gain needed reform.
   ``Business as usual must come to an end, and it must do so
today,'' said Richard R. Green, who ended a 30-year career in the
Minneapolis schools to take on the New York City post.
   Frequently departing from the text of his 20-minute inaugural
address, Green laid out a reform agenda for the next year which
included deep cuts in the central bureaucracy.
   ``By July 1, I will have a management team in place that I can
rely on. And there will be some transfers out of 110 Livingston,''
he said, referring to the downtown Brooklyn headquarters of the
city Board of Education.
   He also said he was determined to remove the time clocks that
teachers are now required to punch. And he said he would work to
find a way to make school facilities more readily available to
parents' groups.
   Green made no mention of his controversial suggestion of an
11-month school year which he made off-the-cuff Wednesday while
touring several schools.
   Among those greeting Green on the podium were Mayor Edward I.
Koch, Gov. Mario M. Cuomo, and Board of Education President Robert
F. Wagner Jr.
   The otherwise serious ceremony also included laughter.
   When Wagner began to administer the oath of office to Green and
said, ``I, state your name,'' Green joked: ``I, state your name.''
   Green had surprised many at an earlier press conference by
high-handedly signaling Koch to sit down. Koch turned the tables on
Green at his inaugural when, at the beginning of mayor's
introductory remarks, he pointed with mock anger at Green and said:
``Sit down, chancellor!''
   Koch continued: ``You are the head of this new army. We are
soldiers in your army. You tell us how to help you and those that
don't, you give me their names.''
   During his remarks, Green said that Koch had told him on a visit
to City Hall that ```you can have anything you want except more
money.' That is a fair point but I consider that a negotiable
issue.''
   Koch shrugged and shook his head.
</TEXT>
