<HEAD>State Health Department to Investigate Hospital Brawley Went To</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 3rd graf may be considered objectionable.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Health Department will investigate
the hospital where a black teen-ager was taken after she said she
had been sexually assaulted by a group of white men, a department
spokesman said Thursday.
   The department will ask for the medical records of St. Francis
Hospital in Poughkeepsie, which treated Tawana Brawley for nearly
eight hours on Nov. 28 following the attack, spokesman Peter Slocum
said.
   Miss Brawley, 16, of Wappingers Falls, was found wrapped in a
garbage bag along a road. She was smeared with excrement and
``KKK'' and ``nigger'' were scrawled on her body. She says she was
kidnapped for four days and sexually abused by six men.
   Her family has complained about her treatment at St. Francis,
where she was taken by ambulance on the day she was found.
   ``We are obviously interested in it simply because of the media
reports,'' Slocum said.
   The health department could impose a fine if it finds care was
improper, ``but our primary concern, rather than any kind of
punishment, is to make clear the standards of care are improved,''
Slocum said.
   He was unsure how long the investigation would take.
   A source described as close to the Brawley family but not
identified told the Poughkeepsie Journal that the family was upset
because Miss Brawley was released from the hospital unable to walk
and lapsing in and out of consciousness.
   Miss Brawley went to the emergency room of the Westchester
Medical Center in Valhalla twice on Dec. 2. She was admitted after
her second visit, hospital spokeswoman Nancy McPartlin said.
   She was discharged Dec. 4, McPartlin said. She said the hospital
would provide no details about Miss Brawley's treatment.
   A spokesman for St. Francis Hospital denied the hospital did
anything wrong when treating Miss Brawley.
   Miss Brawley was treated for a cut on the scalp and examined for
possible hypothermia, spokesman Frank Hemrick said. She was tested
to determine if she was raped, and the records were sent to the FBI.
   The test found Miss Brawley was not raped, according to several
published reports. But a spokesman for the teen-ager, the Rev. Al
Sharpton, claims Miss Brawley was raped and the tests were botched.
</TEXT>
