<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Senate Approves Liquor Measure For Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to allow a state park to serve liquor to
visiting Democrats during their national convention in July
survived some Republican jabs in the Georgia Senate Thursday.
   The Democratic-controlled Senate passed it, 40-13, and returned
it to the House for consideration of a technical amendment.
   The bill was backed by Gov. Joe Frank Harris, a Democrat and a
teetotaler who last year vetoed a bill to expand the areas of Stone
Mountain Park where liquor can be sold to the public.
   Sen. Roy Barnes, a Democrat who is Harris' Senate floor leader,
said the bill to allow the park's governing authority to sell
liquor to private gatherings would aid some large functions planned
at the park near Atlanta ``in July.''
   When Republican Sen. Tom Phillips tried to force another
Democratic speaker to name that event, Barnes drew laughter by
asking: ``Isn't it true that the Republicans chose as their meeting
site Bourbon Street in New Orleans?''
   Barnes argued the bill simply allowed the state to sell the
liquor rather than forcing conventions to bring in their own.
   But Democratic Sen. Max Brannon, an opponent of liquor sales,
said he was ``very shocked this is an administration bill'' and
added: ``I know a liquor bill when I see a liquor bill.''
   Barnes drew laughter when he said: ``If I had my perfect world
to do, there'd be a lot of things different in this world: we
wouldn't have liquor, wouldn't have sin, wouldn't have
Republicans.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Robertson Comes Up Short In South Dakota</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson apparently will not seek a
recount in South Dakota's Republican presidential primary even
though he fell only a few hundred votes short of winning any
delegates, Gordon Howie, Robertson's state campaign director, said
Thursday.
   In official results, released Thursday by the state Board of
Canvassers, Robertson came up 371 votes short of receiving the 20
percent of the GOP vote he needed in order to receive any national
convention delegates from the state.
   ``I think at this point it's unlikely'' a recount will be
sought, Howie said. ``I think we're going to be satisfied having
beaten (Vice President) George Bush,'' he added.
   Officially, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas won the primary with 55.2
percent of the vote, Robertson was second with 19.6 percent, and
Bush third at 18.6 percent. Dole thus will get all 18 of South
Dakota's delegates to the GOP national convention.
   Howie said Robertson's national campaign appears unlikely to
file any complaint that could lead to a recount. ``Obviously, we'd
like to have delegates ... but indications are we're not going to
challenge the vote,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Robertson's Pastor Says Candidate's Religious Past Fair For</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Questioning
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson should not hide from his
religious past while seeking the Republican presidential
nomination, the Rev. Donald J. Dunlap, Robertson's pastor, said in
an interview published Thursday.
   Robertson's ``apocalyptic theology'' concerning the biblical
prophecy of the world's end could help mold his foreign policy as
president, Dunlap told the Roanoke Times & World-News.
   Robertson has tried to avoid campaign questions about his
religious past and statements he made in writings and television
broadcasts. ``Those statements became a matter of the public
record,'' said Dunlap, pastor of Freemason Street Baptist Church in
