   ``They were a mixture of his religious beliefs as they impacted
upon his political beliefs,'' he added.
   He said that ``where he made public policy statements derivative
of his religious beliefs, I think the media and his opponents have
every right to question him on that as much as they have a right to
question (Vice President) George Bush on his involvement in the
Iran-Contra affair, as much as they have a right to question
(Kansas Sen.) Robert Dole about votes he cast in Congress.''
