<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Children'sIssues     03-03 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Issues,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTA Urges Candidates To Focus On Children's Needs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PTA on Thursday urged presidential
candidates to ``pay more than lip service'' to the educational,
after-school and health needs of the nation's children.
   A PTA memo to all 10 candidates, released in time to catch their
attention before the Super Tuesday primaries in 16 states, reflects
a more activist stance on children's issues by the 6.1
million-member association, said Arnold Fege, the PTA's director of
governmental relations.
   Until now, Fege said, the group has focused on individual issues
and never developed a complete agenda.
   ``We see a lot of the candidates kissing kids at rallies, but we
don't hear much on what the candidates intend to do about
children's issues,'' Fege said. ``We want to force the candidates
to take a position on these issues.''
   The PTA's message to the candidates, formally called ``A
Memorandum to the 41st President of the United States: A National
Children's Agenda `Because Children Are the Future,''' asks the
next president to convene a ``children's summit'' of parents,
teachers, government officials and social service workers
immediately after Inauguration Day. The group's task would be to
``recommend a coordinated, comprehensive and workable national
youth and family policy.''
   The four-page memo also recommends:
   _Increased spending on the Chapter 1 and Head Start programs for
disadvantaged children.
   _That the federal government work with the states to develop a
plan to equalize spending on education among the states.
   _That public schools be encouraged to play a bigger role in
providing early childhood, preschool and before- and after-school
care.
   _That the federal government provide sufficient money for
ensuring that all children be immunized against polio, diphtheria,
measles, tetanus, whooping cough and mumps.
   _That the federal government assist states and local education
agencies in providing preventive education programs on drug abuse,
teen suicide, teen pregnancy and AIDS.
   _That the federal government commit whatever resources are
necessary for adequate shelters, health services and education for
homeless families and youths.
   Fege acknowledged that the PTA's recommendations are costly and
he suggested that the money come from additional taxes, rearranging
federal spending priorities or continuing the budget deficit.
   ``Our organization has become indignant that the presidential
candidates are not putting meaty children's issues on the agenda,''
Fege said. ``We want them to pay more than lip service.''
</TEXT>
