<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Gingrich-Wright     03-03 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gingrich-Wright,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gingrich Seeking Support For Ethics Complaint Against House
Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Newt Gingrich said Thursday he has
decided to delay seeking an ethics investigation of House Speaker
Jim Wright to give other activist Republicans time to consider
whether to join him in the action.
   Gingrich, R-Ga., said his announcement last month that he
planned to ask the House ethics committee to initiate an
investigation of Wright prompted several other House Republicans to
inquire about joining his complaint.
   ``We've been meeting with people, answering their concerns and
trying to give them an opportunity to decide whether they want to
co-file with us,'' Gingrich said.
   Under House rules, any member can ask the ethics panel to
investigate another member. The panel, composed of six Democrats
and six Republicans, can reject such a request only by a majority
vote.
   Gingrich declined to identify the other Republicans who had
expressed an interest in joining the complaint against Wright. He
said he has briefed House Republican Leader Robert Michel of
Illinois, but does not expect Michel to participate.
   ``There is a question of whether it would be appropriate for a
leader who has to work with the speaker on a daily basis to be
involved in this type of issue,'' Gingrich said.
   He has called for an investigation of allegations of unethical
conduct by Wright, D-Texas, that have been raised in news reports
over the past 10 years.
   The reports include allegations that Wright has failed since
1980 to file required financial disclosures reports from a company
in which he is a partner and that he received 55 percent royalties
on a book published by a friend whose printing company worked for
Wright's campaign committees.
   Gingrich said Thursday he still intends to seek an investigation
of Wright before the end of the month, even if no other congressmen
join with him.
</TEXT>
