<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Seaton     03-03 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Seaton,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former GM Personnel Vice President Dies At Age 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis G. Seaton, former chief labor negotiator at
General Motors Corp., died Thursday after a brief illness. He was
81.
   Seaton, who had homes in Sarasota, Fla., and Orchard Lake,
retired in 1970 after more than 42 years with the world's largest
automaker. He died in Sarasota.
   He joined GM as a graphic artist in 1928, transferring to the
industrial relationship department four years later.
   In 1946, he was named director of labor relations, with
responsibility for day-to-day relations with the United Auto
Workers and national contract negotiations until his retirement. He
became a vice president in 1957.
   ``Lou Seaton was a pioneer in the fields of labor relations and
personnel policy in General Motors and the domestic automobile
industry,'' said GM Chairman Roger Smith.
   Survivors include his wife, Kathleen; a daughter; son; three
brothers; 10 grandchildren and three great-grandchildren. A funeral
was scheduled for Monday in Orchard Lake.
