<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PresidentialProtection     03-03 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Protection,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidents Have More Privacy With Less Security, Former Agent Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Secret Service agent said Thursday
that former Presidents Ford and Carter will find far more privacy
when no they no longer have federal agents protecting them.
   Michael Endicott, a Secret Service agent for 20 years who now
provides private security for former President Nixon, told the
Senate Government Operations federal spending subcommittee there
should be a time limit on Secret Service protection of former
presidents and their families.
   ``I believe the government should provide funding to the former
president so that they can manage their own day-to-day security
needs,'' Endicott said. ``There is a need for a security or law
enforcement presence around a former president that naturally flows
from occupying the most important office in the country.''
   But Endicott, testifying on a bill that would reduce federal
protection for former first families, said Secret Service
protection often limits the recipient's freedom of movement. He
said he has never felt Nixon's safety has been threatened since he
began to handle his security, traveling to cities around the world
and attending sporting and other public events.
   ``At most of these events, we usually sit in the general public
seats, even though VIP boxes are usually available,'' he said.
``There is more privacy with fewer people. We are able to go to
more ballgames now than when he had Secret Service protection.''
   The big difference, he said, is that the Secret Service must
``protect against the potential threat, while I can protect from
the actual threat.'' Endicott said he, alone, travels with Nixon,
whereas the Secret Service must assign up to 24 agents to protect
former presidents.
   Endicott said most of the threats Nixon has received have come
from people unable to carry them out, such as inmates in mental
institutions.
   ``Former presidents Ford and Carter will find out what President
Nixon did,'' he said. ``There is a hell of a lot more privacy in
smaller numbers.''
   The legislation introduced by Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., would
eliminate Secret Service protection for former presidents and their
families after they have been out of the White House for five
years. It provides for emergency and extended protection after that
if it is deemed necessary by the Treasury Department.
   Chiles said Secret Service protection for Ford and Carter and
their families cost $8 million in 1986. Nixon gave up his federal
government protection, which then cost about $3 million a year, in
1985.
   The Chiles bill also calls for a $300,000 annual limit on staff
and office allowances, to be reduced over a nine-year period to
$200,000. Chiles told the hearing that programs for ex-presidents,
including an annual $99,500 annuity, Secret Service protection,
office allowance and staff, has gone from $380,140 in 1960 to about
$26 million in the fiscal year that ended last Sept. 30.
   ``The American people want former presidents to live a dignified
retired life as an elder statesman, free from any real danger and
free from any need to commercialize _ to huckster _ the office of
the preisdency,'' he said. ``But the programs were left open-ended.
Things have gotten out of hand.''
   Each of the former presidents wrote letters to Chiles on his
legislation. Ford and Nixon agreed with its purpose on security
protection.
   Carter said the elimination of security ``would make it almost
impossible for us to live a normal private life at home free of
uninvited vistors, to attend major events if our attendance is
publicized, or to travel to many places in our country or abroad.''
   He said he can not afford private security. However, he said if
Secret Service experts can reduce the level and cost of his
protection, he would not object.
 
</TEXT>
