<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Hostage 1stLd-Writethru a0710 03-03 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostage, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0710,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Free West German Hostage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to CORRECT Friedhelm sted of Friedholm Ost</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-Iranian kidnappers freed West German
hostage Ralph Schray in west Beirut on Thursday after holding him
for five weeks, and he was turned over to the West German Embassy
in Damascus.
   The West German charge d'affaires, Klaus Auchenbach, refused to
make any comments to reporters as he shuttled between the embassy
and the Foreign Ministry, about a mile apart in the Syrian capital.
   He said it was ``not worthwhile'' for them to wait around,
indicating that Schray would not appear in public.
   This raised speculation the former captive may not be as well as
Bonn portrayed him to be after his ordeal. The Bonn Foreign
Ministry had said earlier that Schray, 30, was in ``good physical
condition.''
   Friedhelm Ost, the West German government's chief spokesman in
Bonn, said only that the Syrian government had handed Schray over
to embassy officials.
   Schray, a Lebanese-born industrial engineer, was freed before
dawn. A Syrian military source in the Lebanese capital said he was
driven the 55 miles to Damascus under heavy Syrian escort.
   On Wednesday, the Holy Warriors for Freedom claimed
responsibility for Schray's abduction and said he would be freed
within hours as a result of Syrian mediation.
   The official Syrian Arab News Agency said Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Sharaa contacted his German counterpart, Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, by telephone to report that Schray has been released and
was safe in the hands of Syrian troops in Lebanon.
   The agency said Genscher ``expressed his deep gratitude to
Syrian President Hafez Assad for all the efforts Syria has exerted
and reiterated Bonn's determination to consolidate the traditional
ties between the two nations.''
   A few hours after his arrival in Damascus, an embassy employee
said Schray was still inside the embassy. He spoke on condition of
anonymity and would not comment on Schray's physical condition.
   Schray's Lebanese wife, Rana Mounla, and his uncle George Abu
Nassar, were seen leaving Beirut in the early afternoon.
   Mrs. Schray, who is pregnant, said: ``I'm going to see him.''
   She said: ``I'm taking clothes for him.''
   She indicated the couple would return to Beirut, saying: ``When
we're back together in Beirut tomorrow we'll both talk to you.''
   Schray's kidnappers also claimed responsibility for kidnapping
two West Germans in January 1987 _ Rudolph Cordes and Alfred
Schmidt. Schmidt was released in September, but Cordes remains in
captivity.
   Schray's mother, Fahima Schray, said from Fort Myers, Fla., that
her son's captivity was ``the most terrible days of my life. It was
so difficult.''
   ``I couldn't sleep last night one minute. This morning,
everything has changed completely, as if I'm a new woman,'' she
said.
   There are 22 foreigners missing after being kidnapped in
Lebanon. They include nine Americans, four Frenchmen, three
Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian and two
unidentified men.
   The hostage held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was seized
March 16, 1985.
   Schray's release brought to seven the number of foreign hostages
that have been released by kidnappers since September: two
Frenchmen, two West Germans, a South Korean, a Norwegian and a
Swede.
   In their statement Wednesday, the Holy Warriors for Freedom said
Schray would be freed as ``goodwill gesture number two.'' They had
also called Schmidt's release a goodwill gesture.
   But they warned: ``We have an assortment of German targets on
our hit list and also have a hand stretched out for dialogue.''
   West German officials say the Germans have been kidnapped in an
effort to pressure Bonn to release two Lebanese Shiite brothers.
   One of the brothers, Abbas Hamadi, has since been put on trial
in Duesseldorf on charges of kidnapping Schmidt and Cordes to press
for the release of his brother, Mohammed Ali.
   Mohammed Ali is being held in Frankfurt on charges of
involvement in the 1985 hijacking of an American TWA jetliner to
Beirut and the murder of a U.S. Navy diver on board.
   The kidnappers warned that any pressure on them ``will only lead
to ... the liquidation of the Cordes case.''
   The group is believed to be led by Abdel-Hadi Hamadi, a third
Hamadi brother, who also is head of the security apparatus of
Hezbollah, or Party of God, a fundamentalist Iranian-backed faction
linked to the kidnapping of the 22 foreigners still missing in
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
