<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ParkFees     03-03 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Park Fees,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. Vento Challenges Interior Secretary on Park Service Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman accused
Secretary of Interior Donald P. Hodel of breaking faith in his
budget proposal to increase operational funds for the national
parks by only $3 million next year.
   Congress intended that some $52 million in park fees being
collected this year be added to the operations and maintenance
account in the National Park Service budget for next year, said
Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn.
   Vento, who is chairman of the parks subcommittee of the House
Interior Committee, told Hodel ``You're breaching faith'' at a
hearing of the full committee on the budget requests of the
Interior Department.
   Park operations and maintenance got $731 million for the current
fiscal year. For the year beginning Oct. 1, Hodel is seeking $734
million.
   Hodel referred Vento to a passage in the committee's report to
the House Budget Committee early last year recommending a ``stable
funding base'' of $675 million.
   But in the catch-all spending bill enacted in December for the
government as a whole, Congress increased the park operations and
maintenance account by about $15 million and then added $40 million
in fee revenue for specified projects.
   ``That $40 million (is added) to the baseline,'' making it $715
million, argued Rep. Larry Craig, R-Idaho.
   ``Our commitment was that we would not offset park fees against
the base operating level,'' Hodel told Craig. ``I think we've kept
faith. We're not being treated fairly.''
   When his turn came, Vento said, ``Are you going to sit there and
tell me there haven't been reductions in other park operations ...
to offset the fees?''
   Hodel replied, ``I am,'' and Vento rattled off a series of
reductions of $2.7 million, $3.2 million and $3.9 million. ``What
are they?'' he asked. He got no direct answer.
   The operations and maintenance request ``doesn't even provide
the 2 percent (pay) increase for employees. You're going backward,
not forward,'' Vento said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
