<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Purim     03-03 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Purim,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Carnival Takes On A Sad Note Because Of Arab Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israelis donned funny hats and costumes
Thursday to celebrate the Jewish holiday of Purim, but the
festivities were overshadowed by three months of Arab protests in
the occupied territories.
   ``We have some very serious news, but first we want to wish you
a happy Purim,'' an Israel army radio announcer said in a phrase
that symbolized the joy and tension of the day.
   The radio then reported that Israeli troops shot and injured at
least three Palestinian protesters and that a 16-year-old Jewish
youth was wounded when an Arab assailant stabbed him in the the
West Bank town of Hebron.
   The youth said he threw a canister of Purim foam at the
attacker, the national Itim news agency said. Pranksters spray the
harmless foam at passers-by on the holiday.
   The radio marked Purim with a prank, saying the Transport
Ministry decided to replace all male taxi drivers with women
because men are ``too arrogant, aggressive and ruin tourism.''
   Purim is a religious holiday honoring Esther, the Jewish queen
of Persia who saved the Jews from destruction at the hands of the
leader Haman 24 centuries ago.
   Jews celebrate the deliverance by reading the biblical Book of
Esther in synagogues. Whenever the reader mentions the name of the
hated Haman, the congregation shouts and shakes noisemakers.
   Jews also mark the holiday by drinking wine, sending gifts and
holding carnival parades. About 500,000 people gathered in Tel Aviv
Thursday to watch 1,500 people march in a Purim parade.
   Media pranks are considered an essential part of Purim, but the
jokes were overshadowed by the unrest in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, where 76 Palestinians have died at the hands of
Israelis since Dec. 8.
   On Israel army radio, actor Tuvia Tzafir impersonated Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir switching
their views on peace with the Arabs.
   A cartoon in the daily Maariv newspaper showed the government
dressed for Purim as a clown rocking on unsteady feet. The drawing
showed a Palestinian wearing the head of a peace dove but holding a
knife and firebomb, and the army in the mask of a barking monster.
   The costumes chosen by children also reflected the political
tension.
   In addition to young Esthers, brides and Ninja warriors, some
boys in Jewish West Bank settlements dressed up as soldiers,
complete with riot helmets, plastic shields and clubs. But one
customary children's costume was missing this year _ that of the
Arab.
   In Jerusalem, 27 students of the Bezalel Arts Academy, which
usually throws one of the best Purim parties in town, were detained
and others dispersed by police during a march Wednesday.
   Police said the students violated conditions of a permit for a
Purim procession when they unrolled signs saying, ``Let's not lose
our humanity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FreedHostage     03-03 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freed Hostage,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed UN Relief Worker Says Injections Were Worst Moments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Hostage, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Swedish relief worker held captive in
Lebanon for 25 days said Thursday the worst moment for him and a
Norwegian colleague was when they were given injections they feared
would be fatal.
   The Swede, 44-year-old Jan Stening, and William Jorgensen, 58,
of Norway, were working for the U.N. Relief and Works Agency when
they were kidnapped Feb. 5. The agency cares for Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon.
   Stening and Jorgensen were freed Tuesday and reunited with their
families at a Vienna hotel the next day, after arriving from Beirut.
   At a news conference Thursday, Stening said: ``When we got those
shots was a very tense situation.''
   He said it happened a few hours before their release, and ``We
both said goodbye ... because we said that was our very last
moment.''
   The purpose of the injections was to make them unconscious so
they could be moved to another location, he said, but the captives
thought the shots were meant to kill them.
   Asked whether they were forced to take the injections, he said:
``We never discussed what we were forced to do. We just accepted
everything.''
   With Stening was his wife Lis, a Stockholm lawyer, and his
12-year-old son Daniel. He did not attend a news conference with
Jorgensen on Wednesday night, explaining that he wanted more time
with his family.
   Jorgensen told reporters one of the kidnappers told them, ``We
thought you came from a secret service'' but an investigation
showed that to be a mistake.
   Stening said four gunmen kidnapped them near Sidon, south
Lebanon's provincial capital, as they were driving in a marked U.N.
car from their base in Tyre to Beirut.
   Both said they had no idea who abducted them. Stening said the
captors spoke Arabic except for the last few days in an apartment
that appeared to be in Beirut, when one spoke English.
</TEXT>
