<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-USAir-Planes     03-03 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USAir-Planes,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USAir Orders 50 Boeing 737s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir has agreed to buy 50 Boeing 737
jetliners with options for 30 additional aircraft, a deal worth
$2.4 billion if all the options are exercised, the airline said
Thursday.
   Delivery of the new jets will begin in April 1989 and continue
through December 1991.
   The twin-engine, short-to-medium range aircraft is the most
popular jet ever sold by the Seattle-based Boeing Co. The deal with
USAir brings to 2,001 Boeing 737s on order.
   Edwin Colodny, USAir chairman and president, said the order ``is
indicative of the health and vitality'' of the airline, which has
its headquarters at Washington National Airport.
   ``Our track record makes it possible to order these new aircraft
which will benefit our passengers and the communities we serve,''
Colodny said in a statement.
   USAir Group, the holding company for USAir as well as Piedmont
Aviation and Pacific Southwest Airlines, recently reported a 1987
net income of $194.6 million on revenue of $3 billion.
   The three airlines together fly 166 Boeing 737 aircraft, more
than any other carrier. Piedmont was the initial customer of the
Boeing 737 series 400 jetliner which is the newest version of the
plane.
   The 50 aircraft on order will include of the smaller series 500
models that will be introduced by Boeing in early 1989. The Boeing
737s have a seating capacity ranging from 108 seats for the series
500 model to 150 seats in the series 400 jet.
   USAir, which traditionally has concentrated its flights in the
Northeast expanded into the fifth largest airline company last year
with the acquisition of PSA and Piedmont. While the three airlines
still operate as separate carriers there are plans to merge them
into a single carrier in the future.
</TEXT>
