<DOCNO> AP880303-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1900EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     03-03 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Loses Steam, Sponsors Consider Calling it Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A general strike called to press for
the end of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's military rule lost steam
Thursday and the sponsors indicated they might end it.
   The indefinite stoppage began Monday and already has lasted
longer than any of five general strikes last year.
   A leader of the opposition National Civic Crusade told The
Associated Press actions by the United States and other countries
will become more important if internal pressure diminishes.
   Many stores that closed on previous days reopened Thursday. Two
factories resumed operations in the main industrial zone, which had
been a virtual ghost town since Monday. Management personnel at
others indicated they were preparing to resume production.
   Some supermarkets and pharmacies had closed, but were open for
business Thursday.
   The banking situation was confused. International banks opened
but limited the amount of withdrawals. Lines formed outside
privately owned local banks as word spread they intended to open,
but some still were closed in the afternoon.
   Riot police in trucks patrolled on Thursday in several
neighborhoods that were the scene of confrontations with
stone-throwing youths Tuesday and Wednesday. No violence was
reported.
   Members of the Civic Crusade predicted Wednesday night that
support for the strike would decline, but were encouraged Thursday
by reports that it had gained support outside the capital and
withheld a decision about ending it.
   Roberto Aleman, who heads the lawyers' component of the alliance
of 200 business, professional, labor and political groups, said
foreign pressure will be crucial in the coming days and weeks.
   ``Anything that tends to damage the government of Noriega, we
support,'' he said. He praised actions designed to freeze
Panamanian government funds deposited in several U.S. banks.
   ``The government will find itself besieged by economic and
diplomatic measures taken in the United States and Latin America,''
Aleman said. ``The measures will oblige the regime to take
extremely unpopular measures such as raising taxes and firing
public employees.''
   He predicted that would increase popular discontent and lead to
broader and more militant opposition.
   Eliott Abrams, assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, said Wednesday the U.S. government is inclined to support
such efforts.
   Air Panama suspended daily flights to Miami, its only connection
with the United States. Sources at the state-owned airline said the
purpose was to avoid any U.S. attempt to embargo aircraft.
   Washington still considers Eric Arturo Delvalle the legitimate
president of Panama. He was ousted last Friday after trying to fire
Noriega, who commands the 15,000-member Defense Forces, which
include the military and police.
   Delvalle is in hiding in Panama.
   The new government named former Foreign Minister Aquilino Boyd
the new ambassador to Washington. It was not clear whether he would
try to take up the post still occupied by Delvalle's ambassador,
Juan Sosa.
   Noriega was indicted last month in Florida for alleged
involvement in smuggling cocaine from Colombia to the United
States. He also is charged with allowing drug traffickers to
launder profits in Panamanian banks.
   A Panama City newspaper quoted a member of the joint chiefs of
staff as denying reports that that Noriega was purging the armed
forces.
   National Assembly member Guillermo Cochez told a news conference
Wednesday the general ordered the early retirements of two colonels
and two majors whose loyalty was suspect. Cochez belongs to the
opposition Christian Democrats.
   Col. Leonidas Macias was quoted by the pro-government paper La
Estrella as saying: ``Everything is normal and no one has been
retired or dismissed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
