<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 2ndLd-Writethru a0820 03-03 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0820,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Urges Palestinians To Form Delegation With Jordan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with Shultz's
comments. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz on Thursday
renewed an American drive to open Arab-Israeli peace talks by
urging Palestinian Arabs to form a joint delegation with Jordan for
negotiations.
   ``Jordan, with Palestinians, is a good concept,'' Shultz said.
He cited family and cultural ties between Palestinians living in
the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza and those living in Jordan.
   ``The structure is there, so there is a lot to be said for this
approach,'' Shultz said on a flight to Israel following a meeting
in London with Jordan's King Hussein. ``I think it is a good one.''
   He described his two-hour meeting with the king as ``very
worthwhile,'' but declined to give details to reporters traveling
to the Middle East with him.
   Pleading that the situation was delicate, the secretary also
would not say what approaches he had in mind for Israel's Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, whom he
will meet separately on Friday.
   But Shultz hinted he was making headway in his effort to convene
negotiations within a month.
   Peres met Shultz on his arrival Thursday night, but no airport
statements were issued.
   From Israel, Shultz plans to embark on quick flights to Syria
and Egypt for more talks, then return to Washington over the
weekend.
   President Reagan, in Belgium for a North Atlantic Treaty
Organization summit, announced Wednesday he was sending Shultz for
added talks with Mideast leaders. Shultz returned to the shuttle he
began earlier this week.
   The U.S. proposal seeks to defuse the explosive situation in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip by opening talks soon on how the 1.5
million Palestinians in the occupied territories could control
their daily affairs.
   According to the U.S. plan, the Israelis, Jordanians and
Palestinians would then open negotiations in December on an overall
peace settlement.
   Israel took the lands from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle
East war.
   ``We are at an interesting and important time in this
negotiation,'' Shultz said Thursday. ``And the best thing I can do
as far as maximizing the prospects of getting anywhere is not to
talk about it.''
   Still, Shultz spoke forcefully about the merits of a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation. He urged all parties involved to
adopt realistic goals.
   ``What I'm trying to do is to get people, all of whom have
dreams, to focus on the dreams that have a foundation of reality .
.. as I go around that is the message I try to carry,'' he said.
   The composition of the Arab delgation that would talk peace with
Israel is a major issue confronting Shultz on his swing through the
region.
   Jordan and Syria demand a role for the Palestine Liberation
Organization. Reporters in Amman with Shultz last week were
informed Jordan would no longer press the PLO to agree to a joint
delegation.
   The issue is important because the United States and Israel both
refuse to negotiate with an organization committed to dismantling
the Jewish state.
   Shultz said all the parties _ the United States, Israel, Jordan
and Egypt _agreed Palestinians ``have to have a say'' in the
negotiations.
   ``To a very considerable degree,'' Shultz said,``it's their
rights, their human condition that's involved. ... By including
them in a Jordanian-Palestinian delegation, you are making
arrangements for that and I think that can work.''
   At a news conference earlier in Brussels, Shultz took a tough
stance on the PLO while declaring that ``any suitable settlement
has to deal the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people.''
   Shultz insisted U.S. policy toward the PLO had not changed since
a 1975 law, enacted as a guarantee to Israel, prohibited
negotiating with the PLO so long as Yasser Arafat's organization
did not recognize Israel's right to exist.
   But Shultz said he wanted to meet with Palestinians as soon as
possible, even though a session could not be arranged right away.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
