<DOCNO> AP880303-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1931EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gephardt     03-03 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Challenges Dukakis on PAC Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt parried a television
attack on his presidential campaign with a challenge Thursday,
saying he'd return PAC contributions if Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis returned every dollar from those who do business with the
state of Massachusetts.
   Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach said the campaign has taken no
money from any corporate PACs or registered lobbyists in
Massachusetts.
   The Missouri congressman said he was defending his record
against his rival's latest television advertisements, which implied
he might have trouble representing American workers while accepting
funds from their employers.
   ``I'll give back every penny of money that I've gotten from
political action funds if he will return the money to all the
people who have given him money who do business with or are
licensed by the state of Massachusetts,'' Gephardt said in a short
airport stop at Baltimore-Washington International Airport.
   Gephardt, who made two whistlestops in Maryland five days before
Super Tuesday balloting, has taken third place to Dukakis and Jesse
Jackson among likely Maryland primary voters, according to the
latest Baltimore Evening Sun polls.
   After his airport news conference, he paid a courtesy visit to
Maryland Gov. William Donald Schaefer. Gephardt said he didn't come
seeking an endorsement, and he didn't get one from the governor,
who said again he will remain neutral at least through the Maryland
primary.
   The campaign exchanges between him and Dukakis have turned
increasingly scrappy as Super Tuesday nears.
   ``We will make public tomorrow (Friday) a partial list of some
of the interests that have given money to his campaign,'' Gephardt
told reporters gathered in a small airport terminal. ``He's got
appointees of his own state government who are awarding contracts
to many of the people who have given money to his campaign. Is that
a conflict of interest? I think that's a legitimate question.''
   The Missouri congressman said he not let special interests
dictate his votes.
   ``I've never made a decision in my public life based on those
contributions,'' he said. ``I have fought for a new trade policy. I
have fought for a new tax policy and in my whole career I've fought
against vested interests and the establishment of this country. And
I find it odd that now Gov. Dukakis calls it into question whether
or not I have been the one who fights for the working people of
this country,'' he said.
   Gephardt said only 5 percent of the $5 million to $6 million
raised in his campaign for the presidency has come from PACs and is
documented in the public record.
   Responding to Dukakis' latest attack that his oil import fee
proposal would saddle Americans with a $50 billion burden, he said
the types of oil industry incentives supported by Dukakis haven't
worked in the past. He defended imposition of an oil import fee,
saying it wouldn't cost consumers in the long run.
   ``The question is, do you want to pay 10 cents more a gallon now
for gasoline and have the money all go to our treasury, or do you
want to sit here and be vulnerable to OPEC and wait for a few years
and let OPEC raise the price by 40 or 50 cents a gallon and take
all the money to OPEC?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
