<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GSAResign     03-03 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GSA Resign,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GSA Chief Resigns After Three Years on Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terence C. Golden, who has been administrator
of the General Services Administration for nearly three years,
resigned Thursday because of his wife's health, a GSA spokesman
said.
   Golden, 43, became chief of the agency in June 1985, after
serving as assistant secretary for administration at the Treasury
Department. Before joining the government in March 1984, he was a
residential developer for a large Dallas firm.
   The GSA is the government's housekeeping agency. It owns or
leases 6,800 buildings nationwide.
   GSA spokesman Joseph Slye said Golden sent his resignation in a
letter to the White House. The letter was not released. The
resignation is effective March 18, he said.
   The agency recently has been under attack for its handling of
$55 million in government telecommunications contracts. The GSA's
inspector general, the Justice Department and a Senate committee
are investigating allegations that agency employees leaked
confidential information to competitors during bidding for the
contracts.
   The GSA's handling of that contract is being scrutinized because
the agency is also taking bids on a contract worth as much as $25
billion over 10 years to replace the government's phone network.
   At the GSA, Golden opened 10 child-care centers in federal
workplaces around the country and 25 more are planned for this
year. He got Congress to authorize $350 million to complete the
Federal Triangle complex of buildings on Pennsylvania Avenue, which
was begun during the Roosevelt administration.
   In February 1987, he restricted smoking for 890,000 federal
workers to designated areas in government buildings.
   The following May, he adopted new telephone regulations allowing
federal workers to make daily phone calls home to check on
children, spouses and day-care centers. Formerly they could only
call home in emergencies.
   He also persuaded Congress and the president to provide more
generous travel expenses to federal workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
