<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0790 03-03 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0790,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Offers Energy Alliance Proposal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 7th graf pvs, He predicted, with more
Jackson comment in Arkansas</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, sweeping through country
hard hit by depressed oil and farm prices, said Thursday he wants
to revitalize the U.S. oil industry and economy with a hemispheric
energy alliance.
   The Democratic presidential candidate said his proposal for a
Pan-American energy security alliance, in cooperation with Canada
and the Latin countries, would free the United States from reliance
on the OPEC nations.
   He said it could also be part of an overall cooperative strategy
to help Latin countries reduce their debt so that they could
purchase more American products, thereby reducing the U.S. deficit.
   Jackson picked up the endorsement of veteran state Sen. Gene
Stipe, who has served in the statehouse for 40 years, and a handful
of other legislators here.
   ``He is the best thing in the race,'' said Stipe, who until
recently had supported Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.
   Stipe said he now backs Jackson because ``I can see he has a
chance to be president. He has the momentum. After Super Tuesday,
they're not going to be able to stop him.''
   He predicted other white Oklahomans would also back Jackson and
help him in the state's Super Tuesday primary.
   Later, at the University of Arkansas, Jackson was endorsed by
John J. Hooker, a former Tennnessee gubernatorial candidate who
said he was representative of many more whites from his home state
who supported Jackson.
   ``After Super Tuesday, the rebels are going to come to Jesse by
the hundreds of thousands,'' he said to cheers.
   Hooker said Jackson's success in five Northern states with
voting-age populations of 1 percent or less had caught the
attention of many whites who did not support Jackson in his 1984
race.
   In an interview later, Jackson declined to specify what his
expectations were for Super Tuesday but expressed cautious optimism
that he would pick up significant white votes.
   ``I can only say that I'm reaching out,'' he told The Associated
Press.
   Jackson said ``one can never be so certain about what's going to
happen Tuesday,'' but added: ``My sense is there's a higher comfort
level'' among whites for his candidacy.
   Jackson is trying to pull white voters into his camp, and
campaign manager Gerald Austin said Jackson's strategy is to pull
in up to 10 percent of the white vote as well as his solid base of
black support on Super Tuesday.
   At the state capitol, Jackson was greeted by a standing ovation
from a joint session of the legislature. He teased some lawmakers
for wearing campaign buttons of other presidential contenders,
telling them not to support candidates that ``are not viable.''
   Jackson is spending most of the pre-Super Tuesday campaign days
bouncing across what he calls ``the new South'' and its bordering
states. He is intent on making inroads in 105 congressional
districts where his campaign sees a chance to gain a significant
part of the 1,307 delegates up for grabs on Tuesday.
   His campaign on Friday will launch a $100,000 TV campaign in
eight states, one featuring endorsements by comedian Bill Cosby and
other spots highlighting Jackson's accomplishments.
   Jackson focuses on the new South, saying that voting rights and
other freedoms have been won by blacks but economic inequity
amounts to a new form of slavery.
   He is trying to pull white voters into his campaign for
``economic justice.''
   His prospects in Oklahoma, where more than 30 banks closed last
year, are good, according to Stipe, although Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
of Tennessee and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri are also strong.
</TEXT>
