<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dominican-Unrest     03-03 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Unrest,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Killed, Another Injured on Third Day of Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters demanding
lower prices set fire to stores in a third day of disturbances
Thursday. A merchant killed one protester and wounded another,
authorities said.
   Police said 300 people were arrested in Santiago, the Caribbean
nation's second-largest city, where soldiers fired tear gas to
disperse rioters. Demonstrations were also reported in slum
sections of Santo Domingo, the capital.
   A Roman Catholic Church leader, Monsignor Agripino Nunez
Collado, called on leaders of government, labor, business and the
church to begin talks on the demonstrations and the country's
economic problems.
   Protests against inflation broke out last week in eight of the
26 Dominican provinces, leaving five people dead and 20 injured. On
Saturday, President Joaquin Balaguer announced a 25 percent
increase in the monthly minimum wage to about $75, but new
demonstrations broke out this week.
   On Thursday, protesters set fire to an undetermined number of
stores in Santiago and hurled firebombs at businesses in Santo
Domingo.
   A merchant in the city fired a gun into a mob that tried to burn
down his store, killing Miguel Cruz Vazquez, 21, and wounding
Andres Antonio Batista, 18, police said.
   Protest organizers, grouped as the Front for Popular Resistance
and Popular Unity Council, said demonstrations would continue
Friday and Saturday if the government did not move to curb
inflation.
   The government has made no comment on the latest violence. Last
week, Balaguer threatened to call out the army to contain unrest.
   Inflation was 30 percent last year, according to private
economists, and might top 50 percent this year.
   The protests have been the worst since Balaguer took office 1{
years ago in the nation of more than 6.5 million people.
</TEXT>
