<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDS-Commission 1stLd-Writethru a0751 03-03 0956</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Commission, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Says He and Koop Mostly Agree on Approach to AIDS
Prevention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 5-8 prv, `The 13-member ... preventive education,'
with 10 grafs to UPDATE with evening session. Should stand for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett told
the White House AIDS commission Thursday he and Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop are in 95 percent agreement about how to attack the
spread of the disease.
   As for the other 5 percent, Bennett suggested it is OK for a
doctor and an educator to differ on what to emphasize in their
messages to the American public.
   ``They can handle it,'' he said.
   Bennett's comments were in response to a statement by retired
Adm. James D. Watkins, chairman of the commission, that many
witnesses had told the panel differences among top federal
officials were sending ``equivocal messages'' on AIDS education and
prevention.
   During a brief evening session, the commission unanimously
adopted 60 pages of recommendations Watkins made last week as the
basis for an interim report to be forwarded to President Reagan
next week.
   The formal report closely follows the Watkins draft, including
his call for an additional $20 billion in state and federal
spending over the next decade to combat intravenous drug abuse and
improve treatment for AIDS patients.
   The most rapid spread of the disease is now occurring among
intravenous drugs abusers who catch AIDS by sharing contaminated
needles and then pass the virus to their sexual partners and
offspring.
   Despite the call for sharply higher spending, the interim report
is viewed as relatively uncontroversial compared with the issues
Watkins says the panel will address in its final report, such as
testing, anti-discrimination and preventive education.
   The version approved by the panel did not delete any of Watkins'
specific recommendations, but contained additional wording in
several sections.
   For example, a paragraph was added to the introduction to
emphasize ``that available data do not provide a basis for comfort
or complacency to any segment of our society. ... We express our
concern that inaccurate and misleading statements suggesting that
(the virus) cannot be spread through heterosexual activity could
stimulate transmission among those who would see such reports as
bases for ignoring the danger that does, in fact, exist.''
   Koop had told the panel Tuesday he was ``outraged'' at media
reports downplaying the danger of the virus spreading through
vaginal intercourse.
   In a section that concentrates on the danger of intravenous drug
users spreading the disease by sharing needles, language was added
to say: ``In addition to direct transmission, the use of drugs that
impair judgment can contribute to sexual transmission.''
   Commissioner Theresa L. Crenshaw, a physician who specializes in
sex therapy, has expressed concern at several hearings that too
much alcohol or marijuana use can lead people to do things they
would not do if they were sober.
   The perfunctory evening session to adopt the final report
followed a full day of hearings that featured Bennett and, on a
separate panel, Ryan White, an Indiana teen-ager who contracted
AIDS during treatment for hemophilia.
   The most publicized difference between Koop and Bennett is over
what emphasis to put on use of condoms and spermicides to prevent
the spread of AIDS among sexually active people.
   ``Whether it (the difference) is real or non-substantive, it is
a real perception out there,'' Watkins said.
   ``Dr. Koop and I are very close, extremely close,'' Bennett
said. ``I think Koop and I agree 95 percent of the way. It's all
right for the surgeon general and the secretary of education to
speak a little differently about these things.''
   He cited a hypothetical situation of a youngster discussing
``what he or she is doing'' with a doctor and with a counselor.
   ``The doctor's advice would probably emphasize the medical
aspects, as it should,'' said Bennett. ``The teacher or counselor's
advice might emphasize other things. Some shading of difference is
OK. Some measure of disagreement is OK.''
   ``When the American people ask for leadership, they are not
saying, `We're a bunch of dummies, tell us what to think,'''
Bennett said. ``They want to know our best thinking. And if our
best thinking diverges on some points, they can handle it.''
   Bennett said he does not dispute Koop's position that sexually
active people, including teen-agers, must be aware that condom and
spermicide use, although imperfect, are the only protection against
contracting AIDS sexually.
   The difference, especially involving adolescents, is where to
put the emphasis, Bennett said.
   What he does not condone, the education chief said, is teachers
going through ``a kind of incantation'' on abstinence and sexual
monogamy in AIDS prevention classes, ``then proceeding for the rest
of the class to talk (to teen-agers) about how to protect
themselves.''
   ``It's like saying, don't smoke, but if you do, smoke low tar.
Don't drink, but if you do, keep it to 70 proof. I think these are
equivocal messages.''
   Koop told the commission earlier in the week that while he also
believes the best advice is abstinence, or at least monogamy, ``I
think it is also realistic to understand that sexually active
teen-agers are unlikely to reverse their pattern and go backward,
and therefore prevention for them has to be our third line of
defense. ... We have to teach them about the protection of
themselves and others through the use of condoms and spermicides.''
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a incurable,
contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering
it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections.
   The disease is spread most often through sexual contact, needles
or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood
products, and from infected pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
