<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-03 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Packs Snow, Knocks Out Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm dumped freezing rain and up to 6 inches of snow on the
East and Midwest on Thursday, downing power lines and causing
hundreds of traffic accidents.
   Meanwhile, rain and thunderstorms battered the central Gulf
Coast region. During a six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. EST,
Pensacola, Fla., had 1.46 inches of rain, Valparaiso, Fla., 1.19
inches and Milton, Fla., .90 inches.
   Dry weather prevailed over much of the rest of the nation.
   In Indiana, downed tree limbs interrupted power in parts of
Indianapolis. Up to 4 inches of snow fell on Kokomo and 3 inches on
Lafayette, Sheridan, Portland and Crawfordsville.
   Power outages also hit thousands of homes in central Illinois.
   Freezing rain, sleet and snow fell on central Ohio, where up to
5 inches of snow were expected.
   Up to 5 inches of snow fell in eastern Kansas, and more than 6
inches fell across parts of Oklahoma and Texas.
   A band of snow extended from western Pennsylvania through
central Illinois to west-central Texas, with freezing rain reported
from Ohio to Missouri. Rain and snow also fell over Montana.
   Earlier, the storm dumped up 13 inches on parts of the Texas
Panhandle, thunderstorms triggered flash floods in east Texas and a
tornado ripped the roofs off mobile homes near Galveston. The
weather was blamed for at least four traffic deaths.
   Up to 4 inches of snow were expected in parts of West Virginia
and up to 6 inches in northeastern Pennsylvania. Up to six inches
were possible in southeastern New York state.
   Temperatures were above 50 degrees from south-central Texas to
the southern and middle Atlantic Coast, with 70s in Louisiana,
Mississippi and Florida. Temperatures generally were below freezing
from the upper half of the Mississippi Valley to northern New
England, with teens across northern sections of the Great Lakes
region.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 17
degrees at Houghton, Minn., to 86 degrees at the southwest Florida
regional airport in Fort Myers.
   The low for the nation was 14 degrees below zero at
International Falls, Minn.
   Friday's forecast called for rain extending from the lower and
middle Mississippi Valley to northern Florida, the Carolinas and
the mid-Atlantic Coast, with thunderstorms from Alabama to
Virginia. Snow will extend from northern Ohio to New Jersey. Rain
and snow will extend from Wyoming across the northern Plains, with
snow most likely in Wyoming. Rain will extend from the northern and
central Pacific Coast to northwest Montana, with rain likely in
Washington and western Oregon. Fair to partly sunny skies will
prevail across the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures will remain below 50 from the northern and central
Rockies to the middle and northern Atlantic Coast. Highs will be in
the 30s and upper 20s from eastern Montana through the upper half
of the Mississippi Valley to New England; above 60 from California
through southern New Mexico and across the lower Mississippi Valley
to the southern Atlantic Coast, and in the 70s in Southern
California, southwestern Arizona and extreme southern Texas, and
from southern Louisiana to Florida and southern Georgia.
</TEXT>
