<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru a0801 03-03 1075</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0801,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Call for `Immediate, Devastating' Embargo Against Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 19th graf pvs, bgng: ``Sosa has ...''
to UPDATE with comments on bank funds.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Republican and Democratic congressmen
introduced a bill Thursday to impose an ``immediate, dramatic and
devastating'' trade, air travel and currency embargo against the
regime of Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The lawmakers said they would seek speedy congressional approval
of the embargo bill.
   But they said they also hoped to prod President Reagan to act
independently to adopt a far stronger series of punitive sanctions
against the Noriega regime than he has approved to date.
   The proposed embargo would bar all imports from Panama, prohibit
all U.S. exports to that nation, bar all air travel between the two
countries and prohibit U.S. banks from transferring any funds to
Panama and its banking system.
   ``By stopping the transfer of funds from U.S. banks to Panama,
we go for the jugular,'' said Sen. Alfonse D-Amato, R-N.Y., a
principal sponsor of the embargo plan.
   ``Because of Panama's heavy reliance on its economic ties with
the United States, the impact of a U.S. trade embargo would be
immediate, dramatic and devastating to Noriega and his cohorts,''
D'Amato said.
   Panamanian opposition leader Ricardo Arias Calderon, president
of the Christian Democratic Party, told reporters later that a
trade embargo would be ``strong medicine'' but that such a remedy
is sometimes needed for people to regain their health.
   Other sponsors of the embargo bill are Sens. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass.; David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Bob Graham, D-Fla.; John
Kerry, D-Mass.; and Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
   The senators told reporters they introduced the embargo
legislation at the specific request of Eric Arturo Devalle, who was
ousted as Panama's president after attempting to remove Noriega as
commander of Panama's defense forces.
   Noriega was indicted by a federal grand jury in Miami last month
for accepting $4.6 million to protect international drug
traffickers using Panama as safe haven.
   Kerry said that imposing the embargo gives the United States the
``best chance'' of removing Noriega but provides no guarantee of
that result.
   But D'Amato predicted imposing the embargo ``would spell the end
of Noriega within a matter of days.''
   D'Amato said the proposed ban on bank transfers to Panama will
worsen Pananama's banking crisis and cash shortage.
   He said it would represent an important blow at a banking system
he said has been used as a conduit for laundering billions of
dollars in proceeds from illicit drug sales in the United States.
   A ban on Panamanian goods will paralyze a $412 million market
representing 60 percent of Panama's total exports, D'Amato said. A
ban on U.S. exports to Panama will affect a 30 percent slice of all
Panamanian imports, he said.
   Delvalle's representatives have been attempting to seize cotrol
of Panamanian government assets in the United States through court
action, saying the new government took power illegally.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the
administration had taken measures to prevent the new government
from gaining access to official Panamanian funds in U.S. banks.
   She said Deputy Secretary John C. Whitehead has signed a
document certifying the administration's position that Ambassador
Juan B. Sosa has full authority over Panamanian assets in any
Federal Reserve Bank or federally insured bank, ``to ensure that
Panamanian government funds in U.S. banks are not removed by the
Noriega regime.''
   Sosa has estimated that Panamanian government deposits in U.S.
banks total about $50 million.
   At a news conference Thursday night at the Panamanian Embassy,
an attorney for Delvalle said federal courts in New York and Boston
have issued temporary restraining orders to prevent the transfer of
official Panamanian funds on deposit in U.S. banks to the
Panamanian government.
   ``We believe that whatever funds are in those institutions are
at this point frozen and cannot be transmitted to the Noriega
regime,'' said lawyer Daniel Resnick.
   Ms. Oakley also said that, at Sosa's request, 17 Panamanian
consular officers in the United States are no longer being
recognized as representatives of that government.
   Mrs. Oakley said there has been no final decision on a proposal
by Delvalle's representatives that a $7 million fee for Panama
Canal operations due the Panamanian government on March 15 be
withheld.
   But, she said, ``We have every feeling that the requests
probably are going to be honored.''
   In Brussels on Thursday, Reagan gave a one-word answer when
asked whether he felt Noriega should be replaced: ``Yes.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who was with Reagan at the
NATO summit, called Noriega ``bad news'' but indicated that the
administration must move cautiously in taking action against him.
   ``We want to do it properly, we want to do it right, we want to
do it effectively,'' Shultz said. His tone contrasted sharply with
that of Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams, who has said
the administration is prepared to abide by the wishes of Delvalle,
whom it still regards as the constitutional leader of Panama.
   Reagan's national security adviser, Colin L. Powell, told
reporters aboard Air Force One en route to Washington that there
was no obvious successor to Noriega in Panama.
   ``There is no apparent leader _ military or civilian _ waiting
in the wings that you can have any reasonable form of assurance to
say, `That's the guy who can succeed Noriega.' So even if Noriega
should leave, we are anticipating a period of instability,'' Powell
said.
   In a another development, the chairman of a House Foreign
Affairs task force on international narcotics control said he will
ask Congress to repudiate Reagan's recent certification of five
Latin American nations as having fully cooperated with U.S. efforts
to eradicate narcotics cultivation and trafficking.
   Task force chairman Rep. Lawrence J. Smith, D-Fla., said he will
introduce legislation next week to reverse the administration's
action and decertify Mexico, Bolivia, Peru, Uruguay and the Bahamas.
   He said the evidence is clear to him that none are in full
cooperation with U.S. anti-narcotics efforts.
   Smith said he also is considering adding Laos and Burma to the
list of allegedly uncooperative nations but said they pose special
problems and that further study is needed before a decision is made.
   The congressman said his list does not include Colombia, whose
government he said has tried to cooperate in eradicating narcotics
cultivation despite intensive pressure from criminal narcotics
cartels headquartered in the country.
</TEXT>
