<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Prisoners     03-03 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Prisoners,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Drives Bulldozer To Knock Down Prison Gate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi climbed onto a bulldozer and
knocked down the gate of a Tripoli prison Thursday as thousands of
Libyans cheered, a Western diplomat said.
   The official Libyan news agency JANA, monitored in Rome, said
400 inmates were freed after Gadhafi ``demolished'' the prison with
the bulldozer. It said the former prisoners chanted slogans hailing
``the festival of liberty.''
   The Western European diplomat said he saw dozens of men with
crewcuts come pouring from the prison, to be joyously greeted by
relatives.
   The diplomat was reached by telephone by The Associated Press in
Rome. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said about 50 other people, who appeared to be Gadhafi aides,
also drove bulldozers during the rally to knock down a wall
surrounding the prison.
   The diplomat said Gadhafi, clad in a military jacket and slacks,
gave a 30-minute speech to the crowd in which the Libyan leader
praised his own record as leader of the 1969 revolution that
brought him to power.
   On Wednesday night, Gadhafi said in a speech that he was
releasing all Libyan prisoners except those accused of plotting
with foreign countries, according to JANA. He promised to destroy
the prison and invited prisoners' relatives to watch.
   The agency quoted him as saying the release included prisoners
who plotted to assassinate Gadhafi in the past.
   The Libyan leader said, however, that the amnesty does not cover
those ``accused of treason by linking themselves with foreign
powers that have tried to use force to arrive at things of their
own,'' according to JANA, which said he put the number of those
prisoners at 100 or fewer.
   Gadhafi's regime has been described as merciless toward
opponents. Libyan dissidents have been assassinated abroad and
Libyan state television has sometimes broadcast executions of
people convicted on treason charges.
   Amnesty International, the human rights organization, said last
September it received no reply to its appeals for 75 political
prisoners it said were being held in Libya.
   The United States bombed Libya on April 15, 1986 after accusing
the Gadhafi government of supporting terrorism.
</TEXT>
