<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-BirthControl     03-03 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Birth Control,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Arrested for Fighting Birth Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a crackdown on violators of China's one-child
policy, authorities in southwestern China arrested people running
an illegal operation to remove women's intrauterine devices, a
state-run newspaper said Thursday.
   The Peasants Daily said the group made huge profits by enticing
women to remove their IUDs with appeals to the traditional belief
that ``more sons equal more happiness.''
   The brief report said the group was headed by Xu Guanghui and Ma
Heyuecai, but gave few details and did not say how many people were
involved.
   It said people in the group removed IUDs from 644 women in Butuo
county in Sichuan province, using unsterilized bamboo and iron
hooks. Many women became infected and several died, the paper said.
   The IUD is the main form of birth control in China's countryside.
   The belief in the importance of having a son has enjoyed a
resurgence in the countryside following the breakup of communes and
return to family farming. More children mean more hands to help at
planting and harvest time.
   The population growth rate has jumped from 1.1 percent in 1985
to 1.4 percent in both 1986 and 1987. China's population of 1.07
billion increased by 15 million in 1987, or nearly 1.5 million over
target, according to official statistics.
   China wants to limit the population to 1.2 billion by the year
2000.
   The government punishes violators of the one-child limit by
imposing fines, but as peasants have become more prosperous, the
fines have become less of a deterrent.
   Authorities plan to tighten enforcement of the one-child limit
by basing evaluations of officials' job performance in part on
their conduct of family planning work. They also called for
increased family planning education.
</TEXT>
