<2ND_LINE>AM-Anthem Dispute,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Banished From Homeroom Foor Singing Anthem</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A principal who banished a high
school senior from homeroom for humming and singing along to the
national anthem when it is played over the intercom says the
dispute is a question of ``who's in charge.''
   Sara Sprague, a 17-year-old member of the choir at North
Kingstown High School, said that her humming and singing were a
``spontaneous reaction to the music'' and that she was within her
rights.
   Principal Paul Rennick said Sara was ``playing games'' by
violating school policy requiring silence when the anthem is played.
   Katherine Janis, her homeroom teacher, said the humming was part
of ``noisy and disruptive'' behavior by Miss Sprague, who has been
banished for the past three weeks.
   The controversy began last month when she began humming to the
anthem and was reprimanded by Janis. The next day, Miss Sprague
sang along _ quietly, she said _ and found herself in the assistant
principal's office.
   The issue went public when Sara wrote a letter to a local
newspaper in protest.
   ``This is a pretty patriotic school. The flag is everywhere.
George Washington is on the walls,'' the principal said. ``It's not
a question of patriotism, it's a question of who's in charge.''
   Miss Sprague's mother, Jane Sprague, said she is backing her
daughter.
   ``It's hard for me to believe that a school supported by local,
state and federal taxes won't let students sing the national anthem
if they want to,'' she said.
</TEXT>
