<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0352</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Bright and Brief</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOORPARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moorpark has gone through four mayors in
four months _ including three in one night.
   John Lane, a sergeant for the Los Angeles Police Department, was
mayor Thursday after becoming the third person to accept the job
Wednesday night.
   At 8:08 p.m. Wednesday, Mayor John Galloway resigned in an
apparent effort to stave off a reorganization that would have put
Lane in the mayor's chair.
   Mayor Pro Tem Eloise Brown took over. She served for 22 minutes
before she was replaced. At 8:30 p.m., the council voted Lane into
the mayor's chair.
   Ms. Brown was partially to blame for her brief 22-minute reign.
She voted against herself in the 4-1 vote ``because I am a good
sport.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version also moved on business wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dancing clay raisins, party animal Spuds
MacKenzie and a piano-playing moonman edged out human actors in a
list of popular TV advertising campaigns. It seems the humans cost
too much and are too risky.
   ``We seem to be heading into a period when we see more created
celebrities, not necessarily human beings, in commercials,'' said
David Vadehra, president of Video Storyboard Tests Inc.
   The New York-based consumer research firm based its 10th annual
survey on interviews with more than 25,000 people about what
commercials they liked best last year.
   Leading the list was the campaign for California raisins, which
used clay models of raisins dancing to the song ``Heard It Through
The Grapevine.''
   Second was Bud Light beer commercials, many of which featured
the English bull terrier Spuds MacKenzie. Other Bud Light
commercials offered variations of what can go wrong if you simply
order a ``light'' without specifying the brand.
   The ad campaign for Pepsi soft drinks placed third, and Miller
Lite beer commercials were fourth.
   Ads for McDonald's restaurants came in fifth. The campaign
included some commercials that featured a piano-playing character
shaped like a moon crescent who extolled dinner at McDonald's to
the tune ``Mack The Knife.''
</TEXT>
