<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Education     03-03 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Education,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers, Students Join In Protest March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 striking high school
teachers and students marched through the city center Thursday
demanding increased government spending on education.
   ``No to austerity, spend more money on education!,'' the
teachers chanted outside the Education Ministry. There are 25,000
high school teachers in Athens.
   The public high school teachers, who make an average of $416 a
month, want a 30 percent raise, improved health benefits and
increased spending on education.
   The students demand a one-year reduction in the four-year
vocational high school curriculum, fewer admission requirements for
technical colleges and guaranteed jobs after graduation.
   They chanted ``We want work, bread, education!'' as they marched
behind the teachers.
   Both students and teachers want Premier Andreas Papandreou's
government to allocate 15 percent of the state budget to education.
   For 1988, the education budget totals 9.8 percent of overall
government spending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
