<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Explosion     03-03 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Explosion,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Die In Dynamite Factory Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABLON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion tore through a dynamite
factory Thursday and killed five people, officials reported. Eight
people were injured.
   The victims in the blast in Ablon, a Normandy town near the
English Channel, were Rene Rubier, 53, director of the Nobel P.R.B
Explosifs factory; his deputy, Marcel Delhom, 58; factory
superintendent Philippe Gentil, 38, and two workers.
   It was the third explosion at the factory in three years. In
March 1985, three people were killed. In March 1987, an explosion
forced the plant to close until Dec. 10 while new safety measures
were implemented.
   The factory employs 135 people and produces about 20 tons of
explosives a day for civilian use.
   Jean Amet, chief administrator of the Calvados region, said the
explosion occurred in a machine that packs the dynamite into
blocks. He said the injured were in satisfactory condition.
   ``I saw a large flame which rose over the buildings, then,
almost immediately, I heard a loud noise and the flash
disappeared,'' said Claude Hubert, an ambulance driver who was
about a half-mile away.
   The blast occurred shortly after the factory opened at 9 a.m.
</TEXT>
