<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Ecology     03-03 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Ecology,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Soviet Bloc Countries End `Ecological Summit'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland, East Germany and Czechoslovakia
ended an unprecedented ``ecological summit'' Thursday by pledging
to combat pollution that may threaten half of the region's
woodlands.
   The three-day meeting in the western city of Jelenia Gora
reflected the neighboring countries' concern about increased
pollution, particularly in border regions. It was their first
high-level meeting devoted to the environment.
   More than 148,000 acres of forests in western Poland are
threatened with destruction caused by air pollution, officials say.
   Deputy premiers from the three countries agreed ``to expand and
deepen cooperation'' in environmental protection, the official
Polish news agency PAP reported.
   They also decided to meet next year in Czechoslovakia and draw
up an environmental protection agreement, PAP said.
   Deputy Premier Jozef Koziol of Poland was quoted as saying the
three countries have ``acknowledged the existing degradation and
have undertaken to take swift joint effective measures in order to
halt and then reduce environmental contamination.''
   The PAP report did not describe the measures.
   A Polish television news report said the agreement provides for
joint research on pollution-control technology and joint production
of such equipment.
   East Germany's delegation was led by Hans Reichelt and
Czechoslovakia's delegation by Jaromir Obzina.
   Participants in an independent ecological seminar organized by
the opposition Freedom and Peace Movement, a banned Polish peace
and ecology group, wrote an open letter to the officials, saying 30
percent to 50 percent of the forests in the region would die by
1995 if pollution levels do not change.
   The letter, drawn up at the Feb. 26-28 seminar in the
southwestern city of Gliwice, demanded that the public in the three
countries be kept informed about environmental agreements and their
progress.
   The letter said ``nothing or almost nothing is done to ensure''
the implementation of documents drawn up at meetings of Soviet bloc
countries.
   The ecology activists said the concentration of sulphuric oxides
in the area is among the highest in Europe and demanded that the
three countries install equipment to control pollution at six
coal-burning power plants in the region.
   Poland has demanded Czechoslovakia pay cleanup costs for several
major oil spills in the Oder river.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
