<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-VotingAge     03-03 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Voting Age,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Constitution To Cut Voting Age From 18 To 16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators rewriting Brazil's
Constitution have voted to cut the minimum voting age from 18 to 16.
   Legislators doubling as a constituent assembly voted 355 to 98
late Wednesday in favor of reducing the minimum voting age. The
proposal would be included in a final draft of the new
constitution, which is expected to be considered by the two houses
of Congress later this year.
   If approved, the constitutional article would permit 5.7 million
more voters, increasing the electorate to nearly 78 million of the
nation's 141 million people.
   Voting would not be mandatory for teens under 18 under the
proposal, while remaining mandatory for those between the ages of
18 and 70.
   Teen-agers interviewed by local newspapers about their new civic
responsibilities had mixed reactions.
   Leandro Martins, 16, told the Jornal Do Brasil newspaper his
generation was not ``responsible enough'' to choose elected
officials, while 17-year-old David Oliveira was quoted as saying
``at last we can have some say in what goes on.''
   The 559 legislators have been meeting since February 1987 to
replace the authoritarian charter handed down by the military
regime that ruled from 1964 to 1985.
   They also are deciding when Brazilians will vote for president
and the country's future system of government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
