<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Honey     03-03 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Honey,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beekeepers Stage Protest March To Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of beekeepers dumped their
beehives outside Parliament on Thursday to protest imports of
artificially sweetened foreign honey.
   Earlier the beekeepers, some wearing white coveralls and black
net face masks, marched through the city center shouting ``No more
foreign honey!''
   There are 20,000 beekeepers in Greece, which produces more than
12,000 tons of honey. Greece is the only member of the European
Community with a honey surplus and exports about 1,200 tons yearly,
the Agriculture Ministry says.
   ``Our goal is to stop the import of adulterated foreign honey
which is being sold here as an European Community product,'' said
Nicolaos Papadopoulos, president of the Attica Beekeepers'
Cooperatives.
   Other beekeepers claimed the imported honey was diluted with
glucose to make it taste sweeter.
   Greek-produced honey is thick and fudge-like, with a distinctive
taste derived from the nectar collected by bees from thyme and
other mountain herbs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
