<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewJustice     03-03 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Justice,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Black Woman Justice Sworn in on Pennsylvania's Highest Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Juanita Kidd Stout was sworn in Thursday as
a justice of the Pennsylvania Supreme Court, becoming the first
black woman in the nation to sit on a state's highest court.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey appointed the former Philadelphia Common
Pleas Court judge to serve out the term of William D. Hutchinson,
who left for the federal bench.
   A justice will be elected to fill the seat in November. Stout,
who reaches the mandatory retirement age of 70 next year, is not
running.
   Stout, who served on the city's Common Pleas Court since 1959,
borrowed from the 4-H Club motto in her remarks after taking the
oath of office.
   ``I promise you that during my tenure on the Supreme Court of
Pennsylvania, however short it may be, I shall strive to make the
best better,'' she said.
   The former English teacher has a reputation for correcting
lawyers in court when they misspeak and for editing the opinions of
colleagues.
   ``The trouble is, when Judge Stout sent me a note like that it
was a correction. When Justice Stout sends me a note now, it will
be a reversal,'' said Common Pleas President Judge Edward J.
Bradley, drawing laughter from the crowd in the Supreme Court
chambers.
</TEXT>
