<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2219EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Falklands     03-03 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Falklands,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Argentina Plans Defensive Alert During British Exercises In
Falklands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina said Thursday it plans
a ``defensive alert'' during scheduled British military exercises
in the Falkland Islands and if necessary ``will execute
corresponding defense plans.''
   The foreign and defense ministries denounced the exercises, due
to begin Monday and end March 31, as ``violating ... (Argentina's )
sovereign rights'' over the islands, which this nation claims were
stolen by the British in 1833.
   Argentina has said the exercises will chill efforts to restore
relations, broken in 1982 when the two countries fought a bloody,
74-day war over the remote South Atlantic islands.
   A joint comminque by the two ministries said the exercises
contradict U.N. resolutions declaring the region a zone of peace.
British officials have said the exercises are essentially defensive.
   The statement said that although Argentina ``repeatedly has
expressed willingness to resolve the dispute in peaceful and
negotiated form'' the government is obliged to ``protect the lives
and property of those who inhabit Argentine soil'' and has adopted
a defensive alert.
   The British exercises will be strictly watched, the ministries
said.
   ``In the event it is necessary, corresponding defense plans''
will be executed, the communique said.
   The ministries did not go into specifics.
   But the statement warned foreign shipping that vessels will be
subject to ``visit, inspection or capture under terms of
international law'' by Argentine authorities ``with the objective
of avoiding their involvement in incidents.''
   The maneuvers were reported to include planned use of Phantom
fighter jets and hundreds of British troops.
   On April 2, 1982, Argentine troops captured the islands, but
Britain sent a task force and defeated the Argentines. In the
fighting, 712 Argentines and 256 British were killed.
   Brig. Gen. Ernesto Crespo, air force chief of staff, said
Thursday that his branch will remain alert to any orders it may
receive from the government regarding the British maneuvers.
   ``You must consider that this is not a simple exercise in the
Malvinas (Falkland) Islands,'' Crespo said. ``It is much more
important and involves peace in the South Atlantic and, as a
result, not only our country but other American states as well.''
</TEXT>
