<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-HighwayRobbery     03-03 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Highway Robbery,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bandits Rob Armored Van on Highway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEREGNO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bandits ambushed an armored van on a
superhighway Thursday, put a hand grenade on the hood to force
guards out of the vehicle and stole $1.3 million in cash and bonds,
the Italian news agency ANSA reported.
   The van, carrying money from Milan to two banks in Sondrio in
northern Italy, was held up in the Seregno area just outside Milan
by gunmen riding in four cars.
   A policeman in Serengo contacted by telephone Thursday said he
had no details. ANSA gave this account:
   A gunman in one car shot out the van's tires. Another car rammed
the van from behind and a third cut it off from the front. The
fourth car parked on the shoulder of the highway headed in the
other direction.
   Four men with pistols and rifles got out. When the driver and
two guards stayed locked inside the van, the gunmen placed a
grenade on the hood.
   Fearing they would be blown up, the three got out. The driver
was hit over the head with a pistol butt. The two others were
forced to open the safe.
   The robbers grabbed the bags, jumped into the car parked on the
other side of the highway and sped off toward Milan.
   A police explosives' expert later detonated the grenade in a
nearby field.
</TEXT>
