<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CondorEgg     03-03 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Condor Egg,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Egg Laid by Rare California Condors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California condor Thursday laid the first egg
ever produced in captivity by a pair of the endangered birds,
boosting efforts to save the species, the San Diego Wild Animal
Park said.
   If the egg hatches at the end of its two-month incubation, it
will be the first California condor ever conceived in captivity,
officials said. Only 27 of the birds exist, all in captivity, said
park spokesman Tom Hanscom.
   Biologists moved the egg from the nest to an incubator,
according to plan, Hanscom said. The egg may not produce an
offspring because the female is old and her mate, a young male, may
be sexually immature, park officials cautioned.
   By taking the egg from its parents at an early point, scientists
hope to induce the pair to ``double-clutch,'' or produce a second
egg to replace the lost one.
   California condors have been decimated in the wild by lead
poisoning, caused by eating lead shot in animal carcasses,
biologists said.
   The last California condor in the wild was captured and brought
to the Wild Animal Park on April 3, 1987 in a last bid to restore
the vanishing species.
   Fourteen of the birds are kept at the San Diego park in
enclosures not on view to the public. The 13 others are similarly
housed at the Los Angeles Zoo.
   Since 1981, scientists have hatched 13 condors in captivity from
eggs taken in the wild. The birds, which have a wingspan of about 9
feet, are dark reddish-brown with a curved beak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 2239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Politics     03-03 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Politics,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Social and Liberal Democrats Party Launched</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The centrist Social Democrats and Liberals
officially united Thursday after eight months of stormy infighting
over the policies of the merged party.
   The new Social and Liberal Democrats Party hopes to end the
dominance of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's governing
Conservatives and the main opposition, the socialist Labor Party.
   The Social Democrats voted nearly 2-1 and the Liberals more than
7-1 to merge in mail ballots after separate party conventions
approved the merger last month. But only slightly more than half
the party members voted.
   Liberal leader David Steel, who is expected to be elected leader
of the new party, told a news conference it will give ``hope to a
whole new generation.''
   Steel pledged to press for rejuvenation of the ailing National
Health Service and run-down inner city neighborhoods.
   The Social Democrats' leader, Robert Maclennan, said Britain
``needs a great national party, with roots in all our communities.''
   Maclennan called the Conservatives ``complacent, centralizing,
autocratic'' and the Labor Party ``the complacent, inert,
bureaucratic alternative.''
   David Owen, who resigned as Social Democrat leader in opposition
to the union, urged members to boycott the vote and called it ``a
fiasco.'' He plans to continue the Social Democrats as a separate
party.
   The two parties placed a distant third in last June's general
election, in which Mrs. Thatcher won a third term as prime minister.
</TEXT>
