<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Boycott,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After No TV For Year, Girl Misses First Show While Finishing
Homework</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old who earned $500 by going a
year without television missed the first show she planned to watch
Thursday night. She was doing homework.
   ``I watched the last half of `Cheers' because my homework ran
into it,'' Jenny Machalleck said. ``I had planned to watch `Cosby'
but I was doing homework through that.''
   Earlier Thursday, she received the $500 check promised by her
parents if she could go for a full year without television. The
deal they made on March 2, 1987, was to cure what she called a
six-hour-a-day TV habit.
   Thursday's experience _ missing TV while finishing school work _
was quite a change, said Jenny, a seventh-grader. ``Before, I would
never worry about my homework. I would just watch TV,'' she said.
   As for her first sampling of TV in a year, she said, ``It was
fun to watch because I hadn't watched in so long. But I found I
hadn't really been missing anything.''
   ``I was just not as enthusiastic as I thought I would be,'' she
said.
