<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Alston,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter Confidant Dies At Age 76</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Henry Alston Jr., a former ambassador to
Australia and a top campaign aide to former President Jimmy Carter,
has died after a short illness. He was 76.
   Alston, an influential Atlanta lawyer who died Wednesday, began
supporting Carter in 1966, the year he lost the governor's race to
Lester Maddox.
   He was chairman of Carter's successful gubernatorial bid in 1970
and headed the Committee for Jimmy Carter, Carter's national
campaign organization, when Carter was elected president in 1976.
   Carter, as governor, appointed Alston to the Board of Regents,
and as president appointed him ambassador.
   Alston, a Navy veteran of World War II, raised millions of
dollars for the University of Georgia.
   Survivors include his wife, Elkin Goddard Alston; a son; a
daughter and five grandchildren. Funeral arrangements were
incomplete.
