<HEAD>Prime Minister Shamir Warns of Possible New Media Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Wednesday he
was considering further restrictions on news media access in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, saying journalists have harmed
Israel.
   Shamir did not say what steps he might take. Under current
regulations, soldiers are authorized to temporarily close parts of
the occupied territories to reporters. The army frequently uses
this measure to keep the news media from the sites of violent
clashes.
   In a sharply worded attack, Shamir accused journalists of being
biased against Israel and suggested such bias was part of official
editorial policy.
   ``There is no lack of people (Israeli officials) who are ready
to explain what is happening,'' Shamir told American Jewish leaders
in Jerusalem.
   ``The trouble is they (reporters) don't want to listen. They are
looking for Arab sources of information. Maybe they even have some
instructions from their establishment.''
   Shamir called on American Jewish leaders to quell within their
ranks any criticism of Israel, saying it was ``non-Jewish to join
an anti-Israeli front of non-Jewish people.''
   Several prominent American Jews, including actor-director Woody
Allen and Rabbi Alexander Schindler, head of Jewish Reform
congregations in the United States, have criticized Israel in past
weeks for its crackdown on Arab protests in the occupied
territories.
   By U.N. count, 76 Palestinians have been killed and hundreds
wounded in unrest in the occupied lands since Dec. 8.
