<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Poetry     03-03 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Poetry,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Poet Judged One Of Six Best Among 20,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vermont office worker won a prize Wednesday for
a poem judged among the six best of 20,000 entries in a worldwide
competition among English-speaking poets.
   Arthur Stone of Morrisville, Vt., was the only American among
six finalists chosen by Ted Hughes, the British poet laureate, and
Irish poet Seamus Heaney. They selected the six from a list of 600
compiled by six other poets from the entries.
   ``It's a nice thing to happen _ it's rather surreal to be a poet
in America,'' said Stone after receiving a check for 500 pounds
($885) and a fountain pen in the Arvon International Poetry
Competition. The prizes were awarded at Sotheby's auction house in
London.
   ``The quality of the poetry was very high and we wished we could
have given more prizes,'' said Hughes, who spent a week with Heaney
reading the 600 poems in Cambridge, Mass., where Heaney is a
professor at Harvard University.
   ``There were 100 more poems we would have liked to give prizes
to, but we will put them in an anthology with the finalists and the
10 runners-up,'' he said.
   The runners-up, who won 250 pounds ($440), included four
Americans: Brendan Galvin, Mary Karr, Patrick Madden and Pat
Maquire. Their hometowns were not immediately available.
   The top prize of 5,000 pounds ($8,850) went to Selima Hill,
whose poem ``The Notebook'' is the imaginary diary of a patient in
a psychiatric hospital. The other five finalists were not ranked.
   Stone, 43, was born in Long Beach, Calif., grew up in the Mojave
Desert and now works for the Office of Alcohol and Drug Abuse in
Vermont.
   He said in an interview he writes poetry as a pastime, jotting
down ideas on bits of paper and often getting his best ideas just
after waking up or just before going to sleep.
   Asked what his colleagues think of his poetry, Stone said:
``Well, they refer to me as `the poet' rather than the information
and planning specialist, which is my job.''
   Stone has had poems published in American literary magazines and
calls ``Late Arrival,'' the 51-line prize-winning poem, ``a
realistic confessional about my initiation into the world.''
   It starts with his birth and plunges quickly into memories of
his boyhood, with people telling him their experiences and advising
him to learn from them.
   Stone said his poem was triggered by a work of another American
poet, Denis Johnson.
   ``There's a lot of cross-fertilization in the arts and it's
extremely important,'' Stone said. ``I'm active in theater and I
play saxophone in a jazz ensemble. It all helps me with my poetry.''
   Arvon is a foundation which teaches writing. The contest was its
fifth. The organization gets its name from the Arvon seat of poetry
in the ``Mabinogion,'' the book of Welsh medieval tales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
