<HEAD>Cubs Give Commitment To Stay At Wrigley Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Cubs on Wednesday promised to stay at
Wrigley Field unless faced with ``circumstances beyond the Cubs'
control.''
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer, who had demanded the commitment from the
club's owners, the Tribune Co., before signing an ordinance
allowing night games at the 72-year-old ballpark for the first time
in Cubs history, said he was satisfied.
   ``I am extremely pleased that the Tribune Co. has responded
positively to my firm commitment of assuring Chicago Cubs fans that
our National League team will stay in Chicago,'' the mayor said.
   Last week, the City Council voted to allow the Cubs to play
eight night games this year and 18 in each of the following years
until 2002. Wrigley is the only major-league ballpark without
lights.
   In a letter to the mayor, the team vowed to stay at Wrigley
Field ``as long as they have the ability to hold games and conduct
business as described in the ordinance, and events or circumstances
beyond the Cubs' control do make this, in their reasonable
judgment, either not practicable or not financially feasible.''
   The letter from John W. Madigan, executive vice president of the
Tribune Co, didn't specify what circumstances could prompt the team
to move.
   But Don Grenesko, Cubs executive vice president for business
operations, said over the weekend that the team wanted an escape
clause if voters banned alcohol at the park.
   Wrigley Field neighbors fearful of unruly fans and traffic
problems night games could bring have threatened to launch a
campaign to vote the precinct dry.
