<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Politics     03-03 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Politics,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Assembly Opens Special Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly opened a special
session Wednesday to try to clear the way for general elections.
Two opposition parties meanwhile squabbled over a plan to merge.
   The one-week special session, the third this year, was called to
adopt new laws governing legislative elections, expected in
mid-April.
   Whether the assembly would be able to adopt new election laws
was not clear, because rival political parties could not agree on
the issue.
   The adoption of new laws is necessary to hold the general
elections.
   Efforts to merge two opposition parties appeared successful last
week but snagged on the role that Kim Dae-jung should play in a new
integrated party to be formed.
   The opposition agreed to join forces to mount a united front in
the coming voting for Parliament following its presidential defeat
last December, .
   Since Kim Young-sam resigned the presidency of the main
opposition Reunfication Democratic Party last month, pressure has
been building on Kim Dae-jung to resign as well as chief of his
Party for Peace and Democracy.
   Kim Dae-jung said he would step aside if the opposition unites,
but he indicated this week he would continue to remain active.
   Fifty-three Reunification legislators Wednesday accused Kim
Dae-jung of reneging on his promise to resign and demanded he take
a back seat in the united opposition party.
   Kim Dae-jung's followers proposed Wednesday that the new party
be led by the two Kims.
   Kim Young-sam objected to the idea, but said he would be
satisfied with being an ordinary party member. He said he wanted to
atone for the opposition defeat last December.
   The two Kims divided 56 percent of the opposition vote in South
Korea's first direct presidential elections in 16 years. That gave
the victory to Roh Tae-woo of the governing Democratic Justice
Party, who received a 36.6 percent plurality.
   Since that defeat, both Kims have been under public pressure to
retire from politics.
