<DOCNO> AP880303-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     03-03 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Wenceslas Square,' A Play by Larry Shue, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some remembrances make for odd, inconclusive
theater.
   Take ``Wenceslas Square,'' which opened Wednesday at the New
York Shakespeare Festival Public Theater. It's a fragmented memory
play about an American theater professor who returns to Prague
several years after the 1968 Soviet invasion and discovers what
repression can do to people who have tasted freedom.
   That seems like an unlikely subject for Larry Shue, best known
as the author of ``The Foreigner'' and ``The Nerd,'' two cheerfully
goofy comedies that triumphed in New York despite critical sniffles
from the press.
   Shue, who died in a plane crash in 1985, apparently based the
play on an incident in his own life. The comedy-drama focuses on
the professor and his assistant, a young photographer who has
agreed to shoot pictures for the scholar's book. Shue was the
photographer, and he tells the story in flashback.
   The episodic play seems unfinished, not completely worked out,
as it follows the professor, played by Jonathan Hadary, and his
assistant (Bruce Norris) during their Eastern European adventure.
The duo meet and interview a variety of theater and government
people, all played either by Victor Garber or Dana Ivey.
   Individual scenes in ``Wenceslas Square'' are often effective
and very funny, but transitions are choppy. Maybe that's why
director Jerry Zaks utilizes a turntable set that keeps the play on
a dizzy merry-go-round course.
   Shue tries to show the accommodation the Czechs made to
restrictions on their personal and artistic lives. It's something
the professor and his assistant gradually perceive, but the evening
never builds to a dramatic pay-off. One wonders what the play would
have been like if Shue had been able to do some rewriting.
   Still there are some wonderful, gentle comic moments, many of
them provided by an impeccable cast. Garber has a delightful scene
as a befuddled Czech trying to decipher the vagaries of the English
language, while Ivey is appealing as the man's sympathetic,
ever-helpful wife.
   The play doesn't so much end as just stop when the professor and
his assistant complete their two-week stay. You really don't know
much more about them after their visit than before. At least Shue
has made the trip a modestly amusing journey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-USMilitary     03-03 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Military,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan To Increase Support For U.S. Base Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and the United States agreed Wednesday that
the Tokyo government will pay a larger share of the costs of
running U.S. military bases in Japan.
   Under the new agreement, signed by Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno
and the acting U.S. Embassy charge d'affaires, L. Desaix Anderson,
Japan will pay all benefits and allowances for the 21,000 Japanese
base workers, including transportation, housing and retirement
expenses.
   The United States pays the salaries of the Japanese workers.
   The pact will replace a year-old accord and boost Japan's share
of allowances for Japanese base workers from a maximum 50 percent
to 100 percent by 1991, the U.S. Embassy said in a statement.
   Japan's financial contribution will account for about 40 percent
of the annual cost of maintaining U.S. bases in Japan once the
protocol is fully implemented, the statement said.
   Tokyo and Washington signed an initial accord in January 1987,
requiring Japan to cover up to half the expenditures for Japanese
workers at U.S. bases. Wednesday's agreement amends that pact.
   In fiscal 1987, Japan set aside $128 million to offset costs for
Japanese employees at the bases. With the yen's rise of about 100
percent against the dollar over the past three years, however, the
cost to the United States of maintaining the Japanese base workers
has skyrocketed.
   The new agreement follows a pledge by Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita during a visit to Washington in January to increase
Japan's contribution toward maintaining U.S. forces in Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0128EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerResearch     03-03 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Research,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philanthropist to Head New Fund-Raising Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE H. BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire philanthropist Armand Hammer said he
will spearhead a campaign to raise $1 billion a year to wipe out
cancer by the year 2000.
   The extra capital ``would provide the resources we need to cure
cancer in the next 10 years,'' Hammer said in a telephone interview
from Los Angeles on Wednesday.
   The money will go directly to research at the National Cancer
Institute in Bethesda, Md., said Hammer, a non-practicing physician
who turns 90 in May. ``There will be no overhead charges,'' he said.
   The institute's annual research budget is $1.4 billion.
   Hammer, chairman and chief executive officer of Occidental
Petroleum Corp., already has donated $100,000 for cancer research
and has received commitments from nine other industrialists to do
the same.
   About 475,000 people died last year from cancer. The death rate
from most major forms of the disease has improved little over the
past 15 years.
   However, the director of the National Cancer Institute, Dr.
Vincent DeVita, expressed guarded optimism on whether the extra
dollars would lead to a cure. At the very least, it would ``make a
dent,'' DeVita said.
   With the help of a mass media campaign, the drive will seek to
raise $500 million in private contributions, which Hammer hopes
will be matched in federal funds. Some congressmen already have
agreed to support the effort, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
