<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Gadhafi     03-03 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Gadhafi,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Announces Amnesty; Reaches Out to United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi said Wednesday he
was releasing all Libyan prisoners except those accused of plotting
with foreign countries, the official Libyan news agency JANA
reported.
   JANA also said that Gadhafi announced he would reach out to the
United States once it changed its policies toward his country.
   Both statements came in a speech to the General People's
Congress, the North African country's highest policy-making body,
according to JANA dispatches monitored in Rome.
   Gadhafi said about 400 prisoners would be freed from the Tripoli
prison on Thursday and the prison would be torn down, JANA said.
   Among those being freed are prisoners who plotted to assassinate
Gadhafi before and after he seized power in 1969, he was quoted as
saying.
   ``I forgive them regardless of the sentences passed against
them,'' the colonel was quoted as saying.
   The amnesty does not cover those ``accused of treason by linking
themselves with foreign powers that have tried to use force to
arrive at things of their own,'' JANA quoted Gadhafi as saying.
There are less than 100 such prisoners, he said.
   It was not clear where these remaining prisoners would be kept
if the Tripoli prison is demolished.
   According to JANA, Gadhafi also announced abolishment of
``extraordinary trials'' and said all cases will be referred to a
``people's court'' run by the People's Congress.
   Gadhafi's regime gained a reputation over the years as being
ruthless toward political opponents. Numerous Libyan dissidents
were assassinated abroad and his regime periodically televised
public executions for alleged treason.
   Last Septemer, the human rights organization Amnesty
International said it received reports of Libyan prisoners being
beaten on the soles of their feet or hung upside down from a perch
and beaten. It said it received no reply to its appeals for 75
political prisoners it says are being held in Libya.
   On relations with the United States, Gadhafi was quoted as
saying the ``animosity will remain'' until the United States
``recognizes our right to live, respects us over our own land and
asks for cooperation with us as equal. And then we shall stretch
our hands to it.''
   He said the United States denies rights to Libyans because it
recogniezes only a 12-mile territorial limit in the U-shaped Gulf
of Sidra. Libya claims the entire gulf.
   U.S. and Libyan forces clashed in the gulf in March 1986, and a
month later U.S. jets bombed Libya in retaliation for Libya's
alleged involvement in international terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
