<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv03   03-03 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 03,0646</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday, March 3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Is Everything Under Control?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In conducting a ``decision-makers poll,'' an
investment house economist asks: ``Overall, is it fair to say that
the Federal budget process is out of control?''
   Fair? While it appears that some experts can't decide on an
answer, that shouldn't deter anyone having a casual acquaintance
with numbers from offering an independent view.
   Consider:
   _The budget has been out of balance for about two decades, and a
president dedicated to budget balance not only hasn't reached that
goal in two terms, but has suffered the worst imbalances of any
president in history.
   _The president now proposes a budget in deficit by $129.5
billion for fiscal 1989, while the Congressional Budget Office
disagrees with that figure to the tune of $46.5 billion more.
   _The failure of Congress and the White House to agree on
deficit-cutting forced creation of a National Economic Commission
to devise some answers by March 1, 1989 _ in effect postponing any
decision until then.
   Well? Is it or isn't it out of control?
   If you agree that it is, you might agree on several other
aspects of government that seem equally in disarray. Taxes, for
example.
   Does the United States have a tax policy?
   If it does, you might experience difficulty in finding it among
all th changes, revisions, amendments, differing opinions,
revocations, increases, decreases, inconsistencies, exceptions and
the like.
   Between 1964 and 1986, Congress enacted 16 major tax bills and
dozens of lesser bills. In 1981, the Economic Recovery Tax Act
promised big corporate tax reductions. By 1986, other acts had
turned it into an increase.
   Such tortured turns provoked the Tax Foundation to comment that
``the history of major tax legislation since 1964 represents a
seesaw of revenue decreases and increases without any apparent
consistency...''
   Perhaps as confusing as any tax event _ and serving to abet the
notion that something is out of control _ is the Tax Reform Act of
1986.
   That act was widely publicized as allegedly cutting, simplifying
and making taxes fairer. Somehow, taxpayers are now finding, a
tax-rate cut can mean higher taxes. Simpler? No, more complex.
Fairer? Debatable.
   A sense of lost control is also impressed on the mind of any
observer of the federal bureaucracy, the cutting of which was a
keystone of the platform on which Ronald Reagan was elected to the
White House.
   You probably recall the promise: Power would be transferred from
the public to the private sector, allowing private enterprise to
grow as government shrank. Government would get off the backs of
people.
   But what happened, in spite of good intentions on the part of
the most powerful political figures in the nation, was very
different. The bureaucracy spread and swallowed some of the private
sector's energy.
   A study just released by The Conference Board, largely business
supported, shows that major companies must devote more _ not less _
attention to federal regulatory and legislative issues since the
Reagan administration took office.
   More than 80 percent of the 300 companies surveyed stated that
both the number and importance of federal issues have climbed since
the beginning of 1981. Nearly half say these issues have increased
greatly.
   ``Sobering and instructive,'' says Seymour Lusterman, who
authored the study.
   Most corporate leaders, he observes, ``have come to believe that
many of the forces behind their regulatory and legislative concerns
are outside the control of any administration.''
   Quite sobering and instructive _ and provocative too. It makes
many people wonder just how and by whom power is exerted, or
whether it is exerted instead by a system out of control.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for PMs Thursday, March 3.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0857EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-FrenchBirdHunters Adv08   03-03 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-French Bird Hunters, Adv 08,0732</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs March 8 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>French Bird Trappers Prepare for a Season of Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FIONA GLEIZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunters in rural France are mobilizing in support
of their traditonal use of a glue-like substance, cages and nets to
trap birds _ methods banned throughout Western Europe since 1979.
   Hunting groups say the centuries-old practices should be
protected as part of France's national heritage. They maintain that
the impact on bird flocks is trivial.
   ``There is an anger which is in danger of exploding,'' said
Henry Sallenave, president of the regional hunting federation in
the Landes in southwestern France.
   ``These are simple people living in contact with the land and
they don't understand the measures, since less than 1 percent of
the migrating (bird) population is taken.''
   Bird protectionists succeeded in 1979 in getting the European
Economic Community to ban such practices as the ``gluaux'' (gluey,
lime-smeared sticks), ``matoles'' (a cage) and ``pantes'' (a
spring-triggered net) to such birds as thrushes, skylarks, wood
pigeons and swallows.
   France agreed to the EEC directive, but contends that an
exception in the agreement for ``judicious exploitation'' of small
numbers of birds covers these traditional French hunting practices.
   So trapping with gluaux has continued, although only in certain
rural districts of southeastern France.
   French officials argue that the ban should not be allowed to
wipe out a small, but significant part of living French history.
   ``France is acting within the spirit of the EEC directive,
because very few birds are taken,'' said Gerard Tendron, a
technical adviser at the French Environment Ministry.
   But the EEC Commission disagreed and brought France before the
European Court in Luxembourg. A ruling is expected sometime this
spring.
   In similar cases brought against Belgium, West Germany, Italy
and the Netherlands, the European Court decided in favor of the ban.
   Premier Jacques Chirac of France has promised French hunters
that the court rules in favor of the ban this time, he will try to
have the EEC directive changed so that it does not apply to
traditional hunting.
   When the thrushes begin to migrate in early October, hunters
plant tall sticks smeared with bird lime, a kind of natural glue
extracted from the holly bush. When the birds land on the sticks,
their feet stick to them.
   Few of the birds caught this way are killed and eaten. Most are
put into cages and used to attract larger flocks that then are
killed by hunters with shotguns.
   Hunting in this way is still allowable but limited to 30 sticks
per hunter. Bird protectionists contend, however, that it is next
to impossible to police the limitations in rural regions.
   In southwestern France, skylarks are trapped with the matole, a
cage perched on three small sticks that falls on top of a bird.
   Wood pigeons and swallows are trapped in the Landes and the
Pyrennees with pantes, huge nets that operate on a system of
springs to trap the birds inside.
   Whole villages often turn out to shoo birds toward the nets set
up in the fields.
   Hunters claim these methods do no harm. Sallenave described the
birds trapped as ``a natural renewable capital'' and said their
methods have little impact on the bird populations concerned.
   Practitioners of the gluaux method say they take only 75,000
thrushes a year while hunters with guns kill about 13 million
annually. The national hunting federation estimates that 30,000 of
the 1.8 million hunters in France use the old-fashioned systems.
   Antoine Reille of the Bird Protection League said his group
opposes these traditional hunting methods on he grounds that they
are not selective and a hunter may not always be able to recognize
a protected bird and free it as he is required to do so by law.
   He and other protectionists say protected robins and ortolans
often fall prey to the trappers. In the Landes, ortolans are a
prized culinary delicacy, eaten whole.
   The protectionists also say that by the time a hunter frees a
protected bird from the gluaux stick, its feathers are so
impregnated by the gluey substance that they fall out in a few days
and the bird dies of cold.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs March 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
