<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-MusicSpecials Adv04   03-03 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Music Specials, Adv 04,0767</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, March 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Willie Nelson, Barry Manilow Have Music Specials on CBS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're heavily into the Bon Jovi and the
Beastie Boys, you're in probably the only demographic group that
won't find something to like in two widely divergent music specials
offered by CBS.
   On Saturday, Willie Nelson is host of his own network special,
``Willie Nelson, Texas Style,'' a tribute to his home state which
he reveals in a soothing hour of country, rock and blues music
combined with an affectionate travelogue to some of his favorite
Lone Star places.
   Then on Monday, Barry Manilow pays homage to jazz and big band
music in ``Barry Manilow: Big Fun on Swing Street,'' set in an
imaginary neighborhood of break dancers, saxophone players and
blues singers, where the '40s meet the '80s.
   Manilow wasn't, shall we say, successful in his last network
venture, the 1985 CBS musical movie ``Copacabana,'' which marked
his acting debut. This time, he sticks to the music. There is no
dialogue in ``Swing Street,'' a bluesy, jazzy, coolly evocative,
extended music video.
   ``There's no dumb sketches on it. We did that on purpose,'' said
Manilow, during a recent break in the midst of his two-year tour.
``Bruce and Jack and I sat down and wrote a conceptual hour that
takes the viewer on a trip down this imaginary place called Swing
Street, during which we meet all the characters who inhabit Swing
Street, and they are played by the guests. There's no talking
except for the voiceovers, and it's all music, because I wanted to
do a music special with a capital M.''
   Bruce and Jack are Manilow's collaborators, Bruce Sussman and
Jack Feldman. Their concept also produced an album, ``Swing
Street,'' that features the performers on the special, plus Stan
Getz, who was in the hospital when the special was taped, Manilow
said.
   Sussman suggested that this kind of high-style music special is
the wave of the future on network television, which still tends to
rely on the standard host-guest-song-sketch kind of variety program.
   ``One of the problems with variety television is that MTV has
forever changed variety television, and it hasn't responded to
that,'' Sussman said. ``This is something else, it's not MTV, but
something that certainly has been influenced by that development.''
   ``Who knows whether this is going to make it rating-wise,'' said
Manilow, ``but what was definitely not making it was somebody
standing up there saying, `My next guest is Dionne Warwick, my next
sketch is,' you know. This sort of had a point of view, even if it
was odd.''
   The special includes Manilow songs such as ``Hey Mambo'' and
``Black and Blue,'' but also standards such as ``Summertime'' and
``Stardust.''
   Manilow's guests are jazz singers Carmen McRae and Diane Schuur
_ her duet with Manilow on ``Summertime'' is a show-stopper _
saxophonists Gerry Mulligan, Tom Scott and Dana Robbins, bass
player Stanley Clarke and singer Phyllis Hyman, plus the vocal
groups Full Swing and Kid Creole and the Coconuts.
   Nelson's special is as bright and sunny as Manilow's is dark and
smoky, with footage of Nelson walking around his Hill Country home,
playing host to his band members and friends on his golf course,
riding his bicycle down to Mona's Yacht Club for a game of dominoes
with the locals, and floating down the Rio Grande with jazz
guitarist Jackie King.
   Next door to the golf course is Willie's own recording studio _
dubbed ``Cut 'n' Putt'' _ where Bruce Hornsby does a session. Ray
Charles joins Willie at Alley Oop's on East Sixth Street in Austin,
and Asleep at the Wheel jams with him at Carl's Corner, a truck
stop.
   Willie also takes a sentimental tour of his boyhood home of
Abbott, Texas, where his sister Bobbie recalls their grandmother
tying young Willie up to keep him from running off.
   ``She staked him just like she did the cow,'' Bobbie laughs.
   ``That didn't stop me from running away,'' Willie recalls. ``It
slowed me down some.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   BLAKE HONORED _ Director Blake Edwards will be honored at the
second annual American Comedy Awards with the Lifetime Creative
Achievement Award. Edwards made such films as ``The Pink Panther,''
``Victor-Victoria, ``10,'' and more recently ``Blind Date'' and
``That's Life.'' The awards show will be broadcast May 17 on ABC.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, March 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1208EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BusinessMirror Adv04   03-03 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 04,0651</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday March 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Basic Economic Change?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Have Americans really changed their spending
habits?
   It is still too early to say, but that might be one of the
developing consequences of the great stock market crash of October.
   Before the crash it was common to hear about the foolish
spending habits of ordinary Americans. Among other criticisms, for
example, it was said that they were living beyond their means,
financing their lifestyle with credit.
   At one point late last year the savings rate fell under 2
percent, a record low. As personal income stagnated, the use of
credit rose.
   It was perhaps the live-for-now consumer style that best
exemplified the time. Jobs were plentiful and money was available,
and enticements of the marketplace left little time for worrying
about future recessions.
   Then came the crash. And while statistics show that only a small
percentage of American households had any direct ownership of
stocks, the suddenness of the decline seemed to shock them into an
awareness of sudden dangers.
   Confidence shrank. Immediately following the crash, the
University of Michigan survey recorded a sharp rise to 45 percent
in the percentage of families expecting bad times financially. Only
38 percent foresaw good times.
   Consumer spending slowed. In fact, in the fourth quarter it
declined from the previous quarter at a 3 percent annual rate.
Motor vehicle and parts purchases fell 36 percent. Furniture and
household equipment dipped 3 percent.
   People even cut into their food budgets. Spending on food fell 2
percent, clothing and shoes 7 percent and gasoline and oil 1
percent. And for the most part, that pattern extended into the
first month of this year.
   Meanwhile, personal saving as a percentage of disposable income
averaged 4.8 percent in the fourth quarter, compared to a
third-quarter rate of 2.8 percent. And the higher savings rate
continued into January.
   While it cannot be attributed to the crash, evidence of another
turnabout was becoming clear: The American economy was relying less
on consumption and more on production, a turnabout that had been
awaited for two decades.
   During that long period, Americans seemed willing, able and
happy to hawk their jewels _ personal, industrial and, some critics
maintained, even those of a spiritual nature. It was a time of
great material success, and greed.
   The danger, Americans were told throughout that two-decade
period, was that no nation could continue to consume more than it
produced without wasting its economic power. But consumption
continued nevertheless at every level of life.
   Lately, however, the scene appears to have changed. The growth
of consumption has waned in relation to that of production.
Manufactured goods, not just agricultural products, are being
exported. Money is being saved. And people have a wise eye on the
future.
   The Michigan survey now shows that confidence has returned to
where it was before the crash _ but with a big difference. The
confidence expressed is mainly about the near term, not for the
more distant horizon.
   What appears to have happened is that families are more cautious
judges; they feel safe in expressing confidence over the next year
because they understand the forces at work. They simply don't see a
recession coming.
   But, unlike the pre-crash confidence readings, consumers are
less certain about the next five years. That suggests realism;
nobody can say what might happen five years ahead. That being so,
overconfidence is foolishness.
   The new attitude appears healthier. Goals appear to be more
realistic. Tempered by the crash, people seem aware that an
economic quake is possible, and that the time to deal with the
possibility is now _ not after it happens.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday March 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1516EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-India-Boy-GirlTest Adv09   03-03 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Boy-Girl Test, Adv 09,0766</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Boy-Girl Tests' Encourage Abortions of Female Fetuses in India</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Repeat to restore dropped material at end.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEEMA SIROHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vaid Rani Chawla has her dearest wish.
She is going to have a son, after two daughters.
   It means an end to the biting taunts of her mother-in-law and
neighbors. She will gain ``honor'' by having a boy.
   ``I wanted people to say that a son is born in Chawlas' house.
One son is a must,'' said Mrs. Chawla, who now is six months
pregnant.
   She knows for sure it's a boy because she had amniocentesis, a
test many Indian women use to learn the sex of their unborn. If the
test shows a girl is on the way, many women have abortions.
   The practice is drawing fire from social activists who say it is
a perverted use of modern science to perpetuate age-old social
prejudices against women.
   The test is intended to detect congenital deformities, but it
has come to be known as the ``boy-girl test'' in India.
   Widely used in developed countries, amniocentesis is a procedure
in which a small sample of the amniotic fluid that bathes the fetus
in the womb is withdrawn by a long hypodermic needle.
   The fluid contains cells that have flaked off the fetus. The
chromosomes in these cells can be examined for evidence of birth
defects, but they also tell the sex of the fetus.
   ``Boy or Girl _ know the sex of the unborn child,'' say
advertisements by clinics in Indian newspapers.
   Mrs. Chawla, 32, shyly admitted she would have had an abortion
if her test had proved ``negative'' _ meaning another girl.
   There are no definite numbers on how many abortions occur after
such tests. One authoritative study said 78,000 female fetuses were
aborted from 1978 to 1983 nationwide following sex-determination
tests. Abortions are legal in India, a country of 780 million
people, as part of the government's population-control program.
   While the issue has generated demands for banning amniocentesis
clinics, doctors who run the lucrative businesses say it is better
to abort a female fetus than to subject an unwanted child to a life
of suffering.
   ``People are willing to keep producing children until they get a
son,'' said K.K. Loomba, who runs New Delhi's most popular boy-girl
testing clinic. ``Tell me, is it not better to let them have a
choice so they don't have six daughters before they have a son?
   ``Either you should educate the masses that there is no
difference between sons and daughters or give them a choice. This
test, in fact, is helping the population-control program of the
government.''
   But Vibhuti Patel, a women's rights activist from Bombay,
counters: ``By this logic it is better to kill the poor rather then
let them suffer poverty and deprivation.''
   Both sides agree that the answer lies in social education to try
to end entrenched anti-female attitudes.
   In India, sons are looked upon as potential wage earners and as
support for parents in old age. Girls are considered a constant
burden on resources, and money is needed for their dowry at the
time of marriage.
   A developing consumer society has increased demands for dowry
from the traditional jewelry to cars, refrigerators, even houses.
   This has given rise to ``bride burning,'' the killing of young
wives by greedy husbands and in-laws _ usually by setting the women
ablaze with kerosene from kitchen stoves and saying it was an
accident. At least two women die such fiery deaths every day in New
Delhi.
   ``There are no short-term solutions to the problems of women in
India,'' said Madhu Kishwar, editor of Manushi, India's only
feminist magazine. ``Banning amniocentesis is not the answer
because it only will go underground and there will be no
monitoring.''
   Ashok Kumar, a businessman waiting in a clinic while his wife
was being tested, expressed the attitude of many Indians.
   ``We have three daughters,'' he said. ``They will get married
and go away while a son will carry my name forward.''
   Besides, he added, old people and neighbors constantly bothered
his wife about it.
   ``We were made to feel that something was missing.''
   He said that even though he and his wife cannot afford four
children, they decided to take another chance for a son.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, March 9</NOTE>
