<2ND_LINE>AM-Unwanted Hero, Adv 07 - 2 Takes,1155</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Vietnam Veteran Rests In Peace At Last</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   It is estimated that up to 1 percent of
Americans suffer from Post Traumatic Stress Disorder, a mental
illness brought on by especially harrowing experiences. While not
limited to a single group, the disorder afflicts as many as half a
million Vietnam veterans. This is one veteran's story.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was before dawn, still dark in the cemetery
where Vietnam veteran John Coughlin was paying another visit to the
graves of two friends. Suddenly, his mind flashed back to Vietnam
where he'd flirted with death, where his legs had been torn by
shrapnel, where he had earned three Purple Hearts.
   Though it was now 1978, long after his return home from battle,
he suddenly sensed that he was under attack. It was May 8, near the
anniversary of a battle in which many of his friends were killed,
and suddenly the Viet Cong seemed all around again.
   He grabbed a shotgun from his car and fired off 14 shots,
yelling insults at the imagined enemy. ``I'm going to get every one
of you that killed my buddies,'' he vowed.
   Some of the shots struck the back of a police station across the
street from the cemetery in Quincy, just south of Boston.
   As police gingerly surrounded him, he shouted, ``I don't want
any hassle. Just leave me alone. I want to die just like Billy and
Jo Jo.''
   John Coughlin died last Nov. 5 alone, save his war souvenirs and
his American and Marine flags. The medical examiner said he died of
an overdose of doxepin, an antidepressant drug. Friends said he
died of a broken heart. He was 42.
   His legacy was that tragic episode in the cemetery that brought
a new awareness to the plight of as many as half a million Vietnam
veterans suffering from Post Traumatic Stress Disorder, the delayed
trauma of combat.
   Coughlin was the first Vietnam veteran to successfully use the
syndrome as a defense against criminal charges.
   Charged with unlawful possession of a firearm, he was allowed to
serve two years on probation while undergoing psychiatric
treatment, and the charges were eventually dropped.
   ``I was convinced that regardless which tab you put on it, there
was a mental illness there and no justice would be served in
prosecuting him,'' said Gerald M. Kirby, a former assistant
district attorney who handled the case. ``Fortunately nobody had
been hurt.''
   Although Coughlin was not a crusader for veterans' rights, his
attorney, Lawrence Siskind, said the court's action helped give
recognition to Post Traumatic Stress Disorder as a serious mental
illness.
   ``This was a court that said there's a problem,'' Siskind said.
``It wasn't just peace groups or veterans groups marching on
Washington anymore. Now somebody could say the VA should do
something, because here it was accepted.''
   Dr. Ted Nadelson, chief of psychiatry services at the Boston VA
Medical Center, said Coughlin ``was kind of a leading edge of a
wedge'' that led to that recognition of the illness.
   Dr. Terence M. Keane, director of the PTSD Center at the VA
Center, said the disorder has been treated for at least 100 years,
but it wasn't until 1980 that the American Psychiatric Association
gave it greater recognition and status by assigning the name.
   In 1981, the VA ruled that veterans could receive
service-connected disability payments if they were diagnosed as
having the stress disorder no matter when it developed after
discharge. Other types of service-connected disabilities must be
claimed within a year of discharge.
   Coughlin was cursed with each of the ills of the disorder _
flashbacks, nightmares, intense depression and anxiety, difficulty
in relationships and the use of alcohol and drugs.
   Vietnam was so difficult for him, and yet, like other veterans,
he couldn't give it up, said Nadelson. ``That is an important issue
for Vietnam veterans, the attachment to it,'' he said.
   Coughlin felt guilt about surviving when friends had been
killed. In the last years of his life, he lived in the past among
his war memorabilia.
   He told friends and relatives a few days before his death that
he wanted to pull his life together. He said he planned to get a
job and move from the room he rented in a three-story rooming house
in Boston where a dozen other tenants lived, some of them, like
him, down on their luck.
   His room resembled a Vietnam bunker, its shades drawn and its
walls painted black. He kept a large American flag on one wall over
the windows. Two smaller American flags were folded away. On the
wall behind his bed hung a Marine flag. Cardboard boxes were filled
with Vietnam snapshots, including a few of Viet Cong bodies, and
newspaper articles on Vietnam, some about him.
   His proudest possession was an American flag his father gave him
when he returned home.
   ``I guess that was the first time my father was proud of me,
when I got decorated in Vietnam,'' he said with tears in his eyes
last July in an 18-minute interview videotaped in color with
Nadelson to help in understanding the stress disorder. He said that
the father of a friend of his had taken the place of his own
father, a businessman who was often busy working.
   Many troubling feelings remained with Coughlin up to his death,
Nadelson said.
   When he signed up for a second Vietnam tour, Coughlin said, it
was not just for flag and country. Part of it was rage.
   ``And liking it,'' he told the psychiatrist. ``Addictive. I'm
talking about killing, the feeling, the power.''
   Coughlin was nervous and emotional on the tape, at times shaking
and weeping. His comments were often disjointed and lacking
elaboration, and at times it was unclear what he meant. One of his
front teeth was missing and he wore a scraggly beard.
   He said he was scared when he first went to Vietnam.
   ``The first couple months there you're afraid. You see
everything. Then it doesn't matter after you see death so much. It
just doesn't matter. You don't allow yourself to have the feelings.
You numb out and then all of a sudden you're put back into people
where things are like it never happened.
   ``You experience life and death, the closeness ... And all of a
sudden you're put back into what they call a real world, a
supposedly civilized world, and you cannot cope. It's not that you
don't want to. It's that you're afraid to get close. You're afraid
to express feelings. The whole atmosphere of people not
understanding ...''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
