<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv06   03-03 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 06,0941</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Modern Broilers Involve More Than Chicken Feed, Says USDA Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Broiler chickens, you might say, have more
than kept abreast of the times, they have a leg up on most other
farming operations.
   Indeed, says an Agriculture Department report on the nation's
broiler industry, raising chickens these days ``seems more like a
factory assembly line'' than part of farming's livestock sector.
   Consider what has happened to broiler production and consumption
in the United States, remembering that the young birds were once
called frying chickens, or fryers, and were a seasonal treat for
most families.
   Now, broilers are everywhere and in many forms, packaged whole
or cut up; in specialized parts such as wings, legs and breasts;
ready to cook; even cooked, baked or barbecued. Not to mention all
the fast-food variations.
   ``This highly integrated, efficiency conscious industry
virtually exploded with growth after specialized broiler operations
emerged in the late 1930s and early 1940s,'' the report said.
``Unlike more diverse beef and hog industries, broiler production
is now dominated by a handful of operators, most of whom control
their products from incubation to retail.''
   When a hog or cattle producer has ``finished'' animals ready for
market, they are sold live to a slaughter plant, which in turn may
sell the carcasses at wholesale to other buyers. Eventually, the
beef and pork reaches consumers.
   But the broiler sector's first point of sale typically is not at
the farm, the report said. It's later when the slaughtered, cut up
or ready-to-cook birds are sold to wholesalers or retailers.
   The report is in the March issue of Farmline magazine published
by the department's Economic Research Service. Most of the article
is attributed to economist Lee Christensen.
   ``Improved genetics, better balanced rations and environmentally
controlled housing increased producers' efficiency in raising
chickens,'' the report said. ``This helped the industry produce
large amounts of economically priced product and capture a greater
portion of the market for meat.''
   Christensen cited some statistics to back up that assertion:
   _Growers turn out heavier birds in less time. A broiler weighing
3{ to 4{ pounds can be produced in 7 to 8 weeks, about half the 12
t0 14 weeks it took 30 years ago.
   _It takes only about 2 pounds of feed or less to grow a pound of
broiler, down from 4 pounds of feed to 1 pound of bird in the 1940s.
   _As a result, the average time it takes to raise a group of
birds, or brood, is nearly two weeks shorter than a decade ago,
allowing growers to produce an extra brood each year. Most turn out
more than six broods annually.
   ``Behind the increase in production has been a corresponding
rise in consumption,'' the report said. ``Much of it occurred while
meat consumption levels in general were climbing. Now, however,
overall meat consumption is leveling off, while broiler consumption
continues to rise.''
   The report added: ``In all, consumption grew more than 29-fold,
from about two pounds per person in 1940 to an estimated 60 pounds
in 1987.''
   As broilers became specialized, great shudders ran through the
poultry industry. Christensen said the independently owned
small-flock operations that marketed chickens through small
processing plants disappeared, giving way to a highly integrated
industry dominated by relatively few processors.
   Most of these firms, he said, are located in northeastern
Arkansas, northern Georgia and Alabama, central Missouri, eastern
Texas, the Delmarva Peninsula of Delaware and Maryland, North
Carolina and central California.
   ``In 1984, 134 firms _ operating 238 federally inspected plants
_ processed more than 4 billion birds weighing nearly 18 billion
pounds,'' Christensen said. ``The four largest firms during that
year operated 41 plants that slaughtered 33.7 percent of all the
broilers produced.''
   By comparison, he said, in 1964, 201 firms operated 320 plants
and slaughtered a third fewer chickens.
   A typical firm might include a hatchery, feed mill, processing
plant, and field service, management and marketing staffs, he said.
The birds are produced under contracts with growers who provide the
facilities and management. Typically, it takes 150 to 300 contracts
to provide a processor's annual needs.
   The farmer, or grower, also has experienced concentration. In
1982, the U.S. agricultural census showed 30,100 farms producing
broilers, down from 42,185 in 1959. But total output rose to 3.5
billion birds from 1.4 billion during the same period, with the
average rising to 116,844 birds in 1982 from 33,637 in 1959.
   Also, the number of broiler farms that each year sell more than
100,000 birds increased to 13,214 in 1982 and represented 89
percent of total production. In 1959, there were only 2,254 of the
large farms, and they accounted for less than 29 percent of total
output.
   Christensen said many problems remain, including cycles of
production and prices, and disease outbreaks. But chicken
consumption will probably continue to climb for some time, fueled
by a growing population and rising per capita consumption, perhaps
to 67 pounds by 1990 and 95 pounds per person by the turn of the
century, he said.
   The broiler industry, however, will not be easy for newcomers,
meaning that future growth will have to come from existing firms.
   ``New firms cannot afford to jump into the business of raising
chickens,'' Christensen said. ``The capital investment needed to
establish new broiler production and processing facilities is very
large, and would be undertaken only after careful analysis.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
