<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-03 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0517</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9 percent decline in new home sales in
January pushed sales activity to its slowest pace since the end of
the last recession.
   A downturn in housing often has been a harbinger of recession,
but analysts said Wednesday they believed falling mortgage rates
offered hope of a rebound in home sales in coming months.
   The Commerce Department said sales of new single-family homes
fell in January for the third consecutive month, dropping to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units. That was the
slowest pace since the last recession was ending in December 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private economists say the 0.6 percent decline
in orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods in January may
not be as serious as it first appears.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday orders for both durable
and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $212.6
billion in January, down $1.25 billion from December, when orders
rose 2 percent.
   It was the first setback in orders since a 1.4 percent drop in
August, but economists noted it reflected a swing in the volatile
transportation category.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. has agreed to
be acquired by R.H. Macy & Co., but an undaunted Campeau Corp.
proceeded with its rival bid for the nation's fifth largest
retailer.
   Federated and Macy said Wednesday they had signed a definitive
agreement under which Macy would begin a cash tender offer of
$74.50 a share for about 80 percent of Federated's 89.6 million
outstanding shares, or a total of $5.25 billion. Stock in the
merged company was included in the deal.
   Campeau said late Wednesday it was increasing its previously
announced $66 cash tender offer to an effective $68 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck & Co. says it was beginning a
three-year overhaul of its flagship merchandise group to make each
segment of its retail business more competitive.
   The restructuring, which will trim an undetermined number of
people from the merchandise group's management, will make Sears
stores more responsive to customer needs and wants, officials said
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks recorded their least profitable year
since the Great Depression in 1987, but a top federal regulator
sees better days ahead.
   The nation's federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7
billion last year on assets of $3 trillion, down from $17.5 billion
earnings in 1986, L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., said Wednesday. But he said the drop in
earnings was due entirely to large banks adding to reserves to
cover anticipated losses on Third World loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
says Congress should consider trimming Social Security and other
entitlement programs as it searches for ways to reduce the federal
budget deficit.
   Greenspan held out little hope Wednesday for major deficit
reductions in other areas _ although he proposed a 15-cent gasoline
tax.
</TEXT>
