<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-03 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Remain Weaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices remain weak amid confusion
over the true level of U.S. oil reserves.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, crude oil for April
delivery closed 5 cents lower at $15.67 per 42-gallon barrel
Wednesday. The contract had been down as much as 30 cents early in
the day.
   Among refined products, wholesale gasoline for April delivery
finished at 44.90 cents per gallon, off .39 cent.
   Near-term contracts for wholesale heating oil moved counter to
the market's bearish trend with the contract for April delivery
settling at 43.93 cents per gallon, up .46 cent.
   Analysts said reports of relatively low supplies of heating oil,
compared to levels of previous years, touched off the buying in
that sector.
   But in general, analysts said the market was confused by
discrepancies in official estimates of crude oil reserves as
compiled by the American Petroleum Institute and the Department of
Energy.
   A gap between the estimates issued in recent weeks has put
traders on the defensive.
   ``There is a scarcity of hard fundamental information right
now,'' observed William Byers, an analyst with Bear, Stearns & Co.
``We've come to the end of the heating seasons, and traders are
looking for something to hold on to.''
</TEXT>
