<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0312EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AFGOffer     03-03 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AFG Offer,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forstmann Little Offers To Top AFG Buyout Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFG Industries Inc., which last week agreed to
be taken private in a $940.5 million buyout by its chairman, is
being confronted by a competing, higher offer.
   The investment partnership Forstmann Little & Co. offered
Wednesday to acquire AFG for more than $33 cash a share, although
it conditioned the size of the premium on its ability to meet with
management and to review internal corporate information.
   AFG announced Feb. 25 that it had agreed to a two-step buyout
valued at $33 a share by a new company by a new company headed by
AFG founder and chairman, R.D. Hubbard.
   That offer would pay $33 cash a share for 94 percent of AFG's
stock and $33 per share in preferred stock or a combination of cash
and stock, for the rest of the shares. Based on AFG's 28.5 million
common shares outstanding, the offer had an indicated value of
$940.5 million.
   AFG rose 12{ cents to $32.25 a share Wednesday on the New York
Stock Exchange. The new offer was announced hours after the market
closed.
   Forstmann Little, which specializes in leveraged buyouts, stated
its offer was not conditioned on financing commitments being
obtained. It indicated its decision on the final size of its buyout
offer depended on ``prompt receipt and evaluation of information
regarding the company'' and on an opportunity to meet with AFG
management.
   The firm stated it was capitalized at about $2.7 billion, with
$2.4 billion of that available for future acquisitions.
   Irvine, Calif.-based AFG, one of North America's leading makers
of flat glass, declined through a spokesman to comment on the
proposal.
   Forstmann Little is in the process of acquiring Stanadyne Corp.,
a major manufacturer of plumbing fixtures and diesel fuel injection
systems, in an $820 million leveraged buyout.
   In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired mainly with
borrowed funds that are repaid with the target company's cash flow
or by the sale of its assets.
   The firm also has led buyouts of Lear Siegler Inc., Dr Pepper
Co., Sybron Corp. and Topps Co. Inc. in recent years.
   Analysts widely had expected competing offers to emerge for AFG,
deeming the Hubbard bid as relatively low.
   Hubbard's offer was made by Clarity Holdings Corp., a newly
formed company headed by Hubbard.
   AFG became well recognized outside its own industry in 1986 when
it launched an unsuccessful hostile takeover bid for Lear Siegler,
the aerospace and manufacturing conglomerate based in Santa Monica,
Calif.
   In 1987, AFG made an unsucessful hostile bid for Gencorp. of
Akron, Ohio, which formerly was known as General Tire & Rubber Co.
   Late last year, AFG announced it had agreed to purchase Ford
Motor Co.'s glass-making operations in Canada, which with annual
sales of about $150 million was the industry leader in that
country. No terms were disclosed for that deal, which closed early
this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0612EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated Bjt   03-03 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, Bjt,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retailer Agrees to Macy Acquisition, Campeau Pursuing Tender Offer</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS4; LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A merger agreement with R.H. Macy & Co. hasn't
dampened the frenzied bidding for Federated Department Stores Inc.,
as rival suitor Campeau Corp. has escalated its attempt to acquire
the nation's fifth-largest retailer.
   Following Federated's announcement Wednesday that it had agreed
to be acquired by Macy for cash and stock worth more than $5.45
billion, Campeau sharply revised its own all-cash proposal in an
attempt to woo Federated shareholders.
   Federated and Macy said they had a definitive agreement under
which Macy would acquire Federated and form a new company,
Macy's-Federated Inc. The deal still must be approved by
shareholders of both companies.
   Macy, the nation's 10th-largest retailer, operates 96 stores in
14 states, while Federated has 650 stores _ including such
department stores as Bloomingdale's, Filene's and Bullock's _ in 36
states.
   Under the agreement, Macy would pay $74.50 a share in cash for
about 80 percent of Federated's 89.6 million outstanding shares, or
a total of $5.25 billion. The remaining Federated shares would be
exchanged for stock in the new company.
   Campeau, which had been offering $68 a share _ totaling $6.1
billion _ for all of the outstanding Federated shares, responded by
changing its offer to $75 a share for 80 percent of Federated's
stock. In a subsequent merger, Campeau would pay $44 a share for
the remaining stock, giving the total deal a combined value of $68
per share, Campeau said.
   Campeau also said it would file suit to challenge $45 million in
fees that Federated agreed to pay Macy if their deal fell through.
If the fees are invalidated or withdrawn, Campeau said it would pay
$46.20 per share for the 20 percent of Federated shares remaining
after a merger.
   Campeau's new proposal expires at midnight EST March 15.
   The amended Campeau bid was announced after the close of trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, where Federated's stock fell $1 a
share to $66.75.
   Wall Street analysts said it was hard to predict what
Federated's shareholders would do, given the difficulty of putting
a value on the stock portion of Macy's offer.
   Macy is privately held, so it is difficult to know how much its
shares are worth.
   ``It's really tough to figure out which is a better deal,'' said
Joseph Ronning, a retail industry analyst with Brown Brothers
Harriman & Co.
   ``If you want immediate money, go for cash'' in the Campeau
offer, said Monroe H. Greenstein, an analyst with Bear Stearns &
Co. Inc.
   But in the long term, Greenstein said, he considered the Macy
bid better because it offered better potential for future growth
for Federated.
   No matter who ends up controlling Federated, the new owner is
expected to sell the company's Gold Circle discount stores and
Ralphs supermarkets.
   Among Cincinnati-based Federated's department stores are the
Bloomingdale's, Burdine's, Filene's, I. Magnin., Rich's, Abraham &
Straus and Lazarus chains.
   Either Macy or Campeau were expected to sell several of those
chains if they acquired Federated. Abraham and Straus and Rich's
were considered likely candidates for a sale by Macy, because they
are direct competitors with Macy stores in New York and Atlanta,
respectively.
   Under the Macy agreement, Federated management would have a
strong voice in the new company, filling 40 percent of the seats on
its board of directors.
   However, Federated Chairman Howard Goldfeder, 61, said at a news
conference Wednesday he would resign after helping Macy Chairman
Edward Finkelstein implement the merger.
   Goldfeder said he expects to be paid $3.06 million when he
leaves the company under a ``golden parachute'' severance agreement
approved by Federated's board of directors. Similar payments are
due other top Federated officers.
   In deciding to merge with Macy, the Federated board had
considered the $68 a share Campeau merger offer as well as an
indication from Campeau that the offer could be increased to $69.50
under certain unspecified conditions, Macy and Federated said.
   The companies stated that Federated's board had turned down
Campeau's alternative $66-a-share tender offer as inadequate, but
it did not characterize the $68 and $69.50 bids.
   Federated refused to elaborate on the statement, and Macy
referred all questions on the board's discussion to Federated.
   New York-based Macy was taken private by a management group in a
$3.6 billion leveraged buyout in 1986. Its stores rang up $5.21
billion in sales during the fiscal year ended last Aug. 1.
   Campeau, through its Allied Stores division, owns the Jordan
Marsh, Stern's, Ann Taylor and Maas Brothers chains.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
