<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0623EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated-History     03-03 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated-History,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Histories of Federated, Macy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Federated Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. traces its
roots to Columbus, Ohio, where German immigrant Simon Lazarus Sr.
opened a men's clothing store in 1848.
   Since then, the business has evolved into the nation's fifth
largest general retailer with more than 650 department stores,
supermarkets and specialty and discount stores.
   The store opened by Lazarus developed into F&R Lazarus Co., a
department store chain.
   In 1929, Fred Lazarus Jr. and Simon Lazarus, grandsons of the
company founder, formed Federated Department Stores with Filene's
in Boston and Abraham & Straus in Brooklyn. Bloomingdale's in New
York joined three months later.
   Today, the company's divisions also include Bullock's,
Burdine's, Foley's, I. Magnin and Rich's department stores; Main
Street and Children's Place specialty stores; and Gold Circle
discount stores and Ralphs supermarkets.
   Federated was based in Columbus for its first 16 years, acting
as a holding company for its founders. It moved its headquarters to
Cincinnati near the end of World War II and became an operating
company.
   The company rang up sales of $11 billion last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.H. Macy & Co. Inc., whose holdings include the
largest store in the world, returned to private ownership in early
1986 when a management group bought the nation's 10th biggest
general retailer for $3.58 billion.
   That has been the biggest acquisition of a retailer, although
the deal will fall to second if Macy succeeds in its bid to acquire
Federated Department Stores Inc. for $5.25 billion in cash plus
securities.
   Macy is widely known for its rivalry with its now defunct New
York competitor, Gimbel's department store, and as the subject of
the perennial Christmas movie favorite ``Miracle on 34th Street.''
The movie centered on Macy's popular Thanksgiving Day parade, which
celebrates the arrival of Santa Claus at Macy's flagship store on
New York's Herald Square each year.
   Started in 1858 by Rowland Hussey Macy, a former Nantucket
whaler who had failed at several earlier attempts in the retailing
business, the first Macy store in downtown Manhattan sold fancy
goods and stationery items.
   The company was acquired in 1896 by Isadore and Nathan Straus,
and it began selling stock to the public in 1927 as it expanded
into a nationwide operation.
   Macy operates 96 stores in 14 states, including Macy's
department stores and Aeropostale, Charter Club and Morgan Taylor's
Fantasy specialty stores.
   Its Macy's store at Herald Square in New York has 2.151 million
square feet of space, making it the world's largest store and as
big as some shopping centers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
