<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Electronics     03-03 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Electronics,0254</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 6 a.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Trade Group: U.S. Electronics Imports Outpaced Exports Again In
1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States continued to import more
electronics than it exported last year, although exports increased
at the fastest pace since 1980, the Electronic Industries
Association said today.
   Exports of electronic products grew to $40 billion last year, 20
percent over the $33.4 billion in 1986, while imports rose to
nearly $57.9 billion, up 15 percent from $50.3 billion in 1986, the
trade group said.
   Peter F. McCloskey, the group's president, said a lower dollar,
improved quality and aggressive marketing are making U.S. exports
more competitive in the world marketplace.
   In 1980, exports rose 21 percent over the previous year, while
imports rose 13 percent. But between 1981 and 1986, the increase in
imports outpaced the rise in exports, the association said.
   The trade group also said its analysis of Commerce Department
figures showed Canada was the No. 1 importer of U.S. electronics
last year, buying more than $5 billion worth. The United Kingdom
ranked second at $3.9 billion, Japan was third with $3.8 billion
and West Germany was fourth at $3.1 billion.
   Japan continued to top the list of foreign suppliers of
electronic products to the United States, with sales of nearly $25
billion last year, the group said. It was followed by Taiwan with
nearly $5.6 billion in sales, Korea with $4.3 billion and Singapore
with $4.0 billion.
</TEXT>
