<DOCNO> AP880303-0315 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0613EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ImportWoes Bjt   03-03 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Import Woes, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Import Car Sales Start Suffering from Higher Prices</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT5 of March 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years of price increases are beginning to
take their toll on foreign car sales, as buyers taking another look
at American models find improved cars with stickers as much as
$2,000 lower than comparable imports.
   Automakers in Japan and Western Europe have been forced to raise
prices to compensate for the plummeting dollar, which has fallen 50
percent against their currencies since 1985.
   While the European companies felt the bite sooner, industry
analysts said Japanese car sales also appear to be softening,
particularly for smaller companies and Nissan, which has been hurt
by a lack of new products.
   ``There is definitely suffering,'' said Thomas O'Grady, industry
analyst with Integrated Automotive Resources in Wayne, Pa.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. have
turned the weak dollar to their advantage by holding down prices
instead of matching their foreign competitors increase-for-increase
as before.
   ``They are all looking at 1988 as the year of the return of the
domestic (car) or the start of that return,'' said Chris Cedergren,
industry analyst with J.D. Power and Associates in Agoura Hills,
Calif.
   Price increases have added as much as $6,000 to the sticker of a
German car and $3,000 for a Japanese model since the dollar began
falling. The price difference between a Japanese car and a
comparable American model has reached $1,500 to $2,000, analysts
said.
   Japanese car prices have risen nearly 25 percent in the past
three years. European autos have risen less on a percentage basis
but more in dollar terms because they predominantly are luxury
models that cost more to start with.
   European makers felt the pinch from the weak dollar first
because Japanese auto prices had a built-in cushion: U.S. dealers
faced with heavy demand had been tacking $1,000 to $2,000 on to the
sticker price and still selling all the cars they could get.
   Buyers didn't begin to notice that Japanese cars were growing
more expensive until late in 1986, when dealers had used up the
cushion and began raising prices. But even then, the difference
meant only a few dollars more in monthly payments.
   Furthermore, buyers who had been weaned from American cars by
the quality and reliability of Japanese cars were willing to pay a
little extra for the imports, said Joseph Phillippi, analyst with
Shearson Lehman Hutton in New York.
   As a result, while total car sales declined 10.7 percent in
1987, Japanese import car sales fell only 9.7 percent while GM,
Ford and Chrysler's domestic car sales together fell 16.7 percent.
   The currency-related price increases pushed European makers such
as BMW, Mercedes-Benz and Porsche further into the ultra-luxury
stratosphere with new cars that cost $40,000 to $70,000, and pushed
many buyers out of the market.
   During January, sales fell by about 28 percent for
Mercedes-Benz, Volvo and Porsche, 51 percent for Alfa-Romeo and 60
percent for Peugeot.
   But the Japanese fought back. Companies such as Toyota Motor
Corp., Honda Motor Co. and Mazda Motor Corp. accepted smaller
profits and squeezed steady efficiency improvements out of their
factories at home to protect their U.S. market share.
   Helped by the strength of the Japanese yen, used to buy raw
materials from weaker-currency nations, they were able to keep
price increases so small that the Big Three accused them of
predatory pricing in the United States.
   They also began shifting some production to the United States
and began offering or planning cars to fill the void left by the
Europeans in the $20,000 to $30,000 luxury market.
   But despite their efforts, higher prices have begun to hurt
Japanese car sales. While Toyota and Honda remain strong, other
makes are showing signs of strain.
   In January, Nissan's import car sales fell 19.6 percent in
January from a year ago and Isuzu's sales fell 16.7 percent.
Japanese makers also are reporting higher inventories of unsold
cars and are increasing their use of buyer incentives, analysts
said.
   Still, they warn, the Big Three have only a limited time to take
full advantage of the import weakness and win back some of the
buyers they lost to the Japanese earlier in the decade because the
Japanese will adapt to the new currency level.
   ``The Japanese will have fully adjusted within 18 months from
now,'' O'Grady said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
