<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SearsOverhaul Bjt   03-03 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sears Overhaul, Bjt,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Announces Overhaul of Sluggish Merchandising Sector</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. says a three-year overhaul
of its $28 billion retail stores operation will make the nation's
biggest general retailer more responsive to customers and more
profitable for investors.
   Retailing analysts see the shakeup as an attempt to revive
sluggish sales and profits within the company's merchandise group,
which saw its share of Sears' total revenue slip to about 58
percent in 1987 from more than 65 percent in 1985.
   ``Basically what we find today is a Sears company not as strong
as it was last year,'' analyst Allan Bortel, a senior vice
president for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said Wednesday.
   Sears says its planned new retailing structure would improve its
competitiveness, which in turn would better serve its customers and
shareholders.
   ``If we have a leaner management organization, because we will
be that much more competitive, we will be delivering greater
revenues and greater income to the bottom line,'' said company
spokesman Philo Holland after Sears announced the restructuring
Wednesday.
   The restructuring, which will trim an undetermined number of
people from the merchandise group's management staff of about
4,000, is aimed at making each department of every Sears store more
competitive, officials said.
   The plan calls for each department, from womens apparel to lawn
and garden supplies, to be reorganized under its own, unique
management structure.
   ``The apparel business will be run differently from the hardware
business,'' Holland said. ``You need different organizational
structures to compete in different businesses.''
   Michael Bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of the
merchandising group, stated that the restructuring would reduce the
number of management levels, making each segment of Sears'
merchandise business leaner and more independent.
   ``We are competing in many diverse businesses, each with its own
unique structure, and (we) have been essentially using one
organizational format to compete in all of these businesses,''
Bozic said.
   ``The changes we make will result in a company that is better
structured to maintain its position as America's premier
retailer,'' he said.
   Officials said they had no estimate of the number of employees
to be affected or the cost savings involved.
   ``The ultimate size and structure will be determined by how we
choose to compete in the different businesses we are
restructuring,'' Holland said.
   He said the reduction in management personnel would be achieved
through attrition, severance bonuses and early retirement offers.
   Bortel said he didn't expect massive layoffs or sales of valued
assets in the near future.
   ``Sears is a very conservative company and does not do anything
in a radical way,'' Bortel said in a telephone interview from San
Francisco.
</TEXT>
