<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worldwide demand for oil may drive
prices up to nearly twice present levels and increase dependence on
Persian Gulf supplies, according to a study by Harvard University.
   The yearlong study released Wednesday said the improved
economies in industrial nations since oil prices dropped in 1986
have discouraged conservation efforts and reduced oil stockpiles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul
Volcker has been named to a professorship at Princeton University
and the chairmanship of James D. Wolfensohn Inc., a New York City
investment banking firm.
   Volcker, who graduated from Princeton's Woodrow Wilson School of
Public and International Affairs in 1949, is the first to hold the
school's Frederic H. Schultz Class of 1951 Professorship of
International Economic Policy.
   The Princeton post and the position with Wolfensohn are
effective immediately, Volcker said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A growing amount of tax money withheld from
workers' paychecks is being misused by employers, often never
finding its way to the government, the Internal Revenue Service
says.
   The total of these delinquent Social Security and income taxes
rose by 49 percent from 1982 through 1987, to almost $3.73 billion,
William M. Wauben, IRS assistant commissioner for collections, said
Wednesday.
   He said about 338,000 employers have failed to pay or account
for that sum.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On-time peformance by the nation's major
airlines improved slightly during January, but three out of every
10 flights still were at least 15 minutes late, the Transportation
Department said.
   The 14 airlines that are monitored in the monthly report had
69.2 percent of their flights arriving within 15 minutes of
schedule, compared with 66.4 percent in December, the report
released Wednesday said.
   Southwest Airlines had the best record in February with 85
percent of its flights arriving on time, while Continental Airlines
had the worst mark with a 65 percent on-time arrival record.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New rules are being prepared to help farmers
pay off loans owed to the Farmers Home Administration, including
provisions that allow the agency to write off some of the debt so
that families can stay on the land, officials say.
   Joe O'Neill, an FmHA spokesman, said Wednesday the new rules
probably will be ready by June. In many cases, over-burdened
borrowers could have much of their debt written off, trimmed back
to reflect their assets in hopes of keeping them in business. He
said he had no estimate of how much debt the FmHA might write off
under the new rules.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
