<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WineExports     03-03 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wine Exports,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Increase in Export Sales of American Wine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soaring sales to Japan and Britain helped
send total U.S. wine exports in 1987 to 11.87 million gallons, a 64
percent increase over the previous year, a trade group reported.
   The dollar's decline against foreign currencies, including a 55
percent drop against the Japanese yen over the past two years, was
largely the cause, the Wine Institute said Wednesday.
   U.S. wineries also have begun more aggressive promotions to
overseas markets, said Sam Folsom, a spokesman for the San
Francisco-based institute.
   Overall, U.S. exports totaled $60.8 million in 1987, up from
$34.8 million the year before. Calfornia wines account for about 95
percent of American wine exports.
   Exports account for only 3 percent of all California wine
shipments, but the sales are considered important because domestic
sales have been less than dynamic in recent years, according to
wine experts.
   Japan is one of the fastest growing markets.
   ``There's a growing awareness of Califoria wines, particularly
among Japanese yuppies,'' said wine consultant Jon Fredriskson.
   Japan was the largest export market in terms of dollars,
importing $14 million worth of American wine, or 2.25 million
gallons, up from $7.3 million worth in 1986.
   Canada imported $10.9 million, but in greater bulk. Its imports
reached 3.3 million gallons, up from 2.6 million in 1986. In terms
of gallons, it was the largest importer of American wine.
</TEXT>
