<DOCNO> AP880303-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-US-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru f0036 03-03 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0036,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Indicates Belief Noriega Should Go</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS grafs 4-5, bgng, Reagan, during ..., to UPDATE with
further Reagan quotes and background. A version moving on general
news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan indicated today he
believes Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega must go, while
Secretary of State George P. Shultz said economic sanctions against
Noriega's government were being ``considered carefully.''
   Reagan, during an unscheduled meeting with British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher at the conclusion of the NATO summit,
was asked during a picture-taking session if he thought Noriega
should relinquish power.
   ``Yes,'' the president responded. He did not elaborate.
   During a subsequent photo session with Belgian Prime Minister
Wilfried Martens, Reagan was asked if the United States was ready
to seize Panamanian assets in American banks.
   ``I can't give you an answer yet,'' he replied. ``We still have
a lot of talking to do.''
   Reagan last Friday said he had no plans to intervene militarily
in Panama and said he thought the American options were limited in
the area.
   Shultz called Noriega ``bad news'' but said that no decision had
been made on sanctions.
   Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams had raised the
prospect in Washington on Wednesday that the next payment due to
Panama for Panama Canal operations would be withheld if such a
request were made by ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said that the
request already had been received.
   At a news conference today in Brussels following the conclusion
of the NATO summit, Shultz told reporters, ``Noriega is bad news
for Panama, he's bad news for the region.''
   He said there were a ``variety of things'' the United States
could do, including restricting the flow of money into the
Panamanian treasury. ``That is being considered carefully,'' he
said. ``We want to do it properly, we want to do it right, we want
to do it effectively.''
   In Washington, Abrams said the administration would respond to a
request by Delvalle to withhold the canal payments.
   ``If he tells us he doesn't want that money going to Noriega,
then we're not going to give it to Noriega.''
   Panama receives a reported $80 million in canal-related fees
annually. Four members of the House Merchant Marine and Fisheries
Committee demanded Wednesday that the administration halt all such
payments to Panama.
   The United States continues to regard Delvalle as Panama's
constitutional president and seeks the removal of Noriega, under
federal indictment on drug smuggling charges, from the nation's
political life.
   Delvalle was ousted last week after attempting to fire Noriega
and has been in hiding in Panama since then.
   At stake is a $7 million U.S. payment due March 15 for canal
tolls, fees and services. Much more is involved in what appears to
be a parallel U.S. effort to keep the new Panamanian government
from gaining access to official accounts in U.S. banks.
   William D. Rogers, of the Arnold & Porter law firm in
Washington, said the administration was taking legal steps to
ensure that the banks may make disbursements only to the Panamanian
ambassador who served under Delvalle, Juan B. Sosa.
   Rogers, who represents Delvalle and his allies here, said the
State Department was issuing ``formal certifications'' that it
regards Sosa as ``the accredited representative of the recognized
government of the country.''
   At the State Department, Ms. Oakley said only that such
certifications were being prepared. She declined to specify their
purpose.
   Asked about the U.S. position on that issue, Abrams told the
Cable News Network: ``We know who the legitimate government of
Panama is. If the government of President Delvalle says to American
banks, `Don't pay money to Noriega,' then all those banks are going
to come to the State Department and say, `Who's got the authority
here? Noriega or Delvalle?'
   ``We're going to answer that question. Delvalle is president of
Panama. And Noriega has been fired and he does not have legitimate
authority here.''
   Sosa estimated that U.S. bank deposits of the Panamanian
government total $50 million.
   Rogers seemed confident that the U.S. government action would
preclude any Panamanian government withdrawals from U.S. accounts,
but neither Abrams nor Ms. Oakley offered confirmation of that
claim.
   Also on Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Lloyd F. McMahon in
Manhattan issued a temporary restraining order blocking Republic
National Bank from turning millions of dollars over to the new
government.
   The Noriega opponents dropped the suit afterward when the bank
agreed to transfer the funds to the Federal Reserve Bank of New
York.
   Rogers said the settlement does not affect four other banks
being sued: Marine Midland NA, Irving Trust Co., Bankers Trust Co.
in New York, and the Bank of Boston in that city.
   ``The point is not to get money but to deny money to Noriega,''
he said.
</TEXT>
