<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Panama-BankSuit     03-03 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Bank Suit,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Bank to Keep Panamanian Funds in Federal Reserve Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This material also was included in PM-US-Panama Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republic National Bank of New York has agreed to
transfer millions of dollars in Panamanian funds to the Federal
Reserve Bank and in return, foes of Panama's dictatorship have
dropped a lawsuit against the bank.
   The settlement was announced Wednesday evening, hours after a
federal judge signed an order barring Republic National from
releasing the contested funds to the regime of military strongman
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The judge's action came at the request of Panamanian President
Eric Arturo Delvalle, ousted last week following his unsuccessful
attempt to fire Noriega but still recognized by the U.S. government
as the legitimate head of Panama.
   The suit appeared to be part of a coordinated effort to deny
money to Noriega's cash-strapped regime, which already has been cut
off from U.S. aid. The State Department also has asked a group of
banks not to disburse Panamanian government funds to Noriega.
   Filed on behalf of the Republic of Panama at Manhattan federal
court, the suit asserted a ``massive transfer of funds'' to Noriega
had already occurred and up to $10 million more would be
transferred unless the court stopped it.
   But late in the day, the bank said the lawsuit ``has been
voluntarily dismissed and Republic National Bank of New York has
transferred to the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, any funds held
by it of Banco Nacional de Panama.''
   William D. Rogers, attorney for the Noriega opponents who
brought the lawsuit, confirmed the settlement in a telephone
interview from his Washington office. But Rogers said he didn't
know much much money had been transferred to the Federal Reserve
Bank for safekeeping.
   ``The point is not to get money but to deny money to Noreiga,''
said Rogers, adding that the settlement doesn't affect similar
lawsuits against three other New York banks: Bankers Trust, Irving
Trust and Marine Midland.
   Those banks were included after the original lawsuit was filed
but were not immediately included in U.S. District Judge Lloyd F.
MacMahon's temporary restraining order which had been signed
earlier in the day.
   Noriega, military leader of Panama, was indicted on drug charges
by two U.S. grand juries in Florida Feb. 4. Delvalle sought to
dismiss Noriega Feb. 25 but was ousted by Noriega supporters and
has gone into hiding.
   On Tuesday, Delvalle took steps through his supporters to freeze
Panamanian assets outside the country.
   Panama's U.S. ambassador, Juan B. Sosa, who has maintained that
Delvalle's ouster was unconstitutional, said he had no precise
figures on the amount of money in Panamanian accounts but estimated
it to be $50 million.
   According to court papers, Sosa told all four banks by telex
Tuesday that only he was authorized to approve transfer of money
from the Panamanian accounts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
