<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ModularHomes Adv05-06   03-03 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Modular Homes, Adv 05-06,0898</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 05</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<HEAD>Repeat for all needing.</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 5-6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Newtown Firm To Offer Expensive Modular Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of Connecticut entrepreneurs have
in hand the blueprints they think will alter the popular image of
modular homes as boxy structures that sway in the breeze.
   Harvey F. Gerber Jr. and his wife, Wendy A. Horgan, have formed
a company that will sell modular houses designed by an architect to
look like and compete with the best custom-built homes.
   It's a new market with few competitors.
   The incentive to homebuyers is that so-called ``high-end modular
homes'' can be built at a lower cost and much faster than
comparable stick-built homes that are constructed from the ground
up, Gerber said.
   The four styles offered by Gerber Builders Inc. are two-story
homes, with large porches, 9-foot ceilings, family rooms, multiple
bathrooms and at least three bedrooms. The houses also allow for
personalized touches, such as a choice of flooring, siding and trim
molding.
   The price ranges from about $70,000 to $130,000 for a
2,000-square-foot house, depending upon whether a buyer purchases
an unfinished model or a completed home. The price of land isn't
included.
   ``What we have here is a product that is aimed at a high-end
market. It is going to be indistinguishable from the best
stick-built homes,'' Gerber said during a recent interview.
   Gerber, 39, and his wife are both former Wall Street attorneys.
They got their start in construction 10 years ago when they began
renovating historic buildings in New York City. They had branched
out into condominium construction in New Jersey when they decided
to focus on modular homes.
   They chose Connecticut because of their connections to the
state. Ms. Horgan, originally from New Canaan, received her
master's and law degrees from the University of Connecticut. Gerber
attended Yale and got his law degree from Fordham University.
   The company has constructed a Victorian-style model on its
11-acre headquarters site in Newtown, an affluent suburban
community about 70 miles north of New York City. The firm is
constructing three other models on a parcel in Sussex County, N.J.
   The completion of the model was the culmination of three years
of design work and planning that has cost the company about $1
million, Gerber said.
   The company's goal is to sell at least 100 homes the first year
and begin construction of Connecticut's first modular home factory
at the Newtown site.
   If all goes well, ground could be broken on the proposed
57,000-square-foot factory this summer. The factory would produce
300 homes a year and the product line would be expanded to include
lower-priced and more expensive models along with the
intermediate-priced models now being offered.
   The Gerber homes currently are constructed by Contempri Homes in
Taylor, Pa., and shipped to Connecticut. All the Gerber homes have
been designed by Deborah Berke, who teaches architecture at Yale
University and runs a business in New York City.
   Modular homes account for about 5 percent of all housing starts
nationwide, and perhaps 15 percent of new houses in the Northeast,
where most modular home factories are located, said Barbara Martin,
special projects consultant for the Buildings Systems Council of
the National Association of Home Builders in Washington, D.C.
   She could name only three companies selling high-end modular
homes.
   George Oswald of Techno Craft Inc., another modular home
company, predicts that 50 percent of the housing starts in the
Northeast will be modular homes by the year 2000.
   Techno Craft, which opened a 100,000-square-foot factory in
McElhattan, Pa., last year, already has about $80 million in orders
for its luxury homes.
   ``We're the ones who broke the sound barrier by going into the
high-end (modular home) market,'' Oswald said.
   The smallest Techno-Craft home is 2,600 square feet, with its
colonial mansion models ranging up to 7,000 square feet, Oswald
said. The cost averages about $50 a square foot. The homes are sold
finished and are available only through developers.
   Gerber plans to sell to individual home buyers and small
contractors.
   His current models cost about $65 a square foot completed, or
about $130,000. It would take a crew several days to assemble the
six pieces of each model and then about three more months to
complete the home, Gerber said.
   To those wanting to save money, the company will sell unfinished
homes for about $35 a square foot, or about $70,000. For that
price, the home comes with much of the work done, such as all the
plumbing and electrical wiring run, and the insulation and
wallboard installed. But an unfinished house has no roof, no
siding, and the plumbing and wiring need to be hooked up.
   The company also will sell kits to those more than 30 miles away
from its Newtown office.
   ``We've gotten universal praise from every bank, appraiser,
engineer, contractor and prospect who has visited the house (in
Newtown) prior to its formal opening,'' said Gerber. ``At the same
time, we haven't had the ultimate test, which is market exposure.
We can't conclusively say we've designed a Hula Hoop, although
that's what we believe.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 5-6</NOTE>
