<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Europe-Takeover     03-03 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Takeover,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Must Name Allies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti
must identify his allies before government regulators will allow an
extension of his offer for Societe Generale de Belgiqe S.A,
Belgium's biggest holding company, a banking commission official
said Thursday.
   The official, who asked not to be named, said the French
investment firm Cerus S.A, through which De Benedetti has sought
control of Societe Generale, had asked to extend its offer beyond
Friday's original deadline.
   But the banking commission demanded that Cerus names all its
allies, specifying how many shares of Societe Generale each owns,
by Friday night before approving the request, the official said.
   Cerus itself has a 18.6 percent stake in Societe Generale. But
De Benedetti claims he and his allies control 47.2 percent of the
company's 28.2 million shares.
   A rival alliance centered around the French investment Cie
Financiere de Suez and Belgium's biggest insurer, Groupe AG, says
it has a majority stake of 52 percent.
   Both sides have voiced doubts on the claims of their opponents,
and have each laid claim to the company's proposed capital increase
of 12 million shares, which was approved by a Brussels court
Tuesday.
   The ruling, however, is subject to confirmation by by a higher
court.
   De Benedetti wants to turn the 166-year-old Societe Generale
into a holding company with interests across Europe and wants to
run the day-to-day affairs.
   The rival alliance wants to keep Societe Generale anchored in
Belgium.
   The company has interests in about half of Belgium's 50 biggest
companies and has an important stake in the country's gas,
electricity and petroleum sector and Belgium's largest bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
