<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   03-03 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in light follow-through selling
from Wednesday's weaker close, analysts said.
   The wheat market continued to show nervousness about the
Agriculture Department's new series of surplus wheat auctions, said
Joel Karlin, an analyst for Research Department Inc.
   The USDA sold 10 million bushels of surplus wheat on Tuesday,
held another auction for 10 million bushels Wednesday and has
scheduled a third auction for Friday, also with a target of 10
million bushels.
   Karlin said wheat traders also were jittery about the dim
prospects for new export sales in the near future.
   Soybean futures prices weakened as soybean harvesting got under
way in South America. A record soybean yield is expected in Brazil.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.05{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
to 1 cent lower with March at $2.01 a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
2{ cents lower with March at $1.91 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent
to 3 cents lower with March at $6.28{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .40 cent to 1.07 cent lower with April at 71.05
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent to .95 cent lower with
March at 79.62 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .60 cent lower
with April at 42.65 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .25
cent lower to .03 cent higher with March at 52.15 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures ended mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
