<DOCNO> AP880303-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1246EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Autos-Engineers     03-03 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Autos-Engineers,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Fighting Shortage of Auto Engineers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. auto industry may be trimming back on
engineers, but the British auto industry is going out of its way to
find more.
   The problem is the long, steady decline of auto manufacturing in
the 1960s and 1970s, when young engineers looking for interesting,
better paying jobs entered other fields.
   Now that automaking in Britain is on the rebound, the country's
Society of Motor Manufacturers & Traders has mounted a large-scale
effort to restore pride in its car industry, said Godfrey Messervy,
the society's president.
   Messervy, in town for the Society of Automotive Engineers annual
convention, said Britain is suffering from a shortage of engineers
even though it is home to leading-edge innovators such as Lotus
Engineering.
   ``There's a tendency for them not to go into the motor
industry,'' Messervy said.
   Sales have begun to recover along with pay scales, he said, and
makers have been improving efficiency and winning back sales in an
import-dominated market.
   Car sales in 1987 were a record of more than 2 million in the
United Kingdom, and the share of the market held by British-built
car rose to 48.3 percent from 44 percent in 1986.
   But the nation doesn't seem aware that it again is growing a
strong auto industry and Messervy's society wants to change that.
   Targeting schools, it is trying to convince parents and students
that the auto industry is a good field for engineers and offering
school career counselors 12-week introductions to the industry,
sometimes with full pay.
   The society also is lobbying the government to repeal a 10
percent tax on car sales that doesn't apply to other consumer
goods. In a nation with the lowest per-capita car ownership rate in
Western Europe, Messervy said repeal of the tax would boost car
sales by 200,000 a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0331 </DOCNO>
