<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1228EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Koppers-Beazer     03-03 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers-Beazer,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British-led Investment Group Offers $1.3 Billion for Koppers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group led by Beazer PLC and
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. launched a tender offer today of nearly
$1.3 billion for Koppers Co. Inc., a construction and chemicals
company.
   Koppers, which is based in Pittsburgh, had no comment on the
offer, which was initially disclosed in an advertisement in today's
edition of the Wall Street Journal. The offer expires March 30.
   Beazer is a general construction company based in London and
Shearson is a New York-based investment banking firm.
   The offer of $45 a share is being made by BNS Inc., a company
that is reportedly 49 percent owned by Beazer and 45 percent by
Shearson. The remainder is held by County NatWest International
Inc., a British investment bank.
   The bid triggered speculation on Wall Street that a higher offer
might arise. In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Koppers
stock jumped $6.37{ a share to $51.50 by midday.
   The bid is conditioned on, among other things, tender of a
majority of Koppers' common shares, approval by the non-managment
directors of Koppers, approval by Beazer's shareholders and the
bidding group's satisfaction that certain elements of Delaware
antitakeover laws are invalid.
   In a letter released in London, Brian C. Beazer, chairman and
chief executive of Beazer PLC, told Charles R. Pullin, Koppers'
chairman and chief executive, that the proposed transaction
``offers excellent opportunity for people connected with Koppers.''
   He wrote that Koppers would become ``part of a worldwide
organization with the extensive resorces, depth of expertise and
financial strength.''
   Beazer said it planned to operate Koppers as an independent
autonomous business and that there were no plans to move its
headquarters from Pittsburgh.
   It said affiliates of BNS currently own 2.1 million Kopper
shares, or about 7.45 percent of Koppers' outstanding common stock.
   Robert O'Gara, a spokesman for Koppers, said the company had no
comment on the offer and refused to comment on whether Koppers'
board planned to meet to discuss it.
   He said Koppers had nearly 28.6 million common shares at the end
of 1987, which would make the value of the tender offer about $1.29
billion.
   Koppers' main businesses are construction materials and
services, which mainly involve road construction, and chemical and
allied products.
   Koppers reported its profit for 1987 fell to $10.2 million, or
36 cents share, from $74.1 million, or $2.59 a share, a year
earlier. The results included a charge of $59.4 million in 1987 due
to settlement of a lawsuit.
   Revenue for 1987 rose to $1.52 billion from $1.4 billion a year
earlier.
   Beazer said it earned $82.8 million on sales of $1.7 billion in
its latest fiscal year ended June 30, 1987.
   Beazer already has interests in the United States. It bought
Gifford-Hill & Co., a cement-maker based in Dallas, in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
