<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Thursday against most major
currencies in light European trading. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they expected the dollar would
trade within a narrow range until the March 17 release of the
latest U.S. merchandise trade figures.
   One senior U.S. bank dealer in Frankfurt said Friday would not
see much traditional pre-weekend position-squaring because few
positions had been taken during the week.
   In London, the British pound stood at $1.7680, unchanged from
late Wednesday. It bounced back from a slight morning drop, when
the Bank of England sold small amounts of sterling for dollars and
marks in an effort to keep sterling below 3.0 West German marks.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 129.30 yen, up from Wednesday's
128.47 closing. Later in London, it fell to 129.15 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with rates late
Wednesday, were: 1.6955 West German marks, up from 1.6945; 1.4035
Swiss francs, up from 1.4005; 5.7355 French francs, up from 5.7345;
1.9025 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9013; 1,249.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,247.00; and 1.2535 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2558
   Gold bullion was lower in London at $427.80 bid a troy ounce,
compared with $429.50 late Wednesday. In Zurich, it also fell to
$429.00, from $429.50 bid late Wednesday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell to a closing bid of $433.96, down from
$434.95 bid late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.22 dollars a
troy ounce, down from $6.24 dollars bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
