<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0854EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Brusca Adv04   03-03 0869</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Brusca, Adv 04,0907</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday March 4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>For American Economist Diplomacy and Economics Go Hand In Hand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Brusca turns 38 on March 14.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a top economist for Nikko Securities Ltd.,
one of Japan's largest brokerage firms, Robert A. Brusca has had to
do more than just showcase his abilities for forecasting U.S.
economic growth or the trade gap. For one thing, he's had to
develop a taste for green tea.
   ``After about the seventh cup in one day I've had just about all
the green tea I care to have,'' said the 37-year-old Brusca, chief
economist in the fixed-income division of Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc., a Nikko subsidiary.
   Since joining Nikko about two years ago and becoming the first
American to be named a chief economist in that company, Brusca has
learned that foreign diplomacy and economics often go hand in hand
_ and that having a sense of humor helps puts the two in harmony.
   His job is to keep Nikko clients in Japan and elsewhere abreast
of U.S. economic conditions and to advise them on investments,
particularly in the area of government bonds.
   But trying to predict the ups and downs of interest rates can
sometimes be as difficult as learning the proper way to bow in
Japan; to exchange meishis, or business cards; or to drink green
tea, Japan's counterpart to coffee.
   In Japan, ``Everything is proper. The business meetings are very
formal. People are very polite,'' said Brusca, an affable man with
thin brown hair and glasses. His wife, Candace, is an aspiring
actress.
   ``When you arrive at a meeting, you're introduced formally.
You're seated in an office or a meeting room with tea tables and
overstuffed chairs.
   ``Then you exchange business cards. They're always handled with
two hands, and once they're exchanged you leave them directly in
front of you. Each person takes turns to talk. It's considered rude
to interrupt.''
   Despite the formality, the wry humor that has become Brusca's
trademark in the financial world still manages to find a frequent
outlet.
   ``I was talking with two Japanese executives who had been
working together for 15 years,'' he recalled. ``The conversation
turned to first names and it came out that those two didn't know
each other's first name.
   ``I said, `Everyone has the same first name (in Japan) _
Mister.'''
   The two stoic men managed to crack a smile, Brusca noted with
pride.
   His weekly reports to clients on the state of the world's
economy can be equally amusing. One dated Jan. 29, for instance,
used the comic book characters Batman and Robin in describing how
economic strength in the fourth quarter was likely to give way to
weakness through 1988.
   ``One of their favorite tricks was to turn their car sharply
while moving at high speed so that it would skid backwards while
going in the same direction until traction overtook inertia and
they were able to reverse direction. The U.S. economy is
experiencing a bat turn of sorts ...''
   And then there was the report two weeks earlier that focused on
West Germany's reluctance to stimulate its economy to help improve
its trade imbalance with the United States.
   ``I want to draw the distinction between being thoughtless and
being mindless,'' he wrote. ``Thoughtlessness implies an ability
... to be more considerate of the needs of others. Mindlessness
implies an inability to think clearly about anything ...
   ``From my perch overseas their (West Germany's) policies look
mindless, but possibly they are merely thoughtless.''
   Brusca says those offbeat analogies are often deleted when
translated from English to Japanese.
   ``The people who read the Japanese (version) have no idea I have
a sense of humor,'' he said. ``And sometimes the people who read
the English version have no idea I have a sense of humor.''
   It's his unflinching wit, though, that helps get the Detroit
native quoted in business publications and on televised financial
news shows. He also writes a regular column in ``Financial World''
and is a contributor to Nikkei Financial Daily.
   When asked nine days after the Oct. 19 stock market collapse how
Wall Street planned to commemorate the Crash of 1929, he quickly
responded, ``with paper hats and paper losses.''
   But Brusca warns: ``Don't mistake that I'm not serious. I'm very
serious about what I do. But the use of humor helps. It's a very
high-pressure job. You can be ungodly serious or you can stay
loose.''
   Advising investors about how and when to spend their hard-earned
money is a tough business, and Nikko didn't hire Brusca just for
his good humor.
   Large Japanese securities firms have gone out of their way in
the past few years to hire experienced Americans to act as teachers
of sorts in helping ``Westernize'' their foreign employers, Brusca
said.
   Before Nikko, he worked as a money market economist and
``Fedwatcher'' at Irving Trust Co. in New York. He also was a
senior economist at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, where he
analyzed international banking activity.
   Brusca also holds doctorate and master's degrees from Michigan
State University.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday March 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
