<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AydsName     03-03 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ayds Name,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lagging Sales Prompt Search For New Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COMPTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publicity about AIDS has reduced sales of
the diet candy Ayds by up to a half, so the manufacturer is looking
for a new name to beef up its image, the chairman said Thursday.
   The diet suppressant has been on the market for 47 years and
remains a profitable product for the Dep Corp., but sales have
dropped by as much as 50 percent over the past few years because of
the name association, company Chairman Robert Berglass said.
   ``You cannot specifically blame the disease on our product in
any way, shape or form. We think it is a negative association and
it would be best not to have it associated in any way,'' Berglass
said in a telephone interview from Dep's headquarters, 15 miles
south of downtown Los Angeles.
   ``Johnson and Johnson does not have a problem with Band-Aid
because it has the name couched within what the product is,'' he
said.
   ``I am sure that if you want to do a study, there are a lot of
names out there with AIDS in it, Band-Aid, Cur-Aid,'' Berglass
said. ``Our problem is that our name is just that one word.''
   Since January, Ayds has been marketed in Great Britain under the
new name Aydslim. If sales show signs of recovery, the appetite
suppressant candy may be sold in the United States under that name
later this year.
   So far, reaction from retailers has been positive, Berglass
said. But consumer reaction has yet to be determined, he said.
   He expects consumer reaction to be available within the next few
months. Most people go on diets in the spring, as they think about
summer swim suits, he explained.
   Until the name question is answered, Dep, which also makes
Lavoris mouthwash and Topol smoker's toothpaste, has a
``frustrating marketing problem,'' he said.
   ``You cannot use the radio and television media to advertise.
You are confined to print in reaching the consumer. People are not
going to listen to your message when they hear it on a verbal
basis. They have to see it. That's why our campaign for the spring
will be in print.''
   Industry analysts disagree over the value of a name change.
   ``I think it's a dumb move,'' said Charles E. Brymer, president
of the New York-based product-naming firm, Interbrand USA.
   ``They should just walk away from the name Ayds and relaunch it
under a new name,'' Brymer said. ``The whole AIDS issue has become
so large that I would not want to market anything under that name.''
   ``If you change the name, you give up the equity,'' said Ira
Bachrach, president of San Francisco-based NameLab Inc. ``Besides,
the problem with the name is more in the mind of the media than the
consumer.''
   Federal health officials believe about 40,000 Americans have
acquired immune deficiency syndrome. By 1991, that figure is
expected to top 270,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0338 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1544EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Merc-Margins     03-03 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Merc-Margins,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Merc Raises Stock Index Futures Margins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates BC version to INSERT 2 grafs after 3rd graf, A
presidental ..., with 2 grafs on reax to Brady report; picks up 4th
graf pvs, David Ruder ....</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange has raised the
margin requirements on its stock-index futures by 2 percentage
points in response to a call for better coordination of the
country's financial markets, officials said Thursday.
   The change, approved Wednesday by the exchange's board of
governors, requires traders of the Merc's Standard & Poor's 500
stock-index futures to post payments equal to 15 percent of the
value of the contracts being traded, instead of 13 percent as
previously.
   A presidential commission that investigated the October stock
market collapse suggested raising margins on stock-index futures as
a way of curbing swings in their prices. The wild swings have been
blamed for adding to volatility in the stock market.
   The presidential commission, headed by New York investment
banker Nicholas Brady, found that professionals in the stock market
can invest in stocks on a margin of as little as 20 to 25 percent.
It said margins in futures should be ``consistent,'' although not
necessarily equal.
   John F. Sandner, chairman of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange's
board of governors, said in a statement that ``maintaining
stock-index futures margin at the 15 percent level will bring the
`consistency' sought by the Brady Commission.''
   David Ruder, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission,
has suggested margins of 20 percent to 25 percent on index futures.
   But Wendy Lee Gramm, the new head of the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, which regulates futures markets, said Wednesday
she saw no need for higher margins on stock-index futures.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange is the nation's largest market
for stock-index futures, accounting for more than 80 percent of all
contracts traded.
   Stock-index futures are traded by investors who use them to
hedge against losses in the stock market as well as speculators who
hope to profit by guessing on the direction of the market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0339 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1556EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-TI-Apple     03-03 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TI-Apple,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments, Apple Cooperate on Artificial Intelligence PC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Instruments Inc. said Thursday it will
sell a computer for artificial-intelligence work based on Apple
Computer Inc.'s Macintosh II, a step that should move ``thinking
machines'' more into the mainstream of business.
   Texas Instruments said the new Micro Explorer would have all the
functions of a standard Macintosh II as well as
artificial-intelligence features, such as the ability to manipulate
symbols instead of just numbers.
   Most other artificial-intelligence (AI) workstations, including
Texas Instruments' own Explorer, cannot be used as general-purpose
computers.
   Other AI companies are also moving to insert their technology
into existing computers, including Texas Instruments' biggest rival
in the field, Symbolics Inc. of Cambridge, Mass.
   However, Cupertino, Calif.-based Apple said it will have an
especially close relationship with Dallas-based Texas Instruments.
In a first for both companies, Texas Instruments and Apple will
both put their logos on the Micro Explorer, which will be marketed
only by Texas Instruments.
   Texas Instruments and Apple said the Micro Explorer could be
used in such varied fields as tax advising, computer-aided design
and assigning gates to airplanes at airports.
   Although artificial intelligence encompasses the whole concept
of making computers think like people, most products on the market
have the more modest goal of augmenting human decision makers by
converting knowledge into a set of rules that can be applied by a
computer.
   The price of the Micro Explorer ranges from about $15,000 to
$30,000, compared to $50,000 to $70,000 for the Explorer, which is
about twice as powerful, Texas Instruments said. An AI package will
also be available for people who already own the Mac II. Shipments
are scheduled to begin in the April-June period.
   Symbolics, in a response to the Texas Instruments announcement,
said its Ivory chip for artificial intelligence is superior to
Texas Instruments' Explorer Lisp chip. It also said its chip will
be plugged into not only the Mac II, but also International
Business Machines Corp.'s Personal System-2 and PC AT, although it
could not give a timetable.
   Texas Instruments said it had no timetable for putting its
artificial-intelligence chip into other personal computers besides
the Mac II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0340 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1612EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Oil     03-03 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Oil,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Biggest Oil Company Reports Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Companies reported Thursday that its
profit rose 14 percent in both the fourth quarter and all of 1987,
but the world's largest oil company would have suffered a decrease
for the year under accounting rules used in the United States.
   The Anglo-Dutch oil giant said after-tax earnings for the final
three months of 1987 totaled 858 British pounds, or about $1.5
billion, compared with a profit of 752 pounds a year earlier. It
attributed the improvement to gains in exploration, production and
chemical businesses that offset lower refinery profits.
   Revenue fell 37.6 percent to 1.34 billion pounds from 2.15
billion pounds, a drop attributed largely to asset sales and
movements in net working capital during the year-earlier period,
the company said.
   For the full year, Royal Dutch-Shell said it had an after-tax
profit of 2.88 billion pounds, or about $4.74 billion, compared
with earnings of 2.54 billion pounds in 1986. Revenue decreased
29.3 percent to 5.3 billion pounds from 7.5 billion pounds.
   Royal Dutch-Shell uses an accounting system that values
inventories on a ``first-in, first-out basis,'' as opposed to the
``last-in, first-out'' basis used by most major American oil
companies.
   The company said that if it had used the American accounting
system, its full-year results would have shown a 15 percent decline
in profit _ dropping to 2.86 billion pounds, or about $4.73
billion, from 3.37 billion pounds.
   For the fourth-quarter, however, its profit would have been ever
better under the American rules, showing a 64 percent rise. Its
earnings for the quarter totaled 986 million pounds, or about $1.71
billion, compared with a profit of 600 million pounds a year
earlier.
   With headquarters in London and the Hague, Netherlands, Royal
Dutch-Shell is the largest oil company in the world. It is the
parent of Shell Oil Co., based in Houston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880303-0341 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1659EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RoxaneRecall     03-03 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Roxane Recall,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Recalls Product, Citing Defective Spoon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roxane Laboratories Inc. has recalled six
lot numbers of its Roxanol 100 pain reliever because of a possibly
defective spoon that the company said could result in an overdose
of morphine.
   The recall, announced Wednesday, is for Lots 860503, 860828,
870289, 870521, 870860 and 871027 of Roxanol 100, a liquid form of
morphine sulfate prescribed for the relief of severe pain in
terminally ill cancer patients.
   The company said there is no problem with the drug itself and
that no injuries have been reported to date. The product is
distributed nationwide.
   A similar product called Roxanol, which is dispensed with a
dropper, is not involved in the recall, the company said.
   The company said a defective spoon was discovered in display
samples of Roxanol 100. The defective spoon has a cylindrical tube,
from top to bottom, into which medication is poured for
measurement; the correct spoon has a plug in the tube just below
the 20mg mark, and the lower third of the tube just below the plug
is open on the back side.
   Roxane Laboratories estimated the risk of the defective spoon
appearing in a package of Roxanol 100 at about 1 in 1,000, but
requested that hospitals, pharmacies and wholesalers that have the
lot numbers in question return the packages to Roxane Laboratories
for inspection. The company said replacement stock is available.
   The company also urged pharmacists and other health care
professionals to consult with patients using Roxanol 100 and
determine if any defective spoons are in their possession.
   Patients taking the drug should consult with pharmacists or
other health professionals, the company said. Roxane Laboratories
said it would supply a replacement spoon in cases where spoons are
found to be defective, or that replacements could be supplied by
pharmacists or physicians.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Eds: The address for Roxane Laboratories is 1809 Wilson Road,
Columbus, Ohio, 43228.
</TEXT>
