<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HawaiiHilton     03-03 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hawaii Hilton,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hilton Says Investor Wants to Buy Waikiki Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Hotels Corp. said Thursday
it has been approached by a Japanese investor about the possibility
of selling its 22-acre Hilton Hawaiian Village on Waikiki Beach.
   However, the company's chairman and chief executive, Barron
Hilton, denied a report that the investors had offered $1 billion,
noting that price would equate to about $340,000 a room, which is
less than other hotels in Hawaii have fetched.
   He also noted that the company has recently spent $100 million
refurbishing the 2,524-room complex, which is owned jointly with
Prudential Insurance Co. of America.
   Hilton didn't identify the investors, but said that the
overtures were unsolicited and that no formal discussions had been
held.
   ``The hotel is not on the market. We do not feel it is in the
best interest of our company to sell the Village at this time,''
Hilton said.
   His statement did not address a report in the Wall Street
Journal on Thursday that the investors also were interested in
acquiring the company's Waldorf-Astoria hotel in New York, and a
company spokesman declined to elaborate.
   Hilton is sole owner of the Waldorf, which also has recently
undergone an expensive refurbishing.
   The Hawaiian Village and Waldorf have turned in especially
strong earnings in recent periods, the company has said.
   Late last year, the company sold the 592-room Beverly Hilton to
entertainer-businessman Merv Griffin for $100.2 million. The
Beverly Hills property also was jointly owned by Hilton and
Prudential.
</TEXT>
