<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     03-03 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $1.15 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 418 money market mutual
funds fell $1.15 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $278.51 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $2.59 billion increase in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group. That rise, in the week ended Feb. 24, put the
funds' assets at a record high of $280.02 billion.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 208 general purpose funds rose $230.5 million to $81.67
billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds dropped $457.8 million to
$115.10 billion, and assets of 113 institutional funds decreased
$1.28 billion to $81.74 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.10 percent from 6.16 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 6.17 percent from 6.23 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
45 days, up from 43 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts fell to
5.74 percent as of Wednesday from 5.75 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, were unchanged at 5.17 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.85
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 6.88
percent the previous week. Yields were 7.16 percent on 1-year CDs,
down from 7.20 percent; 7.57 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 7.62
percent; and 8.04 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.08 percent.
</TEXT>
