<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilStudy     03-03 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Study,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Study Warns of Higher Oil Demand, Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Worldwide demand for oil may drive
prices up to nearly twice present levels and increase dependence on
Persian Gulf supplies, according to a study by Harvard University
released Wednesday.
   The yearlong study, partially funded by a consortium of Japanese
government and busineses, was conducted by Harvard's Energy and
Environmental Policy Center and entitled ``Lower Oil Prices:
Mapping the Impact.''
   It said the improved economies in industrial nations since oil
prices dropped in 1986 have discouraged conservation efforts and
reduced oil stockpiles.
   ``Today's low prices sow the seeds for higher prices tomorrow by
encouraging use, by improving prospects for economic growth ... and
by lulling consumers, industries and government into energy
security complacency,'' the report stated.
   But the study indicated that lower oil prices have also
triggered a long-term economic growth rate of 2.5 percent annually
in the United States and 3 percent to 4 percent in Japan.
   A Harvard study released in September characterized Reagan
administration energy policies as ``myopic'' for failing to
encourage conservation and bolster domestic oil reserves. The
earlier study also called for a $5-a-barrel oil import tariff to
promote domestic oil production and reduce dependence on Persian
Gulf supplies.
   The latest report predicts oil prices could rise from recent
levels _ between $15 and $20 per 42-gallon barrel _ to more than
$30 a barrel by the early 1990s.
   ``As demand growth resumes, then higher oil prices cannot be far
behind,'' the report stated.
   The study found that while governments have been increasing oil
reserves, including the U.S. Strategic Petroleum Reserve, petroleum
companies have reduced stockpiles due to higher demand. The
situation weakens the nation's ability to withstand disruptions in
oil imports, particularly from the Persian Gulf.
   The report was authored by Bijan Mossavar-Rahmani of Apache
International Inc., a Denver-based firm studying international oil
supplies, and Harvard professors William Hogan, Dale Jorgenson and
Richard Cooper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
