<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0742EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GM-Fiero     03-03 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM-Fiero,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant Closing Announcement Shocks Workers, City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers contemplated other jobs and city
officials thought about attracting other employers after General
Motors Corp. said it planned to close the only plant still making
Pontiacs in Pontiac.
   While company officials blamed market conditions for the demise
of the Pontiac Fiero, workers said engineering innovations and
better promotion could have helped.
   Pontiac General Manager Michael Losh blamed the market
conditions for sagging Fiero sales, from 101,720 in 1984 to 47,156
last year.
   Workers were sent home Tuesday after Losh announced that the
plant will shut down after the 1988 model year, idling 1,109.
   The Fiero plant was one of the first at GM to accept
Japanese-style team organization of workers and was used as a model
for other plants, United Auto Workers Local 653 President Harold
Cox said.
   But some workers said the teamwork idea evidently did not extend
to business decisions.
   ``We built the best quality in the corporation for four years,''
said one, Dale Jorden of Clarkston. ``Why are we being laid off?''
   Analysts and others pointed to an overall drop in sales of
sporty, two-seater cars like the Fiero. Toyota MR2 and Mazda RX7
sales also have lagged.
   In addition, the Fiero had problems including engine fires so
frequent that GM recalled the entire 1984 Fiero production run late
last year.
   GM already had closed a foundry, another car assembly plant, a
heavy-duty truck plant and a bus plant in Pontiac and put more than
1,200 other Fiero workers on layoff.
   The Fiero is the last Pontiac manufactured in Pontiac, though
the division will still be based there, noted City Council
President Emmett Elliott Jr., who is also a Local 653 officer.
   ``It was a business decision, but from my position, I'd say it
was a bad decision,'' Elliott said. ``They sell a product all over
the country and label it a `Pontiac' and now they don't even build
it here.''
   Mayor Walter Moore estimated the city will lose $200,000 in tax
revenue and said he has asked to meet with GM officials to discuss
bringing new work to the plant.
   But Council President Pro Tem Peter Tenuta said it was not GM
the city should talk to. ``We should do everything we can to try to
fill those buildings with non-automotive-type jobs,'' he said.
   Cox said he was sorry GM did not do more to promote and market
the car, which was labeled revolutionary when introduced nearly
five years ago because of its mid-engine design, space-frame and
plastic body panels.
   Dick Long, UAW Local 653 vice president, said delaying
engineering changes such as addition of power steering undoubtedly
hastened its demise.
   ``I think the engineering community let us down,'' Long said.
   The announcement came without warning. Only last week GM
approved a $15 million special advertising campaign for the Fiero.
GM's Chevrolet-Pontiac-Canada Group called 12 skilled toolmakers
back to their jobs last week to work on tooling for a redesigned
1990 Fiero.
   Dave D. Campbell, a GM vice president and director of operations
for the Pontiac group, said the decision came at a meeting Monday
after an intensive review that began only three or four weeks ago.
   Losh would not speculate on whether the Fiero plant might reopen
to build a new product.
   Campbell said one possible future product would be a
plastic-body replacement for the Pontiac Firebird and Chevrolet
Camaro that is scheduled for the 1991 model year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
