<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mulheren     03-03 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mulheren,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mulheren Detention Hearing Moved to NY from NJ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A detention hearing for stock speculator John
Mulheren, accused of threatening a witness in the Ivan Boesky
insider trading probe, has been moved from New Jersey to New York.
   U.S. District Judge Kevin Duffy ordered the hearing moved up
from 2 p.m. Friday in Fort Monmouth, N.J. to 10 a.m. in Manhattan
at the request of defense lawyer Otto Obermaier.
   The defense attorney said he wanted the hearing moved up ``to
prevent the prosecution from delaying _ and allowing Mr. Mulheren,
ultimately, to be released on bail.''
   Obermaier claimed federal prosecutors would seek a psychiatric
evaluation of Mulheren to hold him, in effect, without bail for 30
days.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Gage, while denying the
government wanted to delay bail proceedings for Mulheren, conceded:
``It would be irresponsible for us not to get an adequate medical
opinion.''
   Mulheren, 38, the senior partner at the Jamie Securities Co.,
was arrested on weapons charges Feb. 18 by police in Rumson, N.J.
and a federal criminal complaint filed in Manhattan accused him of
threatening a witness in the Boesky probe, identified only as
``Witness X.''
   Mulheren was released without bond Tuesday on the New Jersey
charges, but was immediately taken into federal custody.
   The new hearing is scheduled before U.S. Magistrate Kathleen
Roberts.
</TEXT>
