<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     03-03 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices barely budged in lethargic trading
Thursday as the market looked for more evidence on the strength of
the economy.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond finished unchanged and
its yield held steady at 8.31 percent, the same as late Wednesday.
   Most traders were said to be keeping a low profile in
anticipation of the Labor Department's unemployment report for
February, which is due out Friday and could shed some more light on
the economy's strength.
   ``It's been a dead calm in the bond market for the last several
days,'' said Harold Nathan, senior financial economist for Wells
Fargo & Co. in San Francisco. He said a new decline in commodity
prices, often viewed positively by bond traders concerned about
inflation, failed to cheer the markets.
   He said the market appears to have adjusted to a recent slight
relaxation in monetary policy by the Federal Reserve Board, and was
looking to the employment report for additional evidence on the
economy.
   ``We are not dipping into recession, but the question is how
fast are we growing,'' he said.
   Prices of short-term governments were unchanged to 1-32 point
higher, while intermediate maturities and 20-year issues were
unchanged, according to figures provided by Telerate Inc.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, rose 0.04 to 114.01. The Shearson Lehman Hutton
composite index, which makes a similar measurement, rose 0.19 to
1,192.39.
   In corporate trading, industrials and utilities were unchanged
in light trading, according to the investment firm of Salomon
Brothers Inc.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, fell 0.03 to 286.16.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were unchanged at 5.60
percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills rose 4 basis points to 5.86 percent and one-year
bills edged up 2 basis points at 6.16 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 6 7-16 percent, down from 6{ percent late
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
