<1ST_LINE>d f AM-DalkonShield     03-03 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dalkon Shield,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Doctor Indicted for Testimony on Birth Control Device</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chicago gynecologist was indicted for
perjury and on obstruction of justice charges Thursday over his
testimony on behalf of the A.H. Robins Co. concerning its Dalkon
Shield birth control device, the Justice Department said.
   Dr. Louis G. Keith, 53, an obstetrician-gynecologist at
Northwestern University Medical School in Chicago, testified
falsely in a lawsuit about his role in tests regarding the transfer
of bacteria by the tail string of the intrauterine shield, a
federal grand jury alleged.
   Contrary to his testimony, Keith didn't design, direct or
conduct the experiments about which he testified, said the
nine-count indictment returned in U.S. District Court in Tampa, Fla.
   Keith testified that tests showed the tail string of the Dalkon
Shield didn't transfer fluids or bacteria.
   Keith's testimony came during a trial in Tampa on March 15,
1983, in which a woman, Linda Harre, was seeking damages for
injuries allegedly suffered by the Dalkon Shield.
   The maximum penalty for violating the perjury law is five years
in prison and a $10,000 fine. The maximum penalty for obstruction
of justice is five years in prison and a $5,000 fine.
   The A.H. Robins of Richmond, Va., sought protection from
creditors under Chapter 11 of the Federal Bankruptcy Code in August
1985 after thousands of women alleged they were injured by the
Dalkon Shield. Some 200,000 claims have been filed by women who
said the birth control device caused spontaneous abortions,
infections, sterility and other problems.
</TEXT>
