<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MediaGeneral     03-03 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Media General Rejects Sugarman Takeover Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media General Inc. as expected, rejected a
$1.75 billion buyout proposal from television producer Burt
Sugarman on Thursday.
   In a four-sentence letter to Sugarman, Media General President
James S. Evans said the founding Bryan family, which owns a
controlling interest in the company, deemed the offer unacceptable.
   Evans stated the family would vote against the proposal if put
to a shareholder vote, and that ``under the circumstances no
further action on the part of the board is appropriate.
   Sugarman controls 9.8 percent of Media General's 28 million
shares of publicly-traded Class A common stock and has offered
$61.50 per share for the remainder of the company's Class A and
Class B stock, or a total of about $1.75 billion.
   About 71 percent of Media General's privately-held Class B
shares are owned by Chairman D. Tennant Bryan and Vice Chairman J.
Stewart Bryan III. The rest is owned by relatives and others
closely associated with the family and Media General.
   The 559,168 Class B shares have the power to elect seven of the
company's 10 directors. Furthermore, any change in control of the
company requires approval from two-thirds of the Class B holders.
   After Sugarman made his buyout offer on Monday, the Bryans
issued a statement that their stock was not for sale at any price.
   Sugarman was traveling and was unavailable to comment on Evans'
letter, said spokesman Jeffrey Taufield in New York.
   Media General Class A shares fell $1.25 to $46.12{ a share
Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Media General owns a number of daily newspapers, plus 32
weeklies and several television stations.
</TEXT>
