<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SteelLoan 1stLd-Writethru f0272 03-03 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Loan, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0272,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Resolution Opposing Loan to Mexico.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Senate passing resolution. Also
moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Wednesday night narrowly
approved a resolution by senators from steel-producing states
opposing a $400 million World Bank loan to help Mexico upgrade its
steel industry.
   ``It doesn't make any sense where we have unemployed steel
workers walking up and down the streets of the cities of this
country,'' said Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, who with Sen. John
Heinz, R-Pa., proposed the resolution.
   The resolution was attached on a 48-45 vote to legislation that
would outlaw most uses of lie detector tests by private employers.
Final action on that bill is scheduled for Thursday.
   Heinz complained that the amount of aid in the loan is
equivalent to what would be a $4 billion bailout of the U.S. steel
industry _ which is 10 times larger than the Mexican steel industry
_ at a time when American steel employment has dropped by 56
percent over the past 12 years.
   However, the resolution was opposed by Sens. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn.; Bill Bradley, D-N.J.; Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; John Chafee,
R-R.I., Daniel J. Evans, R-Wash., and Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.
   Bradley said the loan is just the type of aid needed to assure
that a non-Marxist government will continue to rule in Mexico.
Other opponents of the resolution said the Senate should not be
interfering in every decision made by the World Bank.
   Earlier Wednesday, Metzenbaum said Treasury Secretary James A.
Baker III has agreed to vote against the loan if he cannot persuade
the bank to delay its consideration. The World Bank board, which is
made up of 22 members representing 151 member countries, is
scheduled to take up the loan proposal Thursday.
   Baker agreed to the move following a meeting called by Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., Metzenbaum said.
   Metzenbaum said he warned Baker that support for the World Bank
in Congress could evaporate if the loan were made. The United
States provides 20 percent of the World Bank's funding.
   ``It is absurd for the American government to contribute to a
World Bank policy that will hurt the American steel industry and
American steel workers,'' the senator said.
   ``The kind of assistance the World Bank plans to give to Mexico
to make its steel industry more competitive is exactly the kind of
assistance this administration has refused to give to our own
industry here at home,'' he said.
   A Treasury Department spokesman said it is the agency's policy
not to comment on a vote until it occurs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
